<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE OF OZARKS MOURNS SIX KILLED IN CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT LOOKOUT, Mo. -- On Wednesday afternoon, Jerry Watson sent
a memo around to teachers and co-workers in his building at College
of the Ozarks.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, an associate professor of graphic arts and head of the
College Press, simply said, ``Tomorrow...I will be gone all day.
Please continue on the work grades...don't forget to pick up your
Christmas gift...see you on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a note he wrote the day before he would be one of six
members of the College of the Ozarks family to die in a plane crash
less than four miles from the campus airstrip.
</P>
<P>
   The memory was also, according to those who knew him, a classic
example of the way Watson, 55, looked at life. Nowhere in the note,
nor in conversations he had with colleagues before the trip, did he
mention he would be in St. Louis on Thursday accepting a
prestigious Governor's Award for Excellence in Teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no gloat in that man,'' said colleague and former
Watson student Craig Cogdill. ``Instead of bragging, he was
worrying that someone might forget their Christmas turkey. That's
just who he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Also killed were Watson's wife, Pat, 55; Marvin Oetting, 61, the
school's chairman of technical and applied sciences, and his wife,
Judy, 59; Joe Brinell, the 54-year-old airport director who was
piloting the Cessna Citation; and student and co-pilot Bart Moore,
22.
</P>
<P>
   Watson joined the College of the Ozarks faculty in 1971. In the
past three decades he became an institution on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Campus Press is Jerry Watson,'' Cogdill said. ``He had
printer's ink in his blood. It was what he loved. How do you ever
replace a man like that?''
</P>
<P>
   That's a question a lot of people -- faculty, students,
employees -- at this small Ozarks school are asking about all six.
Crash investigation
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators on Friday began scouring the crash site.
Debris from the crash was scattered over about 100 yards on the
Ruth and Paul Henning Conservation Area, a heavily wooded nature
reserve west of downtown Branson.
</P>
<P>
   Officials had determined that the plane crashed in the reserve
about 3.7 miles from the runway. Both wings were dislodged, and the
plane's impact started a small fire. Investigators have ruled out
an explosion on the plane, according to David Bowling, an air and
safety investigator with the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage will be removed with a crane this morning and taken
to the campus airport's hangar to be searched for further clues.
</P>
<P>
   The six bodies were taken to a Branson funeral home, where
autopsies will be performed, city spokesman Jerry Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's pilots last communicated with the school's airport
tower at 3:08 p.m. Central time, said Ed Washington, duty officer
with the Federal Aviation Administration's office in Kansas City,
Mo. The wreckage was found about 6:20 p.m. by a Branson police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known if the foggy weather played a role in the
crash, but the weather did affect the travel plans of others
attending the Governor's Conference on Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mel Carnahan was scheduled to fly back to Jefferson City,
Mo., from St. Louis on Thursday evening after a campaign event. But
his son, Randy, who was piloting his plane, decided the weather was
too bad to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Other pilots trying to leave St. Louis after the conference also
had to change their plans because of fog and rain in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Hubbard, president of Northwest Missouri State University,
rented a car and drove back to Maryville with his provost. His
pilot decided not to fly the university's plane, and commercial
airlines at Lambert-St. Louis International Airport were grounded,
too.
A college's loss
</P>
<P>
   The College of the Ozarks campus was quiet on Friday, both in
mourning and by design. Friday was a day for studying, the day
between classes and final exams, which begin today.
</P>
<P>
   It's normally a day when students leave their studies only for
on-campus jobs and meals. But this day found students gathering on
sidewalks, echoing each other in saying, ``I can't believe it.''
Eyes were wet or bloodshot from recent tears.
</P>
<P>
   On a campus this small, with 1,500 students and 235 faculty and
staff, there is no escaping reminders of this loss. Walk one way
and there is a section of campus devoted to agriculture. A section
synonymous with Marvin and Judy Oetting. The Oettings, who lived in
a college house just beyond the campus dairy barn, were well-known
and well-liked.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Keith, associate professor of agriculture, said he'd worked
with Marvin Oetting for 29 years. Oetting designed the academic
portion of the agriculture curriculum, Keith said.
</P>
<P>
   But his true love was always the nuts and bolts of it. Until the
day he died Oetting was frequently seen among the dairy cattle,
where he stopped to chat with students and offer advice. Even more,
he spent his off hours tending to his personal beef cattle herd.
</P>
<P>
   Keith said, ``Judy retired about a year ago, and both of them
were just really enjoying spending time with the grandkids. He was
getting ready to retire himself, although in his heart he was a
farmer and I'm not really sure what the difference between a
retired farmer and a nonretired farmer really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the agriculture section of campus, roads wander out to
the airport where Joe Brinell and Bart Moore were fixtures. Eric
Middleton, a 19-year-old sophomore from Wichita, Kan., said
everyone involved in aviation liked and respected Brinell and
Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both up here a lot, and they flew together all the
time,'' he said. ``They were both really experienced, really good
pilots.''
</P>
<P>
   Middleton recalled helping start the plane Thursday morning. In
fact, he said he thinks he's the last person at the school to see
the six that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out there, starting the auxiliary units to get the jets
running. Everything looked great. They were doing well, and the
plane was running beautifully. There is no way we can speculate on
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   From where he helped them take off Thursday morning to where
they crashed on return Thursday afternoon is only a few miles
across the Ozarks hills.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the center of campus, there's the administration
building where Pat Watson had begun working in the mid-1990s and
quickly became a student favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Roberts, a 21-year-old senior from Kansas City, Mo., said
he found it hard to believe Friday morning when he arrived at work
that Watson's smiling face wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a mother figure to a lot of us here,'' he said. ``Kids
were constantly in her office, just chatting or asking for advice.
She never turned anyone away.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials were waiting for family members to decide on
memorial services for the victims. The campus chapel held a prayer
service Friday night for students who needed to grieve.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for working on the 930-acre campus, students at
College of the Ozarks attend for free. Students maintain the
school's classrooms, raise food on campus and even run the school's
fire department and airport _ earning the school the nickname,
``Hard Work U.''
</P>
<P>
   Enoch Smith, a junior from Fort Pierce, Fla., said the deaths of
six such well-known and well-liked people from campus had left
everyone in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hear about accidents like this but then it happens
right where you live and to someone you're close to,'' he said.
``You just never know how to react.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what it does is it makes you realize that life is
precious and sweet and you have to take advantage of every day just
like our friends who won't be returning now. Keep your heart and
life in order.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Star's Lynn Franey and The Associate Press contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
