<HEADLINE>
INDIAN RELIGIONS CLASH WITH PROPOSED TELESCOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER
 &HT;     c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
(TUCSON) - In a quiet canyon south of Tucson, Indian religious
observances and the study of qua sars appear to be on a collision
course.
<P>
   Smithsonian scientists next week will submit another application
to build a giant gamma ray telescope array at the Fred Lawrence
Whipple Observatory at the base of Mount Hopkins. The site is about
a quarter-mile from a Navajo-style sweat lodge, whose operator
fears it will interfere with his ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service denied the observatory's first request,
submit ted last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just submitted one site, which wasn't enough to do an
analysis,'' Forest Service spokes woman Gail Aschenbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   But Trevor Weekes, a senior astrophysicist, said the service
cited several reasons for the initial denial, including the
objections of Native Americans and incompatibility of use with the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Aschenbrenner and Weekes said they believe the telescope and the
sweat lodge can share the site in Montosa Canyon, about 35 miles
south of Tucson in the Santa Rita Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   But sweat lodge operator Cayce Boone, a Navajo, said he feels
betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they made a ruling and they couldn't re-appeal it,''
he said. ``But somehow, it went through the loophole.''
</P>
<P>
   Resolving the conflict could be tricky. The Whipple Observatory
has been operating on the site since 1968; the lodge began
performing traditional purifying ceremonies and weddings nearly a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The $16 million gamma ray telescope would be composed of six
dishes arranged at the corners of a hexagon. A seventh telescope
would be placed in the center of the hexagon.
</P>
<P>
   Each 34-foot dish would be used to study quasars, pulsars,
superno vae and other bodies that emit the highest radiation in the
cosmos. The telescope is designed to shed light on high-energy
physics, or physics under extreme conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The observatory is a member of the prestigious
Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics in Cam bridge, Mass.
The center operates several telescopes on Mount Hop kins, one of
the premier spots for astronomical observation in the con tinental
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Weekes believes the sweat lodge has ``a misconception that the
telescope will disturb its aura.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the main road to the existing telescope passes
within 50 yards of the lodge. A smaller road to the proposed
telescope would be farther away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to modify our design to make it the least possible
impact on their activitieekes said. ``It's by no means an
ancient site, and there are no archaeological remains there.''
</P>
<P>
   Weekes and other astronomers involved in the project hope to
meet with Boone and representatives of his group, To All Our
Relations, to iron out any disagreements. Boone's objections to the
earlier proposal were supported by the Tohono O'odham, Hopi,
Navajo, Yaqui and other tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Aschenbrenner said the Forest Service supports such talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be best to come to the table, find common ground and
share the canyon,'' she said. ``We'd like to find room for both
uses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service will have the final say on whether the new
telescope is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Weekes would not say what the observatory will do if its request
is denied a second time. ``We haven't crossed that road yet.'' The
Associated Press contributed to this article. Kerry Fehr-Snyder can
be reached at kerry.fehr-snyder &LR; ari zonarepublic.com or at (602)
444-8975.
</P>
</TEXT>
