<SLUG> BC-FBO-FONTANA-ARRESTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FONTANA HIGH PLAYERS FACE CRIMINAL CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five Fontana High School football players face criminal charges
after allegedly attacking coaches of an opposing football team last
month, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
   One of the five players, 18-year-old fullback Anthony Robinson,
was charged Friday with one count of ``battery on school grounds,''
for allegedly attacking a Loyola High School football coach during
a melee after a Nov.19 game at Pierce College in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The crime is punishable by up to one year in jail ine/or a
$2,000 fine, according to the office of Los Angeles City Attorney
Jim Hahn.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is scheduled for arraignment Jan.4 in Van Nuys
Municipal Court.
</P>
<P>
   The other four`hi plaqess, described as ``arrestees,'' are
juveniles, and were not identified by authorities because of their
age. Their cases have been referred to the Los Angeles County
Probation Department.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the highly publicized incident, which came after
Fontana's 28-7 playoffs loss to Loyola, four Fohi players were
recommended for expulsion by principal Mike Demmer, and nine were
suspended from school for one week for their part in the postgame
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is clear that not only the district doesn't
tolerate (fighting), the law doesn't either,'' said Gus Hawthorne,
a member of the Fontana school board.
</P>
<P>
   The five Fohi players ``are accused of attacking members of the
Loyola coaching staff on the field ... as the two teams were lining
up for a postgame handshake,'' according to a news release from
Hahn's office. ``Investigators said the attack appeared to have
been unprovoked.''
</P>
<P>
   The release indicated ``four Loyola coaches suffered injuries in
the attack, ranging from a chipped tooth (to a) cut lip, bruises,
concussions and neck sprains.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who rushed for 174 yards and a touchdown this season
as the team's No.1 fullback, was not one of the four players
recommended for expulsion from school, principal Demmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was one of the nine players suspended, and he has
returned to campus. ``He was at school today,'' Demmer said Friday
night. ``I feel bad for Anthony because I know him, and this isn't
typical for him. He'll get through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Demmer could not explain why the Los Angeles Police Department,
which handled the investigation, arrested a player Fohi
administrators recommended only for suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to draw the line somewhere,'' Demmer said. ``We set our
criteria, and we went by that. The police do what they have to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Fohi officials based their disciplinary recommendations
aftersxudying videotape of the postgame melee, which at least one
Fohi player said came after Loyola coaches used racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
   Demmer said the district ``over the next several weeks'' will
review policies for handling football postgame situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to put your kids in this kind of situation
again, especially in a high-pressure game,'' Demmer said. ``You get
'em all wound up, and then expect them to drop to the bottom and go
out and shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make coaches more attentive to what people are
saying on sidelines and what the mood of the team is so we can make
a betteR pecision at the end of game.''
</P>
<P>
   Fontana coach Bob Stangel Jr. was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Demmer said he was ``stunned'' when he heard late Friday of the
players' arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some points this becomes counterproductive,'' he said.
``They're kids. They made a mistake. And we're still dragging this
out three weeks later ...
</P>
<P>
   ``A tew players really made a mess, and there's no way you can
get around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne, the school board member, said school district
officials ``need to pick up from this point and go on. We have the
job of educating 37,000 kids, and we need to concentrate on that
and the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
