<SLUG> BC-RAC-PINCAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY BREAKS RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Laffit Pincay's 8,834th winner, a colt named
Irish Nip running in a mere maiden race, arrived shortly after 3
o'clock Friday afternoon with a winter wind blowing in the jockey's
face and fewer than 6,000 fans cheering from a Hollywood Park
grandstand built for four times that many.
</P>
<P>
   Not the setting you'd choose for what Hollywood Park executives
were calling ``the last great sporting achievement of the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   But perfectly fitting for Pincay, the 52-year-old Panamanian who
has proven the adage that 90 percent of greatness is showing up _
fit and ready to ride any horse in any weather on any day big or
small.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rode in rain, snow, sleet, it didn't matter,'' Bill
Shoemaker, whose record had just been broken, said in the
celebration that followed. ``He wouldn't take off, like most jocks
would do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a blue-collar guy,'' said Bob Meldahl, Pincay's agent for
most of a decade in which his dedication has often been tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it mattered what kind of race it was,'' said
Laffit Pincay III, the jockey's 24-year-old son, ``as long as he
got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The record that Pincay has called ``my dream,'' the milestone
that has kept him in competition as the oldest jockey at a major
American racetrack, fell in the sixth race when Irish Nip outran 11
other horses to the finish on the turf course.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Pincay described the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I won the Kentucky Derby all over again,'' said
the man who rode Swale to a Derby victory in 1984. He expressed a
long list of thank yous _ to his wife, Jeanine, to his family, to
Meldahl, to Fred Hooper, the owner who brought Pincay to the United
States in 1966, and to ``the trainers and owners that supported me
all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay had tied Shoemaker's record Thursday with a victory
aboard I Be Casual, marking his fourth consecutive day with at
least one winner.
</P>
<P>
   He finished fifth, third and third in earlier races Friday,
picking up one mount because scheduled rider Victor Espinoza was
late, saying he overslept. Pincay went into the Irish Nip race as a
5-2 favorite, bet down from 6-1 morning-line odds by
souvenir-hunters and sentimentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mandella-trained Irish Nip, fifth in his only previous
outing, shot out of the gate at the start of the 1 1/16-mile race,
and Pincay found himself dueling for the lead with jockey Iggy
Puglisi and Laps n'Bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Nip actually was headed by Laps n'Bounds while racing near
the rail on the second turn. But straightening for home, Pincay
pushed to the front and, whipping his colt right-handed, drew off
to what would become a two-length victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's history at Hollywood Park!'' track announcer Michael
Wrona shouted as Pincay waved his whip overhead and his family and
fellow jockeys surged toward the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Winning trainer Mandella, a Pincay loyalist in the jockey's
leanest years, beamed as he greeted the horse and jockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I studied (Friday's) races last night, I thought the
Mandella horse would be my best chance,'' Pincay said later. ``He'd
run on turf, and he didn't run bad.'' Indeed, it was Pincay's only
winner of the day in six tries.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park was hard-pressed to top Thursday's celebration of
the record-tying win, but track management succeeded. Fireworks
spelled out ``Congratulations'' atop the tote board. Balloons
tumbled from the grandstand roof. Fellow jockeys sprayed champagne,
soaking Pincay's gold and green silks. Then they carried him and
his 6-year-old son Jean-Laffit on their shoulders to the scale. As
always, Pincay weighed in at 117 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Video messages from other jockeys, including Johnny Longden _
who held the record for 14 years before Shoemaker broke it in 1970
_ were unspooled on the infield television screen.
</P>
<P>
   Deadpanned Braulio Baeza, another riding great from Panama:
``It's about time you did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park president Rich Baedeker took the microphone and
presented Pincay with his next great ride _ a $50,000 Porsche
purchased by the Southern California racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   At the postrace press conference, a track chef walked in with a
steak dinner, because Pincay has been saying he'd celebrate the
record with that rare treat. Pincay said he'd eat it later. He'd
waited this long.
</P>
<P>
   As for the horseflesh: Irish Nip was the 44,646th ride of a
35-year career in which Pincay has won seven national earnings
titles, been voted a record five Eclipse Awards as the nation's
outstanding jockey, and endured the most celebrated diets in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lifetime of sacrifice and hard work, this is the
dividend,'' Laffit III, a budding sportscaster in New York, said of
his father. ``After 35 years of starving, you have to ask yourself,
`Was it worth it?' This leaves no question it was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
