<SLUG> BC-SKATE-PROCHAMPIONSHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIPINSKI LEADS WOMEN, URAMNOV LEADS MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The youngest athletes performed the best when the
Metabolife world professional figure skating championships began
Friday night at the MCI Center. But before and during the
competition, the hearts of many of the 10,622 spectators seemed to
belong to the two oldest skaters here _ Denise Biellmann of
Switzerland, who will turn 37 Saturday, and Brian Boitano, 36, of
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night's technical program, with Saturday night's
artistic program to come, the leaders were the 17-year-old Tara
Lipinski of Sugar Land, Texas, among the women and the 26-year-old
Aleksei Urmanov of Russia among the men. Biellmann ranked second
among the five women; Ilya Kulik, 22, of Russia was second and
Brian Boitano was third among the five men.
</P>
<P>
   Lipinski, the 1977 world and 1988 Olympic champion, skated a
sound technical program marred only by a shaky landing on a triple
lutz. She did three triple jumps, but no jump combinations. Surya
Bonaly of France and Biellmann did solid combinations. Lipinski
said she was not trying to play it safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a combination scheduled,'' said the young master
of combinations. ``If I tried one, I'd be off my music and would
have stopped the flow of my program. I have three triples tomorrow,
but no combinations.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without a combination jump, Lipinski's 14 scores showed
eight 9.9s and six 9.8s. In the complex scoring system, she totaled
98.6 points to 97.7 for Biellmann, 97.4 for Bonaly, 97.3 for Oksana
Baiul and 96.3 for Tonia Kwiatkowski.
</P>
<P>
   Biellmann's three triples were clean, and when she did a single
axel instead of a planned double, she did a double seconds later.
``I was very comfortable with the way I skated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When Biellmann won the 1981 world amateur championship in
Hartford, Conn., she dazzled the crowd by spinning on one skate,
with the other skate behind her back and high over her head. She
still does that body-bending move in competition and exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Boitano does not perform such maneuvers. For the last 13 months,
he has suffered from a curvature of the spine that has led to
pressure on the sciatic nerve and resulting pain. He has had to
temporarily abandon triple and double axels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to do everything else better,'' Boitano said, but
in this new program he did not. A shoulder was out of position for
his first jump, and he did a double lutz instead of a triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that,'' he said, ``it was tough. It was a hard program
where I had to hit everything, so when you miss one, it hurts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
