<SLUG> BC-BBN-NETS-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS HAND VICTORY NO. 2 TO BULLS, 71-69 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The rebuilding project of the New Jersey Nets crumbled
Friday night against the ultimate rebuilding project, as the Nets
handed the Chicago Bulls their second victory of the season in the
United Center, 71-69.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, now 4-16, showed few signs of the rhythm they had
found in recent routs of Sacramento and Milwaukee. The Nets were
outshot, outrebounded and outhustled by the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   And these were not your father's Chicago Bulls, nor even your
son's. Forget Jordan, Pippen, Rodman and company, whose six
championship banners hung overhead.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the first half, the Nets were losing by 13 to
the team of Ruffin, Artest, Benjamin, Simpkins and Willoughby. The
security guards, deep in the bowels of the United Center, were
watching hockey on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets could manage only four points in the last four minutes,
and only nine points in the final quarter. The Nets managed only
two fast-break points all night.
</P>
<P>
   With 30 seconds remaining and the score tied at 67-67, Elton
Brand, the No. 1 pick for the Bulls, hit a turnaround from four
feet against Jamie Feick.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury drove the lane for the Nets, throwing up a shot
with 20 seconds to go. It banked in softly, but Marbury landed on
Dickie Simpkins and was called for an offensive foul.
</P>
<P>
   After Brand hit 1 of 2 free throws to make the lead 70-67 with
17 seconds left, Marbury put up a 3-point shot with 10 seconds to
play. It glanced off the front of the rim, and the Chicago crowd of
22,112 exulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elton played with tremendous energy down the stretch,'' said
Bulls coach Tim Floyd. ``When he doesn't have to think and can
shoot it, he's better off.''
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Armstrong hit another free throw to put it out of reach at
71-67. Marbury then put in a meaningless shot.
</P>
<P>
   The game was slow and ugly. The Nets shot 38 percent, the Bulls
36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The main stinker for the Nets was Marbury, who was 7 of 20 from
the field and finished with 18 points and nine assists, below his
recent output. Keith Van Horn made 9 of 18 for 19 points, and Kerry
Kittles 6 of 10 for 17. The Bulls were let by Brand with 16 and Ron
Artest with 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets usually got only one shot per trip, and usually that
shot was from afar, as on offense the Nets were dominated by Will
Perdue and Brand in the post. The Bulls outrebounded the Nets, 54
to 38. The difference showed especially on the offensive boards,
with the Bulls leading 17-7.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period the Nets began to hit more of their shots,
closing to 41-39 at halftime. The run continued after the half. A
slam by Van Horn off a Kendall Gill miss at 6:15 in the 3rd quarter
extended the run to 14-6, with the Nets leading 53-47.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls played without the injured Toni Kukoc, who sat
somberly in black street clothes, and Hersey Hawkins, who missed
his first game since 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
