<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG CITY: IN FUTURE, TAILOR MAY LOOK A LOT LIKE PLASTIC SURGEON
</HEADLINE>
   (ko) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York's avant-garde has already tackled the first great
question of the 21st century: what to wear? Fashion designers have
issued long-range forecasts for the next millennium that are even
more Delphic than their ones for the next season.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar de la Renta: ``The 21st century will be the very first
century in which we celebrate the power of a woman and the essence
of her femininity.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Mizrahi: ``For executives and working people I think it's
going to be about cleanliness. It will be pared down. Very few
details. There will be very few colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Oldham: ``In the future, clothes will be desensitized, less
fraught with social significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan: ``I see fashion becoming more holistic. Combining
our spiritual needs with our earthy ones.'' If that's not clear,
keep in mind some theoretical background from Ms. Karan: ``When you
talk about the next millennium, you're talking about the here and
now. Because the future grows out of the present. It's an
evolutionary process.'' Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   Besides those revelations, you can find a few intriguing
predictions in ``Millennium Mode'' (Rizzoli; $50), the new
illustrated book of future fashion assembled by Roberta Wolf and
Trudy Schlacter. Historian Richard Martin discusses clothes that
change color like mood rings. Designer Stephen Strouse envisions
clothes you put on as a liquid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just get in the shower and press the clothing sprocket,''
Strouse says. ``You dip yourself in the clothes and they're
hot-wired to computers to keep you warm or cool, change colors,
whatever.'' If it gets cold, you can grow a hood and some sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the big names, though, make disappointing prophets.
``Fashion,'' Manolo Blahnik declares, ``should become more personal
and more private.'' Mary McFadden predicts that blue jeans will
still rule. Tommy Hilfilger promises ``a balance between high and
low technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   What's needed, obviously, is a prophet who knows nothing about
designing clothes. It takes the unfettered ignorance of a
journalist to make specific forecasts for the next 1,000 years:
</P>
<P>
   CASUAL FRIDAYS WILL DIE. As more people spend more time working
at home dressed in third-millennium sweat pants, they'll experience
a feeling already known to free-lancers: the desire to put on
something dignified on those rare occasions you venture into an
office.
</P>
<P>
   DRESS CODES WILL MAKE A COMEBACK IN CHURCHES AND THEATERS. As
people have more money and time to pursue spiritual and cultural
bliss, they'll notice that communal experiences are not so
transcendent when the people next to them are wearing shorts and
sandals. The trend will begin with rules printed on tickets at
opera houses (``Sports warm-up jackets are not permitted in the
parterre boxes.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``STAR TREK'' CLOTHES WILL FINALLY BECOME A REALISTIC OPTION.
For most of this century, futurists have been imagining everyone in
tight-fitting jump suits, but until now there has been an
insuperable obstacle: the aging human body. Those futurists
obviously never tried to imagine a 60-year-old William Shatner
squeezing into his old uniform. But bioengineering will make
body-sculpturing affordable for the masses, allowing anyone to wear
skin-tight clothes without shame.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG MONEY WILL BE IN DESIGNER BODY PARTS. Synthetic breasts
will be adorned with initials and little polo ponies as designers
team up with plastic surgeons and say things like, ``Skin is the
ultimate in high-end fabrics.'' The fashion press will cover the
perpetual anxiety over the proper shape of buttocks: ``Is round
finally finished? The spring look in Milan was trim and tapered.''
</P>
<P>
   Once women can design any kind of body, what will men find
sexually appealing? The answer from high-fashion designers will be
a resounding ``Who cares?'' Their socialite clients will continue
dressing for other women, not men. But mass fashions will cater to
men's tastes, which will get very, very kinky.
</P>
<P>
   NATURE WILL MAKE A COMEBACK, SORT OF. As the anatomical fashions
get bolder _ extra breasts on the back, stiletto-shaped feet _
there will be periodic returns to the ``natural'' look (two legs,
two arms). Once wrinkles can be easily eliminated by anyone, some
people will discover a cachet to crow's-feet.
</P>
<P>
   ALL OF THESE FASHION CHOICES WILL TURN OUT TO BE MISTAKES. In
2999, a group of universe-class designers in touch with the
evolutionary nature of history will announce that the next
millennium requires an entirely new wardrobe. And it will not be
cheap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
