<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PANTHERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS START, FINISH STRONG TO BEAT PANTHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Forget the Dallas Stars team that played so well in the
first period to grab a three-goal lead, and forget the one that did
whatever it was they were doing in the second period to cough that
lead up.
</P>
<P>
   They are neither that good or that bad, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, focus on the Stars team that grabbed a go-ahead goal
early in the third period and hung on for a 4-3 victory against the
Florida Panthers on Friday night at Reunion Arena. That is the team
the Stars excel at being, a tight-checking, low-scoring, and yes,
winning hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought our third period was better than our
first,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I thought the first and
third were just solid periods.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that they'd mind if every period for the rest of the season
was like the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars scored three goals, with Sergei Zubov, Joe Nieuwendyk
and Mike Modano all lighting the lamp. There have been 20 games
this season where the Stars didn't score three goals in the entire
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it was the first time in a while we scored three
goals,'' Stars winger Grant Marshall said. ``It surprised us
probably. We just got complacent like we did in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Florida Panthers scored three goals in a span of 1
minute, 40 seconds near the end of the second period to wipe out
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Mellanby followed by Paul Laus followed by Viktor Kozlov
sent the Stars into the second intermission with their heads
hanging.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are playing a team and you get a 3-0 lead that early,
you start playing finesse. You're looking, you're poaching trying
to get that fourth goal,'' Hitchcock said. ``The next thing you
know you are buried in your own end. It's hard to regroup during a
period. I thought we regrouped for the third.''
</P>
<P>
   The meltdown would have been a lot worse and a lot more
dissected had it not been for Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner
scoring 2:52 into the third period to get back what had been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher had drawn three Panthers
defenders to him. Hatcher then found Langenbrunner alone in the
circle, and he hammered it past Panthers goalie Mikhail Shtalenkov.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was left wide open and I just kind of saw a lane and shot
it,'' Langenbrunner said. ``And it found a way through.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything the Stars shot in the first period seemed to find a
way through.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov began by firing in a power-play goal at 4:10 of the first
period. The play began when Panthers winger Radek Dvorak had a
short-handed breakaway that Stars backup goalie Manny Fernandez
stopped and started the break the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, Nieuwendyk had been saying the Stars'
problem was they didn't stay hungry after scoring the first goal.
They let up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, they saw the Panthers struggling and went in for
the knock-out punch. They got two.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk deflected a shot by Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor in
for a 2-0 lead at 10:55 of the second period. Less than two minutes
later, Stars forward Mike Modano weaved through a bunch of Florida
defenders and then roofed a backhand pass Panthers goalie Trevor
Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   It was the last save he didn't make all night.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers pulled him in favor of recently acquired
Shtalenkov. Kidd faced seven shots, stopping only four of them. The
Stars only allowed Fernandez two goals before pulling him in favor
of Ed Belfour after Laus' goal, his first of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has confidence in Eddie, and why shouldn't he,'' Fernandez
said of Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock said it was less about Fernandez or Belfour and
more about sending a wake-up call to the team.
</P>
<P>
   They heard it, getting their second consecutive victory and
their seventh in nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it's not what they did but what we didn't do,''
Marshall said. ``We knew we screwed up and we went back and just
battled hard for 20 minutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
