<SLUG> BC-KC-WALMAR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY FAULTS ELECTRIC-FAN MAKER, WAL-MART IN DEATH OF TODDLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- In mid-July 1995, the Mason family of
Chillicothe, Mo., made some warm- weather adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   Family members slept in the basement, a cool spot in the non-air
conditioned home. But one night Kevin and Laura Mason didn't want
to wake Ryan, their 15-month-old who had fallen asleep while
playing on his bedroom floor. So Kevin Mason put a fan about three
feet away, placed a pillow under Ryan's head and closed the door,
the family's attorney recalled Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That night a blanket or a piece of clothing blocked the blades
of the whirring fan, and the next morning Kevin Mason found the
room ravaged by flames, lawyer Kent Emison said.
</P>
<P>
   The fan did not have a common fire-safety device, he told
Jackson County jurors this week, and that cost Ryan Mason his life.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County jurors on Thursday evening found the Taiwanese
fan manufacturer and Wal-Mart Stores Inc., which sold the fan,
partially responsible for Ryan Mason's death and ordered them to
pay the Masons about $3.6 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   A Wal-Mart spokesman criticized the verdict and said the company
plans to appeal. There was no definitive proof in Wal-Mart's own
investigation that the fan caused the fire, John Bisio said.
</P>
<P>
   He added no attorneys or officials from the manufacturer -- Han
Chi Hang Company Ltd. -- showed up for trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sympathize for the family,'' Bisio said Friday. ``But at
the same time, we have to question this decision. The (jurors) are
acting on emotion. Unfortunately, by affiliation, we are being
punished.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We vouch for the products we carry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Masons contended that the fan started the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic theme of this case is very simple: These fans have
no safety features in the event of an electrical failure,'' said
Emison, referring to a device that can shut off a machine during a
malfunction. ``These could have been put into the fan for less than
a quarter per fan.''
</P>
<P>
   That technology, Emison said Friday, has been available since
the 1950s and is installed in appliances from coffee makers to hair
dryers.
</P>
<P>
   The Masons' ``hope is that this (verdict) will force all
manufacturers to put these safety features in fans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Giles, a spokesman with the Consumer Product Safety
Commission in Washington, D.C., said the federal regulatory agency
had recalled several automatic coffee makers because they had been
built without thermal cut-offs and were deemed a risk to users.
Currently, he said, there are no mandatory federal standards for
electric fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are concerned about any electrical appliance or fan
that causes fires,'' Giles said. ``We would like to get the case on
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 0102EST &QL; 
