<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-SMITH-TROUBLES-TE     12-11 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SMITH-TROUBLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA RICHES HAVE ONLY BOUGHT LEON SMITH MORE TROUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Bill Green is sitting in the second-floor conference
room of the Sullivan House group home where Leon Smith spent the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, where Smith used to sleep, Green remembers
warning Smith about the ``street agents'' who were out to hustle
the young basketball star.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was hanging around those street agents, he'd sit down
and talk with me and agree not to go out with them any more,''
Green said. ``Then the guys would blow their horn, and out the back
door he would go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys would come around and pick him up in a Lexus, or pick
him up in a brand new station wagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, the director of the Sullivan House, has always believed
that Smith, a Mavericks rookie who was a first-round draft choice,
was extremely susceptible to those ``street agents'' and anyone
else trying to cash in on his new wealth. Green also believes that
the feeding frenzy among those people, including his family and
friends, who are out to get their share of the three-year, $1.447
million contract the 6-10 forward signed with the Mavericks last
month, has added to the worries of a young man trying to grow up
alone in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   That might explain at least part of Smith's unsettling behavior
in the past month, from a reported suicide attempt with an aspirin
overdose to being arrested twice in a 24-hour period in Chicago
last week. Smith is currently enrolled in a Dallas-area psychiatric
facility.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Linda Smith, also is of the belief her son is the
target of unscrupulous people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep saying that Leon doesn't have a family, but that's
not true,'' Linda Smith said. ``I have been here, I have tried to
contact him, I have contacted Dallas, I contacted the hospital, and
they treat me as if I have no rights at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sounds like a money thing. People are trying to control
him for their own selfish reasons. It's a money thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Smith, however, has been an absentee mother for most of
her son's life. Leon Smith, 19, was a ward of the state of Illinois
from age 4 through 18. The Sullivan House was one of five group
homes in which he was raised. Linda Smith popped back into Leon's
life about the time he became a basketball star at Chicago's Martin
Luther King High School.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, Leon Smith fell in love with Cappie
Pondexter, whose name is tattooed on his arm.
</P>
<P>
   When Smith received a telephone call from Pondexter's new suitor
informing him that his relationship with Pondexter was over,
friends said Smith had a difficult time handling it, which led to
some of his puzzling actions.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was arrested after police said he threatened Pondexter
with a gun at the girl's Chicago high school on Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Pondexter plays on the Marshall High School basketball team with
two of Smith's sisters _ Angela and Lekeshia.
</P>
<P>
   The Smith sisters have had a strained relationship with
Pondexter for some time _ a relationship that has almost polarized
the Marshall team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Marshall coach Dorothy Gaters is left to try to put the
shattered pieces back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult situation for me,'' said Gaters, a legendary
coach who has won seven state titles and 19 city championships in
Chicago. ``I'm concerned for Leon, as well as for my players. It's
so much stuff happening with teen-agers today with violence and
guns, and that's always in the back of your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaters thinks Smith's life would take a positive turn if he
looked to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I genuinely like Leon,'' Gaters said. ``He's been to so many
group homes, he's very suspicious of people, and now that he's come
into so much money he doesn't trust anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks everybody is after his money, and I'm sure a lot of
people are.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall principal Don Pittman said the worst thing that
happened to Smith was being a first-round draft pick. After San
Antonio drafted Smith with the last pick of the first round, the
Mavericks traded for his rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon wasn't ready for the NBA from a maturity standpoint or a
physical standpoint,'' Pittman said. ``Leon was a victim of
himself, because Dallas didn't do their homework. But they took him
on the first round, and that means guaranteed money, and that
really turned out to be a negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had to work for that, maybe he would have decided this
is not for me. Or, he would have been more focused. But all of this
stuff was laid in his lap, and he just couldn't handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was so out of control Dec. 3 that he was back in jail only
hours after being bailed out by his former high school coach,
Landon Cox.
</P>
<P>
   This time he was charged with busting the windows and ramming a
car that belonged to Pondexter's mother, Vanessa Pondexter, and of
violating a restraining order to stay away from Cappie Pondexter.
</P>
<P>
   With the assistance of the NBA Players Association, Smith is
currently receiving psychiatric treatment at a Dallas-area clinic.
The Mavericks have suspended him without pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has definitely been a crazy situation,'' Pittman said.
``I knew Leon before all of this happened, and hopefully he's going
to receive the help he needs that he can get on with his life.
Hopefully, he hasn't done too much damage to this career.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who twice bailed Smith out of jail last week, said Smith
has been treated unfairly ever since the June 30 NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why in the world would Dallas draft him if they don't want
him?'' Cox asked. ``Why would you want to send a kid like that to
Europe, or to some other league?
</P>
<P>
   ``This boy has a lot of talent, and he can help any team win
some games.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, according to a police report, allegedly swallowed more
than 200 aspirin on Nov. 14 in a failed suicide attempt. Billy
Hunter, the executive director of the Players Association, said
Smith now is receiving the help he needs to turn his life around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon has some issues that he has to deal with, and issues he
should have dealt with a long time ago,'' Hunter said. ``This stuff
has built up over his life. I know what Leon's basketball skills
are. I've got to clean up that other situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, the group home director, tried to absolve the Mavericks
of the negative press they've received during Smith's recent
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it wouldn't have happened with any other
organizaiton,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Green did not totally let the Mavericks off the hook.
Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson did not bring Smith in
for a workout or an interview before the draft, and Green said
Smith's problems would have been clearly noticeable had that taken
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some preplanning should have taken place before the draft,''
Green said. ``But I think they assumed that any kid coming out of
high school that received one and a half million bucks would run
through a wall for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But money has never meant anything to Leon. Basketball is the
thing Leon wanted to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaters is hoping that Smith will finally realize his dream, and
one day play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a kid who just been kicked around the system,'' Gaters
said. ``I'm praying for him, and I hope everything works out for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a sad, sad series of events. I'm really concerned if
he's ever going to come back, and if he's ever going to be a
productive citizen again.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
