r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX     12-11 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES PAVE THE WAY FOR EX-HORNED FROG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Former TCU standout Jason Tucker will earn the
first start of his career when the Cowboys take on the Philadelphia
Eagles on Sunday at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It's a continuation of a whirlwind year for Tucker, who spent
the spring and early part of the summer playing in NFL Europe. He
took a couple of days off before joining the Cowboys in training
camp, but Tucker has played approximately 33 weeks of continuous
football since March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing that position is a lot of running, especially when you
consider how much he's played in the last year,'' said Cowboys
coach Tommie Robinson, who also coached Tucker at TCU. ``It's a lot
of wear and tear on your body. But he's been able to maintain his
strength and stamina. He is running better now than I've seen him
run before.''
</P>
<P>
   Since training camp, Tucker has risen from being the bottom
receiver on the depth chart because of the late start and is now
the group's most versatile player. He initially got the Cowboys'
attention for his play on special teams _ first as a coverman, then
as a kickoff returner. Tucker's quick adaptation to the Cowboys'
offense has allowed him to become a valuable backup at all four
receiver positions.
</P>
<P>
   Because of several injuries at split end _ Michael Irvin, Ernie
Mills and Wane McGarity _ Tucker will start opposite flanker Raghib
Ismail against the Eagles. Tucker, 23, was a fifth-round pick of
the Cincinnati Bengals last season but was released during training
camp. At Robinson's urging, the Cowboys signed him to a free-agent
contract during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me back in training camp that I'd start this
season, I would have said you were lying,'' Tucker said. ``With
Michael and all the guys here, I never expected to be a starter.
But with all the injuries we've had, this is a big opportunity to
showcase what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker has caught 9 passes for 152 yards this season. His 16.9
yards-per-catch average leads the team. He also leads the team in
average yards per kickoff return _ 22.8 _ and has the longest
return of 50 yards. He is fourth on the team in special-teams
tackles with 10. BACK TO WICHITA FALLS
</P>
<P>
   It's official.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are going back to Wichita Falls for training camp
for a third consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Jerry Jones made the announcement at a news
conference Friday, when he also said that the Cowboys would spend
the entire training camp at Midwestern State University, ending
speculation that the Cowboys would split training time between a
site in Texas and one in California.
</P>
<P>
   No dates have been set but training camp is expected to open in
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the decision to nix the California plans was based on
the team's inability to find a suitable training site there, a
preseason game scheduling conflict and a shortened length of stay
in Japan for their trip to the American Bowl in early August.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had hoped training in California would help cut down
on the travel to Japan. However, he said the Cowboys' trip to the
American Bowl will be just an ``extended weekend'' and last only
five days.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Midwestern State is concerned, Jones said it was the
logical choice considering the excellent facilities there and the
hospitality the Cowboys have received the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The only other Texas site that was being considered was one in
the Rio Grande Valley. A lucrative proposal for a permanent
training home there was passed over because of concerns about when
construction would be completed.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he makes training camp decisions on a year-to-year
basis and going to the South Texas or anywhere else is a
possibility for 2001. But the next training camp will be in Wichita
Falls. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Center Mark Stepnoski (strained calf) practiced Friday for the
first time in more than a week. As a result, Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey is optimistic that he will be ready for Sunday's game
against the Eagles. Gailey said it will be a game time decision. If
Stepnoski can't play, Tom Myslinski will start for the second
consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cornerback Kevin Mathis will start opposite Deion Sanders in
place of Kevin Smith, who will miss his third consecutive game with
a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   _ Surgery to repair Wane McGarity's fractured right ring finger
was more extensive than anticipated, ending his season. The Cowboys
placed him on injured reserve Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Receiver Chris Brazzell was signed from the practice squad to
the active roster Friday to replace McGarity. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
