<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PINCAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY SETS RECORD FOR WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Laffit Pincay tied Bill Shoemaker's world record for most
victories by a jockey on Thursday, the jockeys at Hollywood Park
carried Pincay through the winner's circle. They did it again
Friday, and then they popped the cork.
</P>
<P>
   They opened bottles of champagne and sprayed it in the winner's
circle because Pincay rode Irish Nip to a 21/4-length victory in
the sixth race, overcoming a speed duel with another horse and
becoming the all-time leading jockey with 8,834 wins. Shoemaker,
who retired in 1989, rode 8,833 winners.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the closest horse racing can come to baseball's
home-run competition in 1998 between Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
When McGwire broke Roger Maris' home-run record, the Maris family
was in attendance. And Shoemaker was at Hollywood watching Pincay
break his record.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire broke the record, he came to home plate and hugged
his son. After Pincay dismounted, he was carried to the jockey's
weigh scale on the shoulders of his fellow riders. They also
carried Pincay's preteen son, Jean-Laffit, on their shoulders next
to Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll enjoy this as long as it stands,'' Pincay, 52, said.
</P>
<P>
   That figures to be a while. First, Pincay said he intends to
keep riding for at least another year _ if not three years.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the closest active jockey is Pat Day, He's 46 and is at
7,600 winners. He's winning between 250 and 300 races a year. At
that rate it would take him at least six years _ or age 52 _ to
reach 9,000 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Baze, third-leading active jockey, has a little more
than 6,775 winners. He's been the hottest jockey in the past five
years, winning more than 400 races each year.
</P>
<P>
   He could hit 9,000 in less than six years if he stays at that
pace, and he's five years younger than Day.
</P>
<P>
   Baze rides strictly on the Northern California circuit. In horse
racing, Northern California is considered less competitive than
Pincay's home turf of Southern California, and Pincay's backers
already were putting an asterisk to anyone who would break the
record in an area such as Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone breaks it somewhere else,'' Southern
California-based trainer Mike Mitchell said, ``I don't think it'll
be the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think Laffit can break 9,000. That'll be his next
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the only number that mattered Friday was 8,834. Shoemaker,
confined to a wheelchair since an automobile accident about eight
years ago, was able to sit in the paddock and watch the
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great friend, a great person,'' Shoemaker said. ``I
couldn't have picked a better guy to break the record.''
</P>
<P>
   The record-breaker was another vintage Pincay ride. Just as
Thursday when he tied the record, Pincay got his horse to break
sharply from the starting gate before he settled him into a running
style that the race dictated once the gates opened.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Pincay was on the rail, so he allowed Irish Nip to
run toward the lead in the 11/16 mile race on the turf. By the time
they hit the backstretch, Pincay was in a speed duel with 25-to-1
longshot Laps N'bounds. It stayed that way through the backstretch
when both runners cut through a half mile in an honest 47 seconds
and three-quarters in 1:11.
</P>
<P>
   Laps N'bounds proved to be cheap speed and started backing up,
but Irish Nip had more underneath Pincay. Under one of his strong,
arm-pumping hand rides _ he hit the colt sparingly with the whip _
Irish Nip repulsed a late challenge from the Kent Desormeaux-ridden
Quiet One and won drawing away.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, members of Hollywood Park's front office
presented Pincay with a trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trophy is nice, but you can't drive it,'' Hollywood
president Rick Baedecker said. ``We bought you a toy. Enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when they drove out a new Porsche for Pincay to take
home. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
