<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUTTING-MEL-BLOUNT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER STEELERS STAR MEL BLOUNT HAS IT COVERED IN CUTTING HORSE
EVENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The rider who placed third in the limited
nonprofessional division finals of the National Cutting Horse
Futurity yesterday had compiled quite a resume before ever mounting
a horse.
</P>
<P>
   He manages boys homes in Pennsylvania and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   He's building a state-of-the-art arena for rodeos and horse
shows on his 268-acre ranch in Claysville, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   He has four Super Bowl rings and is in the Pro Football Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The budding cutting star is former Pittsburgh Steelers
cornerback Mel Blount, who insists this is no Deionesque, two-sport
endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you've played in front of the world like I have in Super
Bowls, there's no jitters when I ride into the arena to cut,'' said
Blount, 51, who played for the Pittsburgh Steelers from 1970-83 and
was inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1989. ``Cutting really
relaxes me. It's not even close to football. When you make your
living in a sport where everybody judges you on every play and
talks about you on radio and TV, the pressures of cutting is
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount has ridden cutting horses since the late 1960s after
first watching them work when he played college football at
Southern University in Baton Rouge, La. In 1977, he attended a
cutting clinic in Middlebrook, Va., that was conducted by five-time
Futurity champion Buster Welch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put me on a gray mare called Grace,'' Blount said.
``After I rode, Buster said, `I don't know where he came from, but
he sure can ride a horse good,' and that meant a lot. It was like a
confirmation that I had ability to ride.''
</P>
<P>
   After he retired from football, Blount competed in the celebrity
cutting classes at the Futurity in the early 1990s. This year marks
his first time to compete in a regular class at the Futurity. He
finished fourth in the nonpro division.
</P>
<P>
   The commitment to excellence has carried over from his former
arena to his current one. His 3-year-old mount, Doc Pers Dodger,
was sired by the 1984 Futurity open division champion Doc Per.
</P>
<P>
   But cutting across a football field to chase a wide receiver and
cutting across Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum are different athletic
feats for Blount.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a cutting show, you have to prepare yourself, you have to
be tough and mentally focused,'' he said. ``The thing about this
game is there isn't anybody that can back you up. In football, you
have a strong safety to back you up if you let a receiver get by.
In cutting, there's nobody to back you up when a cow gets away from
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``In football, you get a penalty and you get backed up for only
15 yards, and you can recover on the next series. Your team can get
a lot of penalties and still win a game. But if you get penalized
in cutting, you don't recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount's trainer, Tracy Barton, of Rocky Mountain, Va., said the
ex-football star has a knack for competing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he came to the Futurity, he only practiced on this
horse twice, in July, and that was right before he showed it in the
first go-round,'' Barton said. ``So, it was great to see him be so
competitive. He's a natural on a horse, and cutting really fits
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his days of stopping receivers short of catching a clutch
pass, Blount hopes to make big plays in cutting and said he's going
to spur his cutting horse for the big money this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy like me who doesn't show a whole lot, I easily can
say that I'm satisfied with making the semifinals,'' Blount said.
``But I still have a lot of work to do, and my ultimate goal is to
win it. In football, I'd rather not make the playoffs if we weren't
going to win the Super Bowl. You want to get to the big dance. At
this show, I want to get to the big dance, which is the finals.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
