<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA GOES AGAINST MENEFEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Ayala Jr.'s improbable boxing comeback continues Saturday
in San Antonio. He's confident, but admits he doesn't know exactly
what or who's next in the ring after the night's final bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an agenda,'' Ayala, 36, said. ``I'm a free agent.
I'll fight whoever it is. The plan is to fight at whatever weight I
can get a good fight at.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala (24-0, 22 knockouts) is scheduled for a 10-round
middleweight bout against Tony Menefee on Saturday at Freeman
Coliseum. It's Ayala's third bout since being released from prison
in April.
</P>
<P>
   He was a once a junior middleweight phenom on the eve of a world
title fight, when fueled by alcohol and drugs, he broke into a home
and raped a woman on Jan. 1, 1983. He spent the next 16 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   An older Ayala says he is reformed, but still lives with the
guilt of a ``horrible and horrendous crime'' every day. His life
now is boxing and providing for his family, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that I am still competitive and expect to keep
winning,'' Ayala said.
</P>
<P>
   His father and trainer, Tony Ayala Sr., has watched his son's
boxing skills improve since his release. The elder Ayala claims his
son still has the punching power that scored 20 knockouts before
his incarceration. But he also stressed that a new style will be
needed if his son expects to win a world title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony will be aggressive, but more defensive,'' Ayala Sr. said.
``I compare it to George Foreman's comeback. Tony knows he can't
waste any punches or energy like he used to when he was younger.''
</P>
<P>
   In his two previous bouts, Ayala stopped Manuel Esparaza in the
third round on Aug. 20 in San Antonio and stopped Robert Koon in
the fourth round on Sept. 23 in Corpus Christi. His plan is to
fight for at least two years, meanwhile ``taking it slow to get a
series of wins.''
</P>
<P>
   In Menefee (67-6-1, 37 knockouts), Ayala faces an experienced
boxer who has been in the ring with two former world champions. He
was stopped in the eighth round by Roberto Duran in 1993 and lost a
12-round decision to Hector Camacho in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Menefee said winning in Ayala's hometown will be a tough task,
but could be a big boost for a career that has been limited to
fighting in Nebraska, Iowa, and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on turning it up in last rounds to get a knockdown or
stop him,'' Menefee, 27, said.''It would be an excellent
steppingstone back to full-time training and hopefully a title
fight.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 0112EST &QL; 
