<HEADER>
A5918 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CELTICS-ROCKETS-BOS     12-11 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTICS-ROCKETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS HANG ON TO BEAT ROCKETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in the third quarter Friday night, Celtics guard Paul
Pierce misfired on an alley-oop attempt, then jogged up court
laughing at his blunder. At the time, you could hardly blame him
for the lightheartedness. The Celtics-Rockets tilt had all the
suspense and drama of a Teletubbies plot. The Celtics led, 67-52,
and appeared to be on their way to a laughable rout.
</P>
<P>
   By early in the fourth quarter, the laughing had long given way
to flushed faces as the lead slowly dwindled. When Houston tied it,
89-89, on a tip-in by former Celtic Thomas Hamilton with 4:42 to go
_ and the sound of boos began bouncing off the FleetCenter walls _
the home team sought to regroup to ensure another solid effort
didn't go to waste.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Pierce, Kenny Anderson, and Adrian Griffin came up
with big plays for Boston, which scored 5 unanswered points after
Houston tied it and held off another Houston rally for a 100-96
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, most of the players said that despite the fact they
didn't win as convincingly as many figured (they led by as many as
25 points in the first half), the bottom line is that they won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of tough,'' said Griffin, ``but we pulled it out
at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pierce, who tallied 19 points and 7 rebounds,
acknowledged that during the third quarter, he figured the Celtics'
lead was insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the course of the game, I never thought we would
relinquish our lead, but we did,'' said Pierce. ``But even when
they tied the game, I had that feeling that we were going to get
this game and this is not going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics failed to convert after Houston tied it, but at the
other end, Shandon Anderson (15 points), missed a baseline jumper,
Griffin got the rebound, and Pierce drained a trey.
</P>
<P>
   Then with 3:33 left, Houston's Cuttino Mobley (a game-high 23
points) missed, Antoine Walker got the rebound, and Kenny Anderson
hit a pull-up jumper to give the Celtics a 94-89 lead with 3:25
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made the run, but we just started playing ball again,''
said Anderson. ``It wasn't like we were going to run and hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston surged again, however, as Mobley (formerly of the
University of Rhode Island) scored on a reverse layup and a 17-foot
jumper to pull the Rockets to 94-93 with 1:14 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Rockets) were down a lot of points, but they showed a lot
of gumption and a lot of heart to get themselves back into the
game,'' said Celtics coach Rick Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite Houston's rges, Pierce wasorrect. The Celtics
merely stepped up their play after each Houston run and kept the
Rockets at bay. After Houston cut the lead to 1, Kenny Anderson
missed on a short attempt, but Walker got the rebound, and the
Celtics reset. Then Anderson sank two free throws with 20.4 seconds
left, giving the Celtics a 96-93 lead. Carlos Rogers sank one of
two free throws with 14.4 seconds to go. With 12.9 seconds left,
Griffin (who got three boards after Houston tied it), sank 4 of 4
free throw attempts the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had a team-high 20 points, Walker added 16, and Griffin
led all Celtics rebounders with 10. Houston (7-14), which had 27
turnovers lead to 32 Celtics points, had four players in double
figures.
</P>
<P>
   The win improved Boston to 10-8. Although Pitino may share in
his team's adage that a win is a win, and credited Houston for
making a game of it, he criticized his team for getting away from
the play that led to an NBA record-tying 11 steals in the first
quarter and 64 percent shooting in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were spectacular in the first quarter, we were good in the
second quarter and, as usual, with our young basketball team, we
lost our memory of what got us the lead,'' said Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get hypnotized into a different kind of game, an isolation
game, a one-on-one game, and we lose it. We're brilliant, and we
don't comprehend why we're brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, they were able to recapture enough of that brilliance to
avoid what would have been an embarrassing defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics play in New York Sunday. ``We had to take advantage
of homecourt,'' said Waer. ``We need to get up to three t four
games on our road trip, and it's going to be hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
