<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTICS-ROCKETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIR CHARLES IS KING FOR A NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DASUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the spring of 1984 and the championship-bound Boston
Celtics were in Milwaukee for a game against the Bucks. Danny
Ainge, Kevin McHale, Quinn Buckner, and Larry Bird were sitting in
the Milwaukee Hyatt's atrium coffee shop when assistant coach Chris
Ford walked into the hotel lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had a travel bag slung over his shoulder. He had just come
from a scouting mission at the SEC tournament and he approached the
group, most of whom were sampling the hotel's ice cream sundae bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you been, Doc?'' McHale asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you where I've been, Kevin,'' said Ford. ``I've just
seen the guy who's going to kick your ass for the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an exaggeration, but not by much. Barkley and McHale
wound up being two of the best forwards in NBA history. They used
to sit together on the team bus when they joined forces for the NBA
All-Star Game. When he retired this week, Barkley said McHale was
the toughest player he ever guarded.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics saluted Sir Charles at the New Garden Friday night
at halftime of their 100-96 victory over the Rockets. There was a
false rumor that Bill Russell would do the honors, but the task
fell to Cedric Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   Dred in black, limping in the wake of his ruptured quadriceps
tendon sustained Wednesday, Barkley accepted a piece of the
Garden's parquet floor (``I'll put it in my pool room''), and a
photo of himself jousting with Larry Bird. Bird sent a message via
video and told Barkley, ``When you look up and see those
championship banners, just think of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the Garden masses, Sir Chuck said, ``T reason I
wanted to be here tonight is this: One day I was sitting around
with some old guys, big sports fans. One of them said, `I played
against the New York Yankees _ you ever heard of the Yankees?'
Another guy, a hockey player, said, `I played against the Montreal
Canadiens.' I said to them, `yeah, but I played against the
Celtics.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell was in his final season with the Celtics when Charles
came out of Auburn _ billed as the Round Mound of Rebound. ``He
might have een the most unique player I ever saw,'' Max recalled.
``He played like he was 6-10. We heard about this guy coming into
the league, 6-5, 260 pounds, and we thought, `How is he going to
guard anybody on the Celtics?' But he could. He could do anything.
He was so explosive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the size of the man. It's the size of the man's
heart. I was talking with Randy Brown, a Bulls player, and he said,
`Elton Brand reminds me of Charles Barkley,' and I said, `yeah,
Charles Barkley's sister, maybe.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Heinsohn, one of the greatest NBA forwards in history said,
``I voted for him as one of the top five active players when they
had that top-50 vote. That's how much I thought of him.''
</P>
<P>
   A man without a ring, perhaps the Ernie Banks of basketball,
Charles was in the midst of his 16th and final season when he hurt
his left leg Wednesday in Philadelphia. Nice symmetry there. Philly
is where Barkley started his NBA career, and his mother and
grandmother attended his 1,072d and final NBA game.
</P>
<P>
   He had already said this would be his final season. The injury
derailed a farewell tour that would have been Yaz-like. But he
wanted to come to Boston one lat time, and it was at the Hub's
Ritz-Carlton Hotel that he formally annouced his retirement
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The fierce Celtic-Sixer rivalry of the early 1980s was starting
to fizzle when Charles came into the league. He was a rookie when
Bird and Julius Erving tried to strangle one another on the Garden
floor in 1984 (``I got in trouble for holding Larry''), and that
same season featured the final Boston-Philly playoff matchup of
this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got respect for what the Celtics accomplished,'' he said.
``I'm not surprised about tonight. I've always thought these were
great fans. I'm not sure the players on this team understand what
it means to be a Celtic.''
</P>
<P>
   Never silent or politically correct (on the night he retired he
said, ``Just what this country needs _ another unemployed black
man''), Barkley was a fierce competitor and retires as a
card-carrying member of the NBA's All-Time Top 50 and the 1992 US
Olympic gold-medal-winning Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   The Dream Team was probably the most idolized and isolated
assemblage in sports history. Players were sequestered in five-star
hotel, guarded by police, apart from the Olympic Village. Most of
the players had no contact with other athletes or competitions.
Charles was different. He was everywhere in Barcelona _ eating,
drinking, going to events, and mingling with fellow-athletes and
Barcelonese. Nobody got more out of their Olympic experience. It is
the same way he lived and played for 16 years in the NBA, and we
will miss him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 0152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MOZAMBIQUE-NYT &LR;      12-11 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MOZAMBIQUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BURYING THE PAST IN MOZAMBIQUE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, December
11:
</P>
<P>
   With little fanfare, seven million Mozambicans went to the polls
over the last weekend to re-elect a president and overhaul a
Parliament. Those elections represented more than a modest
reconfiguration of government in an obscure corner of the globe.
They were welcome evidence of one of the most important if
little-appreciated benefits of the end of white rule in southern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   During the years of protest and repression in South Africa in
the 1980s, the nightmare was that the struggle to bring down
apartheid might degenerate into a race war. No such war came to
pass. But a nightmare did come to pass in neighboring Angola and
Mozambique, where hundreds of thousands died in ruinous civil wars.
</P>
<P>
   In those countries, the combatants and victims on all sides were
black, and little attention was paid. Few understood that blacks
killed blacks in part because of meddlesome behavior by whites in
both South Africa and the country then called Rhodesia, and because
some blacks cynically allowed themselves to be used as instruments
of white tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   In Mozambique, for example, the notorious rebel movement Renamo
was created by the Rhodesian secret police to counter black
nationalist guerrillas fighting Rhodesia's white-settler rule.
Renamo developed a reputation as an African Khmer Rouge, and
between 1977 and 1992 as many as a million Mozambicans died from
fighting and famine in a war that laid waste to the economy and
much of the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   After Rhodesia became independent as Zimbabwe in 1980, Renamo
was inherited by South Africa's military intelligence, which used
it to bludgeon Mozambique into expelling exiled South Africans
aligned with the African National Congress. Although the war
developed local agendas and took on its own momentum, Pretoria
continued to back Renamo until 1990, when President F.W. de Klerk
began clearing the way for the end of white rule.
</P>
<P>
   Angola's war rages on, fueled by diamonds and oil. Mozambique,
remarkably, is at peace. Its war finally ended with a negotiated
settlement in 1992. An election was held in 1994. Mozambique now
has one of the fastest-growing economies in the world. Foreign
investment is flowing in. Tourism is thriving. Inflation is close
to zero.
</P>
<P>
   In October a stock exchange opened in Maputo, the seaside
capital that used to feature billboards proclaiming that
``Imperialism is the enemy of the people'' and still has streets
named for Lenin, Mao and Kim Il Sung. After years of relying on
donated food, Mozambique now grows nearly enough to feed itself.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit goes to President Joaquim Chissano, who
scrapped his ruling Frelimo Party's original collectivist creed
and, with Western backing, has adhered to a program of fiscal
austerity. He is expected to retain the presidency but may lose the
legislature to Renamo, which transformed itself into a loyal
opposition and exploits the issues of corruption and enduring rural
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   One disquieting feature of Mozambique's peace is that there has
been no attempt to hold anyone accountable for the many heinous
crimes committed during the war. There have been no war crimes
trials and nothing like South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation
Commission. But Mozambique deserves continued Western support after
bearing a disproportionate share of suffering for the injustices of
what is thankfully a bygone era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
