<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5934 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-REDWINGS-LA     12-11 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-REDWINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FALL TO RED WINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ It's not hard to see who wears the rings in this
house.
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Bowman has won eight Stanley Cups, including two with the
Detroit Red Wings. His influence over a game sometimes can drive
the little people crazy, and Friday night the little people were
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Andy Murray wasn't about to say that the Los Angeles
Kings' 3-1 loss in front of 19,983 at Joe Louis Arena was the
result of the respect officials have for Bowman's place in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray's hearty postgame charge into the referee's room with
general manager Dave Taylor was a more lasting image than the
absence of captain Rob Blake, who is injured again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying they changed the course of the game or that
Scotty gets calls because of his stature,'' Murray said. ``I have
too much respect for him, the game and its tradition to say
anything like that. But late in a close game, let the players
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray was referring to a slashing penalty on Glen Murray with
4:53 remaining and the Kings mounting one of their few rallies of
the night. They were still trailing 2-1, but with the man
advantage, the Red Wings scored again. Suddenly the Kings were 0-1
in the first of four games on this trip and leading Dallas by just
three points in the Pacific Division.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who has been injured throughout much of his career, is
sidelined with a groin strain and not expected to play tonight in
Montreal. And the Kings already were playing without leading scorer
Ziggy Palffy, who is back in Los Angeles nursing a sore lower back.
It was the first game Blake has missed this season, but a whopping
120 by the team overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly when you are missing top players from your lineup it
is going to take its toll,'' said Glen Murray, who scored the Kings
only goal, his seventh in six games. ``But all you want at the end
of the game is to play. I didn't think I deserved a penalty in that
spot. If I did I shouldn't have been the only one.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Murray acknowledged that the Kings' second line, which did
not take a shot in the first period, was sluggish coming out. Not a
good thing with the first line already missing Jozef Stumpel
(abdominal surgery) and minus Palffy for at least one more game.
</P>
<P>
   But he was happy with the Kings' power play, which entered the
game with just four goals in their last 46 attempts. Aki Berg
assumed Blake's role as point man on the power play and overall
physical presence and played perhaps his best game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And Glen Murray's goal came with the man advantage early in the
second period, beating former Kings goaltender Manny Legace on a
pass from Bryan Smolinski that tied the game 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   But less than a minute later, Steve Yzerman scored his second
goal of the game. The Kings never had an answer for that.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Blake and Palffy, they played even with Detroit the
rest of the way. Which is why they kept wondering why they weren't
give a chance at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman, who recorded his 1,110th career win last month, recently
has been critical of officials.
</P>
<P>
   There was a call on Mattias Norstrom midway through the second
period that many in the Kings locker room thought was undeserved
and shattered momentum.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing compared to the Kings' final penalty. The play began
with a crushing hit by Berg on Pat Verbeek, who got up and struck
Smolinski. Murray admitted he slashed Verbeek, but thought Verbeek
deserved a penalty for whacking Smolinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to give one you have to give the other,'' Glen
Murray said. ``Those things shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With Glen Murray in the penalty box, Vyacheslav Kozlov scored
the final goal.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, Andy Murray always addresses the club after the
game. This time he left the chore to assistant Dave Tippett and
joined Taylor for a lengthy talk with the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that room is generally off limits,'' Murray said.
``And it is always is important to say something to the team. This
was the first time I haven't all season. I wanted the players to
know that I wasn't going to put up with this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
