<HEADER>
A5944 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-MEETINGS-     12-11 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-MEETINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEILE WILL LIKELY SLIP AWAY FROM DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Barring some extraordinary turn of events,
free-agent third baseman Todd Zeile won't be returning to the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile's agent, Seth Levinson, said the Van Nuys native would
sign in the next 48 hours and the Dodgers said they won't make a
decision on what to do about third base until Adrian Beltre's
situation is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a third baseman right now and we're in a holding
pattern until we get a decision from Major League Baseball,''
Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said Friday upon arriving at
the winter meetings. ``We can't do anything because we have a third
baseman. We !ital!have!off! a third baseman. I don't know why
people expect us to go out and get another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, 20, is asking to be declared a free agent because the
Dodgers allegedly signed him at the age of 15, illegal by baseball
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, who just moved to Thousand Oaks, has make clear his
desire to play again for the Dodgers, who traded him in the Mike
Piazza deal to Florida early last season. And the Dodgers front
office likes him so much that one source said new Dodgers chairman
and CEO Robert Daly personally spoke with Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile's most ardent suitor, the Texas Rangers, are offering a
two-year deal with an option for a third year to keep him. Levinson
is scheduled to meet with Rangers general manager Doug Melvin
today. Sources said if Zeile doesn't give an answer by the end of
the weekend, the Rangers would pull the offer back and go with
rookie Mike Lamb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd Zeile will sign this weekend,'' Levinson said. ``He came
to the winter meetings unsigned, and he's leaving signed.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile batted .293 with 24 homers and 98 RBI with Texas last
season, but also made 25 errors.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile may not be the only free agent the Dodgers pass on during
the meetings. It's been mandated that Malone not sign any until
payroll is sliced, and that could mean Terry Shumpert or Kurt
Abbott also sign with other teams before that happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to do what's in their best interest,'' Malone said
of other players. ``They can't wait on us. Some of them have to
make decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have Kevin Orie, acquired last month in a trade with
Florida, but could trade for a third baseman if they lose Beltre. A
combination of Orie, Dave Hansen and Jose Vizcaino could also play
third.
</P>
<P>
   Contract talk: Financially, the Dodgers aren't in position to
negotiate contract extensions with any of their three players _
Eric Karros, Ismael Valdes and Darren Dreifort _ who will be free
agents after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Dodgers can knock payroll off during these meetings,
they may sit down and try to do something with Karros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric's first choice would be to play his whole career in Los
Angeles,'' Jeff Moorad, Karros' agent, said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would only be down if Karros was given a no-trade
clause through the first two years of the contract. After that,
Karros would have veto power of trades as a player with 10 years
major-league experience, including five with his current team.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's likely Dreifort will be more than willing to test
the free-agent market next winter. Valdes remains on the trade
block.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 0213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
