<HEADER>
A5945 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-AVALANCHE-L     12-11 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-AVALANCHE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS BEATEN BY AVALANCHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The once-mighty Colorado Avalanche came into
the Pond on Friday night just another .500 team and were missing
Joe Sakic to boot.
</P>
<P>
   But the Anaheim Mighty Ducks are just another .500 team
themselves and they found out in a 2-1 loss before 13,927 that two
mistakes can still be two too many in today's NHL.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that the Ducks played a bad game _ they actually
turned in one of their more spirited performances of the season.
But one mistake by the penalty killing unit and a soft goal allowed
by Guy Hebert was all Patrick Roy and the Avalanche needed.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado took a 2-0 lead on goals by Chris Drury and Jeff Odgers
and then held on. Ruslan Salei pulled the Ducks within one late in
the second period, but Anaheim couldn't get another by Roy, who
stopped 24 of 25 shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' best shot at tying the game came midway through the
third period when Jeff Nielsen's point-blank shot was stopped Roy,
who was hugging the right post.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, who failed to convert their only power-play chance of
the third period then all but lost any chance of evening things up
when Marty McInnis was hit with a questionable hooking call at
17:57.
</P>
<P>
   But it was major mistakes in the first and second periods that
cost the Ducks dearly.
</P>
<P>
   After killing off 19 consecutive penalties, Anaheim penalty
killers gave the league's best power play one too many chances and
the Ducks paid the price.
</P>
<P>
   Pascal Trepanier had plenty of time to clear the puck, but
failed to do so. Guy Hebert then stopped Milan Hejduk's shot from
the left circle, but after a wild scramble Salei accidently pushed
the rebound under his goalie and right on the stick of Chris Drury.
The Colorado center calmly lifted a shot over the pile at 18:46 for
his eighth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be Odgers' first goal since Dec. 12, 1998 that
would prove to be the real backbreaker. The Ducks, with the help of
two consecutive power plays had dominated the first 5{ minutes,
only to have a harmless looking backhander by Odgers somehow sneak
between Hebert's pads.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne both had great chances early in
the period and Nielsen rang a one-timer off the crossbar less than
a minute before Odgers gave the Avalanche a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks did continue to apply the pressure and their
persistence finally paid off at 15:04 when Salei scored his first
goal since Jan. 1 on a rising shot from the left point. The goal
came after the line of Kariya, Temmu Selanne and Steve Rucchin had
begun to wear down Colorado, a job that the trio of Mike Leclerc,
Tony Hrkac and Nielsen finished off.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Drury's goal, the scoring chances were few and far
between, and the first 10 minutes seemed to be an extension of
Wednesday night's snooze fest with Vancouver. When the game finally
did open up late in the period, nobody could hit the net.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Forsberg sent Brian Rolston in all alone on Hebert, but
the winger whipped it over the top of the net. At the other end,
both McInnis and Kariya were left unattended in the slot, but
neither was able to test Roy with their shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
