<HEADLINE>
MOISO ADMITS HE HAS NBA ON THE BRAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sophomore forward Jerome Moiso leads UCLA in
scoring and rebounding and has, for the moment, established himself
as one of the Pacific-10's top players. The coaches attribute
Moiso's improvement to maturity, but there's a higher calling at
work: the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso, a projected first-round pick, said he's considering
leaving school after this season. Several UCLA sources said Moiso
intends to leave, with injury the lone obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The NBA) is the main reason, I'm not going to lie,'' Moiso
said when asked about his inspired play. ``I've got to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are in a quandary. If Moiso plays well, they probably
will, too. But if he plays well, he'll probably leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the staff we don't want to develop them (Moiso and
center Dan Gadzuric) too quickly, because we don't want them to
leave,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA might be Moiso's primary motivation, but maturity has
clearly aided his performance. Last year, he was tentative on the
court and lacked confidence off it. A native of Guadeloupe who was
educated in France and speaks moderate English, Moiso continually
disparaged himself. He even asked to come off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's more confident, more aggressive, and more
consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new year for him,'' said UCLA assistant coach Jim Saia,
who recruited Moiso. ``He's acclimated socially, he's more
comfortable around the coaching staff and he knows what to
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   And he knows what the NBA scouts like _ and don't like. No one
questions Moiso's skills. He's 6-foot-10, athletic and capable of
scoring from the low post or 3-point line. But he hasn't shown the
aggressiveness needed to compete against NBA power forwards. Scouts
think he's soft, and that a tough tag to shake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have periods where I'm wondering if I should do this
or do that, but I'm more confident more often,'' said Moiso, who's
averaging 16 points and 7.7 rebounds. ``I'm more aggressive more
often. I want to dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lineup update: The Bruins didn't have enough bodies Friday for a
five-on-five scrimmage, so assistant coaches Jim Saia and Michael
Holton suited up.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric rested his tender knees. Guard Ryan Bailey has
tendinitis in his foot and is questionable for today's game against
Gonzaga. JaRon Rush is suspended, and forward Todd Ramasar is out
several months with a shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   The probable starters are Moiso, forwards Jason Kapono and Rico
Hines, and guards Earl Watson and Ray Young.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Gadzuric, forward Sean Farnham and guard Billy
Knight as the lone reserves if Bailey can't play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
