<HEADER>
A5947 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     12-11 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD IS IN GOOD HANDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Sometimes the record makes the man, cloaks
an athlete in history, dresses up the career of an otherwise
unremarkable figure.
</P>
<P>
   You could say Roger Maris set one of those records when he hit
61 home runs. The mark was so much bigger than the player it
practically consumed him.
</P>
<P>
   And then, sometimes, the man makes the record.
</P>
<P>
   Laffit Pincay set one of those records Friday at Hollywood Park
by riding the 8,834th winner of his unbelievable career.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Shoemaker had held one of those records for 29 years before
Pincay. Johnny Longden had held one of those records for 14 years
before Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Why is the record for career victories by a thoroughbred jockey
significant? Because of the greatness of the riders who passed it
down and the greatness of the rider who owns it for the foreseeable
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any feeling about the record,'' Shoemaker said
from his wheelchair after Pincay rode the maiden colt Irish Nip to
victory in the sixth race. ``Any feeling I had was about Laffit
being the one to break it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker, who has always cheered Pincay on, praised his friend
as ``a great family man and a great rider.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, as always, returned the compliment, saying his friend
the Shoe ``is still No. 1 in my book.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact they've played guardian to the record has made 8,834
the most revered number in the world of horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   But the record might not always be in such worthy hands. Its
future is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, 52, has said he aims to get to 9,000 before retiring.
Even if he reaches that milestone, though, it probably won't be too
many years before his record is under assault.
</P>
<P>
   A worthy challenger would be leading Midwestern rider Pat Day,
third on the all-time list, some 1,220 behind Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   But a more likely _ and more controversial _ threat to the
record comes from the San Francisco Bay Area's Russell Baze, eighth
on the list, 2,043 behind Pincay and gaining every day.
</P>
<P>
   Baze is 41-years-old and had been winning at a rate of more than
400 a year at Bay Meadows, Golden Gate Fields and the Northern
California county fair tracks. At that pace, with good health, he'd
catch Pincay in the middle of the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Returning Wednesday, six weeks from a back fracture that was
supposed to sideline him for three months, Baze rode four winners
at Golden Gate to show he's still the King of the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Baze's winners at the lower-quality northern
tracks should count as much as the victories Pincay and Shoemaker
achieved against the nation's toughest competition. And whether a
man who has never sniffed victory in a Triple Crown or Breeders'
Cup race deserves mention alongside them.
</P>
<P>
   Baze, a pleasant man from a family of horsemen, argues firmly
that he wouldn't cheapen the record, that there's nothing wrong
with his sport's unique policy of counting statistics recorded at
minor-league tracks just the same as those earned in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, a win is a win, no matter what kind
of animal it is or where it happens, whether it's Timbuktu or Santa
Anita,'' Baze said on the phone this week. He says anybody calling
his competition second-rate should ``say that to the face of the
guys I'm riding against.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that in the three years he rode against a jockeys'
room full of Hall of Famers and Kentucky Derby winners in Southern
California, he held his own when given worthy horses.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains that Baze had to go back north in 1991, to a
room of far less accomplished jockeys, to attract the daily supply
of favorites he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a pointless debate. Try to distinguish
``legitimate'' and ``illegitimate'' racing records because of the
quality of the competition or any of an infinite number of other
reasons and you'd end up with 8,834 asterisks on the stat sheet.
</P>
<P>
   But thinking about Baze's potential record run helps one to
appreciate what Pincay accomplished in the past 35 years while
rarely straying from the big-league diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact he did it competing against the best, that's pretty
neat,'' trainer Bob Baffert said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It's neat record because it was held by Longden. It's a neat
record because it was held by Shoemaker. Now it's a neat record
because it's held by Pincay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
