<HEADLINE>
KINGS PLACE PALFFY ON INJURED RESERVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Although the Los Angeles Kings are hopeful Ziggy
Palffy can play Tuesday night in New Jersey, they placed him on
injured reserve Friday night so they can add a player to their
depleted roster.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, sidelined since last Saturday with back spasms, was
placed on the seven-day IR to give the Kings options on defense
after Rob Blake could not play Friday because of a strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jaroslav Modry dressed for the game and played 19
minutes and 56 seconds. Newcomer Jere Karalahti made the trip, but
did not play.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, who leads the club in scoring with 26 points, remains in
Los Angeles undergoing physical therapy at the club's Iceoplex
training facility. He has skated for 10 minutes each of the past
two days and is scheduled to rejoin the team Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still up in the air,'' Kings coach Andy Murray said.
``He hasn't skated much and definitely not with the team. We're
hoping for Tuesday, but it is hard to say right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Payback for Manny: Former Kings goaltender Manny Legace recorded
his second victory for the Red Wings. He faced only 16 shots in the
first two periods, but withstood 12 shots in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Legace, who defeated Nashville 6-3 Wednesday, was the Kings'
starting goalie last season after Jamie Storr and Stephane Fiset
went out with injuries just seven minutes apart in the fourth game
of the year. The Kings won just two of the next 16 games and never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings tried to re-sign Legace during the off-season, but
with Storr and Fiset returning, Legace opted for free agency and
signed with Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset getting close: Murray thought injured goalie Fiset might
be ready to back up Storr tonight in Montreal. But Fiset, out five
weeks with a deep bone bruised yo his right hand, isn't ready even
though Friday's workout went well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first one with the team,'' Fiset said. ``I took a
couple shots off the hand and it felt OK. I think the guys were a
little nervous shooting at it than I was. It felt OK and I could
squeeze the stick better. That is the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Cousineau, who replaced Fiset on the roster Nov. 6,
remains the backup.
</P>
<P>
   Luc stays: Luc Robitaille will remain in his native Montreal
after the team leaves Saturday night to be part of a ceremony to
retire his junior hockey jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille wore No. 15 for nearby Hull, Quebec for three years
and had 68 goals and 123 assist for 191 points during the 1985-86
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty special,'' said Robitaille, who will rejoin the
Kings on Monday in New Jersey. ``It has been a while since I was
there, so it's going to be fun to go back Sunday. I was quite
surprised when they called me. It's quite an honor to have your
jersey up in a building.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
