<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-AVALANCHE-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS BEATEN BY AVALANCHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The once-mighty Colorado Avalanche came into
Friday night's game just another .500 team, struggling without the
services of captain Joe Sakic.
</P>
<P>
   But the Anaheim Mighty Ducks are just another .500 team
themselves and they found out in a 2-1 loss before 13,927 at the
Pond that two mistakes can still be two too many against a team
that still has Peter Forsberg and Patrick Roy.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that the Ducks played poorly _ they actually turned in
a spirited performance over the last 50 minutes. But the penalty
killing unit's failure to clear a puck against the NHL's No.
1-ranked power play and a soft goal allowed by the normally
reliable Guy Herbert doomed the Ducks and sent them back to .500
(13-13-4-1) for the 11th time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played a pretty good game,'' said Ducks coach
Craig Hartsburg. ``But we need to get some momentum going early,
force the tempo of the game, instead of waiting for the other team
to dictate the game to us. We can't wait until we get behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado (14-13-3-1) took a 2-0 lead on goals by Chris Drury and
Jeff Odgers and then held on. Ruslan Salei pulled the Ducks within
one late in the second period, but Anaheim couldn't get another by
Roy, who stopped 24 of 25 shots and tied Hall of Famer Tony
Esposito for third on the NHL all-time victory list by goalies with
423.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, especially Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne, seemed to
be one step away from scoring all night. But the Avalanche blocked
several great chances at the defense and its defensemen were always
there to clear away the few rebounds Roy left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had scoring chances, but we didn't get second or third
opportunities,'' said Kariya of the Ducks, who outshot Colorado,
25-20. ``It was always one shot and clear.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Pascal Trepanier's failure to clear the puck that put
the Ducks behind the eight-ball at 18:46 of the first period. The
Anaheim defenseman had plenty of time to clear the zone, but
couldn't do so and within seconds Drury scored over a pileup in
front of the Ducks' net.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do that you give them a second chance,'' Hartsburg
said. ``And when a good power play gets a second chance it usually
burns you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert stopped Milan Hejduk's shot from the left circle, but
after a scramble Salei accidentally pushed the rebound under his
goalie and right to Drury, who ended Anaheim's penalty-killing
streak at 19.
</P>
<P>
   Odgers' first goal since Dec. 12, 1998 proved to be the real
backbreaker. The Ducks, with the help of two consecutive power
plays, had dominated the first 5{ minutes, only to have a
harmless-looking backhander by Odgers somehow sneak between
Hebert's pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a great goal,'' Hartsburg said. ``It was
unfortunate since he has played so well lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya and Selanne both had great chances to tie the game early
in the second period and Jeff Nielsen rang a one-timer off the
crossbar less than a minute before Odgers scored at 5:44.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks did continue to apply the pressure and their
persistence finally paid off at 15:04 when Salei scored his first
goal since Jan. 1 on a rising shot from the left point. The goal
came after the line of Kariya, Selanne and Steve Rucchin had begun
to wear down Colorado, a job that the trio of Mike Leclerc, Tony
Hrkac and Nielsen finished off.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Drury's goal, the scoring chances were few and far
between, and the first 10 minutes seemed to be an extension of
Wednesday night's snoozefest with Vancouver. When the game finally
did open up late in the period, nobody could hit the net.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Forsberg sent Brian Rolston in all alone on Hebert, but
the winger whipped it over the top of the net. At the other end,
both Marty McInnis and Kariya were left unattended in the slot, but
neither was able to test Roy with their shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get the puck on net before you can score,'' said
Hartsburg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
