<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ARYAN-FAMILY-2NDTAKE-     12-11 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARYAN-FAMILY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: People's Republic.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1994, when Chevie was 21, Kirby and Gloria Kehoe moved their
family to Kingston, Ark., in the Ozarks. There, they became friends
with a gun dealer, William Mueller, and his wife, Nancy. They
traveled the same gun show circuit, shared anti-government views,
and identified with the Christian Identity religion.
</P>
<P>
   But friendship did not stand in the way of profit. In January
1995, Kirby and Chevie Kehoe burglarized the Muellers' home in
Tilly, Ark., and took thousands of dollars' worth of guns and gold
and silver coins.
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe then returned to Washington, on the way stopping at
Elohim City, a Christian Identity community in Oklahoma, where he
asked an escaped convict, Faron Lovelace, to accompany him for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   On June 12, 1995, Kirby and Chevie Kehoe mounted another
fund-raising operation in Colville, Wash., sending Lovelace into
the home of two well-to-do grocery store owners, Malcolm and
Jillian Friedman. Lovelace later said he targeted the Friedmans
because he thought they were Jewish and would be easy to kill if
something went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Lovelace held Friedman hostage and ordered Mrs. Friedman to go
out and collect cash. Then he forced the Friedmans to go to
Spokane, where he set them free.
</P>
<P>
   The money from the Arkansas and Washington crimes went to buy
land near Priest River, Idaho, where Chevie Kehoe planned to set up
a training camp for revolutionaries, prosecutors in his trial said.
</P>
<P>
   By winter, the money was gone, and knowing that William Mueller
had come into a $50,000 inheritance, Chevie Kehoe decided to rob
him again. This time, his accomplice was Danny Lee, a skinhead from
Oklahoma with lightning bolts tattooed on his neck. Lee was known
as ``Cyclops'' because he had lost an eye in a bar fight.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 11, 1996, Kehoe and Lee, disguised as federal agents,
broke into the Muellers' home and waited for the family to return.
It was almost summer by the time the remains of the family _ the
father, mother and 8-year-old daughter, Sarah _ were found in the
Illinois Bayou near Russellville. A woman who was fishing hooked a
shoe and a bone.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kehoe later told investigators that her son told her about
his role in the Mueller murders shortly after the crime, but that
she kept quiet. That July 1996, the Kehoe family had moved to
another remote home, in Yaak, Mont. Cheyne and his wife and son
lived nearby until that winter, when Chevie came to get them. The
two brothers and their families drove south together to look for
work in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyne knew nothing about the murders until they were traveling
together and Chevie began selling guns because they could not find
work. At that point his brother told him, Cheyne later told
investigators, because some of the guns had been stolen from the
Muellers.
</P>
<P>
   By then, investigators were tracing other Mueller guns to the
Kehoes. Shortly after the family disappeared, the pistol from an
empty gun box found in the house was recovered at a Seattle pawn
shop and traced to Kirby Kehoe. Months later, another Mueller gun,
an AR-15 rifle, was recovered from Sean Haines, a former Aryan
Nations youth leader. It had been sold by Chevie Kehoe.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers' luck ran out as they traveled through Ohio, where
a state trooper stopped them for driving with expired plates.
Chevie broke away from being searched because he was carrying a
gun, and Cheyne opened fire. The ensuing gun battle, caught on
videotape by a camera on the trooper's dashboard, was broadcast
nationwide. But both brothers escaped.
</P>
<P>
   With help from their parents, the brothers and their families
escaped to Utah, where the men found work under assumed names. But
according to Cheyne Kehoe and his wife, Tanna, Chevie's behavior
became more violent and erratic. When Chevie said he was thinking
of killing his parents so he could raise his younger brothers
himself, Cheyne decided he had to be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyne surrendered on June 16, 1997. The next day, using his
information, the FBI arrested Chevie Kehoe.
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe was charged with federal racketeering counts that
included the three murders. At his trial in Little Rock this year,
the principal witnesses for the prosecution were his brother Cheyne
and his mother, Gloria.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Gloria Kehoe had called the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms and said her husband had struck her and pointed an
AR-15 rifle at her. ``My husband was going to kill me,'' she said.
``I knew too much. I wanted my nightmare to be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria and Cheyne Kehoe told the jury that Chevie Kehoe
confessed to them that he and Danny Lee had surprised the Muellers,
handcuffed the parents, stunned them with an electric stun gun and
taped plastic bags over their heads to suffocate. Then they had
forced 8-year-old Sarah to tell them where her parents' valuables
were hidden. Then, when Danny Lee said he could not kill a child,
Chevie Kehoe killed her.
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe was sentenced to three life terms. Lee was
sentenced to death. Cheyne had been sentenced to 24 years for the
Ohio shootout, and Kirby Kehoe had been sentenced to 44 months in
prison after pleading guilty to racketeering charges and admitting
he belonged to his son's white supremacist organization.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe said afterward that his mother's testimony
shattered him. ``What more powerful witness can you put on the
stand than a person's mother?'' he asked. He said he told himself:
``It's not Mom up there. It's somebody I don't know. Mom wouldn't
do this to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He contended that his mother, with six sons still at home,
agreed to testify because she was afraid the government would
prosecute her for tax evasion in the sale of the family's property
in Arkansas, where she had used a false Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her husband was in prison,'' Chevie Kehoe said. ``My brother
was in prison. I'm in prison. If she's in prison, where do her six
children go? I was the sacrifice to save my other brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In August, when Kirby Kehoe was sentenced, Judge G. Thomas
Eisele of U.S. District Court said he was sorry that sentencing
guidelines would not let him impose a longer sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're dealing with here is the man who is the father of
Chevie Kehoe, the man who raised Chevie Kehoe,'' he said. Although
Kirby Kehoe was not responsible for all his son's deeds, Eisele
said, ``he was a major factor in his son's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe put it this way: ``I'm the one left at the end of
the chain of these people's beliefs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5957 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SCHOOLS-CHEATING-REVI     12-11 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-CHEATING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEATING ON TESTS: THE HIGHER THE STAKES, THE GREATER THE
TEMPTATION? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, investigators in New York City said they had
uncovered the most widespread public-school cheating scandal in the
nation, encompassing 32 schools, dozens of teachers and two
principals. The methods _ from teachers using palm cards to
overzealous test coaching _ were so varied and so widespread that
they might only be the tip of the iceberg, investigators contended.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same sort of thing occurred recently in Texas, where
school officials and politicians like Gov. George W. Bush were
brandishing the results of a standardized test to claim victory
over ignorance. There, too, a cheating scandal has erupted which
calls some of the achievement into doubt.
</P>
<P>
   While officials trumpet higher scores, it also appears that an
old staple of education is gaining ground: cheating. And it is not
just students who are the culprits, but adults: the teachers,
principals, superintendents and other administrators charged with
watching over them.
</P>
<P>
   This rash of dishonesty has spread at the same time that
superintendents and politicians across the country have set tough
new test-score targets for their school systems. A ``standards''
revolution is sweeping through the classroom, tying promotion and
graduation of students and even cash bonuses for everyone from
principals to cafeteria workers to measurable achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The current scandals have emboldened critics who question the
validity of standardized testing, in particular high-stakes,
high-pressure tests tied to promotion and graduation. And they have
sharpened the argument over whether it is possible to have
accountability without some form of testing.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the spectrum are organizations like Fair Test,
based in Boston, a group that monitors testing abuses and has been
a staunch critic of the testing industry. They see the new
accountability measures _ from publishing test scores in local
newspapers to state takeovers of failing schools _ as a way of
encouraging abuses. ``It's sort of like the Soviet Union; everybody
ends up lying,'' said Monty Neill, executive director of Fair Test.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-test groups oppose even the newest tests, which require
children to organize their ideas into a coherent essay and, in
math, ask them to explain their reasoning, not just present
answers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the fence are educators and scholars like
Diane Ravitch, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, who
passionately defends testing. ``To say that tests create cheating
is wrong,'' Dr. Ravitch said. ``What creates cheating is people who
cheat. If we spent as much time teaching kids as showing them the
answer, they might have learned to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of standards, tests and stark consequences for
failing to meet them _ like withholding high school diplomas _ say
that for too long, an officially sanctioned system of low
expectations has consigned many poor and disadvantaged children to
a second-class education.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about how hard it is to raise test scores, it
sounds like you are defending current practice,'' says Seymour
Fliegel, president of the Center for Educational Innovation in New
York City. New tests that require 9-year-olds to write essays with
correct spelling, grammar and punctuation are a far cry from the
multiple choice bubbles of the past, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea that kids should be able to find a main idea;
that they should know how to find supporting details; how to draw
an inference, vocabulary,'' Fliegel said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is evidence that testing has always encouraged
cheating, at least where the stakes were high enough.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Haney, a professor at the Center for the Study of Testing
at Boston College, points out that the current debate is following
a pattern established in 19th century England. A program called
``Payment by Results'' reigned in English and Welsh elementary
schools from 1862 to 1897. Every student was examined annually by a
royal inspector, and teachers received government grants if their
students performed well. Among the results were that teachers
school-hopped, looking for positions that would pay better.
</P>
<P>
   There were also complaints that teachers tried to get copies of
arithmetic questions used in other schools, and then drilled their
students in them, in the hope of raising test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Test preparation is one of those ethical gray areas, where the
line between what is legitimate and illegitimate may be ill
defined. In fact, many school districts not only sanction test
preparation but spend large portions of their budgets paying for
it.
</P>
<P>
   The public schools have embarked on a new mission _ or at least
begun a new fad. Suddenly, teachers and students are expected to
produce results. But the reality is that real change and real
progress in the schools is hard to produce and takes time. Cheating
may be one of the unintended consequences of the increasing
reliance on standardized tests and the pressure to perform better,
fast.
</P>
<P>
   That is one motivation behind the accusations in New York and
Texas. Last January, the Texas Education Agency sent letters to
Houston and 10 other school districts saying that an analysis of
test results showed that unusually high numbers of wrong answers
had been erased and replaced with correct ones. In April, the
county attorney in Austin charged the city's school district and a
top administrator with test tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials have publicized statistics showing a narrowing
achievement gap between white students, who typically score higher,
and blacks and Hispanics. But in a legal challenge to the tests, an
expert witness has testified that 10th-grade test scores among
black and Hispanic children have been inflated by holding back
those who are failing, so they are not counted in the results.
</P>
<P>
   Even when tests are conducted honestly and scores do go up
sharply, it is often for reasons that have little to do with
improvements in teaching or learning. More commonly, the big jumps
_ what statisticians call statistical outliers _ betray something
more insidious at work: a new magnet program that attracts more
affluent or gifted students, perhaps, or test preparation mania.
Ultimately, standardized tests are probably most useful in
measuring the improvement, or decline, of an educational system
over an extended period of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
