   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ With a week to go before Russia
elects its next parliament, and rushes headlong toward next
summer's presidential election, the national political debate can
be summed up in two words: mud and war. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MIGRANTS (Beijing) _ Tens of millions of rural Chinese
have moved to cities in search of a better life, but are consigned
by law and social practice to second-class citizenship. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-IRAQ-WEAPONS (United Nations) _ The Security Council is
expected to vote, probably sometime Saturday, on a new plan to set
up a monitoring system for Iraq's weapons programs. The outcome
right now is hard to call. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   BALKANS-WAR-SUSPECTS (Washington) _ As NATO peacekeeping troops
enter their fifth year on patrol in Bosnia, dozens of Bosnians
accused of genocide, rape and other war crimes have not only eluded
capture, but are reported to live openly with little fear of
arrest. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Dateline to come) _ Developments in the
fighting between Russian troops and Islamic militants in the
breakaway republic. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF-REPORT (United Nations) _ The U.N. Children's Fund is to
issue a report Monday on the welfare of children, and it is
expected to conclude that they are worse off in many places at the
end of the century than at its beginning. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-FREE-SPEECH (Winnipeg, Manitoba) _ Increasingly in
Canada, unpopular speech is illegal speech, and new laws aimed at
stifling remarks that could be construed as insensitive or
offensive are running up against others protecting freedom of
expression. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL (Washington) _ Curtainraiser on handover of the
canal, with historical background and political explanation of how
it's being played politically. Clinton steers clear while
conservatives raise their hackles. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-RACISM (Salvador, Brazil) _ A spate of complaints about
blatant discrimination, focusing on the famed pre-Lenten
celebration of Carnival, is challenging this predominantly black
city's cherished image of itself as a model of racial harmony. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S.-NUKES (Undated) _ Newly declassified documents show
that while the United States publicly vowed not to keep nuclear
weapons in Japan, it secretly stored them not only on Okinawa but
also on the islands of Chichi Jima and Iwo Jima and was prepared to
do the same at as many as 11 other Japanese sites. By Judith
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   E.U.-MILITARY (Paris) _ By equipping itself with the ability to
send up to 60,000 troops to a crisis zone like Bosnia or Kosovo,
the 15-nation European Union will finally become a strategic player
the United States will have to reckon with, say French defense
officials, who have long chafed under American military and
strategic dominance. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-TUDJMAN (Zagreb, Croatia) _ As the body of its
president, Franjo Tudjman, lay in state at the presidential palace
Saturday, Croatia declared three days of mourning, canceling
sporting events and shutting down movie theaters. Tudjman's death
at 77, from stomach cancer, was announced at 2 a.m. Saturday on
state television. By Stephen Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-EUROPE (Istanbul) _ Turks woke up Saturday feeling a bit
closer to Europe. Few could say exactly what that meant, but nearly
everyone seemed to like it. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT-WOMEN (Kuwait) _ The depth of a division over a historic
proposition that would have made this tiny Persian Gulf country the
first among its close neighbors to grant full political rights to
women has left Kuwait a split society, and the ballot's defeat left
little doubt about which side retains the political upper hand. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
