<P>
   ANTIOCH-WOMEN-RUGBY (Yellow Springs, Ohio) _ At a famously
liberal college that has not had a sports team in decades, a new
women's rugby club has attracted an enthusiastic following. The
team is called the Antioch Radicals. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   ARYAN-FAMILY (Undated) _ Chevie Kehoe, who became one of the
nation's most notorious white supremacists by age 23, talks in
prison about his formative years growing up in a militantly
anti-government family. Sometimes parents get what they want:
murderous, racist sons. By Jo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   FIREFIGHTERS-HEROES (Rockford, Ill.) _ The emotional tribute on
Thursday in Worcester, Mass., for the six firefighters who died in
a warehouse blaze showed the depth of respect and reverence that
Americans maintain for the people who answer their calls for help.
It was a response that even tragedy seldom evokes. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   BOY-ALONE (Memphis) _ On Monday, a family friend who stopped by
the East Memphis apartment where Travis Butler lived discovered
that the 9-year-old had been staying there alone for a month with
his mother lying dead on the living room floor. The boy did not
tell anyone about her death, he said, because he was afraid he
would have to go to a foster home. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Fort Campbell, Ky.) _ Life on an Army base after
an 18-year-old private is convicted of beating a gay soldier to
death with a baseball bat. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
