<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5961 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-MIGRANTS-ART-2T     12-11 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MIGRANTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BEIJING, BIAS AGAINST RURAL MIGRANTS IS SUFFERED BY THEIR
CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ By some measures, the Xingzhi primary school in
western Beijing is a huge success. Started in 1994 with just nine
students, it now has 1,266 students from all over the country, and
had to turn away hundreds of applicants this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Its founder, Li Shumei, and her husband, Yi Benyao, who both
moved here from a dead-end town in central China, have taken this
private school from a hut in a vegetable patch to the converted
grounds of a paint factory in just five years. While its classrooms
may be crowded and a bit shabby, the sing-song recitations and the
happy riot at recess testify to real school spirit.
</P>
<P>
   But the school is unlicensed and illegal, and its booming growth
attests to one of China's most enduring social tensions: the
degrading treatment of the tens of millions of rural Chinese who
seek better lives in the cities but are consigned by law and habit
to second-class citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Li, 38, and Yi, 37, run their school on a shoestring, trying
to provide education for some of Beijing's 100,000 children of
so-called migrant workers _ most of whom are actually long-term
residents of the city whose work in construction, vending, garbage
collecting and other low-end jobs is vital to the city's life.
</P>
<P>
   Schooling is supposed to be compulsory for Chinese children, and
cities are supposed to make sure migrant children get an education.
Beijing and other cities have complied with the letter of the law _
by allowing migrant children to attend public schools if they pay
stiff fees that few can afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely not fair, but we all feel there's nothing we
can do about it,'' said Yi, whose school _ named, hopefully, after
a famous early 20th century educator _ gets no government aid. More
than once, the school has been driven off a new site by police.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, according to one recent survey by
government researchers, more than 100 unlicensed schools, most of
them much smaller than Xingzhi and some run by people with no more
than a junior high school education, have sprung up in Beijing. The
educational plight of the migrant children is so acute that some
official newspapers have carried exposes, and students and faculty
members from teacher colleges have given volunteer help.
</P>
<P>
   A horrified journalist, chronicling a visit to an especially
desolate migrant school for The Beijing Youth Daily, was stunned to
see how far removed from the mainstream the children were.
``Suddenly,'' the writer noted, ``I realized that they were not
wearing the red scarf,'' the near-ubiquitous Young Pioneer kerchief
that is obligatory for Chinese schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the reporter added, these pupils were ``luckier than the
children still playing in the vegetable markets every day.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of the 3 million or so migrants in Beijing are single
and work here temporarily, a growing number stay on for years, if
not for good. Lacking the treasured permanent residence
certificate, they must annually prove that they have a job and
apply for new temporary permits. Others, unable to obtain the
needed papers, must dodge the periodic police sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   The country's system of residential permits was originally
established by the Communist government to control the movements of
people and prevent the growth of vast urban shantytowns. Now, in a
freer society and a fast-developing economy that demands labor
mobility, it appears increasingly outdated, and the authorities
seem to be at a loss to cope with a ``floating population'' that
may surpass 100 million people nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   For China's leaders, the permit system still serves a crucial
political purpose: It protects urban workers from competition that
would push down wages and spread both unemployment and the urban
worker unrest that the authorities most fear.
</P>
<P>
   The legalized privileges of official urban residents, who make
up less than one-third of the national population, seem certain to
rankle more and more in the years ahead, especially after China
enters the World Trade Organization and opens up markets for
agricultural products. The new global competition is expected to
kill off marginal producers and force farming to become more
efficient _ driving more rural people to search for work in the
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The migrants already face a raft of prejudices. They are blamed
in official residents' everyday conversations for virtually all of
Beijing's crime, crowding and dirt. Even in official discourse,
they are invariably referred to as ``outsiders,'' and social mixing
with permanent residents is rare. Many migrants live in illegally
built rented rooms, subject to demolition during crackdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But the discrimination is more than cultural. To protect the
incomes of natives, some cities, including Beijing, have legally
banned the hiring of nonresidents for many jobs above the lower
rungs.
</P>
<P>
   An article in The Economic Daily this month stated baldly:
``Workers without an urban residence permit suffer from general
social discrimination. They are not only treated unequally in
wages, housing, medical care, unemployment insurance and schooling
for their children, they also face the risk of being fired at any
time.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Li and Yi are trying to make the best of a bad situation.
Ms. Li, a former teacher in their home province of Henan, was
working in a Beijing street market in 1994 when some relatives'
children needed schooling. She started with just nine children, but
was soon besieged by other migrant parents.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1995, with enrollment at 50 and rising, her
husband moved from Henan to become principal of the expanding
school. They were finally able to rent the former paint factory off
a litter-strewn alley through the $10,000 gift of a
Chinese-American in Los Angeles who had read about their struggles
in a newspaper for Chinese overseas. They have transformed the
factory into something approaching a school, with classrooms
surrounding a well-used exercise yard, and have rented a separate
building for teaching fifth- and sixth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   But the budget, built from the grateful payments of migrants who
want their children to have a chance at better lives, remains
paltry. ``We are eating next year's food to get by this year,'' Yi
said. ``We can barely manage.''
</P>
<P>
   The tuition for each child is $36 per semester, plus $7 for
books. Adding up to $86 per year, this is just feasible for the
workers, who are often earning less than $100 a month.
</P>
<P>
   To attend public schools nearby on the outskirts of Beijing,
migrant applicants must pay special fees of at least $360 per year,
as well as the $80 for books and fees that official residents pay.
In the city center, all these fees can be much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Yi is the first to admit that a lower budget takes a toll. Only
one-fourth of the school's teachers are certified, teaching classes
with more than 50 children each _ ``but we still have to reject so
many students who want to come in,'' he said. Only with volunteer
teachers can nonbasic subjects like art and music be taught.
</P>
<P>
   The school uses some of the same textbooks as the public
schools, and gives the same final exams as a way to check on
progress. In the early grades, the migrant children at Xingzhi do
just about as well as public school students, Yi said, but by fifth
grade they are falling behind.
</P>
<P>
   Since the school is not certified, even the best students may
not be able to gain entry to high school. A few cities in China
have begun to give accreditation to similar migrant schools, Yi
said, but in Beijing, he added, the response to numerous
applications has been, ``be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Without any legal status, the school was driven out of several
previous locations by developers or the police. The education
department still refuses to license the school, but with the help
of some well-connected sympathizers, Xinzhi has obtained tenuous
permission from the police to keep operating at the factory site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the students and the teachers constantly worry that this
school may be closed down,'' Yi said. ``They always feel ill at
ease, and it's not good for either of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the biggest obstacles to educational progress, Yi
said, may be a less tangible one, resulting from the pervasive
ostracism and ridicule of poor, rural migrants in the big city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids feel they must be inferior to the public school
kids,'' he said. ``We spend a lot of time telling the students that
they don't have to feel inferior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
