<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRAZIL-RACISM-ART-2TA     12-11 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-RACISM-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL CARNIVAL'S FABLED AMITY MAY HIDE BIGOTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALVADOR, Brazil _ To outsiders, this alluring port city of 2
million appears to be a model of racial harmony, a place where
blacks and whites can mingle and marry without friction. Its
residents have long prided themselves on that image, propagated by
the novels of Jorge Amado and countless Brazilian pop songs, and
made it a promotional tool for their booming tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   But now a spate of complaints of blatant racial discrimination
has sparked court cases and a municipal investigation, forcing a
re-examination of that cherished belief. Even worse, the focal
point of the furor is the famed pre-Lenten Carnival in this
predominantly black city, an annual festival in which all barriers
and inhibitions are supposed to melt away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows racism exists here, but when you go to talk
about it, no one wants to recognize it exists, much less recognize
that it is structural,'' said Juca Ferreira, the city councilman
who initiated the official investigation. ``The myth of racial
democracy is so strongly ensconced here that it has become an
instrument of social hypocrisy and stratification, which is
precisely why we need to undertake this exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began just before last February's celebrations,
when a pair of college friends, Venusemar Andrade and Adriana
Marambaia, went to sign up to parade in a Carnival club called A
Barca, which has about 2,000 members. Miss Andrade is black, Miss
Marambaia white; Miss Andrade's application to join was rejected
without explanation, while Miss Marambaia was immediately admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Miss Marambaia recalled in an interview here, a
leader of the club, one of more than 100 ``blocos'' who enroll
revelers in return for fees of up to $300, approached her and said:
``Are you crazy? Blacks can't join this bloc.'' Another, whom she
has known since childhood, scolded her, asking, ``How many more
darkies are you planning to bring around?''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Andrade said she was ``shocked, hurt and wounded'' when she
learned the reason for her exclusion and decided to file a criminal
complaint of racial discrimination against the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't remain silent, because it was a question of honor,
not just for me, but for all black people,'' she said. ``As a
citizen and a consumer, I have the right not to be blocked by my
color.''
</P>
<P>
   Her tenacity has since spurred other blacks to come forward to
complain of incidents of prejudice and bigotry during Carnival,
which rolls around again in early March.
</P>
<P>
   In another court case, a black teacher married to a white man
was prevented from joining her lighter-skinned child at a ball when
a private security officer grabbed her by the arm, her complaint
alleges, and said, ``Look at this blackie trying to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the club that turned down Miss Andrade deny any
violation of Brazil's 1997 antiracism statute, and her case has
only begun to wind its way through the country's notoriously slow
court system. But her suit has already brought about changes:
nearly 40 of the principal clubs have signed a ``code of conduct''
that severely limits their right to reject applicants and requires
a published explanation, which can be appealed, if they do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnival reflects the way this city feels and thinks about
itself, and so this is a decisive moment for us,'' said Lidivaldo
Britto, a special government prosecutor who is in charge of
pursuing all complaints of racism here. ``It is high time we
resolve this question so that the black majority can begin to fully
partake in and enjoy all aspects of civic life.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But nothing about race in Brazil is ever as simple as black and
white, beginning with those categories themselves. In contrast to
the United States, where a person with even a trace of African
heritage is almost always considered black, Brazil considers itself
a racial rainbow, with more than 60 terms to designate shades of
skin color. They range from ``preto'' for someone as dark as Pele
to ``brancarao'' for an extremely light-skinned person of mixed
race.
</P>
<P>
   Given that flexibility, many Brazilians who in the United States
would be regarded as black prefer not to classify themselves as
such. The majority of the country's 165 million people may have
some degree of African descent _ even President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso claims a black ancestor _ but they often choose to identify
themselves with vaguer, all-purpose designations like ``moreno,''
or brown-skinned.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Usually, as the court cases here suggest, being lighter-skinned
brings with it more privileges. But now the city's traditional,
white-run blocs are complaining vehemently that they are being
discriminated against and are victims of a double standard, since
Ile Aiye, the main ``bloco Afro,'' as some 20 black Carnival groups
are called, continues to be allowed to forbid the entry of whites.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at Ile Aiye's headquarters in a working-class
neighborhood on the outskirts of town, Antonio Carlos dos Santos, a
founder of the 25-year-old group and its current president,
acknowledged that such a restriction exists. But he was
unapologetic, saying the group was a private cultural association
rather than a public business and therefore entitled to choose its
members.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We formed this group as a reaction to the separation of the
races, to the perverse cultural apartheid that exists here, and we
are not going to give up our black-only policy until we achieve our
objectives and prejudice no longer exists,'' he said. ``If we let
whites and foreigners join, do you think that is going to improve
conditions in the neighborhood or get the police to change their
attitude toward blacks?''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the tensions between white and black clubs also have
to do with the color of money. Carnival here has been transformed
in recent years from a casual neighborhood-focused event into a big
business, with supermarket chains, beverage distributors and
cellular telephone companies paying $250,000 or more to underwrite
the best-known clubs and their balls and parades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnival is the epicenter of the entire musical and cultural
economy, with everyone wanting exposure so that their name gets
known in the media and their songs get publicized and played on the
radio,'' Ferreira explained. ``It has become a real industry.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, there is fierce competition among the groups to
be able to parade during nationwide prime-time television
broadcasts, when corporate sponsors are likely to have their
affiliation seen by the largest number of people, especially
middle-class revelers who might want to travel here in the future
and enroll in their favorite club. But in contrast to most
Brazilian cities, the order in which the groups parade here is not
determined by a draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year after year, the same old blocos have a monopoly on prime
time,'' dos Santos complained. ``The Afro blocs, like us and Olodum
and Filhos de Gandhi, we always end up going out at two or three in
the morning, and so it is hard to attract sponsors, a lot of whom
in any case seem to think that black people don't buy cell phones
or refrigerators.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the annual three-month run-up to the Carnival festivities
beginning, both black and white clubs are already busy designing
their costumes and floats and rehearsing the songs they will be
singing.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Britto said he expects ``we will not have a problem
with discrimination, because society has been mobilized.'' But Miss
Andrade, who started the whole furor, seemed less confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, the clubs are all going to be more cautious from now on,
because they have been given a good scare,'' she said. ``But the
problem doesn't end on Ash Wednesday. I know, for instance, that
when I go into certain boutiques to shop for clothes, I am still
going to have trouble getting salesclerks to wait on me, and it
will be because I am black.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
