</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKS SEE THEIR DESTINY IN CLOSER TIES WITH EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Turks woke up Saturday feeling a bit closer
to Europe. Few could say exactly what that meant, but nearly
everyone seemed to like it.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit flew to Helsinki, Finland, where
leaders of the 15-nation European Union were concluding a summit
meeting. There, at an afternoon ceremony, he saw Turkey declared
``a candidate state destined to join the union on the basis of the
same criteria as applied to the other candidate states.''
</P>
<P>
   That declaration vindicated a dream that has been on the minds
of growing numbers of Turks for nearly 200 years. It was as strong
a statement of Turkey's European vocation as any European power has
ever made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision carries great importance for Turkey,'' Ecevit
said before boarding his plane to Helsinki. ``It is now understood
that there can be no Europe without Turkey and no Turkey without
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am of the opinion that our preparations for full membership
will take place much faster than expected,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit flew to Helsinki, however, only after the European
Union's senior security official, Javier Solana, had traveled to
Ankara late on Friday to meet and reassure Turkish leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In its carefully worded invitation, the European Union reminded
Turkey that it admits only countries that ``share the values and
objectives of the union.'' It stressed that applicants are screened
``with particular reference to the issue of human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey will have to undertake sweeping political and economic
reforms if it hopes to have a realistic chance of joining Europe's
powerful trading bloc. Yet that prospect seems to have wide
political support, even within the ruling elite.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit considers himself a nationalist of the left, and Deputy
Prime Minister Devlet Bahceli heads a party that has for decades
embodied nationalism of the right. The fact that the coalition
government is now embracing Europe's offer reflects the breadth of
political consensus on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday the largest Turkish newspaper, Hurriyet, carried a
banner headline reading ``First Muslim Candidate!'' Its lead
article declared, ``Turkey, which has been trying for two centuries
to integrate with Western civilization, has taken a historic
step.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hurriyet columnist, Cuneyt Ulsever, predicted in a television
commentary that the pace of political reform would now start to
quicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must admit that this nation is unable to make reforms on
its own,'' Ulsever said. ``It always changes under external
pressure. Once we sign the candidacy document, we will have to be
open to every form of monitoring. In the years to come, Turkey will
be under a microscope. Much will be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers that serve observant Muslims and Kurdish
nationalists, two groups that have complained of government
repression, hailed the decision from Helsinki. They said Turkey
would have to begin tolerating forms of speech and expression that
are currently illegal.
</P>
<P>
   While some Turks hoped the Helsinki deal would lead to a
loosening of the political system, others worried about its impact
on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of Greece, European Union leaders suggested
that they would impose two conditions on Turkey as it moves toward
membership. Turkey may have to submit its disputes with Greece to
the International Court of Justice in The Hague, Netherlands, and
might someday have to stand by and watch the ethnic Greek regime on
Cyprus join the European Union, without the ethnically Turkish
north.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit brushed aside suggestions that these were harsh
conditions, but they provoked a flurry of protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey is being asked to pay a heavy price,'' said Kamran
Inan, chairman of the foreign affairs committee in Parliament.
``This statement is brokered to serve the interests of Greece, not
Turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Those views seemed in the minority, however, as Turks looked
forward to what could become a period of reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in Europe want this to succeed,'' said one
European ambassador. ``They want to show the Muslim world that a
country can prosper by being democratic and pro-Western. Their
dream is that people in a place like Libya will notice what's
happening and maybe start to think, `This is the way to go.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5967 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-RIGHTS-REVIE     12-11 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-RIGHTS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHNYA: THE NO MAN'S LAND IN THE FIGHT FOR HUMAN RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grozny means ``terrible'' in Russian, and the capital of
Chechnya is once again living up to its name.
</P>
<P>
   As the Russian army reduces the already ruined city to rubble,
warning 40,000 civilians to get out or be ``destroyed'' with the
Muslim fundamentalist terrorists who Moscow says are its real
targets, a feeling of outrage and impotence spreads in countries
that went to war against Yugoslavia over similar outrages in Kosovo
only a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   So the question arises: What is the world to make of the new
doctrine it thought was emerging _ a doctrine that seemed, after
Bosnia and Kosovo and East Timor, to be empowering the bulk of the
world to intervene in countries that abused their own citizens?
Large parts of the world, it seemed, were embracing the idea that
universal standards of human rights were putting at least some
limits on sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes the harshest test of that doctrine: Russia, a
humbled superpower desperate to hold together its very territory,
not to mention its national pride, in the face of international
condemnation of its methods. ``Human rights are no reason to
interfere in the internal affairs of a state,'' Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov protested last week, offering the same
argument that Russia and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic made
during last spring's NATO air war against the Serbian attempt at
``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, is that some countries are more
sovereign than others. Sheer power still counts.
</P>
<P>
   Partly out of respect for its power, the European countries and
the United States have made some allowances for Moscow's conduct of
the war, recognizing that what Russia is trying to do in Chechnya
is very different from what the Serbs tried to do in Kosovo. But
they still point out that the ham-fisted Russian tactics could cost
thousands of innocent lives. ``The continuation of it and the
amassing of hundreds of thousands of refugees,'' President Clinton
said Wednesday night, ``will further alienate the global community
from Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those mild remarks, hinting at the prospect of a freeze on
International Monetary Fund loans to Russia and mostly verbal
criticism by the European Union, provoked chilling ire from
President Boris Yeltsin as he was visiting China on Thursday.
``Clinton allowed himself to pressure Russia yesterday,'' he said.
``He must have forgotten for a moment what Russia is. It has a full
arsenal of nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin knew full well when he sent Russian troops into Chechnya
that international criticism of Russian actions there was likely to
be limited to finger-wagging.
</P>
<P>
   But does that mean the interventionist doctrine is being dealt a
mortal blow? Is there still room for Kosovo-like operations when
dictators _ or democrats, for that matter _ commit war crimes on
their own territory? In fact, human rights are likely to remain a
strong reason to interfere in the internal affairs of some states,
as two examples show: East Timor, where Australia led an
international peacekeeping force that went in after Indonesian
atrocities were committed against the people for voting in favor of
independence, and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia and Yugoslavia do not have nuclear weapons, a fact
that allowed stronger nations to reach a consensus and step in to
halt the outrages. Still, for every Kosovo or East Timor the world
eventually bestirs itself to save, there is some Rwanda that the
``international community'' stays out of, or a Somalia that it just
gives up on.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of inaction in Chechnya _ like critics of inaction in
Rwanda _ argue that there's a double standard, and so there is.
President Clinton offered an answer to that objection early in the
Kosovo operation last spring, when he laid out his sense of
America's obligation to intervene: when it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't respond to every tragedy in every corner of the
world, but just because we can't do everything for everyone doesn't
mean that, for the sake of consistency, we should do nothing for no
one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From a moral standpoint, of course, that rationale is more
questionable when the failure to intervene is in a place like
Africa. There, it is easy to imagine that the rich nations of the
West often stay aloof more for their own convenience or out of
prejudice than because they see no way to help. In Chechnya,
though, it is obvious that the risks really do preclude military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, despite having stood by during an equally brutal, if
utterly unsuccessful, Russian campaign to subdue Chechnya five
years ago, countries in both hemispheres have shown a growing
willingness to use military means to force states to respect human
rights. And having now built a couple of precedents, one result is
that even mere words may carry more weight against abuses than they
did during the Cold War, when the option of military action was
immobilized virtually everywhere, so the words of outrage were
mostly empty.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, under international pressure, even Russia showed some
sensitivity, softening its ultimatum and assuring civilians in
Grozny that they would have time and transports to take them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will remember 1999 as the year in which sovereignty gave
way in places where crimes against humanity were being committed,''
said Kenneth Roth, the executive director of Human Rights Watch,
the New York-based organization.
</P>
<P>
   With Russia (and China) having a veto in the Security Council,
consensus on outside intervention to protect civilians in Chechnya
is as unlikely as it would be in Tibet, but that does not mean
Western nations are hypocritical in refraining from an intervention
that could prove suicidal, so long as they urge Russia to stop and
think again.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0066 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-RIGHTS-REVIE     12-11 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-RIGHTS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHNYA: THE NO MAN'S LAND IN THE FIGHT FOR HUMAN RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grozny means ``terrible'' in Russian, and the capital of
Chechnya is once again living up to its name.
</P>
<P>
   As the Russian army reduces the already ruined city to rubble,
warning 40,000 civilians to get out or be ``destroyed'' with the
Muslim fundamentalist terrorists who Moscow says are its real
targets, a feeling of outrage and impotence spreads in countries
that went to war against Yugoslavia over similar outrages in Kosovo
only a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   So the question arises: What is the world to make of the new
doctrine it thought was emerging _ a doctrine that seemed, after
Bosnia and Kosovo and East Timor, to be empowering the bulk of the
world to intervene in countries that abused their own citizens?
Large parts of the world, it seemed, were embracing the idea that
universal standards of human rights were putting at least some
limits on sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes the harshest test of that doctrine: Russia, a
humbled superpower desperate to hold together its very territory,
not to mention its national pride, in the face of international
condemnation of its methods. ``Human rights are no reason to
interfere in the internal affairs of a state,'' Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov protested last week, offering the same
argument that Russia and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic made
during last spring's NATO air war against the Serbian attempt at
``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, is that some countries are more
sovereign than others. Sheer power still counts.
</P>
<P>
   Partly out of respect for its power, the European countries and
the United States have made some allowances for Moscow's conduct of
the war, recognizing that what Russia is trying to do in Chechnya
is very different from what the Serbs tried to do in Kosovo. But
they still point out that the ham-fisted Russian tactics could cost
thousands of innocent lives. ``The continuation of it and the
amassing of hundreds of thousands of refugees,'' President Clinton
said Wednesday night, ``will further alienate the global community
from Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those mild remarks, hinting at the prospect of a freeze on
International Monetary Fund loans to Russia and mostly verbal
criticism by the European Union, provoked chilling ire from
President Boris Yeltsin as he was visiting China on Thursday.
``Clinton allowed himself to pressure Russia yesterday,'' he said.
``He must have forgotten for a moment what Russia is. It has a full
arsenal of nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin knew full well when he sent Russian troops into Chechnya
that international criticism of Russian actions there was likely to
be limited to finger-wagging.
</P>
<P>
   But does that mean the interventionist doctrine is being dealt a
mortal blow? Is there still room for Kosovo-like operations when
dictators _ or democrats, for that matter _ commit war crimes on
their own territory? In fact, human rights are likely to remain a
strong reason to interfere in the internal affairs of some states,
as two examples show: East Timor, where Australia led an
international peacekeeping force that went in after Indonesian
atrocities were committed against the people for voting in favor of
independence, and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia and Yugoslavia do not have nuclear weapons, a fact
that allowed stronger nations to reach a consensus and step in to
halt the outrages. Still, for every Kosovo or East Timor the world
eventually bestirs itself to save, there is some Rwanda that the
``international community'' stays out of, or a Somalia that it just
gives up on.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of inaction in Chechnya _ like critics of inaction in
Rwanda _ argue that there's a double standard, and so there is.
President Clinton offered an answer to that objection early in the
Kosovo operation last spring, when he laid out his sense of
America's obligation to intervene: when it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't respond to every tragedy in every corner of the
world, but just because we can't do everything for everyone doesn't
mean that, for the sake of consistency, we should do nothing for no
one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From a moral standpoint, of course, that rationale is more
questionable when the failure to intervene is in a place like
Africa. There, it is easy to imagine that the rich nations of the
West often stay aloof more for their own convenience or out of
prejudice than because they see no way to help. In Chechnya,
though, it is obvious that the risks really do preclude military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, despite having stood by during an equally brutal, if
utterly unsuccessful, Russian campaign to subdue Chechnya five
years ago, countries in both hemispheres have shown a growing
willingness to use military means to force states to respect human
rights. And having now built a couple of precedents, one result is
that even mere words may carry more weight against abuses than they
did during the Cold War, when the option of military action was
immobilized virtually everywhere, so the words of outrage were
mostly empty.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, under international pressure, even Russia showed some
sensitivity, softening its ultimatum and assuring civilians in
Grozny that they would have time and transports to take them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will remember 1999 as the year in which sovereignty gave
way in places where crimes against humanity were being committed,''
said Kenneth Roth, the executive director of Human Rights Watch,
the New York-based organization.
</P>
<P>
   With Russia (and China) having a veto in the Security Council,
consensus on outside intervention to protect civilians in Chechnya
is as unlikely as it would be in Tibet, but that does not mean
Western nations are hypocritical in refraining from an intervention
that could prove suicidal, so long as they urge Russia to stop and
think again.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, most of life's greatest wounds _ for individuals and
for countries _ are self-inflicted,'' said Clinton. ``I don't think
the strategy will work.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if Yeltsin knows that the allies are not going to risk
military confrontation over Chechnya, the world seems to have come
a long way from the early 1990s, when the fragile pretense of
civilization began to fall apart in Bosnia and every outside power
remained impotent until 1995. Many people paid for that indecision
with their lives, and hundreds of thousands more did in Rwanda in
1994 when the United States and the world turned their eyes aside
from genocide.
</P>
<P>
   After it became clear that inaction in Rwanda had only allowed
the chaos there to engulf neighboring Congo, Clinton admitted that
it had been a colossal mistake for the United States to block a
U.N. mandate for a stronger international force. Now there is a
U.N. tribunal to assess criminal responsibility and try to ensure
that nothing like that bloodletting happens again.
</P>
<P>
   That does not, of course, mean every atrocity will now be
stopped. Realistically, it still seems likely that the major powers
will let internal politics and domestic constraints make their
interventions selective. Just last week, the chief U.S. delegate to
the United Nations, Richard Holbrooke, was telling Africans that
while America wants to help with their problems, it remains
unwilling to send U.S. troops there.
</P>
<P>
   So increasingly, regional security organizations seem likely to
become the first defense against atrocities. Europe and the United
States have told African countries that it is up to them,
primarily, to organize international forces to intervene, as they
have in Sierra Leone and Liberia. And the European Union, wary of
having to rely on the United States again, is moving rapidly to
acquire the ability to raise and send peacekeeping forces on its
own. But as all of these examples show, it still takes too long for
the world to get its act together.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan may have done the best at
defining the uncertain progress in a speech last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we recall tragic events such as those of Bosnia or Rwanda
and ask, `Why did no one intervene?' the question should not be
addressed only to the United Nations, or even to its member
states,'' he said. ``Each of us as an individual has to take his or
her share of responsibility. No one can claim ignorance of what
happened. All of us should recall how we responded, and ask: `What
did I do? Could I have done more? Did I let my prejudice, my
indifference, or my fear overwhelm my reasoning? Above all, how
would I react next time?'''
</P>
<P>
   It takes time to rouse the world to anger, which sometimes comes
too late to do any good. So Annan's challenge applies perfectly
well in Chechnya _ not just to Americans or Western Europeans but,
above all, to the ordinary Russians in whose name Yeltsin's
government is issuing unacceptable ultimatums to innocent
civilians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
