<HEADER>
A5974 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-XMAS-LIVESTOCK-REVIEW     12-11 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XMAS-LIVESTOCK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW MUCH IS THAT PIGLET IN THE WINDOW? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By TOM KUNTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the first day of Christmas my true love sent to me ... a cow?
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe it doesn't roll off the tongue like partridge in a
pear tree. But believe it or not, it's the kind of gift you can
send, thanks to what is surely one of the world's oddest holiday
catalogs, that of Heifer Project International (www.heifer.org).
</P>
<P>
   Since 1944, the nonprofit charity, based in Little Rock, Ark.,
has shipped livestock to poverty-stricken areas all over the world
(inspiring a memorable 1987 headline in this very newspaper:
``Doomed Cows Get Foreign Homes'').
</P>
<P>
   The Heifer Project's holiday gift program, begun about 10 years
ago, seems rather like those adopt-an-adorable-Third-World-urchin
ads you see in magazines:
</P>
<P>
   1) You decide to spring for, say, a $120 goat in honor of dear
Aunt Gertrude (actually, each nominal livestock ``purchase'' goes
to the charity's entire program).
</P>
<P>
   2) Aunt Gertie receives a handsome gift card, describing your
generous contribution in her honor: a lovely goat!
</P>
<P>
   3) Hard-up family A in country X gets goat and agrees to donate
the animal's first female offspring to destitute family B, which
agrees to do the same thing and so forth in a continuing process of
rural enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it: This is the gift that keeps on smelling
funky. Here's a sampling of what else is available from the
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Gift of a Pig: $120
</P>
<P>
   Share of a Pig: $10
</P>
<P>
   Catalog copy: The holidays are right around the corner, and it's
time for more piglet gifts for your mother. Something about their
cute, squishy faces and their curlicue tails brings a smile to
Mom's face. Over the years, her holiday gifts have ranged from pig
T-shirts to pig doorstops to pig weather vanes _ and everything in
between. This year, how about the gift of a real live pig to put a
smile on Mom's face and brighten the future for a struggling
community?
</P>
<P>
   Gift of a Sheep: $120
</P>
<P>
   Share of a Sheep: $10
</P>
<P>
   Catalog copy: When you were just a wee thing, Aunt Dee Dee
taught you the basics of knitting. And the wool sweaters you
created together were nothing short of wonderful. This holiday
season, let her know what all of those knitting sessions by the
fire meant to you: give the gift of a sheep through Heifer Project
and share those moments of ``shear'' pleasure with a family in
need.
</P>
<P>
   Flock of chicks: $20
</P>
<P>
   Catalog copy: It's time to buy the kids' favorite teacher a
holiday present _ but you suspect that Mrs. Lynley doesn't need
another engraved Christmas tree ornament. How about the gift of a
flock of chicks in Mrs. Lynley's name to wish her happy holidays
and to thank her for giving your ``chickadees'' the gift of wisdom
throughout the school year?
</P>
<P>
   Gift of a Llama: $150
</P>
<P>
   Share of a Llama: $20
</P>
<P>
   Catalog copy: Uncle Gene has traveled the world. His incredible
stories and eccentric gifts were always the highlight of Christmas
morning festivities. Remember the camel saddle he brought you when
you were 9?
</P>
<P>
   Now it's your turn to provide your adventurous uncle with a
present he'll never forget: a rugged llama that will mean the world
to a family in need.
</P>
<P>
   Gift of a Water Buffalo: $250
</P>
<P>
   Share of a Water Buffalo: $25
</P>
<P>
   Catalog copy: At dawn in northern India, 9-year-old Parmatma
Prashad rises from the bed of burlap-covered hay he shares with his
father and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing shorts and a tattered sweater, Parmatma carries a steel
pail to the shed. In the early morning chill, Parmatma carries out
a routine chore that is changing his family's life: He milks the
buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
