<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-MCAULIFFE-PROFILE-3TA     12-11 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCAULIFFE-PROFILE-3TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TOP FUND-RAISER MADE PILES FOR HIMSELF, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Mo., Calif., Ohio)   (EDS: A short version of this story, MCAULIFFE-PROFILE-SHORT, will
also move.)  
(js) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a sweltering June evening this year President
Clinton headlined yet another Democratic Party fund-raiser, but
this time the guest of honor was Terry McAuliffe, Clinton's closest
and most loyal Washington friend as well as his tireless money man.
</P>
<P>
   Shedding his prepared remarks, the president said, ``I love this
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to understand why. The ebullient McAuliffe says he
and his staff have raised about $275 million, an unprecedented sum,
for Clinton's causes: election campaigns, the 1997 inaugural
celebration, a legal defense trust, the millennium festivities, the
presidential library and Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry's more wired than your local electric plant,'' Mrs.
Clinton said at the fund-raising dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Many of McAuliffe's connections were at the dinner _
billionaires, labor union bosses, Democratic Party leaders and
lobbyists. These contacts are at the center of Clinton's political
organization, the fund-raising causes McAuliffe loves to talk
about.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe's political clout and profile have grown significantly
during the Clinton presidency. He is a frequent White House guest
and often hits the links with the president. Their close
relationship was once again highlighted in the summer, when
McAuliffe temporarily agreed to guarantee the Clintons' mortgage on
the New York house they were buying.
</P>
<P>
   His closeness to the first couple and the expanding network of
political contacts he has built in the Clinton years have also
enhanced an enterprise that McAuliffe has built more quietly: a web
of business deals, from telecommunications to real estate, that the
fund-raiser keeps far from the public spotlight. His business
confederation, a veritable McAuliffe Inc., has generated tens of
millions of dollars, but McAuliffe keeps his affairs so private
that he does not even have a business listing in the Washington
telephone directory.
</P>
<P>
   His quietly acquired private fortune is illustrative of changes
in the political culture here. Raising money for politicians was
once a ticket to an ambassador's post or other influential job in
the government. Other presidential money men have hung shingles as
lobbyists, openly trading on their access, or peddled influence as
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Charting a new course, McAuliffe has transformed the art of
raising money for public figures into the art of raising money for
himself, leveraging a personal fortune from his political
fund-raising contacts. Although he is a lawyer and once headed a
lobbying firm, he resigned from the firm in 1994 when he began
raising big money for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the past, famous fund-raisers like Lew Wasserman, the MCA
founder, and Walter L. Shorenstein, the San Francisco real estate
magnate, were successful multimillionaires before they became
Democratic kingpins. And former top government officials, like
executives with the well-known Carlyle Group, have done well after
leaving government, though ethics laws restrict some of their
activities.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the energetic McAuliffe has never held a full-time
government post and is not subject to federal ethics laws.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe lives in a Virginia suburb of Washington but calls a
Florida house-building company his main business. And though he is
chairman of the Florida company, he was unable to provide the
company's address in a deposition this year. The aide who handles
his frenetic schedule has been working out of his obscure title
insurance company in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Although the capital is the central nervous system of both his
fund-raising and business dealings, McAuliffe does not have his own
Washington office, so when he is in town he often conducts business
at restaurants like the Palm and the Oval Room. In lengthy
interviews at both restaurants he shed some light on his private
deal-making and its symbiotic relationship with his political
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met all of my business contacts through politics,'' he
said. ``It's all interrelated.'' When he meets a new business
contact, he went on, ``then I raise money from them.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether people deal with him because of his close
association with the president, he said, ``No question, that's a
piece of it.'' But he quickly added other reasons, including his
ties to Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority leader, and
Tony Coelho, the director of Vice President Al Gore's presidential
campaign; his Rolodex of 5,000-plus names; and his ability to
personally relate to people. Dozens of associates agreed with
McAuliffe's explanation of his success.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton offered the following remarks, through an
aide, about his friendship with McAuliffe: ``Since Hillary and I
moved to Washington, the time we have spent with Terry and his
family has been wonderful. I wish we all had a fraction of Terry's
energy, his enthusiasm and his belief in the fundamental goodness
of people. It is safe to say that I do not have a more loyal friend
than Terry.''
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe says he uses his influence to get people together with
Clinton or to recommend them for presidential appointments, but he
never discusses substantive issues with the president or tries to
lobby him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay away from issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His political contacts are myriad and beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   One, a union executive, helped arrange more than $50 million in
union pension fund loans to McAuliffe's real estate ventures. One
loan, for $6 million in 1992, helped McAuliffe clear up his
entanglements with a failed savings and loan, court records show.
This year the Labor Department sued the union executive, calling
the $6 million loan imprudent.
</P>
<P>
   Another McAuliffe contact, a wealthy Cincinnati businessman and
Republican, provided the backing for McAuliffe's 1995 acquisition
of the house-building company. The deal also helped rescue the 1992
pension fund loan, which was then in default, according to records
and people involved in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe's connections also led to his being retained in 1997
by Gary Winnick, a Los Angeles multibillionaire, who in turn
provided the opportunity for McAuliffe to turn a $100,000
investment into an almost $20 million windfall, McAuliffe said.
This year McAuliffe said he arranged a golf game for Winnick with
Clinton, during which Winnick pledged $1 million for the Clinton
presidential library, which is to be built in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, McAuliffe was no golfing Friend of Bill, and
his finances were less secure. When Clinton, then the governor of
Arkansas, began his quest for the White House, railing against the
``Washington insider establishment,'' McAuliffe headed a Washington
lobbying firm, and he was best known for his ties to Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s McAuliffe was caught up in the collapse of
his father-in-law's savings and loan, and federal regulators were
close to shutting down McAuliffe's politically oriented Washington
bank.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe, 42, retains his boyish enthusiasm after 20 years of
raising money. Mack, as he is often called, was born and raised in
Syracuse, N.Y., the son of middle-class Democrats. He first raised
money for President Jimmy Carter's re-election campaign, masking
his youth by wearing fake glasses.
</P>
<P>
   By 1984, McAuliffe was being profiled in the news media as the
Wunderkind of fund-raising, but less noticed were his budding
business activities. When he was only 30, McAuliffe became chairman
of the Federal City National Bank, a small bank near the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   At the bank, according to public records, McAuliffe arranged
business-related loans that helped Coelho, then the House
Democratic whip, and Jim Wright, then the House speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, McAuliffe raised record amounts of money for
the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, headed by Coelho.
The two men broke ground by broadening the ties between the
business community, which had tilted Republican in its political
giving, and the Democratic Party. Coelho and McAuliffe continue to
do business deals and raise political money together.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe was finance director for Gephardt's 1988 presidential
campaign. The committee had millions of dollars in deposits and
loans with the Federal City bank.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1991 the bank was in trouble and was cited by federal
regulators for unsafe or unsound practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were in terrible trouble,'' McAuliffe said, noting
that ``the liquidators were ready to roll.'' But McAuliffe said his
``greatest business experience'' was to ``rally the board members''
and save the institution through a merger with a bank headed by a
Republican, Richard V. Allen, President Ronald Reagan's former
national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe became vice chairman of the new bank, though some
shareholders later questioned whether McAuliffe was afforded
special treatment, according to papers filed in a lawsuit against
the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said McAuliffe's treatment was proper, given his ability
to bring in business.
</P>
<P>
   Allen and McAuliffe struck up an alliance as a Democratic
president took over in 1993. That year, at Allen's urging,
McAuliffe sought and received the (unpaid) job of U.S. ambassador
to a South Korean trade fair. McAuliffe made Allen's son his deputy
and raised $500,000 for the exposition from one of Allen's clients,
who faced legal troubles in South Korea. After the fair, Allen's
son went to work for McAuliffe's law and lobbying firm.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe's profile in Washington's political and business
circles was growing.
</P>
<P>
   Every night Alecia Dyer sends McAuliffe a long list of phone
messages. To call McAuliffe, people dial a Washington phone number.
Ms. Dyer answers the phone, but for the last two years she has been
based in the central Florida office of Jefferson National Title
Insurance, which is the Florida branch of McAuliffe Inc.
</P>
<P>
   It traces back to Richard R. Swann, an Orlando lawyer who was
overseeing fund-raising in Florida for Carter when he met McAuliffe
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Much came of that first encounter. McAuliffe married Swann's
daughter. Then he became entangled in the collapse of Swann's
savings and loan. Finally, McAuliffe helped his father-in-law get
back on his feet using his political contacts.
</P>
<P>
   The two men have contrasting styles. Swann said he loves
complicated real estate deals, but ``Terry doesn't like reading
papers'' or ``to sit still.''
</P>
<P>
   Swann hit bottom in 1990 when federal regulators took over his
American Pioneer Savings Bank, based in Orlando. Swann petitioned
for bankruptcy. The court allowed an $8 million claim against Swann
by the government, but the regulators recovered only $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse also hit McAuliffe. He said he lost his $800,000
investment in American Pioneer. In 1991, court records show,
Resolution Trust Corp., the federal agency that took over American
Pioneer's assets and liabilities, sued McAuliffe and a former unit
of the bank to foreclose on a real estate loan. Swann says
McAuliffe was named as a defendant to clear title to the land.
</P>
<P>
   There was also opportunity in the thrift's demise. In 1991,
McAuliffe, guided by Swann, bought some American Pioneer real
estate _ once valued by the thrift at $50 million _ from Resolution
Trust Corp. for $39 million, records show.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe's equal partner in the deal was a pension fund
controlled by the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers
and the National Electrical Contractors Association. McAuliffe put
up $100. The pension fund put up $39 million, but enjoyed a
preferred position on any profits.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe arranged the financing through Jack F. Moore, a
secretary of the union and a trustee of the fund. Moore and
McAuliffe knew each other from the Gephardt presidential campaign
in 1988, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, now retired, praised McAuliffe in an interview and
defended the pension fund's fiduciary care. But he declined to
discuss the fund's dealings with McAuliffe because he and another
former trustee have been sued by the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
   The civil suit, filed last May, accuses Moore of acting
imprudently when the fund bought back shares of McAuliffe's
interest in the partnership. (McAuliffe used some of those proceeds
to buy Jefferson National.)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department also said that the fund had made an
imprudent $6 million loan in 1992 for a real estate development
company controlled by McAuliffe. The $6 million pension fund loan
was used by McAuliffe to clear up the Resolution Trust Corp.
lawsuit, but the new pension fund loan was soon in default, court
records show. Swann says the problem was a downturn in the Orlando
housing market.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The next step toward recovery _ the acquisition of a distressed
house-building company that was buying some of the troubled land
from McAuliffe's company _ was arranged in late 1995 with the help
of another of McAuliffe's fund-raising contacts.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the house-building company, American Heritage Homes, is
one of Florida's largest and most successful builders. McAuliffe is
its chairman. Most of the money to finance the purchase came from
American Financial Corp., a Cincinnati conglomerate that owns 60
percent of American Heritage, Swann said.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman and chief executive of American Financial is Carl
H. Lindner, a wealthy Republican who also gives money to Democrats.
McAuliffe became close to Lindner, who, along with his company,
gave $350,000 to the Democratic National Committee between 1993 and
1995. (They gave $437,000 to the the Republicans).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe remains close to Moore and Lindner. McAuliffe says the
pension fund came out all right, too _ an overall return of at
least 6.5 percent. But the Labor Department complaint says the
pension fund lost money on the $6 million loan. The case is
expected to go to trial next year.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will not be the first incidence of McAuliffe's name
surfacing in legal matters that mix politics and business.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 the Justice Department began examining Washington real
estate deals involving McAuliffe, court records show. The inquiry
ended in 1997when Prudential Insurance Co. of America paid
$317,500 to settle a civil suit in which it had been accused of
failing to disclose a $375,000 consulting arrangement in 1993 with
McAuliffe in connection with Prudential's lease of office space to
a federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   This year, McAuliffe's role in a questionable plan to swap
contributions in 1996 between the Teamsters union and the
Democratic Party surfaced during the federal trial in New York of
the former political director of the union, who was convicted of
fraud and conspiracy. McAuliffe, in an interview, acknowledged
discussing a potential swap.
</P>
<P>
   ``You help me, I'll help you,'' he said. ``That's politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But he denied doing anything wrong, saying he had not known that
the plan _ which was never implemented _ was meant to aid the 1996
re-election campaign of Ron Carey, the former Teamsters president.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry also involved handsome fees McAuliffe earned in 1996
for lobbying union leaders to choose Household Financial Group's
credit card for their members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took the Household guys around, I know most of the union
presidents,'' McAuliffe said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe has been a peripheral figure in the inquiries into
Democratic Party campaign finance abuses in the 1996 campaign
because he was the national finance chairman of the Clinton-Gore
re-election committee. But a contentious feature of Democratic
Party practices _ the use of the Lincoln Bedroom as a perk for
donors _ grew out of a memorandum McAuliffe wrote to Clinton's
secretary in early 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The story behind the memorandum explains the roots of the
Clinton-McAuliffe friendship. In late 1994, Clinton was in the
doldrums after the Democratic defeat in the November congressional
elections. Harold Ickes, his politically astute deputy chief of
staff, was trying to persuade the president to put McAuliffe in
charge of his re-election finances.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ickes said Clinton did not know McAuliffe ``that well,'' and
there was ``high-level resistance'' in the White House to McAuliffe
because of his ties to Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I leaned on the president and the president said do what's
best, so I went ahead,'' Ickes said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes was used to maneuvering around opposition when it came to
fund-raising. According to Ickes, senior White House aides had also
opposed McAuliffe's soliciting money from Lindner while the White
House was weighing whether to intervene on his behalf in an
international trade dispute over banana quotas. Ickes says he let
McAuliffe raise the money. McAuliffe said he was not aware of the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In late 1994 McAuliffe and Clinton had breakfast. McAuliffe said
the president asked what he could do to help and McAuliffe replied
that he should be more accessible to donors. A few days later
McAuliffe sent his memorandum asking Clinton's secretary to arrange
breakfast, lunch or coffee for top supporters so they could
``discuss issues and exchange ideas with the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wrote on the back of the memorandum _ words McAuliffe
said he never saw _ that he was ``ready to start overnight visits
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's re-election, his friendship with McAuliffe
continued to deepen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like the president,'' McAuliffe said. ``We like everybody
to like us and we like to like everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, McAuliffe also deepened his private business
activities, operating out of an office in downtown Washington that
belonged to Winnick's Pacific Capital a billion-dollar operation
based in Beverly Hills. Winnick retained McAuliffe as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe, who forged a relationship with Winnick through a
business associate active in Democratic politics, explained the
arrangement this way: ``Gary likes the action. He wanted a stable
of people around him with great contacts'' to ``help him work on
deals.''
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe said the contacts were not political, but he also said
that he was hired in part because ``Winnick was looking for a
little political action.''
</P>
<P>
   After one year with Pacific Capital, McAuliffe had produced no
deals and Winnick ended his retainer. By early 1998 McAuliffe was
consumed with helping Clinton defend himself in the Monica Lewinsky
matter, playing golf most Mondays with Clinton and talking
frequently with reporters to help defend his embattled friend.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, before the break-up, Winnick had offered McAuliffe
an opportunity to invest in a new Internet-related venture that
would own and operate undersea fiber-optic cables. The venture, now
known as Global Crossing Holdings, had potential risks and rewards.
It also faced myriad regulatory issues in Washington and around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   For McAuliffe and all the other early investors, Global Crossing
turned out to be a bonanza. McAuliffe says his initial $100,000
investment grew to be worth about $18 million, and he made millions
more trading Global's stock and options after it went public last
year. And recently, McAuliffe said he took a telecommunications
deal to Winnick that Global Crossing will put money into.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe says he is a dealmaker and a matchmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to have 25 balls in the air at the same time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of them: He sits on 10 corporate boards, none of
them public companies. He travels to Africa and Asia, where he
meets with heads of state. He's trying to buy six companies, in
areas like telecommunications. He is an active stock trader. He
speaks and plays golf regularly with his best friend, Clinton. And
his schedule includes family time: McAuliffe and his wife, Dorothy,
have four children.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some of his friends say McAuliffe Inc. is too invisible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've complained to him about his lack of infrastructure _ how
can we get you a fax,'' said Ed Rogers, a Republican lobbyist who
was one of McAuliffe's sources of information during the
impeachment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe defers to his lawyers and bankers when it comes to
documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've signed thousands of documents, but never read them, '' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's retirement poses a strategic question for McAuliffe:
what happens to his unique mix of politics and business once
Clinton steps down as the titular head of the Democratic Party?
Another Washington confidant of the president, the lawyer Vernon
Jordan, has already made his decision. He is joining a New York
investment bank. However, McAuliffe is likely to remain active in
politics and fund-raising and is already busily raising money for
Mrs. Clinton's Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McAuliffe Inc. may be entering a more visible phase.
Ms. Dyer is moving back to Washington, where she plans to work with
McAuliffe in a downtown office.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe is involved in plans to open a high-powered Washington
restaurant called the Caucus Room. The other investors include such
top Republican and Democratic lobbyists as Rogers, Thomas Boggs and
Haley Barbour, the former chairman of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a business person,'' Rogers said. ``His ideology derives
from that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
