<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5986 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MIRANDA-RIGHTS-REVIEW     12-11 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRANDA-RIGHTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOU THE RIGHT TO REMAIN SILENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JUAN FORERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do any Americans with a television not know that they have ``the
right to remain silent,'' ``the right to a lawyer,'' and that
anything they say may be used against them in a court of law?
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to television and its Kojaks and Andy Sipowiczs, these
phrases from the Supreme Court's landmark 1966 Miranda decision are
surely among the best-known phrases in the language.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda was a controversial decision, one that law enforcement
officials, in particular, railed against. They argued that no
criminal in his right mind would talk after being advised that he
didn't have to. A few months after the decision, the legendary
Manhattan district attorney, Frank Hogan, told the U.S. Senate
Judiciary Committee that the Miranda ruling was a ``fundamentally
unsound edict'' that ``significantly inhibits the making of a
statement by a suspect to a police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a surprising number of instances, suspects sing, despite
clear warnings about the pitfalls of self-incriminating comments.
``If you take a look at the Miranda warning and say it slow and
clear to a person with half a brain, you would think why would they
say anything after that,'' said Bob Connelly, a retired New York
City homicide detective who supports Miranda. ``But they do it all
the time. A lot of them just want to take it off their chest.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the warning became standard operating procedure in police
departments, many of the detectives whom Miranda opponents said
were hamstrung by the ruling made their peace with it. It became
ingrained in their routine, drummed into them as academy cadets and
reinforced throughout their careers. ``Our members have accepted
Miranda,'' said James Fotis, executive director of the Law
Enforcement Alliance of America, which represents 65,000 active and
retired officers.
</P>
<P>
   Even detectives express support for Miranda. ``If a friend of
mine was to be arrested for something, I would want him to know his
rights. There's a need for it,'' said Detective Sgt. Michael
Bettin, a narcotics investigator with the Essex County, N.J.,
Sheriff's Department. George Lytwyn, a retired Newark, N.J., police
detective, added: ``It's like when you get up in the morning and
brush your teeth _ it's automatic.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, investigators often get creative delivering the
warning, angling to minimize the possibility that a suspect will
ask for a lawyer and remain silent. ``Some of them get cute about
it, the way they phrase it, the way they time it, the way they try
to maneuver around it,'' said Susan Hendricks, deputy attorney in
charge of the criminal division for the Legal Aid Society in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Hernandez, a retired Newark, N.J., police detective, said
investigators will try to ingratiate themselves, bringing a suspect
coffee or a sandwich, making idle chitchat to make a suspect feel
comfortable _ all with an eye toward drawing out a confession.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling's critics, however, continue to regard Miranda as a
loophole that sets criminals free. Paul Cassell, a University of
Utah law professor who has crusaded against Miranda for years and
will argue for Section 3501 before the Supreme Court, said Miranda
creates a ``mine field'' that allows ``indisputably guilty
criminals'' to go free.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Uviller, a Columbia University law professor who wrote a
book about the year he spent with New York police officers, said
Miranda ``deters confessions or prevents the use of evidence in
some important cases.''
</P>
<P>
   This view has now received its most significant judicial
validation in 33 years. The activist 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in Richmond, Va., ruled last February, in a case involving
a confession from an accused bank robber, that an obscure 1968 law
permits the admission of confessions in federal court as long as
they were ``voluntary,'' in light of the circumstances and
regardless of any particular warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The law, known as Section 3501 of the Omnibus Crime Control Act,
has been ignored since its passage. But in February, the 4th
Circuit Court ruled that Section 3501 could substitute for the
Miranda rules in federal court because, in the court's opinion, the
rules themselves were not required by the Constitution. That has
opened the way for the U.S. Supreme Court to decide whether Section
3501 could limit or even overturn Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of overturning Miranda are not certain. For one
thing, Miranda warnings are not required in most arrests, which are
racked up by patrol officers on their beats. ``Most arrests are
made when people are caught red-handed,'' said James Fyfe, a Temple
University criminologist and former New York City Police
lieutenant. ``In almost all those cases, the evidence is so strong
that it's not necessary to talk to a suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Miranda comes into play only when the officer _ almost always a
highly experienced detective, more often than not working homicides
_ has arrested a suspect and plans to interrogate. And when the
process moves forward, investigators and criminologists say, good
detectives facing guilty suspects often obtain a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Uviller believes that Section 3501 would be a sensible
alternative. Nonetheless, while detectives don't see Miranda as
flawless, many say it has resulted in better investigations and
stronger cases. They say many of those who remain silent after
being read their rights are often convicted with other evidence,
especially the sort of advanced forensic evidence, such as DNA
analysis, that was undreamed of back in 1966. And then there is the
sense that Miranda is simply fair play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It put the police department on the line, outlined that it had
rules to obey,'' said Detective Peter Killen, who joined the New
York City police four years before the Miranda ruling and now works
in the 68th Precinct in Brooklyn. ``And when it came to the
suspects, well, the suspects were given rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1259EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0079 &Cx1f; var-z
