<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5987 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-COLDS-CAUSES-REVIEW-N     12-11 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLDS-CAUSES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S SOMETHING TO SNEEZE AT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is a patron saint of nagging mothers, it is surely
William Henry Harrison, the ninth president of the United States.
Standing in the cold rain on March 4, 1841, too proud to wear a
hat, delivering a 105-minute speech that is still one of the
longest inaugural addresses ever, he caught a cold and died of
pneumonia a month later (becoming the first president to die in
office and thus keeping his campaign promise never to run again).
</P>
<P>
   Such cautionary tales may impress parents and grandparents, but
of course they have no impact on children, who are too busy
escaping without their hats and boots to listen anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But, wait. This is the age of science: Aren't we supposed to
know that colds and flu are caused by viruses? The germ theory may
appeal to the intellect, but don't we know in our hearts that no
good can come from a bare head, wet feet or wearing a coat that, as
our mothers might have said, you could spit through?
</P>
<P>
   How about time-honored scourges like sudden warm spells during
the winter, failing to change out of wet clothes or going back and
forth between sweltering heat and frigid air conditioning?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not aware of any of those things in particular
predisposing to common colds,'' said Dr. Kristin Nichol, a cold and
flu expert who is chief of medicine at the Veterans Affairs Medical
Center in Minneapolis, and a professor at the University of
Minnesota, a place where they are supposed to know how to dress for
winter. ``I don't think things like stepping in puddles or letting
your head get cold have been linked to catching a cold.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it stressful to get very chilled, and mightn't that
lower one's resistance? Maybe just worrying about getting cold and
wet could derange a person's immune system.
</P>
<P>
   A woman of science, Dr. Nichol was dubious. ``But I do think
that if one becomes physically exhausted or overextended or
rundown, one may become more susceptible,'' she finally allowed.
Aha!
</P>
<P>
   For people who really want to avoid colds and flu, Dr. Nichol
had this advice: ``Get a flu shot. Wash your hands a lot. One of
the common modes of transmission is to get virus-infected particles
on your hands from touching a surface or shaking someone's hand.
Then if you touch your nose or eyes, you may become ill.''
</P>
<P>
   If you do get sick, Dr. Nichol added, ``Try to avoid coughing on
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was still true that a cold will last seven days if
treated and a week if left alone, she laughed politely.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, it seems as if doctors used to have a lot more remedies.
The Merck Manual of 1899 lists plenty of nostrums for ``acute nasal
catarrh,'' including gargling with a carbolic acid solution,
inhaling ammonia or chloroform, adding a bit of arsenic to your
cigarettes or taking hot foot baths before retiring. And if all
else failed, there was always tincture of jaborandi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
