<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5989 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u v BC-LADN-BUDGET-ADD &LR;      12-11 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET-ADD </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Dec. 121 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   ARMYCORPS-LAUSD (Los Angeles) -- The Army Corps of Engineers --
designated to run Los Angeles Unified's billion-dollar school
construction program _ has suffered failures and missteps on dozens
of occasions in recent years, according to interviews and documents
reviewed by the Daily News. Although experienced in massive
building projects and heralded for its emergency work after natural
disasters, the corps' snafus range from missed deadlines to
million-dollar cost overruns to blatant stealing by engineers. Like
the tales of the corps' good deeds, the horror stories come from
all over the country, as far away as blue-collar New Jersey, as
close to home as Hansen Dam in Lake View Terrace. By Greg Gittrich
(Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   CALDERA-ARMY (Los Angeles) -- Army Secretary Louis Caldera
denies playing any role in the decision by top Los Angeles Unified
School District administrators to put the Army Corps of Engineers
in charge of overseeing the district's massive school construction
project, including the controversial Belmont Learning Center. By
Greg Gittrich (Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national
news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILDCARE-NIGHTMARE (Los Angeles) _ Fabiola Ayala used to think
it was a joke _ parents so desperate for good quality daycare that
they placed their unborn children on waiting lists that seemed to
stretch into eternity. Now the 31-year-old Burbank mother is living
the nightmare. For the past eight months, Ayala's 2-year-old son,
Dylan, has been on the waiting list for Burbank's Horace Mann Child
Care Center _ and he's still not at the top of the list. Los
Angeles' supercharged economy is a boon for most, unless you are a
parent who has gone back to work and now is on a waiting list for
childcare you can't afford regardless. A new state study found that
there are six children of working parents for every licensed
child-care spot in the state _ and the problem is most acute in Los
Angeles County. By Sherry Joe Crosby (Will move on the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
