<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5992 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CALDERA-ARMY-LADN     12-11 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALDERA-ARMY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY SECRETARY SAYS HE DIDN`T INFLUENCE DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Greg Gittrich  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Army Secretary Louis Caldera denies playing any
role in the decision by top Los Angeles Unified School District
administrators to put the Army Corps of Engineers in charge of
overseeing the district's massive school construction project,
including the controversial Belmont Learning Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News reported last week that Caldera was a
strong supporter of the Belmont project when he represented the
area in the state Legislature and previously worked for O'Melveny &AMP;
Myers, the law firm being sued for malpractice by the LAUSD over
its handling of Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera, who has repeatedly declined to be interviewed on the
connections, released a statement through a federal spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consistent with routine U.S. Army Corps of Engineers practice,
the partnership agreement was entered into by the U.S. Army Corps
of Engineers locally without my knowledge or involvement,'' the
statement read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been involved in any way with school construction
in Los Angeles since I left the Legislature in September 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldera's role was questioned because the Corps of Engineers
reports to him and he has close ties to Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1997, Caldera wrote several letters to state
and school officials praising the district's innovative plan to
combine a 5,000-student high school with a shopping mall and a
low-income housing development.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Caldera urged the school board to approve it,
specifically praising the legal techniques used by O'Melveny &AMP;
Myers that allowed the district to buy the Belmont property and
select a developer without competitive building.
</P>
<P>
   Those same legal decisions were questioned in a September audit
of the project by the Los Angeles Unified's internal auditor and
are the subject of a malpractice lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   O'Melveny &AMP; Myers has denied that the school district's decision
to recruit the Army was connected in any way to the firm's intense
and ongoing lobbying effort to save Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD Chief Operating Officer Howard Miller said he has had no
contact with Caldera or members of his Washington, D.C., staff, and
was unaware of the potential conflict of interest until being
informed by the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to bring in the Army's services came from Rep. Howard
L. Berman and board member Caprice Young, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Young's top aide told the Los Angeles Daily News she mentioned
the idea to Miller about two weeks ago after Berman suggested it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been following the newspaper stories about the
absolutely astonishing and perhaps scandalous mess in the school
construction program at Los Angeles Unified,'' Berman, D-Mission
Hills, said in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the Army Corps knows how to build things quickly and
well using private contractors. They can supervise it well and get
it done according to specifications without corruption. I thought
they'd do a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman said he brought in the corps to build Hansen Dam and has
the agency ``checking out a gymnasium at a veteran hospital'' in
his district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caldera's past never occurred to me,'' he said, adding he
never spoke to the secretary about the idea and doesn't plan to.
</P>
<P>
   As for Belmont, Berman said, he doesn't know ``who would be
better. The Army corps deals with big projects and big messes all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1301EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
