<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ROCKEFELLER-FOUNDATIO     12-11 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKEFELLER-FOUNDATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKEFELLER FOUNDATION TO FOCUS SOLELY ON POOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In response to the emergence of more powerful
foundations and its own sense that it might have been spreading
itself too thin, the Rockefeller Foundation is changing its mission
to focus exclusively on the world's poor. The foundation, which is
based in New York, gives away about $170 million a year to hundreds
of causes. The foundation expects to announce its plans Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization has the capacity to eliminate poverty, eliminate
hunger and greatly reduce disease and provide excellent education
to everyone,'' said Gordon Conway, a British agricultural ecologist
who joined the foundation last year as its 12th president. ``But it
will only do that if it is steered in that direction. If you are
going to steer globalization, you need a new response from
foundations.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Conway's direction, Rockefeller now plans to take a
globally integrated approach to helping those who have been left
behind as the rest of the world enjoys tremendous prosperity and
huge advances in technology and science. The foundation, which
already spends roughly 70 percent of its money overseas, will no
longer distinguish between its international and domestic
initiatives but will try to develop broad strategies to address the
specific challenges facing the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller's giving will also be much more focused, Conway
said. The foundation used to give in nine areas, ranging from
school reform to the global environment, which may continue in some
fashion or be phased out. Financing for programs involving arms
control and domestic energy will end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundation had built up a whole range of programs that are
disconnected to each other,'' Conway said. Because those programs
were not related, there was little synergy. ``You were not getting
something that was greater than the sum of the parts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach is also designed to address the widening
disparity between the haves and the have-nots. ``We are in a new
age right now,'' Conway said, as much of the world is becoming
increasingly integrated in finance, trade, culture and technology.
``The rich are getting richer, and the poor are getting poorer, at
least in relative terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at the poor, giving will now be focused on four major
areas: culture and creativity, employment, food and health care.
</P>
<P>
   This new focus is by no means a radical departure from the work
the foundation has been doing since it was created by John D.
Rockefeller in 1913 ``to promote the well-being of mankind
throughout the world.'' The emphasis is clearly a continuation of
many of the foundation's existing programs and is ``in the absolute
core of the mission,'' said Peggy Dulany, the daughter of David
Rockefeller and a member of the foundation's board until earlier
this year. ``We are very pleased with the shifts in emphasis,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the change does represent an attempt by the foundation, one
of the nation's oldest, to maintain a critical role in philanthropy
at a time when it is no longer one of the largest foundations in
the country. With roughly $3 billion in its endowment, Rockefeller
is dwarfed in size by newer foundations like those of David and
Lucile Packard or Bill and Melinda Gates, which have three to six
times as much money. As these foundations take an increasingly
important role in the world of philanthropy, Rockefeller is
struggling to have a major impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a limited amount of money for what we want to do,''
said Linda Hill, a professor at Harvard Business School and a
member of the Rockefeller board.
</P>
<P>
   What Conway hopes to do is continue to capitalize on
Rockefeller's reputation and its ability to bring together people
from government, business, other foundations and charities to
tackle issues by serving ``as a broker and facilitator,'' he said.
He described the foundation's work as ``more akin to small-scale
business practice: brokering, deal-making, spotting opportunities
early and risk-taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller can also afford to continue to take a longer
perspective than other groups, Conway said. ``In most situations,
we're going for the long haul,'' 10 to 15 years, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take on this daunting task of making globalization
work for everyone,'' he said. ``It means focusing, partnership and
looking for root causes and exploiting our convening power.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Rockefeller began its search for a new president two years
ago, the institution has been undergoing an extensive review,
including various sessions and retreats for staff members and
outsiders. ``We've had retreat after retreat,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Conway's major challenges will be to have the foundation
develop a coherent strategy for attacking problems in a global
fashion while making sure it works closely with communities to
understand what they need. As a scientist, he learned, early on,
the necessity of gathering information from farmers about their
needs. Already, he is moving people from New York out to the field,
opening offices in Africa, for example.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
