<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-CHILD-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING GEOPOLITICS WITH A TINY PROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It is a large predicament for such a small boy.
</P>
<P>
   For 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, who survived for two days adrift
on an inner tube in the Atlantic Ocean, after a failed crossing
from Cuba drowned his mother and 10 others in late November, the
ordeal may be just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   His father in Cuba, and more important, Fidel Castro, want him
home. Relatives in Miami, and many in the politically powerful
exile community here, say he already is home, wrapped in the arms
of the Cuban-Americans who live in Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, which had once seemed content to let
Florida courts decide the case, now seems willing to consider
sending the boy home, this after a week of large demonstrations
outside the U.S. diplomatic mission in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Those demonstrations, coupled with threats from Castro that more
are to come, caused U.S. officials ``to tremble,'' bragged the
boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who has refused to come to the
United States to try and reclaim his son in what he called a
corrupt state court.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, lawyers representing the boy filed a petition for
political asylum in the United States, which could extend his stay
with relatives here for at least 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not turn this into a political thing,'' said his
21-year-old cousin, Marisleysis Gonzalez, who has become the boy's
closest friend in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But with Elian's face on a billboard in Havana and on T-shirts
in Miami; with marchers chanting his name on either side of the
Florida Straits; and with the Republican presidential hopeful John
McCain taking up his cause during a campaign stop here Friday, that
is an impossible dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1303EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0085 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-CUBA-CHILD-REVIEW-NYT     12-11 0358
</HEADER>
