<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6010 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-MCAULIFFE-PROFILE-SHO     12-11 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCAULIFFE-PROFILE-SHORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TOP FUND-RAISER MADE PILES FOR HIMSELF, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Mo., Calif., Ohio)   (EDS: A longer version of this story, MCAULIFFE-PROFILE, has
moved.)  
(js) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a sweltering June evening this year President
Clinton headlined yet another Democratic Party fund-raiser, but
this time the guest of honor was Terry McAuliffe, Clinton's closest
and most loyal Washington friend as well as his tireless money man.
</P>
<P>
   Shedding his prepared remarks, the president said, ``I love this
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to understand why. The ebullient McAuliffe says he
and his staff have raised about $275 million, an unprecedented sum,
for Clinton's causes: election campaigns, the 1997 inaugural
celebration, a legal defense trust, the millennium festivities, the
presidential library and Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Many of McAuliffe's connections were at the dinner _
billionaires, labor union bosses, Democratic Party leaders and
lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence was a symbol of how McAuliffe's political clout
and profile have grown during the Clinton presidency. His close
relationship with the president was highlighted in the summer, when
McAuliffe temporarily agreed to guarantee the Clintons' mortgage on
the New York house they were buying.
</P>
<P>
   His closeness to the first couple and the expanding network of
political contacts he has built in the Clinton years have also
enhanced an enterprise that McAuliffe has built more quietly: a web
of business deals, from telecommunications to real estate, that the
fund-raiser keeps far from the public spotlight. His business
confederation, a veritable McAuliffe Inc., has generated tens of
millions of dollars, but McAuliffe keeps his affairs so private
that he does not even have a business listing in the Washington
telephone directory.
</P>
<P>
   His quietly acquired private fortune is illustrative of changes
in the political culture here. Raising money for politicians was
once a ticket to an ambassador's post or other influential job in
the government. Other presidential money men have hung shingles as
lobbyists, openly trading on their access, or peddled influence as
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Charting a new course, McAuliffe has transformed the art of
raising money for public figures into the art of raising money for
himself, leveraging a personal fortune from his political
fund-raising contacts. Although he is a lawyer and once headed a
lobbying firm, he resigned from the firm in 1994 when he began
raising big money for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe lives in a Virginia suburb of Washington but calls a
Florida house-building company his main business. But although the
capital is the central nervous system of both his fund-raising and
business dealings, McAuliffe does not have his own Washington
office, so when he is in town he often conducts business at
restaurants like the Palm and the Oval Room. In lengthy interviews
at both restaurants he shed some light on his private deal-making
and its symbiotic relationship with his political fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met all of my business contacts through politics,'' he
said. ``It's all interrelated.'' When he meets a new business
contact, he went on, ``then I raise money from them.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether people deal with him because of his close
association with the president, he said, ``No question, that's a
piece of it.'' But he quickly added other reasons, including his
ties to Rep. Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority leader,
and Tony Coelho, the director of Vice President Al Gore's
presidential campaign; his Rolodex of 5,000-plus names; and his
ability to personally relate to people. Dozens of associates agreed
with McAuliffe's explanation of his success.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton offered the following remarks, through an
aide, about his friendship with McAuliffe: ``Since Hillary and I
moved to Washington, the time we have spent with Terry and his
family has been wonderful. I wish we all had a fraction of Terry's
energy, his enthusiasm and his belief in the fundamental goodness
of people. It is safe to say that I do not have a more loyal friend
than Terry.''
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe says he uses his influence to get people together with
Clinton or to recommend them for presidential appointments, but he
never discusses substantive issues with the president or tries to
lobby him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay away from issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His political contacts are myriad and beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   One, a union executive, helped arrange more than $50 million in
union pension fund loans to McAuliffe's real estate ventures. One
loan, for $6 million in 1992, helped McAuliffe clear up his
entanglements with a failed savings and loan, court records show.
This year the Labor Department sued the union executive, calling
the $6 million loan imprudent.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe's connections also led to his being retained in 1997
by Gary Winnick, a Los Angeles multibillionaire, who in turn
provided the opportunity for McAuliffe to turn a $100,000
investment into an almost $20 million windfall, McAuliffe said.
This year McAuliffe said he arranged a golf game for Winnick with
Clinton, during which Winnick pledged $1 million for the Clinton
presidential library, which is to be built in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, McAuliffe was no golfing Friend of Bill, and
his finances were less secure. When Clinton, then the governor of
Arkansas, began his quest for the White House, McAuliffe headed a
Washington lobbying firm.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe, 42, retains his boyish enthusiasm after 20 years of
raising money. He was born and reared in Syracuse, the son of
middle-class Democrats, and first raised money for President Jimmy
Carter's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, McAuliffe raised record amounts of money for
the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, headed by Coelho.
The two men broke ground by broadening the ties between the
business community, which had tilted Republican in its political
giving, and the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe says he is a dealmaker and a matchmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to have 25 balls in the air at the same time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of them: He sits on 10 corporate boards, none of
them public companies. He travels to Africa and Asia, where he
meets with heads of state. He's trying to buy six companies, in
areas like telecommunications. He is an active stock trader. He
speaks and plays golf regularly with his best friend, Clinton. And
his schedule includes family time: McAuliffe and his wife, Dorothy,
have four children.
</P>
<P>
   But McAuliffe's name has surfaced in legal matters that mix
politics and business. In 1995, for example, the Justice Department
began examining Washington real estate deals involving McAuliffe,
court records show. The inquiry ended in 1997 when Prudential
Insurance Co. of America paid $317,500 to settle a civil suit in
which it had been accused of failing to disclose a $375,000
consulting arrangement in 1993 with McAuliffe in connection with
Prudential's lease of office space to a federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   For McAuliffe, Clinton's retirement poses a strategic question:
what happens to his unique mix of politics and business once
Clinton steps down as the titular head of the Democratic Party?
McAuliffe is likely to remain active in politics and fund-raising
and is already busily raising money for Mrs. Clinton's Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   He is also involved in plans to open a high-powered Washington
restaurant called the Caucus Room. The other investors include such
top Republican and Democratic lobbyists as Ed Rogers, Thomas Boggs
and Haley Barbour, the former chairman of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a business person,'' said Rogers, a Republican lobbyist.
``His ideology derives from that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CHARITY-DONATIONS-ART     12-11 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARITY-DONATIONS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPERITY YIELDS A LAG IN CHARITY TOWARD THE POOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Tenn., Texas, Mass., Maine, Va., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As incomes of the better-off Americans rise in this age of
prosperity, with the stock market and corporate profits booming,
charities report that both individuals and companies are donating
less to organizations that support the homeless, the young and the
hungry than they did in leaner times.
</P>
<P>
   Leading charitable organizations like the Salvation Army and
United Way say that as a result, they are struggling with a surging
demand for their aid, and the private donations they collect are
falling far short of the need.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so stunning to me is that people in America have this
image of prosperity and everybody benefits,'' said Deborah Leff,
president of America's Second Harvest in Chicago, which oversees a
network of 189 community food banks nationwide that distribute
nearly $400 million in donated food to 26 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Leff said contributions to Second Harvest's $10 million
annual budget have been rising but by nowhere near enough to meet
the demand. ``I think people just aren't aware of the need,'' she
said. ``They think of hunger as a distended stomach in some
developing country. That's starvation, not hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Jones, director of development and national spokesman for
the Salvation Army, the nation's biggest charity, said, ``In this
era of prosperity, need continues to skyrocket, especially in the
major cities.'' Giving to the Salvation Army is up in some cities
and down in others but nowhere does it meet the need, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I continue to hear from places like Memphis and Houston of how
many more people are coming to ask for help in paying their rent or
utility bills,'' he said. ``The army is facing not only more need
but a more complex kind of need,'' in serving more and more
families than single adults.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Clolery, editor of NonProfit Times, a newspaper for
executives of nonprofit groups, said, ``Demand for services is
through the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   The travails of the nation's purest charities _ those, unlike
colleges, museums, hospitals and churches, that serve the indigent
exclusively _ clash with evidence of a slowly falling poverty rate,
rising incomes, and the overhaul of the welfare system three years
ago that has coaxed many recipients into jobs. The charities say
that with their mostly low-wage jobs, many former recipients earn
less than they collected in welfare checks along with food stamps,
health care and subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, better-off Americans who might help are spending and
borrowing more than ever and reaching record levels of bankruptcy
and debt, so they have less to save and to give. ``One would have
expected that at a certain level of prosperity, people might reach
a certain limit of their consumption,'' said Julian Wolpert, a
professor at the Woodrow Wilson School at Princeton University who
specializes in tracking philanthropy. ``But we're not getting
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the nation has never looked so bountiful. Bill
Gates , the chairman of Microsoft Corp., and his wife, Melinda,
have created a foundation that dwarfs even those of the
Rockefellers and Fords, and by the end of this year, Harvard will
have amassed more than $2.3 billion in a single capital fund drive.
Giving USA, which monitors philanthropic giving, reports a
prosperity-driven surge in giving to a record $175 billion last
year, up nearly 11 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But about 90 percent of the money goes to religious
organizations, some of which operate services for the poor, and to
other organizations that cater mostly to the rich and the middle
class, like the opera, ballet, museums and universities. ``They add
nicely to our quality of life,'' Wolpert said of these
organizations, ``but they are also the kinds of things that we
ourselves use.''
</P>
<P>
   No one keeps track of contributions to programs the poor use.
But Giving USA reports that contributions for human services,
including most forms of traditional charity, represented 9.2
percent of all giving last year, a decline from 13.9 percent in
1970.
</P>
<P>
   And by a variety of measures, people are also giving less to all
forms of philanthropy. The Independent Sector, a coalition of
philanthropic organizations, says that households donated 2.1
percent of their incomes last year, compared with 2.5 percent a
decade ago, and that the number of those making any contributions
fell to 70.1 percent last year from 75.1 percent in 1989. After
inflation, the organization reports, a family's average gift to
human service organizations fell to $250 last year from $271 four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Animals get more sympathy than children, said Joyce Strom,
president and chief executive of the Massachusetts Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Children in Boston. ``If there's an animal
abused,'' she said, ``people will flock to the cause and raise
money on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Strom's organization, which serves 100,000 children a year,
must struggle with curbs in government support of its services and
the costs and difficulties of raising money from the public.
</P>
<P>
   State payments for the society's services to children amount to
$24 million of its annual budget of $30 million. While salaries and
other costs rise, the state has frozen the payments of support,
some for as long as 12 years. So in going after private donations,
Ms. Strom said, ``I have to raise money just to fill the hole I'm
in, and it's really, really tough to raise money.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Ms. Strom said, ``We have to turn people away all
the time. People who are reported for child abuse and neglect but
who are screened out because their cases are not serious enough.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts are unsympathetic with the travails of low-budget
agencies that serve the poor. ``It's their mission to complain,''
said Paul Schervish, director of Boston College's Social Welfare
Research Institute, who sees the nation entering a golden age of
philanthropy, with the baby-boom generation leaving tens of
trillions of dollars to their estates and charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening is these groups are facing competition,''
Schervish said. ``It doesn't mean people are giving any less.''
Part of their contributions to organizations like Harvard and
Boston College is used to educate the poor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Petit, a director of the Child Welfare League of America
and former commissioner for human services for the state of Maine,
said: ``There is a large gap between what these families require to
be whole and what is available to them. The early, front-end
investment in children is not occurring at a sufficient scale to
make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Such charities' accounts of the gap in their resources and needs
vary only in the details. At the United Way, said Tony De
Cristofaro, a spokesman, ``over the last 10 years, we have had
increases virtually every year in contributions.'' But he said the
share that donors designate for health and humans ``is flat at best
or declining.''
</P>
<P>
   Other charities describe similar gaps in needs and resources.
From a 48,000-square-foot warehouse in Washington and a
12,000-square-foot warehouse nearby in Arlington, Va., the Capital
Area Food Bank dispatches almost 2 million tons of food a month to
780 food pantries, like Martha's Table and So Others Might Eat, and
to church kitchens that feed 200,000 people a month in the
Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1988, we were seeing one out of five children'' in the
Washington area, said Linda Brantley, the food bank's president and
chief executive. ``Then five years down the road, it was one out of
four. Now we are seeing one out of three.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Platek, vice president for fund development for Associated
Catholic Charities of Houston, has noticed that supporters now give
for buildings and endowments more readily than for services.
</P>
<P>
   The organization just completed a successful drive for $11
million, mostly for a new central program building. But raising
money for emergency services _ disaster relief, food, shelter and
clothing _ is much harder. In part because of the change in the
welfare system, ``we had a 40 percent increase in the numbers of
people served through emergency assistance from 1996 to 1998,'' Ms.
Platek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the people we're seeing are the working poor,'' she
said. ``They have full-time jobs, but housing is eating up the
paycheck. We've seen a big increase in that. We're straining.''
</P>
<P>
   Philanthropic contributions by corporations, typically about 1
percent of their profits and about 5 percent of all giving
nationally, have been declining more than those from individuals,
many charities report. This has put a strain on the National Urban
League in New York, whose affiliates provide education and job
training to minority clients.
</P>
<P>
   With mergers and plant closings, said Milton Little, executive
vice president and chief operating officer, ``this has been an
extremely difficult year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Charity executives say it is hard to determine why Americans do
not share more of their prosperity with the poor. They speculate
that in moving to gated communities in the suburbs, people who
rally to help hurricane victims portrayed on the evening news do
not see the need around the corner. Herman Ewing, president of the
Urban League of Memphis, said prosperity, for all its appeal, can
undermine the sharing and the bonds of neighbors and communities,
and gives people a lot to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result of prosperity is isolation, arrogance and
in-your-face,'' Ewing said. ``This among people who were once
interdependent in terms of basic survival needs. The idea that
you're looking out for me for food and I'm looking out for you for
this or that is all by the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Ober, executive director of the Children's Aid Society of
Pennsylvania, in Philadelphia, said: ``I'm concerned that we are
not a kinder society. Child welfare agencies serve the most at-risk
families. I'm not sure there's a value attached to having some
responsibility for those families.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Boris, director of the Center on Nonprofits and
Philanthropy at the Urban Institute in Washington, said, ``We're
not as generous as we could be.'' But a reason may be that so many
of the decade's newly rich have not turned their attention to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be a lag,'' Ms. Boris said. ``Maybe the whole
generation of folks making money are not yet a part of the network
of people who give.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
