<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOY-ALONE-740(TRIMS)-     12-11 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOY-ALONE-740(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERN AND CASH RISE FOR BOY WHO LIVED WITH DEAD MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ As Monica Thomas and Saprena Smith dug into the
fried catfish lunch special at The Cupboard Too restaurant
downtown, their conversation turned to the 9-year-old boy whom many
people here now feel they know on a first-name basis, even though
most have never seen his face.
</P>
<P>
   Travis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a conversation all week with my friends where
his name hasn't come up,'' said Ms. Thomas, 30, a court reporter.
``That little boy had to be awfully brave, to survive for so long
alone.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, 32, also a court reporter, added, ``It's so sad.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a family friend who stopped by the East Memphis
apartment where Travis Butler lived discovered that he had been
staying there alone for a month with his mother lying dead on the
living room floor. The boy did not tell anyone about her death, he
said, because he was afraid he would have to go to a foster home.
</P>
<P>
   His mother is said to have been ill, possibly from high blood
pressure. The police do not suspect foul play and are not treating
the death as a homicide. Her funeral is scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, who family and friends say had been taught not to ask
for favors, had managed to get himself to school on time every day,
do his homework and go to the store to buy what he needed with
money that was in the house. On Thanksgiving, he fixed himself a
frozen pizza, but he has said that he had worried he would not have
a Christmas tree this year.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, most of Memphis had heard the boy's story. Now,
his maternal grandparents have taken him to their home in Carthage,
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   But Travis is fast becoming the main focus of this city's
holiday spirit. A local bank has set up a trust fund. A local
transportation company has organized a clothing, toy and gift
donation center for the boy, noting that he wears size 10 slim
pants and size 3 shoes. And local talk radio stations have been
abuzz about the boy's self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   Some are comparing his story to that of the boy who lost his
mother coming over from Cuba. But most of the soul-searching among
residents here is centering on what Travis Butler's story says
about this city and this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just tragic that a little boy is so scared of what's
going to happen to him in the system,'' said Alex Elder, 37, a
lawyer, ``that he won't call for help.''
</P>
<P>
   His lunch companion at The Cupboard Too, Wilson von Kessler, 33,
also a lawyer, said it reminded him of a William Faulkner story he
had read about a son living with his dead mother. ``It's just a
little perverse,'' he said. ``But I think it says something about
what a dysfunctional society we live in.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, on Main Street, Chris Woodears, 40, a print
press operator, was sitting in the sun on his lunch break talking
to a friend about the little boy. ``People are afraid of their
friends, strangers, anybody, these days,'' he said. ``Everybody
just keeps to themselves. When I was coming up everybody took care
of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Family members and neighbors said the boy's mother, Crystal
Wells, 30, did not associate with many people. Travis' grandmother,
Shirley Wilder, told reporters that she had little money and so had
not seen her daughter, Ms. Wells, for more than a year, but had
spoken to her on the phone in October.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials are searching for the boy's father, who has
never had any contact with Travis.
</P>
<P>
   Since picking the boy up on Tuesday, Ms. Wilder and several
cousins and aunts have tried to shield him from television and
newspaper photographers and reporters. On Thursday, when the family
returned to the boy's apartment to gather his things, he wore a ski
mask and pulled his shirt over his face. Most people here do not
know what Travis looks like.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we read the story on Wednesday,'' said Nancy Spoon, a
medical office worker, ``it made us sick to our stomachs. We had
never laid eyes on the boy. We didn't know what color he was. We
just knew he needed help.''
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Spoon and two others in her office spoke to officials at
the National Bank of Commerce and asked them to start a trust fund
for the boy. As of Friday, the fund had raised more than $13,000
and was expecting much more. Bank officials said the local response
had been overwhelming, and they had received calls from throughout
the country as well as Canada and Europe.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the Wolfchase Galleria shopping mall, Mabel Wall, 75, who was
Christmas shopping with her granddaughter, said: ``I just think it
is one of the saddest things I have ever heard of. It seems the
little boy is just an extra-smart kid, but the world is so wicked
these days. I feel like children are the ones being hurt most.''
</P>
<P>
   Debra Finley, 39, a fingerprint clerk at the county jail, was
hoping she could do a little to stop the boy's pain. On Friday, her
day off, she went to an NBC Bank branch and delivered her $20
donation to the Travis Butler Fund, along with a $10 donation from
her sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hate to see him go through anything like that,'' she
said, ``I'm praying that Travis has a good Christmas, and a good
life.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6034 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-N     12-11 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Dec. 12, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-RIGHTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Chechnya has become the no
man's land in the fight for human rights. As Russia demolishes the
Chechen capital of Grozny, what is the world to make of the new
doctrine it thought was emerging _ a doctrine that seemed, after
Bosnia, Kosovo and East Timor, to be empowering the bulk of the
world to intervene in countries that abused their own citizens? Now
comes the harshest test of that doctrine: Russia, a humbled
superpower desperate to hold together its very territory, not to
mention its national pride, in the face of international
condemnation of its methods. By Craig R. Whitney. (Moved in `i'
category)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-MAVERICK-REVIEW (Washington) _ The deluge of hype about
the rise of Sen. John McCain overshadows a fundamental question:
Can a politician win the Republican nomination by bashing the
Republican Party? In the history of the Republican Party, far more
so than in the Democratic Party, the presidential nominee has
rarely been an insurgent; it is almost always the man with the most
institutional support. McCain has not only taken stands that are
unpopular within the GOP; he is actively disliked by many within
the party and groups aligned with it. By Richard L. Berke. (Moved
in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-TOBACCO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Is the legal fight against guns
is a sequel to the tobacco war _ a struggle against products that
kill, and against industries that have dodged or defeated change in
Congress? As with the anti-tobacco campaign, the threat of ruinous
monetary awards is supposed to force gun manufacturers to change
their practices. But the parallels between the two may be
overdrawn. Unlike tobacco, which is harmful when used as intended,
guns do have certain legitimate and safe uses, and in order for the
manufacturer's product to harm someone, a third party is usually
involved. Thus, the gun lawsuits appear to be weaker than the
anti-tobacco claims. By Barry Meier. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-CHEATING-REVIEW (Undated) _ A rash of systematic
cheating on school tests, most notably uncovered in New York and
Texas, has spread at the same time that superintendents and
politicians across the U.S. have set tough new test-score targets
for their school systems. The `standards' revolution is tying
promotion and graduation of students and even cash bonuses for
everyone from principals to cafeteria workers to measurable
achievement. Does this make the temptation to cheat even greater
than it would be otherwise?
</P>
<P>
   HACKERS-IMAGE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The computer hacker, a uniquely
modern character in film, television and theater, has undergone a
radical transformation since its birth in the early 1980s. Gone is
the plaid-shirted, pizza-stained nerd who guzzles soda while
fumbling through cyberspace. Today's hacker characters are
portrayed wearing black leather, trench coats, form-fitting vests
and pants, tinted sunglasses .. and they're usually villains. By
Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   COLDS-CAUSES-REVIEW (Undated) _ In this age of modern science,
we're supposed to know that colds and flu are caused by viruses.
The germ theory may appeal to the intellect, but don't we know in
our hearts that no good can come from a bare head, wet feet or
wearing an inadequately warm coat? What about time-honored scourges
like sudden warm spells during the winter, failing to change out of
wet clothes or going back and forth between sweltering heat and
frigid air conditioning? By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   MIRANDA-RIGHTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Supreme Court's 1966
Miranda ruling, which guarantees certain rights for criminal
suspects, was initially opposed by much of the law enforcement
community. But most detectives have long since accepted it and
incorporated it into their routines. And in a surprising number of
instances, suspects still make self-incriminating statements even
after being told they have the right to remain silent. By Juan
Forero.
</P>
<P>
   XMAS-LIVESTOCK-REVIEW (Undated) _ One of the world's oddest
holiday catalogs must surely be that of Heifer Project
International. Since 1944, the nonprofit charity has shipped
livestock to poverty-stricken areas all over the world. The Heifer
Project's holiday gift program, begun about 10 years ago, seems
rather like those adopt-an-adorable-Third-World-urchin ads you see
in magazines. By Tom Kuntz.
</P>
<P>
   BULLY-PREVENTION-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Educators are
redoubling efforts to discourage student aggression from an early
age. And they are turning to tools like `Quit It! A Teacher's Guide
on Teasing and Bullying for Use with Students in Grades K-3.'
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SYRIA-REVIEW (Lebanon) _ Syrian President Hafez has a
record of ruthlessness, but he has also ruled with finesse and
brought about three decades of domestic stability. Little wonder,
then, that he has long been seen as the Arab neighbor with whom
Israel most wants to make peace. More than any of his Arab
counterparts, Assad is seen as a man who understands both power and
survival. And he has kept what few bargains he has struck with
Israel. So he is viewed as someone who, if he made a deal, would
make one that sticks. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-CHILD-REVIEW (Miami) _ Playing geopolitics with a tiny
prop: a look at the plight of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez and the
U.S.-Cuban tensions it has ignited. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
