<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CROATIA-TUDJMAN-850&AMP;A     12-11 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-TUDJMAN-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROATIA MOURNS FOUNDER OF THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia _ As the body of its president, Franjo Tudjman,
lay in state at the presidential palace Saturday, Croatia declared
three days of mourning, canceling sporting events and shutting down
movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Tudjman at 77, after a long struggle with stomach
cancer, was announced at 2 a.m. Saturday on state television, which
immediately began to broadcast somber music and prepared
documentaries about Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
   The country was well prepared for the death of the president,
who had been lying incommunicado in a suburban hospital for the
last six weeks. Still, as his body was driven to the presidential
palace Saturday morning in a hearse, attended by policemen on
motorcycles, many people lined the route in silence, with sober
faces, and some were in tears.
</P>
<P>
   Practically all day long, state television showed his coffin,
covered by a Croatian flag and surrounded by his various medals and
decorations, with a Croatian flag in flowers at the foot of the
bier and a pale wooden cross rising above it. Two guards in bright
red medieval uniforms stood by as various personages of the new
state, in black suits, took turns, by sixes, in standing by the
coffin. Ordinary citizens, many kneeling to cross themselves and
some wiping away tears, filed by to pay their respects.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman, who began his career as a partisan general and
Communist in the service of Tito's Yugoslav Federation, will be
buried as a Roman Catholic and Croatian nationalist. He lay in
state on the grounds of one of the loveliest villas owned by Tito,
whose penchant for the good life and for military uniforms was
emulated by Tudjman once he became one of the leaders who buried
Tito's creation, a Communist Yugoslavia whose ``brotherhood and
unity'' motto only papered over the nationalist rivalries that
later erupted into war.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's death comes in the middle of an important political
transition for Croatia, which he led to independence in 1991, and
ran with an authoritarian hand through his powerful political
party, the Croatian Democratic Union, known by its local acronym
HDZ.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy in trouble, many people unemployed and with
widespread allegations of corruption, both Tudjman and his party
were at low points in their popularity. Parliamentary elections due
on Jan. 3 were widely expected to result in the defeat of the HDZ
and the victory of an opposition coalition.
</P>
<P>
   During Tudjman's long illness, the party scheduled the elections
to try to take advantage of holiday good feelings, a shortened
campaign and the presence at home of Croats who normally work
abroad and are generally Tudjman supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The party is expected to continue to use the aura of Tudjman _
and the national mourning and state funeral and Mass now scheduled
for Monday _ to try to improve its electoral chances.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning was supposed to begin on Monday, but will now start
only after the funeral. Elections for a new president must be
concluded within 60 days, and it is not clear whether the HDZ will
have the first round of presidential voting on the same day as the
parliamentary election, separate it or even delay the parliamentary
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ivica Racan, a key opposition leader and leader of the Social
Democratic Party, expressed sorrow for Tudjman's passing and said:
``Without a doubt, Tudjman has marked modern Croatian history and
gave a lot to the creation of independent Croatia.'' At the same
time, Racan said that while he did not expect parliamentary
elections to be postponed, ``they will be on the border of
irregularity.''
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's party has not said whom it will nominate to succeed
him. The most popular of its possible candidates is the current
foreign minister, Mate Granic, who is Washington's favorite. Granic
praised Tudjman and emphasized his efforts to bring Croatia ``to
the threshold of European integration.'' Granic added, in words
used after Tito's death in 1980: ``We must continue on his way.''
</P>
<P>
   But even HDZ leaders say the new Parliament is now likely to
pass constitutional amendments weakening the role of the president.
Racan and the opposition say they would prefer a parliamentary
democracy, with a figurehead president.
</P>
<P>
   While Tudjman was vital to the settling of the conflict in
Bosnia and the 1995 signing of the Dayton peace accords, he helped
to keep Croatia more isolated from the West and the European Union
through his authoritarian style and repression of dissent and the
independent media.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's reluctance to cooperate with the International War
Crimes Tribunal in the Hague, his conviction that the West was out
to undermine Croatia's independence, his historical revisionism
about the crimes of Croatia's fascist regime during World War II
and his encouragement of the Bosnian Croats not to cooperate fully
with Bosnian Muslims angered Washington and the West. It is
unlikely that his funeral will be attended by Western officials at
the most senior levels _ in marked contrast to the almost
unparalleled gathering of world leaders when his model, Tito, was
buried.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The acting president, the parliamentary Speaker Vlatko Pavletic,
went on television to announce that ``the big heart of President
Franjo Tudjman has ceased to beat.'' Pavletic, who is said to
harbor his own presidential ambitions, told Croats to ``express
your tears freely,'' then added: ``But let us be prepared to
continue to build Croatia in accordance with her history and future
and faithful to the ideals of freedom and social justice.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the perceived lack of social justice _ with a narrow,
wealthy elite close to the ruling party and widespread poverty
below _ that has done the most harm to the reputation of Tudjman
and his party.
</P>
<P>
   A leader of the opposition Liberal Party, Bozo Kovacevic, said
that Tudjman gave much to the country. But after 1995, Kovacevic
said, ``he did more damage to Croatia than good,'' producing
``widespread corruption, nonfunctioning state institutions and
leading Croatia to international isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   At the European Union summit meeting in Helsinki, Finland,
Javier Solana, the European Union representative for foreign
affairs and security, said Tudjman's death should open the way for
change. ``We have to hope that the elections that will now take
place in Croatia, the new political situation, will help Croatia in
the direction of a democratic country,'' Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksandra Kolaric, a historian, said that with television so
somber and the theaters closed, she managed to rent three videos
for the mourning period. When she logged on to her internet news
group at just after 2 a.m., when Tudjman's death was announced, one
participant asked: ``What do we do now?'' The answer was immediate:
``Go to the video club.''
</P>
<P>
   But by noon, she said, her local shop was nearly out of videos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
