<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAEAST12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking note of the NBA Eastern Conference
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The numbers don't work on a trade of the Celtics'
Antoine Walker and Vitaly Potapenko for the 76ers' Theo Ratliff and
Larry Hughes, and the move was never discussed. But the plot
thickened when each side felt the other was floating the rumor in
an attempt to hurt the other.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia assistant coach (and former UMass leader) John
Calipari found himself in the middle of the mess for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a call asking if I did it,'' he said. ``I said, `Me? I
don't deal with those things.' I'm not involved in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixers head coach Larry Brown still remembers being passed by
Rick Pitino at the last second for the Celtics job, and you may
recall the Celts were not pleased with the way Philly backed out of
the Dino Radja trade in the summer of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   SHAQ'S OUT, 'ZO'S IN
</P>
<P>
   Unless Shaquille O'Neal has a surprising change of heart, center
Alonzo Mourning is expected to join Heat teammate Tim Hardaway on
next summer's U.S. Olympic men's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said Wednesday he will not play in the 2000 Olympics
because he wants to spend time with his young daughter. That makes
Mourning's addition to the roster highly likely. Among the nine
players already on the team, Tim Duncan is the only center.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING THROUGH
</P>
<P>
   How's this for resiliency: Heading into Saturday's games, Miami
is 135-61 over the past four years when playing without one of its
current starters. The Heat is 9-3 over that span without Hardaway,
9-1 without P.J. Brown, 44-16 without Jamal Mashburn, 41-17 without
Dan Majerle and 32-24 without Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   TOO DEPENDENT ON TWO
</P>
<P>
   Among coach Jeff Van Gundy's concerns is how poorly the Knicks
play when either Latrell Sprewell or Allan Houston struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When him and Allan both struggle on the same night, it's going
to be difficult for us,'' Van Gundy said. ``I'm a bit concerned
that they feel the burden to score even when they're double-teamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're being asked to play heavy minutes. There's no doubt
about that. At some point, I'm going to try to get it down to 38-39
minutes, but I know that when we take one of the two out, we go
right down the drain. So, that makes it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   MENDING SLOWLY
</P>
<P>
   Nets center Jayson Williams had hoped to come back in December,
but he recently conceded he won't be back before January, if at
all. ``My kneecap's just swimming around in my leg,'' said
Williams, who is on the mend from a broken leg suffered last
spring. Asked if he has considered missing the entire season,
Williams said, ``That runs in and out of your mind, but I don't
think I can go the whole summer without knowing how my leg feels.''
</P>
<P>
   BIRD'S COMEBACK
</P>
<P>
   Pacers coach Larry Bird made a comeback Wednesday when he played
four on four in what he said was his first competitive basketball
game since retiring in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bird, assistant Rick Carlisle and veterans Chris Mullin and
Derrick McKey took on Pacers youngsters Jonathan Bender, Al
Harrington, Jeff Foster and Zan Tabak. Bird's team won two of three
games, including the finale when Bird hit the last two shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to take the last shot. Even if we got beat,
I was going to take the last shot,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington argued that Bird cheated: ``They were fouling. And
they wouldn't give us the ball when we tried to call a foul. They
only gave us one foul call and that was when Carlisle threw Foster
out of bounds. And they didn't want to give us that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
