<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6043 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAFEATURE-BARKLE     12-11 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEATURE-BARKLEY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big, bold, Barkley
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Charles Barkley, the world got the truth, and it
was not always what you wanted to hear. It, in fact, was not always
right. But he said it because he believed it, and he seemed to
never be disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   So when he looked down at his distorted kneecap Wednesday night
in Philadelphia, Barkley told himself the terrible truth. ``It's
over,'' he said to himself.
</P>
<P>
   The injury, a ruptured knee tendon, was a devastating one that
very well could have ended his career if he were not planning to
quit after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen that type of injury before, but never above the
kneecap,'' said Philadelphia 76ers president Pat Croce, a licensed
physical therapist who was the Sixers' strength and conditioning
coach during the first eight seasons of Barkley's career with the
team. ``I never saw one where the muscle belly rolls up like a
Venetian blind.''
</P>
<P>
   So, returning after such an injury would have been difficult.
``It would take me coming back as his physical therapist,'' Croce
said. ``It would take a good year of rehabilitation. He has the
work ethic. He has a lot of work to do just to get full range of
motion in his knee. We knew we were seeing him for the last time on
a court here, but may have seen the last basketball by him on any
court.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that bad, but not impossible. ``This is something that
happens suddenly and violently, the muscle retracting in a jumping
motion,'' said Dr. Jack McPhilemy, the Sixers' orthopedic
specialist. ``That may have been what happened. He's 36, so it's
certainly going to be harder for him. If anybody could come back,
Charles could. This is not an injury you couldn't come back from.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, McPhilemy said he'd never seen a similar injury
sustained by an NBA player and never even heard of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be sitting here and thinking about coming back, but if
I look at reality, God always sends us little subliminal messages
we don't want to listen to,'' Barkley said. ``I do think in my
heart he wanted it to end here, where it started.''
</P>
<P>
   When Barkley went down, close friend Allen Lumpkin, the 76ers'
director of travel and team services, hurried to the locker room.
``I went in to help, as I would with any injured player,'' Lumpkin
said. ``But when I saw his knee, I got queasy. His kneecap wasn't
where it was supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had the time of his life playing in the NBA, perhaps
like no one who was so good. He enjoyed himself. He talked to fans
at the games, joked with reporters. He laughed with and at his
foes. He clowned with teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of Barkley was less pleasing. He was a night owl
who got into his share of altercations that led him to a court
room. He could be vulgar and insensitive and reactive.
</P>
<P>
   And, boy, could he talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys have seen me go from a boy to a man, do some good
things, some great things, some stupid things,'' he said.
``Everybody does those things. . . . But I have no regrets. I have
nothing but 16 years of great memories. I've been all over the
world, I've met unbelievable people who I would never have gotten
the opportunity to meet. I met some of the best actors in the
world, I met some of the best athletes in the world, I met
presidents, Bishop (Desmond) Tutu. I met just regular people who
made an impact on my life. I played in two Olympics. I've exceeded
all my expectations, all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As confident and as cocky as you have to be to be great at
something, I still never expected to accomplish and do the things I
did. I have no sadness in my heart. I'm proud that I feel like I
was a great player for a long time, helped the league grow, helped
young guys to mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'll always be a 76er deep in my heart. If I'm
fortunate enough to go to the Hall of Fame, it would be as a 76er.
I guess that's the big fella's way of working things out for you. I
said it was definitely over before the season started. This kind of
seals it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
