<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAITEM12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stackhouse makes Mom proud
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse left North Carolina
after his second season in 1995, he promised his mother that he
would earn his college degree. Next Saturday, Stackhouse keeps his
promise.
</P>
<P>
   He will participate in the UNC commencement exercises and
receive his B.A. in African American Studies. A potential snafu _
the Pistons play at home against Philadelphia that night _ was
avoided when the team said it was OK for him to fly to Chapel Hill
for the 2 p.m. event and then fly back in time for the 7:30 p.m.
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream come true for me,'' Stackhouse said. ``This is
really an exciting time for me and my family, and I'm thankful to
the Pistons for helping to make this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Pistons coach Alvin Gentry said: ``We are really proud of Jerry.
For him to leave school early and be able to complete his degree
this soon is really an accomplishment. It is a testament to his
maturity, and he and his family should be very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons will honor Stackhouse during the game, calling the
event the ``Stackhouse Graduation Party.'' There will be several
related promotions, including free admission to any fan who wears a
graduation cap and gown.
</P>
<P>
   BARKLEY ENEMIES? NOT
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, Charles Barkley fought with the Lakers'
Shaquille O'Neal. Two years ago, he was one of the more vocal
players lambasting the 76ers' Allen Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of Barkley's season- and career-ending knee
injury, both players expressed nothing but respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people put in that nonsense that because he doesn't
have a (championship) ring, he's not a great player,'' O'Neal said.
``Barkley's a good friend, good person, good player. I'm going to
miss him. He's always going to be one of the greatest forwards
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Iverson: ``People already think me and Charles are fuming,
and we're not. I talked to him, hugged him, told him I loved him
and that I'm sorry things happened like that. ``It was just sad for
me to see him, knowing I said some negative things about him, some
things I didn't mean, some things I just said out of frustration,
and probably vice-versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Barkley is somebody that made me want to play this
game. Michael Jordan, Magic Johnson, Isiah Thomas, Larry Bird _
those guys made me want to play the game. I have a lot of respect
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To Houston's Charles Barkley. He could rub you the wrong way,
but he played the game like few others and, in the wake of a
career-ending injury that would have sent many into hiding, held a
news conference where he was his typical revealing self.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal. He said he'll blow off an
Olympic team invitation so that he can rest in the offseason. Rest
is understandable, but for someone who can't make a foul shot,
you'd think he'd jump at the chance to work at that aspect of his
game _ and represent the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
