<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAWEST12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking note of the NBA Western Conference
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Target Center security staff dealt with a couple
of hecklers during a Timberwolves loss to the Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, sitting at courtside, started the stink by mouthing
off to referee Ron Olesiak, who had ejected Wolves coach Flip
Saunders. Olesiak then asked that the fan be removed. That was when
the real festivities ensued.
</P>
<P>
   From about 20 rows up, a large bald man in a fringed leather
jacket, jeans and sneakers walked toward the court and hollered at
Olesiak, at the security guards and at the Minneapolis police
officers. He wanted Olesiak arrested (he wasn't) and he wanted the
first troublemaker to keep his seat (he did).
</P>
<P>
   While all this is going on ,16,661 were chanting, ``Jesse!
Jesse!''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura probably would have been locked up himself if he
weren't the governor of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   JUST SQUEAKING BY
</P>
<P>
   Portland won its first six by an average margin of 20.2 points.
Since then, the Blazers have been slowed by injuries, poor shooting
and an inability to get the ball inside consistently. After
shooting 50.8 percent from the field in their first 10 games, they
have shot 41.5 percent in the last 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been feeling good about the wins,'' guard Steve
Smith said. ``We've been sort of lucky. We've just been squeaking
by.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a funk,'' said Brian Grant.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE WHAMMY
</P>
<P>
   A flop on the road over the past three seasons at 5-82, imagine
how giddy they were in Denver when the Nuggets beat the Knicks and
76ers in a span of two nights.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets' Ron Mercer, who missed three games with a case of
the flu, badly wanted to play against the Celtics Wednesday. And he
played very badly _ 1-for-6 from the field, two points and two
turnovers, two shots blocked by Paul Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   MAD ABOUT LOSING
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver's road losing streak was stopped at 30, 13 shy of
Sacramento's record. Victory came in Dallas, 104-95. There wasn't
much in the way of celebration, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny, the feeling in the locker room wasn't one of
euphoria as you might think, because these guys expected to win a
lot more games than we have,'' beleaguered coach Brian Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a sense of relief, it was almost a sense of anger
that we should have had one last week, which I kind of like because
it shows me the character and competitiveness of the guys in the
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Grizzlies general manager Stu Jackson isn't returning calls so
he won't have to talk about Hill's future.
</P>
<P>
   BRYANT BUMBLES ALONG
</P>
<P>
   After winning seven in a row, the Lakers were undone, in part,
by a rusty Kobe Bryant. Back in the lineup, Bryant scored 27 points
but turned the ball over six times and the triangle offense ground
to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   On his turnovers, Bryant said, ``I hate it, I hate it, I hate
it, I hate it. You want to try so bad to make up for it. Try to
cancel that and get that out of your game as much as you can. But
you just have to study it and see why that happens in certain
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Lakers are looking better and better. After they
romped on Orlando, Magic coach Doc Rivers said, ``I like
</P>
<P>
   them a lot. I told Dave (Wohl, assistant coach) sitting on the
bench, 'Man, they're better than I thought. They're really good.'
They're good because their system is good and they believe in it. I
think (Shaquille O'Neal) 100 percent believes in his coach (Phil
Jackson) for the first time in his career.''
</P>
<P>
   325 POUNDS OF MILLER
</P>
<P>
   Here are Suns center Oliver Miller's numbers: 57 percent
shooting, 5.3 points, 4.5 rebounds, 1.27 blocks, 325 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has made no progress since training camp in his
never-ending battle to control his weight. His goal was to be in
the 290s by opening night.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix coach Danny Ainge, who wants Miller at 300 or less,
says, ``His attitude has been great. He's saying all the right
things.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a but here. ``He hasn't convinced me. You're not going
to convince me completely if you're 25 pounds overweight.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
