<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hatch's advice to Bush: Stick with me, kid, you'll go places
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The last Republican presidential debate of 1999
gives Texas Gov. George W. Bush a chance to ease growing concerns
about his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley, meanwhile, will meet in
Manchester, N.H., Friday in a debate despite Bradley's recent
monitoring for an irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP debate Monday in Des Moines, Iowa, will be the third in
three weeks for the Republicans. And Bush's performance in the
first two has raised questions about his once seemingly inevitable
march to the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He now trails Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) in several New
Hampshire polls, although Bush is leading by a wide margin in most
other states.
</P>
<P>
   The debate last Monday in Arizona produced the most memorable
line of the campaign season so far. Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah),
barely registering in most polls, told Bush he needs more
experience to be president and could get it as his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should be president,'' Hatch said. ``You should have eight
years with me and, boy, you'd make a heck of a president after
eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   FORBES HAMMERS BUSH OVER STREET DEDICATION
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes continued jabbing at Bush on the abortion issue,
calling on the governor Thursday to rescind legislation renaming a
portion of a Texas road for a doctor who performed abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no justification for a self-described pro-life
Republican governor to celebrate and honor an abortionist. This
raises serious questions about George W. Bush's commitment to the
pro-life cause,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   But the doctor in question, the late John B. Coleman, was known
for more than his willingness to perform abortions at the Houston
clinic he owned. Coleman was a pioneering African-American
gynecologist whose financial support was essential for black
candidates in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman's clinic was the target of arsonists in 1985, and
anti-abortion groups protested his appointment as a regent of Texas
A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN PLAYING HARDBALL TO GET ON N.Y. STATE BALLOT
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Thursday he will file a lawsuit to force a change in
the ``confusing and Byzantine'' presidential primary process before
New York state's March 7 primary. New York requires that candidates
qualify by obtaining signatures in each of its 31 congressional
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Other states, including Georgia, require only a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Only Bush and Forbes expect to be on the ballot in all 31
districts. Four years ago, Forbes successfully sued to be included
in 25 of the 31 districts.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and most of the state's GOP leadership are
supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA GOP FEELING PINCH FROM BUSH'S FUND-RAISING
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fund-raising juggernaut has made it harder for some state
parties to raise money, Georgia GOP Chairman Chuck Clay said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised $1.7 million through just three events in
Georgia, part of the record-setting $60 million his campaign has
taken in this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that a lot of the financial elite in Buckhead that
have really ponied up for Bush haven't given aso the (state)
party,'' Clay said. ``We probably would have received some of that
money at some point this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay said he expects the party will raise $1.2 million in 1999,
no better than what the party raised in 1997, the last year without
a major election in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   GOP POLLSTER OFFERS TIPS ON HOW TO TALK WITH JEWS
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Frank Luntz's latest missive to the
Republican Jewish Coalition suggests a number of unsubtle ways for
GOP candidates to win the votes of Democratic-leaning Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Charlton Heston as Moses graces the cover page of Luntz's
research report, which he calls ``The Four Questions and 10 More.''
The title is a play on a segment of the Passover Seder.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty more schmaltz to be found inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jews listen attentively for the personal angle,'' Luntz writes
in advising candidates to show more heart when they talk to Jews.
</P>
<P>
   His major point is that Republicans must alter their style, not
their policies, to win Jewish votes. ``Republicans show too much
anger and not enough heart for the typical Jewish voter,'' he
writes.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz, who could not be reached for comment, argues that
Republicans can overcome some stands on social issues that many
Jewish voters find distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro-life Republican candidates, if they use less divisive
social language, can win a significant portion of Jewish support if
they are vocally and unconditionally pro-Israel,'' Luntz says.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish voters are concentrated in California, Florida and New
York, where Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is poised to run for the U.S.
Senate against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. Giuliani, a Luntz
client, outpolled his Democratic challenger among Jews in the last
mayoral election.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA DEMOCRAT HOPING TO RECLAIM SEAT
</P>
<P>
   Five seats stand between the Democrats and control of the House
of Representatives next year. The Democrats hope to nearly erase
that gap in just one state, California.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to a crop of candidates that give Democrats a strong shot
in three other California districts, former Rep. Jane Harman said
last week that she will seek her old seat against freshman
Republican Steve Kuykendall in the beachfront communities of Los
Angeles. Harman has plenty of money to make the race. She spent $16
million of her husband's stereo components fortune in a losing bid
for governor last year.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates hold similar views, moderate to conservative on
economic issues, in favor of gun control and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
