</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MEAT-ECOLI _ WASHINGTON _ The USDA's 'science-based' inspection
system doesn't test for several strains of e. coli bacteria that
scientists with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention now
say may cause half the e. coli illnesses in America. While food
safety efforts have focused on the infamous 0157:H7 strain that
killed two children in the Jack-In-The-Box outbreak in 1993, its
toxic cousins _ strains once found only overseas _ have begun
appearing here. ``I've been screaming about the non-0157 strains
for years and nobody listened,'' said the head of the Food Safety
Initiative at Tufts University. (Montgomery/Jaspin, Cox News
Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCE-MEMORIAL _ WASHINGTON _ Rallying his troops by e-mail,
retired Marine Gen. Charles G. Cooper warns, ``we're in the assault
phase of this momentous battle.'' His foe: the United States Air
Force. The Air Force has won most of the early skirmishes, but ``we
are dug in and determined,'' said Cooper. The battle is over
control of a strategic Virginia ridge overlooking the Potomac
River. The Air Force chose this prime spot near the rows of somber
white crosses at Arlington National Cemetery to build a memorial.
But the Marine Corps charges that the site is too close to its
famed Iwo Jima Memorial. (Dart, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Monday.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE _ WASHINGTON _ Over all, are schools this year
reacting sensibly to the shootings last spring? Educators, law
enforcement officials, software and hardware vendors, public
officials, parent of a murdered child, and teacher who was shot
while shielding a student comment. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
