<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA SUSPENDS ASSAULT ON GROZNY, OFFERS TO EVACUATE RESIDENTS
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW Bowing to international pressure, Russia temporarily
suspended its siege of the Chechen capital Grozny on Saturday and
offered to help evacuate thousands of residents trapped by weeks of
air and artillery attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The offer came after harsh criticism from the United States and
other western countries of a Saturday deadline Russia had set for
inhabitants of Grozny to flee or else die under a promised
onslaught of invading Russian forces. On Friday, Russian officials
eased that ultimatum and said they were willing to negotiate with
Chechen officials on a settlement to spare civilian lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our ultimatum to the bandits, and a warning to
civilians, so they could leave the city,'' Russian Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin said Saturday. ``We gave a warning, and created
conditions for people to leave,'' he said, according to the
ITAR-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Putin vowed that Russia will resume its offensive ``if (the
militants) do not lay down their arms.'' The Russian news agency
Interfax reported that military operations, including air strikes,
would begin again after midnight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin is reportedly eager to capture Grozny prior to
national parliamentary elections set for Dec. 19 (next Sunday). The
three-month long war against Chechnya enjoys widespread support
among the Russian public.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 40,000 residents, including many elderly and infirm,
remain in Grozny. Among them are some 4,000 guerrillas, according
to Russian and United Nations estimates.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Russian official, Emergencies Minister Sergei Shoigu,
flew to the border region of Chechnya on Saturday to assemble truck
convoys to meet civilians willing to flee Grozny. He also made a
radio appeal beamed into Chechnya asking locals to assist in
arranging a mass exodus from the city.
</P>
<P>
   A safe passage leading from the city to the town of
Pervomaiskaya, 12 miles northwest of the capital, was opened
Tuesday, but few Chechens have taken the route. Russian officials
said a second route was being arranged on Saturday, southwest
through the Grozny suburb of Chernorechye and the town of
Alkhan-Yurt.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday marked the fifth anniversary since Russian troops
launched their first broad action in Chechnya in 1994 to crush its
bid to create an independent Islamic state. At least 30,000 people
are believed to have died in that conflict - now called the First
Chechen War -- which ended in 1996 with a humiliating retreat by
Russian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The latest war began three months ago after Russian blamed
Chechen militants for a series of bombings of apartment buildings
in Moscow and other cities that left about 300 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Casualty figures resulting from the Russian offensive have been
difficult to assess, but international human rights groups have
condemned the military for indiscriminately bombing civilians and
creating a refugee crisis in neighboring Ingushetia, where more
than 200,000 Chechen refugees have fled.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said the operation would continue until a stable Chechnya
is brought back into the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end-game of Russia's policy in Chechnya is to normalize
the life of the people and restore law and order based on the
constitution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe there is little resistance remaining in Grozny,
as militants have fled into the mountains of southern Chechnya not
controlled by Russia forces. But Russian military commanders want
to avoid a repeat of the fierce street battles with rebels who
inflicted heavy casualties during the 1994-96 war.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Valery Manilov, first deputy chief of staff, said
Saturday on Russian television that ``unorthodox action'' would be
taken to capture Grozny, but he added that the operation would not
involve ``a frontal storm or massive strikes.'' Leaflets dropped on
Grozny on Monday warning residents to flee the city or die seemed
to promise devastation. According to reports from the city, roughly
80 percent of buildings already have been destroyed or damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny will be taken with minimum losses on December 20, said
Beslan Gantamirov, the commander of Chechen volunteers who are
fighting on the side of Russian forces. He made the remarks in an
interview published Saturday in the newspaper Kommersant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
