<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD SORE SPOT FURTHER IRRITATES U.S.-CHINESE RELATIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's strong protest over two recent American laws
promoting Taiwan's participation in the World Health Organization
is the latest sign that Chinese-American relations have soured
since the countries reached a landmark trade agreement less than
one month ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Ministry summoned a senior diplomat from the
American Embassy on Friday and accused the United States of
``seriously infringing upon China's sovereignty and grossly
interfering in China's internal affairs,'' according to a report by
the New China News Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwan is a province of China,'' the deputy foreign minister,
Yang Jiechi, reportedly told the American charge d'affaires, Eugene
Martin, ``and under international law does not have the right to
join the international organizations for which statehood is
required.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan lost its U.N. seat to the mainland in 1971 and has been
excluded ever since from major affiliated agencies like the health
organization. But China has acquiesced to Taiwan's involvement in
some international technical and economic groups.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States does not recognize Taiwan, in practice
it has close ties and provides defensive military aid. But on
numerous occasions, the United States has assured China that it
will not support Taiwan's membership in the United Nations or its
major agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In signing the recent laws, President Clinton agreed to report
to Congress on efforts to promote Taiwan's participation in the
global health agency and other organizations. The administration is
under pressure from Congress to provide broader support for Taiwan,
and officials apparently hoped to finesse the issue by pushing for
Taiwanese involvement short of formal membership.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, China accused the United States of ``playing
semantics in order to help Taiwan squeeze into'' such
organizations. Yang said the laws ``completely violate'' American
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   China knows that hostile sentiment is rising in Congress, but it
appeared to feel especially betrayed by President Clinton's signing
of the bills, which Friday's protest mentioned specifically.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 15, top American and Chinese officials toasted their
sweeping agreement on terms for China's entry into the World Trade
Organization. But the afterglow was short-lived. American
condemnation of China's all-out suppression of pro-democracy
activities and of the Falun Gong spiritual group has caused
tension. Last week, the American Embassy here protested when it
became known that a democracy advocate, Fu Sheng, had been detained
and beaten after meeting the embassy's human rights officer.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, at the close of a short visit by President Boris Yeltsin
of Russia, China and Russia issued a joint statement filled with
attacks on American foreign policy. The statement said that
unidentified parties, obviously the United States, are trying to
force on the world ``a single model of culture, value concepts and
ideology'' and are violating the sovereignty of countries under the
guise of ``humanitarian intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials hope that the November trade agreement will
provide a concrete ``anchor'' for Chinese-American relations. On
his arrival in Beijing on Thursday night, Joseph Prueher, the newly
appointed ambassador, said, ``Our common interests transcend the
issues that keep us apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
