<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-E.U.-MILITARY-(2TAKES     12-11 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E.U.-MILITARY-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH SAY ARMS PLAN FINALLY MAKES EUROPE A PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ By equipping itself with the ability to send up to
60,000 troops to a crisis zone like Bosnia or Kosovo, the 15-nation
European Union will finally become a strategic player that the
United States will have to reckon with, say French defense
officials, who have long chafed under U.S. military and strategic
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders adopted the plan in Helsinki, Finland, on
Friday, giving themselves until 2003 to build the command and
planning staffs, the intelligence bases, and the decision-making
and deployment apparatus needed to realize their new ambition.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have cautiously welcomed the plan, but put the
Europeans on guard against diluting the strength of the U.S.-led
NATO alliance by duplicating its structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``What fear of duplication really conceals is worry about the
appearance of a new political partner, the European Union,'' the
French defense minister, Alain Richard, said in an interview.
``It's a new situation that's a bit disturbing, that upsets old
habits, because at the moment, inside the Atlantic Alliance, there
are only dispersed European states _ the only common, cohesive
element is NATO itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The allied military structure is led and dominated by the United
States, so much so that Richard said it would eventually sap the
alliance unless Europeans pulled themselves up by their bootstraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Europe takes on more responsibility by building up its
military strength, that will contribute to the long-term
equilibrium of the Alliance,'' he said. ``Now the European Union is
stepping up to its responsibilities and over the next few years
will become a genuine actor on the scene, one that didn't exist
before.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other French officials said that the military
headquarters that the European Union would set up in Brussels,
Belgium, would be nowhere near the size of the NATO military staff.
A European military secretariat reporting to Javier Solana, former
secretary-general of the alliance, will decide how many military
planners the European Union needed, Richard said. ``I'm persuaded
that it should be basically rather modest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other French officials said a small European general staff would
probably number no more than a few hundred officers, who would draw
heavily on planning done by their counterparts in the member
states.
</P>
<P>
   The new European defense structure would also include a military
committee of chiefs of participating national defense staffs to
advise the European political leaders, who would decide when and
where to send forces. The 60,000 troops earmarked for European use
in a crisis would be the same ones that NATO could use if it
decided to get involved, French officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to depend in part on national resources, and in part
on NATO,'' Richard said, adding that the European plan was fully
consistent with a plan adopted at the NATO summit meeting in
Washington last April to improve the effectiveness of future
multinational military operations like the bombing campaign in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The requirements, the performance levels, the expected
specifications are all the same,'' Richard said. ``There will still
be a little duplication,'' he conceded, but he said it would be
minimal.
</P>
<P>
   The United States should help contribute to a new strategic
balance within the alliance by allowing the U.S. military to buy
more arms from European defense industries, Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told our American friends several times that in our
opinion, and this isn't just a French view, even if it's
unintended, security regulations and limits on access to the
American market are a real impediment to the existence of a
trans-Atlantic market,'' he said. ``It's a delicate subject,
because it has to do with national security concerns that are
legitimate and respectable, and it's not a subject that will be
solved with loud public discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials in Europe agree. But strong European uneasiness
and resentment of U.S. strategic, technological and economic
superiority has led to fears of a resurgence of anti-Americanism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiery rhetoric and anti-American tirades by some senior
leaders in Europe complicate this situation immensely, and are
difficult to ignore on our side of the Atlantic,'' Jacques Gansler,
a senior Pentagon official, warned a gathering of French defense
industrialists in Toulouse the week before last.
</P>
<P>
   Gansler said the United States wanted more trans-Atlantic
defense industry cooperation but insisted that effective safeguards
by the allies over the U.S. technology they wanted were ``an
absolute prerequisite.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard said, ``I think the United States side needs to think
about this to see if they aren't in danger of closing the American
market to European producers.'' In Washington, France has not been
seen as being as trustworthy as Britain in handling U.S. defense
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Britain, which long refused to discuss with its
European partners any security arrangements outside NATO, that
finally allowed France to achieve its longstanding ambition to lead
Europe to a modest autonomous defense capability.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain agreed on that objective
with President Jacques Chirac more than a year ago, setting the
stage for European leaders to adopt the plan last June in Cologne,
Germany, and spell it out this weekend in Helsinki.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of Britain and other allies, including Germany
and the Netherlands, the leaders agreed that Europe would deploy
forces on its own only in situations where the alliance, meaning in
effect the United States, had decided not to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the condition, that's the agreement,'' Richard said,
adding that he had told Secretary of Defense William Cohen in
Brussels early this month that France and the United States were
pulling on the same string by insisting that some of the allies
should increase defense spending, for NATO's sake as well as
Europe's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's not realistic for Europeans to say we are
spending enough and that all we need to do is create more synergy
and achieve more efficient cooperation,'' Richard said. ``I think
that in spending on new equipment we are falling short.
Pragmatically, without forcing them, we have to persuade a certain
number of our partners to make a bit bigger commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   According to alliance figures, the United States spends about
3.2 percent of its gross domestic product on defense, down from 6
percent during the Cold War, with France and Britain spending 2.8
percent and 2.6 percent respectively. But Germany spends only 1.5
percent and Spain only 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Richard said that Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping of Germany
was arguing against continued defense cuts. ``There are political
obligations, and the defense system, by its size and the level of
resources that it has, must be consistent with them,'' Richard said
of the defense spending debate in Germany. ``I'm convinced that
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   France, another French defense official said, would press its
European partners to set spending targets for buying the new
satellite-based navigation and guidance systems, fighter planes,
and transport aircraft that would be needed to make a European
fighting force fully deployable within 60 days, the target set by
the Helsinki plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be easier, actually, for the Europeans to agree not to
fall below these spending targets than it would be for them to
agree to them as part of a NATO plan,'' this official said. ``There
they could always fall short and say the United States had pressed
them to accept unrealistic goals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
