<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One thumb down
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At least one team was against the NHL's plan to go
with two referees per game: Tampa Bay, which is the unofficial
league leaders in whining about penalties this season.
</P>
<P>
   Several Lightning players are convinced referees are out to get
them, and coach Steve Ludzik said the lack of consistency on calls
between the two game officials in the two-ref system creates more
harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a game earlier this year when Fredrik Modin was pulled
down in our end by Eric Lindros and nothing was called and that was
fine,'' Ludzik said. ``But then Modin, to catch up to Lindros in
the other end, hooked Lindros and he was called for a penalty. The
one referee let go the Lindros penalty but the other in his half of
the ice called one on Modin. It should've been a (tit for tat) type
of thing. I've seen that a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Team captain Chris Gratton said of the team's recent rash of
penalties, ``We're on a really tight leash. We've had a couple of
incidents, but we have to forget all that. We're not going to get
any close calls go our way it seems but we have to get past that.''
This comes from a guy who yelled at referee Lance Roberts to,
``Open your eyes!'' after a non-call. A fine example by the team
captain.
</P>
<P>
   AN ARM FOR AN ARM?
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Maple Leafs, upset after Pittsburgh goalie Tom
Barrasso slashed leading scorer Yanick Perreault, breaking a bone
in the center's left forearm, were livid after Colin Campbell
suspended Barrasso for only four games. Perreault could be out two
months. ``I'm glad the league did something,'' Perreault said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But four games? I will be out 20 to 22 games. ... My goal was
to score. His goal didn't seem to be to stop me because he wasn't
going for the puck. I'm not saying he intended to break my arm, but
he didn't go for my skates, which is usually what the goalies do on
that play.''
</P>
<P>
   Perreault had surgery that used a metal plate and six screws to
help mend the bone. He will need another operation to remove the
plate later this winter.
</P>
<P>
   SHEPPARD NOT HAPPY
</P>
<P>
   The honeymoon is over for Ray Sheppard in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Signed as an unrestricted free agent, Sheppard now is
complaining about not getting enough ice time with the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   At least one teammate or coach wasn't thrilled with him. They
stuck a press credential in his locker, as in, ``Take a seat in the
box.'' ... The comments from Sheppard that upset coach Terry
Murray: ``I'm not used in the (same) capacity that I've been for
all of my career. I've always played the first or second line and
have always played on the first unit on the power play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
