<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLFEATURE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for a miracle
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Twenty years ago, mere months before the miracle,
aspiring members of the U.S. Olympic hockey team had a Christmas
gift exchange. The idea was that each player would draw a name out
of a hat and buy a present for that person.
</P>
<P>
   Don Waddell, then a talented defenseman from Northern Michigan,
drew Herb Brooks. It goes without saying that several teammates
jumped at the opportunity to aid Waddell in his gift selection. The
final decision was about what you would expect: a whip and a sign
reading, ``Ayatollah.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' reaction?
</P>
<P>
   ``Interesting,'' was all Waddell, now the Thrashers general
manager, would say.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' work at the ensuing 1980 Olympics in Lake Placid is
woven in gold in sports history. The U.S. victory over the Soviet
Union and the gold medal recently was chosen as the No. 1 sports
moment of the century by Sports Illustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach hasn't been involved in a miracle since _ unless you
count what happened last week. Pittsburgh general manager Craig
Patrick, an assistant to Brooks on the '80 team, fired a terrific
coach, Kevin Constantine, and replaced him with Brooks, who had
been scouting for the Penguins the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give the game back to the players,'' Brooks
said. ``I don't believe in suffocating them and treating them like
a bunch of robots. Hockey should be fun. We're in the entertainment
business, let's face it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Patrick plans for this to be a short-term solution, it might
work. Jaromir Jagr despised Constantine and his structured,
defensive systems and seemingly had quit playing the past few
games. The change will serve as a natural motivator for several
players who felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   But long term? Forget it. Brooks is 62 and hasn't coached in the
NHL since going 40-37-7 with New Jersey in 1992-93. Even with that,
he is under .500 all-time (190-198-61) in stints with the Devils,
New York Rangers (1981-85) and Minnesota North Stars (1987-88).
</P>
<P>
   Constantine knew he was cooked when Patrick never offered him a
contract extension beyond this season. But what more could this guy
have done?
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins don't have the talent they had during their Stanley
Cup years and goalie Tom Barrasso no longer ranks among the
league's elite. Constantine got Pittsburgh to the playoffs the past
two years with records of 40-24-18 (a Northeast Division title) and
38-30-14 despite Mario Lemieux's retirement, Ron Francis's exit,
Petr Nedved's yearlong holdout, a mediocre defense and, oh yes,
severe financial constraints that eventually led to bankruptcy and
rumors of a franchise relocation.
</P>
<P>
   This season? Things weren't great. But the inmates were starting
to run the asylum. Constantine sensed his players had quit on him
last week, yelling to them following a 5-2 loss to San Jose: ``If
you're trying to get me fired, you're doing a good job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   They succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Expect Brooks to try to step up the tempo. More forechecking,
more wide-open play. ``We agree on a lot of philosophies,'' Patrick
said, ``and I believe he is a better fit for what we have on the
ice. I believe he can get the best out of what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was at a transmission shop last week getting the fluid
changed in his car when he was told by somebody at the station he
had a phone call. It was Patrick, the only person other than
Brooks' wife who knew where he was.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity knocks again. The Penguins need a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
