<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unhappy Czech mates
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two short-term Thrashers, Vladimir Vujtek and Martin
Prochazka, were among the Czech natives who sounded off about their
negative experiences in the NHL to the Prague Post. Vujtek suffered
a 200-stitch gash and a concussion in an exhibition game and did
not recover enough physically or mentally to satisfy coach Curt
Fraser or general manager Don Waddell. The two also believed
Prochazka didn't adapt to the NHL game after several good years in
the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Prochazka said, ``I've played on the left wing for seven years,
but when I came to Atlanta, they had me on some paper as a right
wing, and no one cared any more. Their attitude toward us was just
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Vujtek, who also had brief stops with Montreal, Edmonton and
Tampa Bay, said, ``I won't ever try to play overseas again. I'm
taking the gash as a final warning.''
</P>
<P>
   He also felt he was misled by the team: ``The coaches claimed at
training camp that they would count on me and Martin and that we
would play in one front line. Unfortunately, it wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   SIX PACKS
</P>
<P>
   There is not a direct correlation between success and penalty
minutes (or lack there of). Consider the Kings and Sharks, who are
two of the league's better teams but are among the most penalized.
The following are the six most and least penalized teams, with
average minutes per game, and their winning percentages (through
Thursday).
</P>
<P>
   TOP SIX
</P>
<P>
   TeamPMPct.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta17.8.308
</P>
<P>
   San Jose17.6.545
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay17.0.407
</P>
<P>
   Chicago16.7.321
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles16.6.643
</P>
<P>
   Calgary16.5.411
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM SIX
</P>
