<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-670&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA PERSISTS WITH ITS VOW TO DESTROY REBELS IN GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAVKAZ CHECKPOINT, Russia _ A top commander of Russian forces in
Chechnya said Saturday that the Russian military was determined to
destroy the Islamic militants in Grozny by the end of the winter,
signaling that while the Russians have backed off from threats to
bombard the Chechen capital this weekend, they still seek an early
and decisive victory over the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't allow them to survive the winter,'' Maj. Gen.
Vladimir A. Shamanov, who commands the Western Group of Russian
Forces, said of the rebel force in Grozny, which was heavily hit in
the 1994-96 war in Chechnya and whose marketplace has been reduced
to rubble by the current bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military units have surrounded the Chechen capital. And
early last week, the Russian military spurred an international
outcry by dropping thousands of leaflets in the besieged Chechen
capital urging the unknown number of civilians there to leave by
Saturday or risk terrifying bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military quickly backed away from the ultimatum. But
it has not changed its overall strategy: seizing Grozny and chasing
the remnants of the Chechen rebel force and its core of Islamic
militants into the mountains near Georgia, Chechnya's southern
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Shamanov is one of the leading architects of Russia's military
campaign in Chechnya and a hawk on the Chechen question. He met
with a small group of reporters at a checkpoint at the border
between the Chechen republic and Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He is a popular figure in the army and said last month that he
would rip the epaulets off his uniform in protest if the military
is stopped from completing its campaign in Chechnya. He has
described the 1994-1996 war as a betrayal. He was recently
hospitalized with exhaustion, but appeared vigorous Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the current war, Shamanov's force entered Chechnya from
Ingushetia, driving to the Argun river to link up with the Eastern
Group. That link effectively blocked Grozny and separated Chechnya
into two theaters: Grozny, and the settlements to the south that
stretch to the mountainous border with Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, cars and buses of Chechen refugees shuttled back
and forth across the border. About 79,000 Chechen refugees have
fled to Ingushetia through this checkpoint, but about 56,000 have
since returned, according to Col. Anatoly N. Khrulyov, the
commander of the Kavkaz checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers would suggest that conditions are rough in the
refugee camps in Ingushetia, and that many people feel the
situation in Chechnya may be stable enough _ under Russian control
_ to return. The colonel added, however, that some refugees do
appear afraid to go back to Chechnya until it is clear who is in
charge in the breakaway region, where the 1994-96 war ended with an
agreement only to leave its status _ officially that of a Russian
republic _ in limbo until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   There still appears to be much fighting ahead, however,
particularly over Grozny. Shamanov said that the city remains a
strategic objective, not because it is the Chechen capital but
because several thousand rebels are believed to have taken refuge
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grozny is not gold,'' he said. ``Our task is to destroy the
organized resistance of the bandits and terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the thousands of civilians in Grozny, however, has
complicated that task. Nobody knows for sure how many people reside
in Grozny. Shamanov estimated that there were up to 7,000 civilians
in the city, but Nikolai Koshman, Russia's deputy prime minister
for Chechnya, has said there may be as many as 50,000. Grozny was
home to almost 400,000 people in the 1980s. A large but unknown
number of its residents have left since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Russian military hoped to scare residents in
Grozny to leave by issuing its ultimatum. Now, it has dropped its
explicit threats and has sought instead to expedite the evacuation
of the city.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A corridor for refugees has been established leading north from
the city through the town of Pervomaiskaya and a new corridor was
inaugurated Saturday that leads south to Alkhan-Yurt. Alkhan-Yurt
lies on a major highway that crossed the Caucasus, and a checkpoint
there to process refugees was opened Saturday with great fanfare by
Sergei Shoigu, Russia's minister for emergency situations and a
leading politician in next weekend's parliamentary elections in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage civilians to leave, the Russian military has not
bombed Grozny for five or six days and it has promised not to bomb
the corridors. Only a trickle of refugees has crossed through the
northern checkpoint, and no refugees appeared Saturday in
Alkhan-Yurt, probably because there was no prior notification in
Grozny that it was being established.
</P>
<P>
   Shamanov declined to say precisely how long the Russian military
would wait before resuming its bombardment of Grozny, but he said
there would be no bombing attacks there ``in the near future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1432EST &QL; 
