<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McCAIN-CAMPAIGN-915(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDERDOG McCAIN DEVELOPS ANTI-CAMPAIGN STYLE  
(lb) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John McCain is not just running against Washington.
He seems to be running with great glee against all the conventions
of modern campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of repeating one carefully scripted ``message of the
day,'' the Arizona senator may well spout a hundred messages,
depending on what voters ask him at his free-wheeling town
meetings. He long ago tossed away a stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has McCain taken a poll since last January _ mostly because
his cash-poor campaign cannot afford it. But he has turned this
into a virtue, telling audiences: ``I will never be driven by a
poll in conduct of American security policy, I promise you that.''
</P>
<P>
   And while these days, other presidential candidates keep a wary
distance from journalists, rationing interviews like treats for
starving dogs, McCain practically stalks reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As candidates once did, he constantly invites more questions _
even after every conceivable subject has been exhausted, from
national security policy to big tobacco to poetry to sports to
books to World War I to his favorite food.
</P>
<P>
   In short, if Bill Clinton was the master politician who
transformed strategists like James Carville into cult figures and
brought campaign stagecraft to a new high gloss, then McCain is
running as the blunt anti-politician who won't lie, who won't spin.
</P>
<P>
   And in the wake of the Lewinsky scandal, audiences in New
Hampshire are eating it up. For the first time last week, a series
of polls showed McCain surging ahead of Gov. George W. Bush in the
nation's first primary state, despite Bush's formidable support
from the Republican establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he did a fabulous job,'' said Ed Nutter, a retired
businessman who has become a McCain connoisseur after watching the
senator at five town meetings, most recently in a high school in
Pembroke. ``He's direct.''
</P>
<P>
   In the lakeside town of Meredith, Rusty Chase, 24, was clutching
McCain's autobiography in hopes of getting an autograph. ``He's
honest,'' Chase said admiringly.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest that McCain's methods are uncalculated.
His aides are aggressive about trying to manipulate news coverage
through the well-planned leak, occasionally timed for McCain's
appearance on weekend talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   And the campaign telegraphs that the man is the message when it
calls his campaign bus the ``straight-talk express'' and the plane
for his announcement tour ``Maverick One.'' Large posters of McCain
as a dashing young naval aviator also remind audiences of his
searing years as a prisoner of war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the senator acknowledges that he needs the journalists
he courts to propel him forward with enough free publicity to
overcome Bush's campaign war chest of $60 million or more. In the
New Hampshire and South Carolina television air wars, the Bush
campaign is already outspending McCain at times by as much as two
to one.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's underdog strategy is to damage Bush in the early
primary states, where personal appearances still count before the
multistate, coast-to-coast primaries set in on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go from New Hampshire to South Carolina, Arizona and
Michigan,'' said Greg Stevens, McCain's media consultant. ``If we
win three out of the four, let's say, who's the front-runner? Who's
proving to a national audience that they're the candidate that's
doing the best? That carries into those multiple-state days.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers counter that New Hampshire is a unique state
that likes to support mavericks and allows independents to vote in
party primaries. They argue that McCain will fade once the
primaries go national and organization and media become important.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only really two states in which John McCain is
competitive,'' Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, told reporters.
``One is New Hampshire. One is Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, McCain and his aides worry that he may be rising in the
polls too quickly in New Hampshire. ``It's a double-edged sword,''
John Weaver, McCain's political director, said of the surge in the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's success has helped his fund raising. This quarter
is his best yet and last week he surpassed the $16 million mark. In
January, he will be eligible for $5 million in matching federal
money.
</P>
<P>
   But the downside of success is that in New Hampshire, as McCain
notes, ``the definition of `win' is in the eyes of the media.'' If
journalists come to assume that he will win New Hampshire, McCain
may not get the kind of publicity bounce he is counting on to
propel him into South Carolina, which votes 18 days later. And a
strong second-place showing in New Hampshire _ which once might
have been impressive _ instead could crush his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, having been in this position, anything short of
a win is not good news for him,'' said Tom Rath, a New Hampshire
adviser to Bush. ``They must win here.''
</P>
<P>
   So McCain must maintain his lead in New Hampshire while building
support in South Carolina where he lags far behind Bush.
</P>
<P>
   To step up his national exposure, the senator has begun a series
of addresses on national policy. He rolled out a military plan last
week, and plans speeches in the next two weeks on health care,
Social Security and the environment in South Carolina and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   He and Bill Bradley, the insurgent Democratic candidate, also
plan an unusual joint appearance on Thursday to underscore their
support for taking big money out of politics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McCain plans to spend more time in South Carolina, and his
campaign is starting to flood the state with surrogates. McCain's
wife, Cindy, held a debate-watching party there last week.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the state's congressmen who were part of the ``Contract
With America'' class of 1994 _ Mark Sanford and Lindsey Graham _
have promised to barnstorm the state for him. The new money has
also allowed McCain to go on the air with his introductory
commercial, with its footage of the young man as a prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
   And for now, McCain continues to bounce from town meeting to
town meeting, noticeably drawing energy from the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   At times he is irreverent. When only one person at a Rotary Club
lunch showed any response to one of McCain's usual applause lines _
that a good teacher should not earn less than a bad senator _ the
senator suddenly bellowed: ``Get it? All right, fellow Rotarians,
wake up!''
</P>
<P>
   He woos young people by telling of his trip to the MTV Awards
with his 15-year-old daughter Meghan and his reaction to rappers
and rock stars. ``That was the greatest assault on my senses since
I was in prison,'' he says, usually drawing whoops of laughter.
``But I know who Puff Daddy is. I met Busta Rhymes. He was wearing
a dress. I thought I might borrow it from him. My personal favorite
is Nine Inch Nails.''
</P>
<P>
   At other moments he tries to teach the students of patriotism by
speaking of Mike Christian, a Navy navigator who had been shot down
in Vietnam six months before McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Christian, he said, had used a bamboo needle and scraps of
colored cloth to sew an American flag inside his shirt. The
prisoners would hang it in their cell each day and say the pledge
of allegiance to the shirt _ until their guards found it. The
guards beat Christian until his ribs broke and his eyes were
swollen shut. And then, tossed back in his cell, he tried to sew
another flag.
</P>
<P>
   By the time McCain finished this story recently at Pembroke
Academy, the entire gymnasium had fallen to a hush.
</P>
<P>
   But it is when he is railing against big corporations, big
money, and special interests that the senator becomes most
animated.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over he calls Theodore Roosevelt his hero and vows that
as president he would break the stranglehold of money on politics.
</P>
<P>
   `And if I fail to win the nomination,'' he told a crowd in
Meredith last week, ``at least people knew what I stood for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1440EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6065 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-11 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MARTINI MIGRAINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I was so happy to see Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, she hadn't changed a bit: friendly blue
eyes and golden curly hair. Clever and spunky. Still taking it on
her slender shoulders to solve mysteries that baffled everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   I was standing in Restoration Hardware, in a Proustian reverie
about Nancy Drew, sweet memories of reading the stories to my
mother as we drove, sometimes sitting after we'd parked to finish a
chapter.
</P>
<P>
   It was gratifying to find new copies reproduced to look
perfectly old. No more hunting through flea markets for worn sets
to buy little girls for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But then I got the creeps.
</P>
<P>
   They had my number. They knew what I wanted, even before I did.
</P>
<P>
   I have no original tastes. My niche is a cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, prowling in vintage shops, I unearthed old
treasures: a silver penguin cocktail shaker from the '30s, a brown
leather club chair, a mica lamp, tin toys.
</P>
<P>
   Now when I leave home to shop for Christmas, I'm still home. My
choices are eerily cloned at Restoration Hardware. There are
reproductions of the penguin cocktail shaker, the brown leather
chair, the mica lamp, the tin toys. The same music that plays at
home is playing here: Louis Armstrong, Duke Ellington.
</P>
<P>
   I also find myself transported back to the house I grew up in,
with reproductions of the leather firewood holder my father used,
the floor wax my mom used, the bark-covered bowl with nutcracker we
had, the glow-in-the-dark stars on the ceiling of my bedroom, the
Slinky, the marbles, the Interstate highway bingo games, the
Christmas tree bubble lights.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't Americans ever get nostalgic for something new? Even
Brooks Brothers now has ties with martini shakers, cocktail recipe
books and a CD compilation improbably called ``Brooks Brothers
Cocktail Jazz.'' We are awash in sock monkeys, yo-yos, eight balls,
dashboard hula dolls, highball glasses, Etch-a-Sketch key chains,
Lionel trains, Silly Putty, Lucy, Erte, Barbie, Elvis, Marilyn,
nuns, dice, Martians and martini everything.
</P>
<P>
   At the millennium, yuppies are using new technology to create an
eternal present out of their past.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, I'm sure, we'll have TV ads and stores that speak to us
personally and morph their merchandise to match our unspoken
desires.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Internet is expanding by reductive marketing _
trying to pinpoint and mold our preferences.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of privacy does not make me as paranoid as the loss of
individuality.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Avila reported on NBC News that big online stores use a
technology called ``collaborative filtering.'' They pair you with
another buyer with identical tastes and then propose the other
guy's picks to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You buy 10 wines from Wine.com in Napa,'' Avila explained.
``The computer finds another buyer who bought those same 10 wines
and then bought another one. The computer then suggests to you, you
buy the same wine.''
</P>
<P>
   After I bought some stuff on Amazon.com, they began greeting me
personally and telling me what they thought I would like next. They
presume if I order Gabriel Byrne's memoir, I'll also want Yeats and
Joyce. If I order a CD by the Buena Vista Social Club, they predict
I'll like Santana and Bob Dylan and Randy Newman. And if I order a
book by Barbara Tuchman about the Middle Ages, they bet I'll need a
history of dreadnoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Capelli, a spokesman for Amazon.com., explains how they
define and refine: ``We work through the power of aggregating a
vast database'' of 13 million customers. ``People have similar
tastes, similar interests, similar things they want to explore, so
Amazon.com does that work for you.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a little sinister. Your tastes are cloned and
cross-referenced so quickly you end up with the sense that
idiosyncrasy is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you want to lie to them or confuse them, simultaneously
ordering a bottle of Veuve Clicquot and a bottle of Thunderbird;
Jacqueline Susann's ``Valley of the Dolls'' and a biography of
Schopenhauer; a John Tesh CD and a Lil' Kim CD.
</P>
<P>
   But the scary thing is that they'd probably find a doppelganger
for all these weird combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers of the world, disaggregate!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
