<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: UNFROZEN IN DAMASCUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, OK, I know what the quid is, but what's the quo?
</P>
<P>
   I know that when the Syrians come here this week to talk peace
with Israel they will demand the total return of the
Israeli-occupied Golan Heights. But what will Israel be asking for
in return? Prime Minister Ehud Barak hasn't spelled that out.
</P>
<P>
   Some serious people believe that Israel should focus purely on
the strategic deal _ trade the Golan for a wide, U.S.-monitored
buffer zone with Syria _ and not worry about trade, tourism or
normalization; Syria doesn't have much to trade, and real
reconciliation would seem unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the key issue here is security, and Barak's logic is
as follows: Syria has a large standing army and can keep many, many
troops and tanks constantly deployed near its border with Israel,
so that a surprise attack is possible at any time. That's Israel's
constant fear. Israel has a small standing army, so it uses the
Golan as a land buffer that would slow down any Syrian surprise
attack long enough for Israel to mobilize its reserves. The key is
whether Israel can trade the Golan for an even better security
arrangement _ one that would push Syrian troops and tanks so much
farther away from the frontier that, along with U.S.-run early
warning stations and other restrictions, it would make a Syrian
surprise attack impossible before Israeli reserves could be fully
deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israeli generals feel such a deal is both possible and
preferable to the status quo, particularly if you add in the
regional implications: bringing Syria into the circle of peace
would close down the Lebanon front and totally isolate Iraq and
Iran. That would constitute a major strategic realignment of the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But while such a strategic deal is necessary, it is not
sufficient. Syria has always seen itself, rightly, as the Arab
heartbeat of the conflict with Israel. Without a heart transplant
in Syria, without Damascus opening itself to Israeli trade, tourism
and diplomats, the war will not be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Egypt was always in charge of the hardware of this conflict _
the tanks and planes,'' notes Stephen Cohen of the Center for
Middle East Peace. ``With Egypt inside the conflict, a lethal war
against Israel was always possible. Without Egypt, such a war was
impossible. Syria was always in charge of the software of this
conflict _ the existential struggle against Zionism, as well as the
maintenance of a rejection front of Palestinian, Iranian and
Lebanese resistance groups. With Syria inside the conflict, the
existential war with Israel was always there. With Syria out, that
war would basically be over.``
</P>
<P>
   Internal reform and an opening of Syria to the world is critical
for another reason: Egypt is a homogeneous state with a long and
stable history. Syria is a multi-ethnic state, with constant
internal tensions. For Egypt, the war with Israel was a policy that
could be changed when Egypt's interests changed. But for President
Hafez al-Assad, the war with Israel hasn't been just a policy, it's
been the glue holding Syria together and the foundation, and
justification, of his own regime. That's why it's essential that as
Syria makes peace, and a new generation takes power there, the new
Syrian generation be seen to build its identity, and legitimacy,
not on rejection of Israel, but rather on modernizing Syria and
opening it to the world. Otherwise, no peace accord can be stable.
</P>
<P>
   That will take a huge amount of money, which is the other reason
Syria will have to change internally. Egypt made peace with Israel
in the Cold War, when superpowers were ready to buy countries just
to get them to join their bloc. The superpowers didn't care what
your country looked like inside; they just cared whose side you
were on outside. But Syria is making peace in the age of
globalization, when no superpower pays you to join its bloc and
when the big money is with the global supermarkets, like Wall
Street. Neither the U.S. Congress nor Wall Street will invest in
peace with Syria without Syria reforming its sclerotic economy.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote last week that we needed to force Assad to choose:
Either remain a failed state or use peace with Israel to build a
bridge for Syria into the world. I had no idea he was so close to
that decision. It's too early to tell if it's real. But if it is,
it could be extremely important for transforming both the hardware
of the Arab-Israeli conflict and its software.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
