<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GAYS-MILITARY-(2TAKES     12-11 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRACKS LIFE OF GAY HARASSMENT IS DETAILED AT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Note language throughout may be offensive to some readers.) 
(ATTN: Ky., Mo., Neb., Tenn.) (rk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. _ All about the base there was the surface
bustle of the modern Army: Troopers jogged by in crisp formation to
a proud cadence. A woman sergeant in tailored fatigues darted into
the PX with an infant on her hip, shopping for the evening meal.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this reassuring scrim, a steady stream of young
paratroopers quietly arrived at the door of the fort's humble white
courthouse, summoned to tell of more aberrant days and nights on
the post.
</P>
<P>
   Though trained to be tough, the young men were clearly nervous
in testifying at a court-martial that was gauging the Clinton
administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy toward
homosexuals as assuredly as it fixed the guilt of an 18-year-old
private who crept up with a baseball bat and bludgeoned a gay
soldier to death last July here in the barracks of Delta company.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the trial last week, the court's pronouncement of
guilt upon Pvt. Calvin Glover for the premeditated murder of Pfc.
Barry Winchell seemed almost anticlimactic to the larger set of
facts gradually established before the court about the
ineffectiveness of the administration's controversial policy toward
gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   The young witnesses disclosed a casual culture in which gibes
and taunts were directed for months at Winchell by Glover and
others. Such terms as a ``faggot,'' ``queer,'' and ``homo'' echoed
amid beer-filled nights of barracks carousing that, the record
showed, were devoid of superiors' reprimand or notice. Testimony
demonstrated that regulations were regularly violated and
harassment complaints positively discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was done, sir,'' said Sgt. Michael Kleifgen, who told
of one fruitless attempt to complain to the post inspector general
about what the sergeant considered a clear violation of regulations
by a master sergeant, who referred to Winchell as ``that faggot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way all of us were, sir,'' Spc. Lewis Ruiz, a
friend of the slain soldier, testified about the barracks culture
in which braggarts and bullies stepped to the fore to pick on
soldiers' perceived weaknesses, to coin stinging epithets, and to
goad conflict that superiors made no sign of stopping in the case
of 21-year-old Winchell.
</P>
<P>
   As rumors and taunting spread about Winchell's dating of a
nightclub drag queen, friends testified that the private kept his
silence about his harassers because he feared the consequences of
the ``don't tell'' part of the policy that provides for expulsion
if a soldier's homosexuality becomes known. The trial showed that
Winchell, of Kansas City, Mo., had already had his rights violated
under the ``don't ask'' stricture as a sergeant had questioned him
about his sexuality and looked into his private life, despite
official prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was having fun,'' the sergeant responded, when asked
why he did not order his platoon members to cease their harassment
of Winchell.
</P>
<P>
   In the critical turn of events last July 3, the third dictum of
the administration's gay policy _ ``don't pursue'' _ came to haunt
Winchell. He knocked down his homophobic tormentor, Glover, of
Sulphur, Okla., and paid with his life 26 hours later as he slept.
</P>
<P>
   The murder case, which is drawing national attention to the base
as a lethal example of gays' dilemma with the military, will
conclude this week with the court-martial of the man accused of
being Glover's accomplice, 25-year-old Spc. Justin Fisher, of
Lincoln, Neb. Witnesses testified that Fisher provided Glover with
the bat and intense prodding for ``letting that faggot'' best him
in a fight.
</P>
<P>
   What the Army treated last summer as a slaying stemming from
youthful drunken violence finally evolved into something more
decisive as the court-martial slowly, obliquely accepted the
possibility of a homophobic hate crime in the ranks. In the charge
to the court, the presiding judge, Col. Gary Holland, allowed
Glover's record of repeated anti-gay epithets and threats, as
confirmed by barracks witnesses, to be weighed as a factor in
determining motive and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's significant,'' said C. Dixon Osburn, co-executive
director of the Servicemembers Legal Defense Network, a gay rights
group that monitors military justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He specifically cited that important point,'' said Osburn,
finding a glimmer of progress by the military as it wrestles with a
gay policy that has produced mainly controversy over the past six
years.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, the number of discharges of gay service members
increased to 1,149 in 1998 from 682 in 1993. There has been a
corresponding rise in harassment complaints to gay rights groups,
Osburn said, as gays either leave the service or suffer abuse
without complaint in fear of confirming their homosexuality and
being subject to expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of Glover underlined the fact that little came of
promises of heightened sensitivity toward gays made by the Clinton
administration in 1993, when the ``don't ask'' policy was
introduced. The trial underlined the fact that Army authorities did
not begin to hold sessions down the ranks on the gay policy until
after Winchell had been murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a former soldier who is gay told of the joke that one
of his superiors here made of a token sensitivity session. Javier
Torres, an Army private for two years before he quit, told the CBS
News program ``60 Minutes'' that his superior declared with evident
disgust: ``This is a meeting about fags. Don't bother them; they
won't bother you.''
</P>
<P>
   A critical moment in his decision to quit the Army, Torres said
in a segment of the program to be broadcast on Sunday, came when
his drill sergeant unapologetically bellowed a homophobic cadence
in leading his platoon on a five-mile run: ``Faggot, faggot down
the street/ Shoot him, shoot 'til he retreats.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the spit-and-polish of this post's celebrated unit, the
101st Airborne Division, the trial of Glover suggested a leadership
void in the off hours of the unmarried soldiers who were part of
Winchell's world. ``We watch TV, drink, just talk _ that's about
it,'' Pvt. Benjamin Boyer told the court in describing the
circumstances in which the taunting of Winchell flourished.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Glover defense team underscored the young soldier's routine
heavy drinking at night as a factor in the cruel behavior of some.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can find the larger life of this base encouraging for
its sense of normalcy, even as the trial of Glover laid bare a
jagged alternative. Glover's parents testified, keening at their
son's weakness in the face of peer pressure. ``Cal wants to belong
to something so bad,'' said his father, Rue Glover, sad-eyed before
the court, which sentenced his son to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, Winchell's anguished parents expressed pride
in their son's putting himself at risk as a patriotic serviceman.
But in a statement, the mother and stepfather, Pat and Wally
Kutteles, added, ``We never dreamed that he would be killed by
labeling, prejudice and hatred at home.''
</P>
<P>
   And they asked: ``Why did leaders turn a blind eye to the
excessive drinking occurring on base? Where was the supervision in
the barracks? Why were people allowed to taunt our son, hit our son
and harass our son?''
</P>
<P>
   Of the ``don't ask'' policy, they warned, ``It won't protect
anyone else's child.''
</P>
<P>
   The most mournful-looking figure in the trial audience was Cal
Addams, a performer known as Calpurnia, whom Winchell befriended in
Nashville, Tenn., and began dating last March. A former Navy medic,
Addams commented as a veteran of a gay's travails in the service.
``Barry had been looking his entire life, he told me, for a way to
feel comfortable with himself,'' Addams said after the murder. ``He
had only just begun to find that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1507EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-TOWERS-NYT &LR;      12-11 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-TOWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHENS SEE DANGER FOR THEIR HISTORY MADE OF STONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Hundreds of stone towers, some nearly 1,000 years old,
dot the jagged cliffs of the Caucasian mountain range in Chechnya.
One of the region's prized symbols, they have survived through
earthquakes, wars and the deportation of the Chechen people in
1944, but Chechens fear that the towers are now threatened by
Russian bombing in the region's second war in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how any of the towers can survive such bombing,''
said Lecha Ilyasov, 38, a philologist and photographer who lived in
Russia most of his life before returning to Chechnya two years ago
to document its culture.
</P>
<P>
   Ilyasov recently returned to Moscow _ leaving Grozny, Chechnya's
capital, through military checkpoints and police patrols _ to
attend a conference on the threat that the latest bombing poses to
Chechnya's culture.
</P>
<P>
   He came with two other members of the LAM Center for Research
and Popularization of Chechen Culture, a nongovernmental group. It
is supported by human rights advocates and the Andrei Sakharov
Museum and Public Center in Moscow, named for the Soviet dissident.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians are wary of Chechens; militants from the region
are widely suspected in the September apartment bombings that
killed nearly 300 people in Moscow and elsewhere. Like other
Chechens, Ilyasov said, he has been stopped and interrogated by
Moscow police.
</P>
<P>
   Even simply bringing photographs of the towers to Moscow for the
conference was not easy, he said. To escape possibly having the
pictures confiscated, he said he arranged for them to be smuggled
out of Chechnya by women, who are less likely to be stopped by
Russian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   To Chechens, the towers symbolize the close-knit clan traditions
and the aversion to outside control that are considered hallmarks
of their history. And Chechens fear that Russian forces may strike
at the towers now both because of their symbolic importance and
their possible use as a strategic redoubt for retreating Islamic
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The towers are very important to Chechen culture,'' said
Johanna Nichols, a professor at the University of California at
Berkeley who is an expert on Chechen language and culture. ``Every
clan in Chechnya traces its ancestry back to a mountain village
with a set of towers that belongs to that clan.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time there were thousands of towers, stretching from the
mountains to the plains and as far as the edge of Grozny. A wealth
of folklore and legend surrounds the structures; the first known
documented mention of them is in Arab manuscripts dating from the
10th century.
</P>
<P>
   They were originally built as multipurpose structures, housing
livestock and families and serving as lookout posts, and were
constructed to withstand even earthquakes, to which Chechnya is
prone.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that some of the Chechen towers were destroyed by
invading Mongols as far back as the 14th century. Five hundred
years later, during Russia's colonial wars in the Caucasus, czarist
soldiers destroyed still more.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet secret police also destroyed some towers. When the
police executed Stalin's order for wholesale deportation of the
Chechens to Central Asia in 1944 for allegedly collaborating with
the Germans, they feared that Chechens would take to the hills and
use the towers as strongholds from which to conduct guerrilla
warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chechens did just that. The last die-hard, Chechen lore
says, climbed out of his lair in the late 1970s, a sick old man.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1994-96 war in Chechnya, Russian artillery and
airstrikes destroyed Russian cultural treasures: an old Orthodox
church as well as the main library in Grozny, named after Anton
Chekhov, and its nearly 3 million volumes, including rare Russian
books.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechens thus fear that the Russians will have no
inclination to hold back from destroying the towers during the
bombing now.
</P>
<P>
   The Argun gorge, where some rebels have already retreated, is
home to some of the oldest and most prized towers and a necropolis
of 50 crypts. And the region has reportedly come under ferocious
bombardment by Russian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Ilyasov said the rebels, too, have little interest in preserving
the towers, and are far more concerned with setting up a
fundamentalist Islamic state. The rebels object to pagan markings
on the towers, which were built hundreds of years before Chechens
were converted to Islam. Ilyasov said that after he made a film
about the necropolis, the Islamic militants threatened him and
denounced him for promoting pagan beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're against anything Chechen,'' he said. ``They say
everything must be purely Islamic and Arabic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ilyasov would like to see the towers added to the United Nations
list of the world's protected monuments, which he hopes would
increase international attention if they are bombed and might help
save them from attack. Preserving the towers, he said, would ``show
our young people what a great and civilized culture our forefathers
had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
