<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SOC-U.S.-WOMEN-2TAKES     12-11 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-WOMEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A WOMAN SHOULD BE CALLING THE SHOTS FOR THE WOMEN'S
TEAM
</HEADLINE>
  (Replaces SOC-U.S.-OLYMPICS)  
(rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having won the World Cup of soccer with a women's team, the
United States should now attempt to win an Olympic gold medal with
a woman as coach. The four candidates to replace Tony DiCicco, who
resigned last month to spend more time with his family, are his
assistant coaches, Lauren Gregg and Jay Hoffman, along with Clive
Charles of the University of Portland and Bobby Howe, who is
director of coaching for the U.S. Soccer Federation.
</P>
<P>
   If loyalty and merit were the only considerations, Gregg would
already have the job. At 39, she is the one coaching thread that
embroiders the long success of the American team. Her career
reflects the evolution of the women's game: a player on the first
NCAA championship team at North Carolina in 1982, an assistant
coach for the U.S. teams that won the 1991 and 1999 Women's World
Cups and the 1996 Olympic gold medal. She has given her life to
soccer and it is time for soccer to give something back by naming
her coach as the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia,
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support Lauren,'' DiCicco said. ``I think she gives us the
best chance of winning in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe has never coached women at the college or national level.
Hoffman has, but not as long as Gregg. Charles coached two of the
American stars, Tiffeny Milbrett and Shannon MacMillan, at
Portland, along with the top men's goalkeeper, Kasey Keller. But
his international record is unimpressive. While Gregg has twice
coached the Americans to victories in the Nordic Cup _ the
unofficial world championship for under-21 players _ Charles
finished no higher than third in three attempts. And he was part of
the biggest debacle in American soccer history, serving as
assistant coach for the men's 1998 World Cup squad that finished
last among 32 teams, sinking in the quicksand of finger-pointing
and ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring Charles to run the women's team a year after such an
embarrassing collapse would be the soccer equivalent of hiring Ben
Johnson to run the Olympic drug-testing program.
</P>
<P>
   A coach is expected to be hired by Jan. 2, when the American
women leave for a pre-Olympic tour of Australia. The U.S. women's
team has never had a woman as head coach since it began play in
1985. Three coaches, three men. It is widely believed that Charles
has the job locked up and that the interviewing process is a
formality. That would be a mistake. Soccer is a game of passion,
but this is a decision that needs to be based on reason, not
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   The soccer federation, which is the national governing body, has
a mixed record in managing the women's team. On one hand, it treats
female players more professionally than any other federation in the
world. It held the 1999 World Cup in huge arenas, spent $3 million
on a training camp, provided a nanny and a sports psychologist and
even chartered a plane for the team for a cross-country flight
between the quarterfinals and the semifinals. But relations with
the women have often been tense and advances, even fruit and bagels
after practice, have come grudgingly.
</P>
<P>
   The players went on strike in late 1995, before the Atlanta
Olympics, when the federation proposed offering bonus money only
for a gold medal. Paltry bonuses were paid to the players for
winning the 1999 World Cup, the victory was coolly embraced and the
federation clumsily waited two months before offering to renew
DiCicco's contract.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to treat the women in a paternalistic manner and
threatened to sue when they opted to play an indoor victory tour of
their own instead of participating in an outdoor world tour the
federation had planned. A cereal war erupted over whether players
could appear on boxes of the brand shaped like flakes or the one
shaped like soccer balls.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the federation has a right to protect its marketing
interests, but it should not take the hardball negotiating of the
women personally. This is the necessary transition of a sport that
was once amateur and is now professional. The women are bargaining
from strength. They are more successful and more popular than the
men, deservedly so. After earning next to nothing for so long, they
have the right to a bigger slice of the financial pie.
</P>
<P>
   The federation has no reason to resent their achievement or to
punish their assertiveness by hiring a coach from the outside and
cleaning house. The women's team gave American soccer legitimacy
and visibility. It should be embraced as a wind that can lift
everyone's sails.
</P>
<P>
   This is an inviting opportunity for the federation to disprove
the suspicion that it remains an old-boy network, and that a strong
British influence will result in the hiring of Charles because he,
too, is a Brit. Only two of the 16 teams in the Women's World Cup _
Germany and Sweden _ had women as coaches. The United States should
set the same example in providing diversity that it has set in
providing the world's best female players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not either/or; if the women get more, it doesn't mean the
men have to get less,'' said Lynn Berling-Manuel, publisher of
Soccer America, the country's leading weekly soccer publication,
who supports Gregg's candidacy. ``This is an opportunity for
women's soccer to push all of soccer along. It will attract
publicity. It will bring tremendous credibility for the women's
game to have a female in a leadership position. It will provide a
valuable role model.''
</P>
<P>
   A whisper campaign questions whether Gregg is tactically
proficient enough to be a head coach. The players are supposedly
wary of her consuming energy. She is too aggressive. She toots her
own horn. Berling-Manuel is right when she says that these are the
same vague, discriminatory murmurs that are often used in denying
jobs to women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gregg started the soccer program from scratch at the University
of Virginia in 1986 and took it to the Final Four in five years.
And since when do players hire the coach? They got along with her
well enough to win two world championships and an Olympic gold
medal. Gregg has been instrumental in building the world's top
system and she offers the best hope for continued success. With the
next Women's World Cup moved up from 2003 to 2002, it is even more
urgent that continuity be maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that whoever comes in is going to start
rebuilding now and throw away the Olympics,'' DiCicco said. ``You
can't throw it away with all the hype and all the attention NBC is
going to pay. Whoever takes over should try to improve the team.
That might mean some changes, but not wholesale changes. Let's see
if we can win another gold medal. Lauren offers the best chance to
keep the championship team together and winning.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg was indispensable to the American success last July as the
team's tactical analyst, chief scout and video expert. She spotted
a weakness in Nigeria's defense of free kicks, and American goals
rang up like a gas pump in a 7-1 victory. Expecting to play China
in the final, she logged every corner kick and free kick the
Chinese players had taken during the tournament. She knew which
foot they preferred, which teammate they most often passed to,
whether their kicks swung inward or outward. She helped design the
roach-motel defense that funneled China's attack inside and did not
let it back out.
</P>
<P>
   She recorded nearly every penalty kick the Americans rehearsed
in the six months leading to the World Cup, noting whether the kick
was accurate, whether it missed, whether it was high or low, placed
to the left or the right, whether it was struck with confidence.
She drew up the list of shooters for the penalty kick finale. Five
kicks, five goals. She recognized soccer as a player's game, but
she also believed that little should be left to chance.
</P>
<P>
   The soccer federation should feel the same. The best way to
achieve Olympic success is an orderly transition from DiCicco to
Gregg. Dr. Robert Contigulia, president of the federation, did the
right thing in 1998 by giving Bruce Arena, an American, the chance
to coach the American men. He should do the right thing again by
giving a woman the chance to coach the American women.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the politically correct thing to do, just the correct
thing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1516EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
