u i BC-CONGO-U.S.-NYT &LR;      12-11 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO LEADER PROMISES COOPERATION WITH MEDIATOR IN CIVIL WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Congo President Laurent Kabila said Saturday in
talks with Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. representative at the United
Nations, that he would be willing to work with an African mediator
to find a political settlement to the civil war in his country,
which still rages despite a July peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, speaking from Kinshasa before returning to New York
after a two-week tour of 10 African nations, said it was necessary
to view any commitment with caution in a civil war that has
restarted several times in recent years and has drawn in half a
dozen nations on one side or the other. But he said all sides and
their supporters now appeared ready to discuss a political solution
under the auspices of the Organization of African Unity, which has
so far failed to appoint an envoy called for in the July agreement.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and African diplomats said a leading candidate for the job
has finally emerged. He is Sir Ketumile Masire, a former president
of Botswana. Africans had hoped to appoint former South African
President Nelson Mandela, but relations between Mandela and Kabila
are not good. Mandela has instead taken on the task of trying to
settle a civil conflict in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who spoke for two hours Saturday with Kabila, met
Friday in Kampala, the Ugandan capital, with Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni and leaders of the three main rebel factions
fighting in eastern Congo. Earlier on the trip, Holbrooke discussed
the Congo war with officials in Angola, Zimbabwe, Zambia and other
countries that have supplied the sides with troops, money or
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the parties we talked to blamed the other parties,''
Holbrooke said. ``I told them we're not running a court of inquiry.
We just want to get moving, get the United Nations in the field
with military observers and peacekeepers.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. liaison mission is now stuck in Kinshasa, unable to
operate. This situation fits a pattern in relations with Kabila,
who agrees to an international operation and then in effect
prevents it from doing its job. A U.N. human rights investigation
into allegations that troops loyal to Kabila killed thousands of
refugees from Rwanda in an earlier round of the civil war in
1996-97 stalled for months and finally gave up more than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who will take over as Security Council president in
January, said he planned to hold open meetings on wars in Angola,
Congo and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States, this administration, is committed to help
in the region,'' he said. ``But we are not going to go in blindly
with a United Nations peacekeeping operation just to make it look
as if we're doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has asked for nor is anyone expecting American
troops,'' he said. ``Still, we pay 25 percent of the costs, and
Congress has to approve missions we pay for. We want to get this
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that he and Susan Rice, assistant secretary of
state for Africa, who is traveling with him, will recommend to
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright that Howard Wolpe, President
Clinton's special envoy for Africa, return to the region this week
to follow up on developments in Congo and elsewhere. Wolpe was
formerly chairman of the House foreign relations subcommittee on
Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1517EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ANTIOCH-WOMEN-RUGBY-A     12-11 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIOCH-WOMEN-RUGBY-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WAS WON ON THE PLAYING FIELDS OF ANTIOCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YELLOW SPRINGS, Ohio _ Antioch College abolished football 70
years ago, but on Friday students celebrated homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   The game was rugby. The players were women. The ``home'' field
belongs to the high school down the road. The homecoming ``king,''
18-year-old Kate Donnelly, wore a strapless pink number she picked
up at a church tag sale for $2, and was crowned with a wreath
borrowed from the Christmas display at a nearby gas station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to facilitate traditions,'' said Kevin
Franck, 21, a sociology major from Annapolis, Md., who had
appointed himself last year's homecoming king and donned a feather
boa. ``We're trying to pretend we've had it all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Things have always been a little off-center at Antioch, and so
it is with the iconoclastic campus's flirtation this fall with
intercollegiate athletics.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a lark with an experimental physical education
class has become a dominant activity at the liberal arts college of
650 students _ on Friday, more than 100 people braved bitter winds,
cheering and screaming as their team lost 19-0 to the University of
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   The college has spent at least $4,000 buying jerseys and socks
and cleats and balls for a sport that is exploding in popularity
across campuses but typically draws little attention or support
from administrators.
</P>
<P>
   A place notorious for taking itself too seriously is having
serious fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community was searching for celebratory ritual,'' said Bob
Devine, the college president, in an effort to explain the
phenomenon. ``Antioch doesn't think in school-spirit terms.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a place where Melinda Kanner, associate professor of
anthropology and now rugby coach, had to ask the archivist to
research the school colors (blue and gold). Nobody knows the alma
mater. There remains much confusion over the mascot: Letterman's
jackets in the bookstore say ``Antioch Radicals'' on the back;
history points to the Bluejackets, probably named for Union
soldiers in the Civil War; Ms. Kanner backs ``Barbarians'' and some
have suggested an even more esoteric name, the ``Antioch Other.''
</P>
<P>
   But what at first seems thick with irony might just make perfect
sense.
</P>
<P>
   Antioch, which was founded in 1852 and has long been a beacon of
racial and gender equality, ahead of its time politically, proudly
offers an ``alternative'' education in which what is normally on
the margins is placed at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Many see rugby, a brutal sport played without padding and
dependent on teamwork, as a metaphor for the college's system of
governance, in which the students sit on every important committee
and the entire community is invited to weekly open meetings that
often become verbal battlegrounds.
</P>
<P>
   It seems fitting for a place that uses narrative evaluations
instead of grades that a touchdown in rugby is called a try.
Rugby's reputation as a haven for gay women makes sense on a campus
where students say lesbians are the dominant culture.
</P>
<P>
   Women's rugby ``absolutely challenges, at its core, all the
cultural notions and assumptions that we have about gender, body,
power, sex,'' said Mary Jo Kane, the director of the University of
Minnesota's Tucker Research Center on Girls and Women in Sport.
``That's what's fun about it, but why it's also most marginalized
and trivialized, because it causes the most threat.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rugby historians have uncovered evidence of secret schoolgirl
matches in England as far back as 1913, but American women have
only been playing the sport for about 20 years. The number of
college teams has more than doubled to 272 this year from 129 in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kanner, a lifelong athlete, sees team sports as essential to
a liberal education. ``It's about organization; it's about
self-discipline; it's about testing their own limits,'' she
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The intellectual approach is apparent in the team huddle before
kickoff, as the women shout: ``Superior-Mental-Organization!''
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the team's 18 players had ever touched a rugby ball
before. Some, like Nadine Alonzo, had played soccer or other
sports, but like this one better. ``I used to get red-carded all
the time for hurting people,'' said Ms. Alonzo, a 19-year-old
sophomore from Manhasset, N.Y. ``Now I'm supposed to hurt people.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Leilah Weinraub, a first-year student from Los
Angeles, are part of a team for the first time. ``Usually I try to
fend for myself, think for myself, rely on my own facilities _ it's
still hard for me to think in terms of other people,'' said Ms.
Weinraub, 19. ``It's totally weird to be a jock all of a sudden.
After the game, people high-five you, they give you beers, they
want to give you advice. It's like, what? I'm talking about
sports?''
</P>
<P>
   It has been an education for the fans as well. Clueless about
the rules, they cheer sometimes when the other team scores. Their
chants are of the ``hey, hey, ho, ho'' variety, adapted from years
of political protests. In a riff on Antioch's infamous policy in
which people are required to obtain verbal consent before any
sexual contact, one student carries a hand-lettered sign, ``Ask
Before You Ruck'' (``ruck'' is a rugby tackling formation).
</P>
<P>
   In an institution that has spent much of its history on the
brink of bankruptcy (it even filed once) and is often riven by
politics, this is the first time in recent memory that people have
come together not to ponder problems but to do something positive.
Dissident alumni are withholding donations to protest the college's
relationship with other Antioch campuses, established in the 1970s,
and some are concerned that the co-op program, in which students
alternate semesters of study and work, is losing its cache.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noting that football, and all varsity sports, died
not because of lack of interest but because students thought it an
undemocratic, warlike symbol of the imperialist establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people that come here weren't the jocks or the
preppy people in high school,'' said Shannon McCarville, 20, the
team kicker. ``They were the people that got teased by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Students and faculty agree that if it were football, it would
never fly. But there is already some buzz about co-ed basketball,
with pickup players wondering whether they, too, might get some
snazzy uniforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
