<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS; PENNSYLVANIA SENATE; FORBES; REFORM PARTY;
FORDICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two's a Challenge, But Seven's a Crowd
</P>
<P>
   For months, the morning line on next year's Senate race in
Pennsylvania has been that Republican incumbent Rick Santorum
should be one of the easiest targets for Democrats in their battle
to recapture the Senate. He is a conservative in a state that
typically elects moderates, his 1994 margin of victory was a flimsy
2 points and he has since struggled to raise his poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Democrats think Santorum is so vulnerable that no fewer
than seven _ so far _ are competing for the right to take him on.
</P>
<P>
   And that's turning out to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, when the Democratic State Committee gathered in
Harrisburg, six of the contenders showed up to work the corridors
and caucuses in search of support. That struck many committee
members as perhaps too much of a good thing and they have since
begun to push the thought that perhaps it would be better,
politically, if some candidates dropped out, lest the party end up
badly battering itself in a divisive, money-devouring primary next
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Not one of the seven contenders is widely known throughout the
state, and some face serious campaign money problems. The one with
the best chance to be nominated and go on to beat Santorum, many
Democratic leaders think, is Rep. Ron Klink, who hails from the
Pittsburgh area.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible of the other candidates, all from the
Philadelphia area, are former state Labor Commissioner Tom Foley,
former U.S. Reps. Marjorie Margolies-Mezvinsky and Peter Kostmayer,
and state Sen. Allyson Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   As Klink's supporters see it, in a nomination fight he would
have his base area in western Pennsylvania mostly to himself
whereas his main competitors would be scrapping for _ and
splintering _ the vote in their base area in eastern Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   As the fall contest nominee, the Klink supporters go on, Klink,
who tends to vote liberal on economic issues and conservative on
social issues, would be ideally positioned not only to go for the
state's big centrist vote but also to steal some of Senator
Santorum's conservative base.
</P>
<P>
   An analyst, Charles E. Cook Jr., wrote recently in the Cook
Political Report that if that reasoning was correct, then ``the
question is, who is running second and third in the primary field
and how long will it take before the field becomes more
manageable?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Santorum is vulnerable,'' Cook said. ``But Democrats have a
long way to go before they can take advantage of that
vulnerability.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes Uses Highway As a Political Wedge
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes has long argued that he is a more implacable foe of
abortion than Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and therefore more
deserving of the Republican presidential nomination. And now as
part of his campaign pitch, he insists he has proof.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he said, the governor signed a bill that named a
stretch of Texas highway for a Houston doctor, John B. Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, Forbes said, performed abortions and was frequently a
target of anti-abortion protesters.
</P>
<P>
   No other governor anywhere has ever allowed a public highway or
public building to be named for someone who performed abortions,
Forbes says. The governor's signature on the Texas bill, he
contends, ``raises questions about his commitment to the pro-life
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush insists he is as opposed to abortion as any candidate. His
office says the highway bill was meant to honor Coleman because he
was a leading force in Texas for better schools and colleges for
blacks and because his son, Garnet, is a Texas state
representative.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is not convinced. He says the governor should ``rename
the highway immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   A Battle to Control The Reform Party
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump and Pat Buchanan are getting all the headlines when
it comes to coverage of the Reform Party. But while they squabble
over who should be the party's presidential nominee, another
squabble has broken out within the party that ultimately could
prove to be more serious.
</P>
<P>
   Top leaders can't agree on where to hold the party's nominating
convention next August.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, the party's departing chairman, Russ Verney
of Dallas, and the party's chairman-elect, Jack Gargan of Cedar
Key, Fla., can't agree. They are in the middle of a civil war that
threatens to rip the party in half and disrupt its nominating
process.
</P>
<P>
   Even more to the point, Ross Perot and Jesse Ventura can't agree
where to hold the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Verney is the closest political confidant of Perot, the party's
founder. Gargan is a confidant of Ventura, the governor of
Minnesota, the Reform party's highest elected officeholder and the
power behind the coup last summer that saw Gargan win the party
chairman's job.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Verney and Gargan are proxies in a power
struggle between the Texan who has twice run for president on the
Reform ticket and has not ruled out a third run next year, and an
upstart former professional wrestler who says that one day he might
run for president on the Reform ticket, but not in Election 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This is not about Buchanan, who has some Perot allies, or Trump,
who is close to Ventura. This is about control of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Verney did not seek re-election as Reform chairman at last
summer's national party convention, saying it was time to let
someone else serve. But he was the most outspoken backer of the
candidate whom Gargan beat with a contention that Verney and Perot
had run things for too long.
</P>
<P>
   Verney is scheduled to leave office Jan. 1. However, he is
keeping busy as a lame-duck chairman _ too busy for Gargan.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, in September he persuaded the party's 11-member
national executive committee to choose California for next year's
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan and other Ventura allies argued that the site should be
more central, perhaps in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   No way, Verney said. And he had the votes to back that up.
</P>
<P>
   But last week the Ventura forces struck back.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan and other close allies of the governor persuaded the
party's 143-member national committee to overturn the vote of the
smaller executive committee and move the convention site to
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   '`Totally and completely a fraud,'' Verney protested, saying no
one had bothered to notify him that a vote was being held.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will of the members,'' countered Gargan.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Fordice Saga Comes to a Close
</P>
<P>
   And now for our final chapter of the Fordice Saga ...
</P>
<P>
   When last we visited the unhappy Mississippi couple, the
governor, Kirk, was having trouble persuading Pat, his wife of 45
years, to decamp the Executive Mansion in Jackson and grant him a
divorce so he could marry Ann Creson, a high school sweetheart.
Mrs. Fordice was particularly miffed, as were many Mississippi
voters, because the governor, an outspoken advocate of ``strong
family values,'' was publicly squiring Ms. Creson around.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes word that Pat Fordice has relented and irreconcilable
differences have been reconciled _ more or less. Mrs. Fordice has
negotiated herself ``a very favorable agreement,'' her lawyer said,
and is headed for a new life in a new home.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kirk Fordice, he leaves office in January and wedding
bells are expected to chime about Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the papers in the case have been sealed by the court.
</P>
<P>
   End of saga.
</P>
</TEXT>
