<HEADER>
A6096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     12-11 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TRUMP WAS A FRONT-ROW WITNESS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donald Trump was sitting in the front row when Stephan Johnson
slumped into a coma. The fight was held in the Trump Taj Mahal, the
hotel casino that bears his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love boxing, but it's a dangerous sport,'' Trump said,
shortly after Tuesday's memorial service for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Trump always has the best seat in the house, particularly when
he owns the building. His head never moves with the ball at tennis
matches because he is preoccupied scanning the audience, but he
says boxing compels him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the essence of competition,'' Trump said. `It's one on
one. In boxing, you can't blame the team because the guard didn't
pull in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an alpha-male attraction to boxing that makes it hard
to control, which is why boxers with marginal CAT scan results like
Stephan Johnson are suspended in the diligent province of Ontario
but licensed in the complaisant state of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Even some public officials of discernible conscience like John
McCain and Mario Cuomo show a fascination with boxing, which is why
it is always on the verge of being ``reformed'' rather than
abolished as a bloody relic from a savage past.
</P>
<P>
   The grisly business is also good for hotels and casinos in
outposts like Atlantic City and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing and gaming have always gone hand in hand,'' Trump said
the other day, declining to put a dollar sign on how much a big
fight card is worth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, a human being has died, almost literally in front
of Donald Trump's eyes. Stephan Johnson died last Sunday after 15
days in the hospital, but his life was more or less over when he
crumpled in the ring a few feet from the owner of the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   From a 10-minute telephone interview it is difficult to judge
just how shaken Trump really is, but the tenor of his conversation
was sober, without any of the grandiose asides for which he is
famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible,'' Trump said. ``He was comporting himself
very well, and he may even have been winning, but then he went down
and he didn't even move. A lot of people didn't see the punch. He
just went right out.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump continued: ``I've seen a lot of fights. The Golota-Grant
fight that night was murderous, but it wasn't as good as this one.
I've seen fights where the fighter goes down and they help him to
the dressing room and then he collapses, but I've never seen a
fighter carried out of the ring like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is always a first time. Now that he has seen another human
being suffer irreparable brain damage in front of his eyes, does
Trump have any second thoughts about being in the boxing business?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that we do not sanction the fights,''
Trump said. ``That is done by the New Jersey State Athletic Control
Commission. All we are is the venue _ and fighting is popular.
Every fight sells out. We have other things like gymnastics; they
don't sell out. All I know is, boxing sells out.''
</P>
<P>
   If he wanted, Trump could get out of the boxing business, could
end his alliances with the shady officials in New Jersey, some of
whom are already under serious investigation for corruption, as
well as promoters like Don King, who need no introduction.
</P>
<P>
   As a moral gesture, has Trump considered his own personal
abolition of boxing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I went to the Wharton School for Finance,'' Trump said.
``If boxers went to the Wharton School, they would be at a
disadvantage in boxing. Let's face it: Tough kids are the best
fighters. The nicest environment they know is the ring. What would
they be without boxing?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was suggested, many of them would be healthier in their
old age, and some would live to old age. But Trump said boxing was
a way of overcoming poverty and worse violence, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the old story about the boxer after a fight who said:
`That wasn't so tough. What was really tough was my father hitting
me on the head with a hammer.'''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Trump is supplying the figurative hammers for two
men to use on each other. He is joined in this cruel deal by the
suave executives at HBO and the slick proprietors of venues like
Madison Square Garden and now Radio City Music Hall, who sell
tickets for humans knocking each other senseless. And they are
enabled by governors like Christie Whitman of New Jersey and George
Pataki of New York who are not yet sufficiently horrified at the
carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Not even death is a goad to change. Trump said ``we are working
on something'' as a benefit for the Johnson family, and his
organization did house the Johnson family while the fighter
lingered in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Now life goes on. The buses rumble down the parkway bearing old
people from rest homes with dollars in their pockets for the slot
machines. And the big rollers arrive in limousines for a boxing
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate what happened,'' Trump said. ``It's something you have
to get through. I think boxing is an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases, the boxing ring is better than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he go back soon to a boxing match?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I relish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing goes on. Men continue to hit each other in the head in
buildings with the name Trump on them.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
