A6109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-RECEIVERS-2TAKES-     12-11 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RECEIVERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHANGE IS AT HAND AMONG RECEIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the 1985 National Football League season, and in Chicago,
they were doing a shuffle to the Super Bowl. Bo Jackson was a
first-round pick and Earl Campbell was about to retire. The Jets'
Kenny O'Brien was the highest-rated passer in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Kosar was arriving in Cleveland, as Mark Bavaro was
coming to the Giants. There was no NFL team in Arizona, but two in
Los Angeles: the Raiders and the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   In pro football years, it was a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   Consider then that the 1985 season was also the last time a wide
receiver named Rice, Irvin or Moore did not finish ranked among the
NFL's top 10 in either catches or receiving yards.
</P>
<P>
   And now, 14 years later, it appears that streak will end.
Michael Irvin and Herman Moore have missed much of the season with
injuries, and Jerry Rice, while still proficient, is well outside
the top 10. But just as Rice supplanted an established veteran like
Art Monk and Irvin supplanted Al Toon, Drew Hill or Gary Clark, in
1999 there are new names in the top 10 roll call of the NFL's best
receivers. They are Marvin Harrison, Germane Crowell, Jimmy Smith,
Muhsin Muhammad and Isaac Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   It is a changing of the guard, an ascent of a new breed of
receivers: big and small, physical and quick. Or best of all: big,
physical and quick.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the catalog of the league's elite receivers is more
than a kiddie corps. There are some familiar names with a seasoned
resumes, like Cris Carter or Tim Brown, who are each in the top
five in catches and yards this season. Moore, who is only 30, is
returning to the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   But the shift is dramatic leaguewide.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: even the Giants, who have not had a Pro Bowl
receiver in 31 years, have got into the act. Amani Toomer, 25, and
Ike Hilliard, 23, are each on a pace to have 1,000 receiving yards.
The Giants, in their 75th season, have never before had two
1,000-yard receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The standout of the youth movement at wide receiver is the
Indianapolis Colts' Marvin Harrison, who leads the NFL with 12
touchdown receptions and 1,239 receiving yards. His 82 receptions
are second only to the Jacksonville Jaguars' Jimmy Smith, the
two-time Pro Bowler who has 85 catches.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, 27, is only 6 feet and 181 pounds, but like Rice, he
is relentless about preparing for each new opponent. His teammates
call him Meticulous Marvin.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison's routes are precise, and he creates separation from
defenders with his acceleration after the pass is thrown, a skill
that defensive backs call ``sneaky quick.'' It matters more than a
receiver's 40-yard dash time.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, in what many saw as a coming-of-age victory for the
young Colts, the Miami Dolphins' skilled defense focused on holding
down Harrison and succeeded for most of the first three quarters.
As the Colts attempted one final last-minute drive, nothing had
changed in the Miami defensive huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 30 seconds to go and the mood was `Stop 88,'''
Dolphins cornerback Sam Madison said, referring to Harrison's
jersey number.
</P>
<P>
   Madison's post-game analysis was different. ``We didn't stop
him,'' he said. ``It was almost like he had been setting us up. At
crunch time, he just ran away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison caught two passes for 34 yards in that final drive,
putting the Colts in position for the game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of comparisons made about me to other
receivers from other years,'' Harrison said last week. ``It's nice,
but that kind of status is more of a goal than a reality. Those
guys have done it for many years. I am just beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   But what a beginning. In the midst of his fourth season,
Harrison already has 278 career receptions, which is more than Rice
had in his first four seasons. Harrison still has four games left
this year and played on a team that combined for only six victories
in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He is hardly the only new name helping to create the feel of a
generational shift at the wide receiver position.
</P>
<P>
   As Toomer said: ``I watch television on Sunday nights and
they'll put the day's 100-yard receivers on the crawl at the bottom
of the screen. You see all these different names you're not used to
seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Names like that of Crowell of Detroit, a 23-year-old,
second-year player, who in his last five games alone has 33 catches
for 630 yards with 4 touchdowns. Crowell, who has 1,035 receiving
yards this season, may have the whole package scouts look for. He
is fast and big at 6-3 and 220 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Crowell, who reads from the Book of Psalms in the final minutes
before a game, was drafted in the second round last year, five
spots before the Giants' slumping wide receiver Joe Jurevicius.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' Bruce, 27, has 11 touchdown catches and is hardly
unknown, since he was the league's second-ranked receiver in 1995
and a Pro Bowl choice in 1996. No one in the history of the NFL has
caught more passes in his first three seasons than Bruce, who had
224. But at 27, he is still pulling away, and maybe a better
all-round receiver.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the Jets' Keyshawn Johnson, who is 27; Smith, the
elder statesman of the younger crew at age 30 who is also first in
receptions and second in receiving yards this year; and Minnesota's
22-year-old Randy Moss, who, like Crowell, has speed and size at
6-4, 200 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Two other big receivers who rank among the league's elite are
Carolina's Muhammad, 26, who is 6-2 and 217 pounds, and Chicago's
Marcus Robinson, 24, who is 6-3, 215 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no consensus among NFL general managers about
what has brought about the emergence of a new class of receivers,
except the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change of guard is happening because it's time,'' Giants
general manager Ernie Accorsi said. ``We've got younger guys
catching up on older guys. I do see a trend in the game: you've
either got big receivers or little guys who can run fast. Your
first choice is to have both in one guy, but if you can't find
that, you try to get a speed guy and a big guy because the league
is going to littler cornerbacks and if you have a big guy, you have
a tremendous advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   As the game becomes more pass-happy, with most new rules
favoring an offense that throws the football, there are also more
good, big athletes becoming wide receivers early in their football
careers. Even at the high school level, the glamour isn't reserved
just for quarterbacks and running backs. College programs have
helped the cause, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``More colleges run pro-style offenses,'' said the Colts'
president, Bill Polian, who drafted Harrison and Buffalo's Andre
Reed, a top receiver since the late 1980s. ``So receivers come out
a little more ready or schooled in what will work for them in the
NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to a new pass-catching order, one, temporarily at
least, without Rice, Irvin or Moore. But new guys have a long way
to go to draw equal historically.
</P>
<P>
   For example, once Rice did crack the league's top 10 for the
first time in 1986, finishing second in catches and leading the
league in receiving yards, he remained among the top five in at
least one of those two categories _ and almost always both _ during
each of the next 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   That is what you call having some catching up to do.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
