<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GESTURING BY ATHLETES: THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE
UGLY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The psychiatrist says the throat-slashing gestures in pro
football may be a positive force, offering vicarious satisfaction
to fans and sublimating the players' desire to really hurt someone.
The psychologist says the gestures are symptomatic of something
much darker and more complicated than end zone posturing: Players
are acting out the projections of an angry America.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard gesture to interpret beyond the obvious
in-your-face, I'm-the-man message. Why is it necessary for some of
the country's richest, best-looking and most admired young men to
signify themselves with what seems to be a cheesy, adolescent,
retrograde symbol? Isn't scoring a touchdown enough? When did
winning become empty? Whatever happened to cool? Analyze that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me give you the superego argument,'' said Dr. Thomas J.
Ferraro, a Long Island psychologist who works with athletes,
particularly golfers. ``The country is freer, but there's more
aggression and fans are bored with overcontrolled, no-risk work.
They look to sports for explosive excitement. They throw snowballs
and batteries because they don't have a sense of justice,
self-love, guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players, narcissistic and lacking in identity, reflect the
fans' anger. There's no authority for them anymore. They ignore
Fassell and Parcells and Valentine. Joe Torre is an aberration. How
can a coach have authority in a time when `Married ... With
Children' has replaced `Father Knows Best'?''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Howard Katz, a Boston psychiatrist and psychoanalyst, thinks
that ``while sports serves as an outlet for aggressive energy, the
important question is: When does it go over the line? The throat
slashing is not OK if it undermines the other values of the game
such as sportsmanship and respect for opponents. I think the throat
slashing can be seen as a descendant of the antics of Jimmy Connors
and John McEnroe in tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, what Latrell Sprewell did to his coach was an assault. I
find it strange that some people excuse it or look the other way as
if it were somehow part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro and Katz are first-stringers in a new generation of
shrinks drawn to sports as an adjunct to a general practice. There
is excitement, money and publicity in dealing with a relatively
healthy population outside of managed care.
</P>
<P>
   The psychologists, in particular, concentrate on performance
enhancement, particularly on teaching athletes to focus on
realistic goals and to disconnect the emotional bonds that hamper
them. It's surprising how many athletes get injured or find other
ways to lose so they can punish the parents who pushed them.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between sports and mental health professionals
has traditionally been shaky; there seems to be a tendency for the
psychiatrists, in particular, to either dismiss athletics as
beneath their professional dignity or to be such passionate fans
that they blur their professional boundaries. Traveling with
athletes, befriending them, thrilled by access and confidence, they
think of themselves as part of the team.
</P>
<P>
   This can be as harmless as aping jocks. It has been as dangerous
as psychiatrists' becoming drug connections. Perhaps worst of all,
and most common, as evaluators of prospects or counselors to
troubled players, some shrinks lose sight of any responsibility to
the needs of the individual.
</P>
<P>
   Like many sports doctors in general, they see their job as
getting the athlete back in the arena _ to win, not necessarily to
become healthier. Their allegiance is to the customer _ team
management _ rather than to the patient.
</P>
<P>
   There is no great body of psychoathletic literature (we are
still waiting for Coach Jung), perhaps because athletes are so
devoted to quicker fixer-uppers _ drugs, religion, surgery _ and
rarely have the patience or playing time for psychoanalysis. Also,
few serious scholars outside the kinesiologists of physical
education and a few anthropologists have spent enough time on the
field and in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   My own favorite text was a Freudian analysis of baseball in
which the batter, who was the child, swung his bat in an attempt to
interrupt the relationship between dad, the pitcher, and mom, the
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, there are Oedipal aspects to sports,'' Ferraro said.
``Men play sports to re-enact the Oedipal conflict and work through
their anxieties. Think about that throat-slashing gesture. Cutting
off the head of the opponent. Think about the symbolism. Are you
saying, I chopped off his but didn't lose mine?''
</P>
<P>
   These would be interesting thoughts to bat around with Sprewell,
with Keyshawn Johnson (among the most celebrated of the throat
slashers), with Dennis Rodman and with Connors and McEnroe.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, some of this may be aired Friday, in New York, when
Katz will moderate a panel sponsored by the American Psychoanalytic
Association titled ``Sport, Society and Development: Helping Kids
Field Their Dreams.'' It is free and open to the public, at 10:30
a.m. in the Astor Salon of the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are seeing individual aggrandizement becoming more
important than subjugating oneself for the team,'' Katz said. ``I
think we have to realize that some of this comes from sports
itself. Teams utilize competition among members as a motivational
force; players are competing among themselves for space and time
before they compete against other teams. Aggressiveness is a major
tool. There seems to be a progressive movement in pro sports of
going over the boundaries, and then the field is no longer a safe
place for aggressive energy. Sprewell went beyond the boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate danger is when this becomes reflected in youth
sports. One high school baseball team I work with was recently
involved in an ethnic name-calling incident with another inner-city
school. It escalated into fistfights and then bats were raised. The
coaches and the umpire were just barely able to contain it. They
were badly shaken. But I'm even more worried when I see parents and
adult coaches abusing the 13-year-old umpire of a game among
8-year-olds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
