<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      12-11 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALLING THE PLAYS IS SOMETIMES THE COACH'S CALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan of the Denver Broncos is considered by many
National Football League coaches to be the best play-caller in the
game. The head coach spends dozens of hours during the week
planning.
</P>
<P>
   When he eats, he thinks about plays. When he dreams, he sees X's
and O's. During the Broncos' two Super Bowl runs, watching Shanahan
call plays was like seeing a skilled pilot perform the perfect
aerial maneuver. It was a thing of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   And Shanahan would never, ever permanently hand off the
play-calling duties to someone else on his staff, as coach Jim
Fassel of the New York Giants has done. In Shanahan's world, to do
so is blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the utmost confidence in my offensive coordinator, Gary
Kubiak,'' Shanahan said this past week, ``but the reason I have not
given up the play calling on a long-term basis is because I think
what happens is you remove yourself from the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``You become detached. I think it hurts you as a coach
in the long run. And what if you give those duties to your
offensive coordinator, and for a year or two he calls the plays,
then leaves for a head coaching job? Then instead of you learning
all of the nuances of the offense those few years, your offensive
coordinator learned them and took those lessons to another team.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the league, opinions differ on whether a head coach
should call the plays. When Fassel set aside his ego and handed the
play-calling duties to his quarterbacks coach, Sean Payton, last
Sunday, it was hailed as a smart move by the New York news media.
</P>
<P>
   But when you look elsewhere, a different picture emerges. In
some instances, as with Shanahan, the head coach calling the plays
works well. Coach Mike Holmgren of Seattle called the plays for the
Green Bay Packers during two Super Bowl runs.
</P>
<P>
   There have been mixed results in other situations. Bill Parcells
took over the New York Jets' play-calling duties this season and at
times has made strange decisions. Tom Coughlin, who began calling
the plays this season as well, has his Jacksonville Jaguars playing
at a high level.
</P>
<P>
   But without the buffer of an offensive coordinator between
Coughlin and his quarterback, Mark Brunell, the two have had their
rough moments, disagreeing at times on how the offense should be
run.
</P>
<P>
   The question of who should call the plays may center more on
control than anything else. The coaches who favor calling their own
plays think that since the head coach is the leader of the team, he
should command the troops on game day like a field general.
</P>
<P>
   Other head coaches feel an offensive coordinator can do a better
job because the head coach has too many different duties during the
week, like overseeing the defense or special teams or worrying
about team morale. An offensive coordinator does not fret about
such things, just the plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' game against the Jets last week was a good example
of how a coach's freeing himself from play-calling duties can help
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Payton works closely with the Giants' quarterbacks, and he knows
that because of the offensive line's struggles this season, the
quarterbacks are not crazy about long drop-backs to set up their
passes. The deeper the quarterback drops in the pocket, the longer
the offensive line must hold its blocks.
</P>
<P>
   So Giants quarterback Kerry Collins had a number of quick three-
and five-step drops against the Jets, as opposed to the deeper
seven-step drops Fassel had mostly been calling. The quick
drop-backs led to quick throws, and thus put the offense in more of
an attack mode.
</P>
<P>
   Another aggressive move by Payton came at the expense of Bill
Belichick, the Jets' smart defensive coordinator. Belichick, like
most of his brethren, studies game films relentlessly and composes
a game plan for his defense. He puts his thoughts on a large card,
as many coordinators do.
</P>
<P>
   The Jet players are then told what to expect in certain
situations. In most games this year, Fassel introduced few new
wrinkles to the offense, so Belichick thought he had a good idea of
what the Giants were going to do.
</P>
<P>
   But Payton wanted to change the Giants' tendencies and make
Belichick's studying _ and his card _ less useful. One example: a
third-and-4-play on which the Giants operated with their ``even
22'' personnel, which calls for two tight ends and two backs. Often
in this situation the team works out of the shotgun and passes.
Payton changed that by running out of the shotgun instead, catching
the Jets off guard.
</P>
<P>
   When Fassel was an offensive coordinator with Arizona, he ran a
wide-open offense. He was then, and is now, a smart offensive
coach. But he was also trying to get a head coaching position.
Fassel wanted to impress teams, and he did.
</P>
<P>
   But in New York, Fassel has grown more conservative and relied
heavily on his defense. As a head coach he seemed less willing to
take the chances he did as a coordinator with the Cardinals. Payton
helped put a little more spice in the Giants' offensive game.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, no matter who is calling the plays, the bottom
line is if it is successful, that is all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   COLTS LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Bill Polian of the Indianapolis Colts is already
looking at his team's future salary-cap situation. And he needs to,
because Polian will soon face the sort of problems that almost
destroyed the Dallas Cowboys, a team to which the Colts are often
compared.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts' threesome of quarterback Peyton Manning, running back
Edgerrin James and wide receiver Marvin Harrison currently consumes
12 percent of the team's salary cap, or about $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The three players could, in several years, eat up 25 to 30
percent of the cap, the way the Cowboys' threesome of Troy Aikman,
Emmitt Smith and Michael Irvin do now.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Colts could be severely restricted in the future
when it comes to bringing in free agents, as the Cowboys have been.
But Polian's draft skills should help offset any talent drought.
The Cowboys have drafted poorly in the last five years, while
Polian is one of the best talent evaluators in football.
</P>
<P>
   DITKA'S DAYS NUMBERED?
</P>
<P>
   Two 6-10 seasons and a current 2-10 record will most likely make
the New Orleans Saints' owner, Tom Benson, seriously consider
firing coach Mike Ditka after the season.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Benson might ask Ditka to make changes in his
staff, something Ditka would probably decline, thus forcing
Benson's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, only a strong run in the playoffs can save the job of
coach Pete Carroll of the New England Patriots. The Broncos'
offensive coordinator, Gary Kubiak, is a candidate to replace him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1640EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
