<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT TIME AROUND, RANGERS TRYING YOUTH
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBO-NOTEBOOK) 
(rk) 
 By   MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Texas Rangers have adopted a strange
course to take them past the New York Yankees, the team that has
stunted their October growth each time they have reached the
playoffs in three of the past four years. First, they traded Juan
Gonzalez, their No. 1 run producer, and now they have shed through
free agency two of their three other veteran outfielders, their
second baseman, two starting pitchers and a potential starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of planned it that way,'' General Manager Doug Melvin
said, discussing some of the Rangers who were not offered
arbitration and thus will not return. ``We signed them to contracts
to let our farm system catch up. Our system hadn't been doing well.
We wanted to keep the players down there. Now the farm system has
gotten to the point where we feel we have to give our younger
players a chance. But our payroll is still high enough that it
makes us a contender.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers surprisingly had the major leagues' second-highest
payroll this year, behind only the Yankees. But the expensive
collection of players was no match for the Yankees' more expensive
collection. For the second successive season, Gonzalez scored the
team's lone run in a three-games-and-out first-round playoff
encounter with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin traded Gonzalez because the club would not give him the
kind of money he wanted _ it wasn't Monopoly money _ to sign a
contract extension. The other outfielders, Tom Goodwin and Roberto
Kelly, were allowed to leave as free agents because they had
outlived their usefulness. So had second baseman Mark McLemore and
pitchers John Burkett and Mike Morgan. Jeff Fassero had been an
Aug. 31 pickup, someone the Rangers hoped would help in the
postseason and who started three games.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, the homegrown Ruben Mateo and Gabe Kapler, acquired in
the Detroit package for Gonzalez, will join Rusty Greer in the
outfield. Luis Alicea will get a chance to win a large share of the
second base job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be younger and more athletic with Kapler and Mateo,''
Melvin said. ``They're better all-around players, strong players.
Kapler's at the next stage of development. Mateo will be in his
first full year in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, who will be 22 years old next season, is the Rangers'
prized prospect. His introduction to the majors last season was
marred by injuries, including a broken bone in his left hand that
ended his season on Aug. 4. Kapler, 24, was the Tigers' 57th-round
selection in the 1995 draft but became a power-hitting prospect,
though he had a disappointing rookie season, struggling to hit
.245.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Gonzalez and Goodwin combined for 42 home runs and
161 runs batted in, Gonzalez obviously producing the bulk of those
numbers. ``If Mateo and Kapler hit 40 homers and drive in 130 runs
between them,'' Melvin said, ``that will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin cited other numbers: ``There's a big gap between the
$450,000 for the two of them and the $11 million that Juan and
Goodwin will make next year.''
</P>
<P>
   So was this a downsizing of salary, as other teams have done in
recent years when payrolls spiraled out of control? Did Tom Hicks,
the Rangers' relatively new owner, order Melvin to slash the
payroll?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the general manager said. ``He just said we have to have
an awareness of the payroll. We would spend the money if we thought
it was wise spending. With younger players coming along, it didn't
make sense to pay Tommy Goodwin the money he deserved to make.''
</P>
<P>
   The payroll will drop, Melvin acknowledged, but he added:
``We'll have the flexibility. We lost money with what was the best
team in franchise history. We didn't draw three million. We drew
2.7. We felt we needed to make some moves.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was one edict Hicks delivered, it was that the Rangers
would not pay the fee assessed against the teams with the five
highest payrolls based on the average annual value of players'
contracts, not just the 1999 salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin watched the numbers carefully and succeeded in avoiding
the tax man. The Yankees, Los Angeles, Baltimore, the Mets and
Atlanta will pay fees totaling just over $12 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the only way the Rangers fared better than the
Yankees. And while the Rangers get younger and more uncertain, the
Yankees remain, well, the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the tough part,'' Melvin said. ``You hope the Yankees
won't be as good every year. No doubt they have an advantage. They
give $2.5 million to a set-up reliever. We weren't willing to give
that to our second baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, aren't conceding anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can still win,'' Melvin said. ``I think we could
win 95 games again, but it will be tough putting younger players
into the mix. It's a possibility. I don't see why not. Obviously,
pitching is still the key. We feel our bullpen, which was real good
last year, can be as good or a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   Most immediately, the Rangers want to re-sign two free agents,
Aaron Sele, their No. 1 starter last season, and Todd Zeile, their
third baseman. They should know about Zeile by the end of the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
