<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTABLE LACK OF INTEREST 
THE AGENT GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBO-NOTEBOOK-RANGERS) 
(rk) 
 By   MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many teams did not seem to have much interest in the winter
meetings, which once were the high point of the off-season. The
meetings began Friday and run through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys are coming in Friday night and leaving Monday,''
one general manager said. But John Schuerholz of Atlanta planned to
arrive Sunday, and Ron Schueler of the Chicago White Sox didn't
plan to come at all. Neither did Brian Cashman of the Yankees, but
that wasn't his decision.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second year of the revived major league meetings.
They had ended after the 1992 gathering because officials and
owners looked at those meetings and saw that they were not good.
Player agents dominated them, getting 35 clients signed in a
three-day frenzy to contracts totaling $225 million. If the money
doesn't sound like much, remember this was seven years ago. It was
unprecedented in the 17-year history of free agency.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of the revived meetings last year, the Los
Angeles Dodgers signed Kevin Brown to a $105 million contract over
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``General managers fear the meetings will be a stage for
agents,'' one said. ``They're sitting face to face with them. They
go from one room to the next. They go back and forth within the
same day.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the general managers don't trust themselves to
be able to say no to the agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Agent Game
</P>
<P>
   Agents have discovered a way to make much more money than they
get from the fees their clients pay after signing
multimillion-dollar contracts. They sell their businesses to larger
companies for many, many more millions of dollars. In the past
year, three companies that represent baseball players have been
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Arn Tellem, a Los Angeles lawyer who clients include Albert
Belle, and Alan and Randy Hendricks of Houston, whose clients
include Roger Clemens, have sold their businesses to SFX
Entertainment, the company that also bought the agency run by David
Falk, agent for Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent agency to follow that path is Steinberg, Moorad
&AMP; Dunn of Newport Beach, Calif. Leigh Steinberg is noted as the
agent of the NFL quarterbacks. Jeff Moorad is the baseball agent,
representing such players as Shawn Green and Raul Mondesi. The sale
of the firm to the Assante Corp. of Winnipeg for $120 million
prompted a general manager to make a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why aren't their players entitled to some of that money?'' the
general manager said. ``Players should call the agents and say,
`Shouldn't I get a percentage of what you just made on us?' Without
the players, the business isn't worth what a company paid for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if the Hendricks brothers didn't have clients of
Clemens' caliber and Moorad did not have a player who could command
a $14 million annual contract, their businesses would not be worth
all of those millions.
</P>
<P>
   Assante's president, Martin Weinberg, basically confirmed that
view when he explained that it was easy to place a value on the
Steinberg-Moorad firm. ``It has a lot of multiyear contracts with
cash flow that can be counted on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the general manager's idea of giving a share of the sale
price to the agents' clients was mentioned to Moorad, he didn't
rush to endorse the plan. But he said, ``That's an interesting
perspective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1651EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
