<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' MARVIN JONES REGAINS ALL-AMERICAN TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teammates are falling around him, and the sight is painfully
reminiscent. But linebacker Marvin Jones has been left standing
this season amid the tumbling New York Jets. And he has started to
evoke memories of the time he was the most acclaimed defensive
player in college football.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Jones was second-guessing himself about his
halting play. Was he afraid to reinjure his surgically repaired
left knee?
</P>
<P>
   Jones decided to look at old films from college, when he was
everybody's all-American.
</P>
<P>
   Since his moment of self-doubt, Jones has been so good on the
field that as the Jets struggle with the loss this week of still
another player _ linebacker Bryan Cox is out after having abdominal
muscle surgery _ they do not have to abandon their usual defensive
stratagems.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a Jet defense orchestrated by Bill Belichick, which faces
Dan Marino and the Miami Dolphins at Giants Stadium on Sunday, will
at times use Jones on the inside of the 3-4 scheme, which is
dominated by linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is also the man in the middle of the 4-3 alignment,
although in both formations he is excused on passing downs to make
way for players of greater range. His being in the middle _ the
place Jones would like to be all the time _ is reminiscent of him
at his best, during his years at Florida State in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' resurgence this season is happening after he missed all
of last season with still another serious injury; he tore both the
anterior cruciate and the medial collateral ligaments in his left
knee when a teammate landed on him during a summer practice.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the films of last Sunday's loss to the New York
Giants, the Jets' coaching staff credited Jones with taking part in
17 tackles. That is a remarkable figure, considering that the
Giants had 75 offensive plays.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is only the third time Jones has played into December
since joining the Jets in 1993. In his seven pro seasons, he has
played only one year completely free of injury. That was 1997, Bill
Parcells' first season with the Jets. That is no coincidence, since
Parcells is a stickler for off-season conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Jones grew up in Miami, a Parade all-American linebacker at
Northwestern High School. Miami was a city famous for linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones considered Miami, but his brother had attended Florida
State. And anyway, Jones said: ``I was looking for stability. Bobby
Bowden had been at State for 20 years. Dennis Erickson was in his
first year at Miami, and Steve Spurrier was in his first year at
the University of Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   After Jones capped a three-year all-American career by capturing
the Lombardi Award as the top defensive player in college, along
with the Butkus trophy as college football's top linebacker, he
opted for the 1993 draft as a junior and thought about which team
might choose him. He knew the Patriots were going to draft first
under their new head coach, Bill Parcells, and he was kind of
hoping Parcells would take him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had a thing for the Giants, LT and the Big Blue
wrecking crew,'' Jones said of the days when Parcells led the
Giants and Lawrence Taylor. ``But I figured that he would go for a
quarterback. Drew Bledsoe was putting up big numbers in college,
and it was Parcells' first year, so he wanted to start with a
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, who had the third pick in the draft, traded it to
Phoenix for running back Johnny Johnson and the No. 4 choice. The
Jets chose Jones, as the first defensive player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Before the year was out, his season ended with a hip fracture.
The next season he sustained an ankle sprain that forced him to
miss every practice, although he played in almost every game. Then
in 1996 he sprained his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through it all: `Why me,'' Jones said. ``After last
season I decided I wanted to take care of a lot of things,
concentrate on myself physically and mentally, things I had never
done before.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked out in the Jets' off-season conditioning program,
something he eschewed until Parcells took over. He cut back on
socializing late into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just figured it out,'' he said. ``I had the time to think
about what would make me happy, what would make me at peace with
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even when this season began he was far from his best. Jones
was still not attacking the way he knew he should. Parcells noticed
that Jones still had his tentative moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were playing Buffalo in the second game,'' Jones
said, ``and I just realized it wasn't me. Whether I was worried
about the knee, I don't know. But I decided after that I was
running to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He also watched the college films of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed for me against Denver,'' Jones said of the game
Oct. 3 at Mile High Stadium, the Jets' first victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had five solo tackles and batted away a pass during that
game.
</P>
<P>
   He is now second on the team in tackles to strong safety Victor
Green, the perennial leader. Jones has 73 tackles and has recorded
his first career interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these things I did in the off-season, the physical and
the mental, helped me,'' he said. ``I don't look at it as I've been
dealt a bad hand now. I look at it as just having had some
interruptions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
