<SLUG> BC-SOC-NCAA-MEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANA AND SANTA CLARA, BOTH WEARY, TO PLAY FOR SOCCER TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ No one could blame Indiana and Santa Clara for
practicing ever so lightly Saturday for Sunday's match to determine
the collegiate champion in men's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   After both teams were engaged in quadruple overtime games in the
semifinals a night earlier, they needed all the rest they could
get.
</P>
<P>
   The college semifinals this year were what several regular
followers of the tournament called the greatest day in college
soccer, men's or women's.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana eliminated UCLA, 3-2, in 141 minutes 24 seconds in the
second game Friday night, after it took Santa Clara 138:50 to
eliminate a highly technical Connecticut team by 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana and Santa Clara are fairly familiar with each other.
Santa Clara has defeated Indiana three times, but the Hoosiers
routed the Broncos, 4-0, in last year's semifinals before winning
their fourth championship with a triumph over Stanford. This will
be their first meeting in the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, finals are not classic games,'' Jerry Yeagley,
in his 27th year as coach of the Hoosiers, said about Sunday's
game. ``We won't be able to tell the effects of the semifinals
until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The semifinals were a special night for college soccer. It
marked one of the most entertaining days in the history of the
final four and I have been to just about all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeagley went to the semifinals as a player with West Chester
State and won a national title in his senior year in the 1961
edition of the tournament, which was started in 1959. He has taken
Indiana to 13 semifinal games as coach. And he has the most
victories (477) among all active soccer coaches in Division I.
Steve Negoesco of San Francisco has the most victories (526) of all
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana has a record of 20-3-0 this season and will be seeking
its fifth national title Sunday at Ericsson Stadium in a game that
will be broadcast live by ESPN at 1 p.m. Santa Clara is 16-3-3 and
will be vying for its second championship.
</P>
<P>
   While Indiana's titles have been captured outright, Santa Clara
shared the title with Virginia in 1989 in subfreezing temperatures
at Rutgers Stadium in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara may have the advantage over Indiana in having played
all of its tournament games on the road. Under the direction of
coach Mitch Murray, the Broncos have also won three overtime games
in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana and Santa Clara are very well organized defensively and
have similar statistics in that area. Indiana has 14 shutouts and
has allowed 14 goals, while Santa Clara has 11 shutouts and has
allowed 17 goals. One man Santa Clara's defense impressed the most
was Ray Reid, the coach of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as good a defensive team as we've seen in the country,
and obviously we had trouble breaking them down,'' Reid said of
Santa Clara, which ended Connecticut's 12-game winning streak.
``Hopefully, this will be a building block for next year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana allowed its first goal in four games in the tournament
in the victory over UCLA. The Hoosiers had a two-goal lead with
goals from Pat Noonan and Yuri Lavrinenko, but UCLA rallied in
regulation on goals by Steve Shak in the 77th minute and Scot
Thompson in the 83rd before Ryan Mack, Indiana's indefatigable
midfielder, scored his winner in the fourth sudden-death overtime.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the Hoosiers got the opportunity to defend their
title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1654EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
