<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TRANSIT-STRIKE-(TR     12-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRANSIT-STRIKE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC TO SEEK PENALTIES AGAINST TRANSIT UNION IF IT STRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ratcheting up the pressure on union negotiators for
New York City's 33,000 subway and bus workers, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said Saturday that city lawyers would seek an injunction
Monday that would lay out the financial penalties the union would
face if it goes on strike.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said some contingency plans designed to reduce
disruption across the city, including wider deployment of privately
operated vans, may be set in motion before the union's contract
expires at 12:01 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference, the mayor also said that the police were
vigorously investigating an incident of vandalism in the subway
system on Friday afternoon on the suspicion that it might have been
committed by union workers.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by Police Commissioner Howard Safir, who said 2,400
additional officers would be called in to work each day if a strike
occurs, the mayor said the subway vandalism occurred at 4:20 p.m.
Friday at the 34th Street station of the Eighth Avenue line, where
a switch was activated to move a local train to the express track.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of switching the train, the tampering tripped a security
system and turned off power, he said. But the vandalism, which
Giuliani said could have been accomplished only by someone with a
key to the switch, could have resulted in a collision and serious
injuries if the safety device had not been tripped, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make a very big deal out of this,'' Giuliani said.
``If we catch the person who did it, we would expect that person to
go to prison for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clear warning to union leaders that they should discourage
acts of violence or sabotage, he added that he ``will hold the
union accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Union officials were in negotiations and could not be reached
for comment on the mayor's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Marc Shaw, the executive director of the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority, said Saturday that the
incident had caused train service to be delayed for 30 minutes. But
he said it had not posed a threat to safety because, when the track
switch was activated, it immediately caused signal lights to turn
red and also set off an electronic braking system that would have
prevented trains from going through the red lights.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who met Saturday morning with more than 10 of his
commissioners and senior advisers to refine plans designed to cope
with a strike, said city lawyers would seek an injunction Monday
that lays out financial penalties that the union would face if a
strike occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Such penalties are dictated by the state's Taylor Law, which
prohibits strikes by public employees. Under the law, each worker
would be fined two days' pay for each day of the strike, and the
city could seek penalties from the union to cover losses.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the potential loss, which the mayor said Friday
could reach $25 million a day, appeared to be growing Saturday,
since Safir said he expected the expense of adding police officers
for traffic control and security of the subway system to be $3.9
million a day, nearly four times a previous estimate by Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   In threatening to seek full compensation from the union, the
mayor said city lawyers would seek penalties to cover expenses that
are incurred even before a strike begins. Unlike the resolution of
prior court battles involving the Taylor Law, he said, the city
would not lessen its demands for full compensation as part of a
settlement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``In the past, people have been willing to compromise in the
months after a strike is over and begins to be forgotten,'' said
city Corporation Counsel Michael Hess, who joined Giuliani at the
press conference. To that, the mayor said, ``I won't forget.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its contingency, the city planned to set up a Web
site, www.nyclink.org, to provide detailed information on such
things as the areas where cars with fewer than three people will be
banned, increased schedules for commuter trains, and the location
of more than 50 parking lots that are to be set aside to discourage
people from driving into Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said some plans may be set in motion as early as
Monday, including a plan to encourage the operators of private van
services to broaden and increase their routes, filling some of the
void left if subway and bus service is interrupted. He said
companies that supply food, retail products and other goods in
Manhattan would also be encouraged, beginning Monday, to adjust
delivery schedules to avoid the morning and late-afternoon rush
hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
