<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-Gore-Ga-Cox     12-11 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Gore-Ga-Cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Influential Black Politicians Vow to Help Gore
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some of the nation's most influential African American
politicians vowed Saturday to wage a political crusade ``of
biblical proportions'' to elect Al Gore president and to restore
Democratic control of Congress next year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in response, promised to use the presidency to counter any
challenge to affirmative action, one of the most significant
legislative gains of the modern civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who says that affirmative action is no longer needed
because we've reached the promised land has confused wilderness
with Canaan,'' the vice president declared.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's declaration followed a summit with hundreds of black
leaders from around the country at the offices of Atlanta Life
Insurance Co., the nation's largest African American-owned and
-controlled company.
</P>
<P>
   The company's offices are located on Atlanta's historic Auburn
Avenue, the main thoroughfare of the community from which the late
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. led his historic civil rights crusades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no accident that Vice President Gore has come today here
in Atlanta, to the most historic street in African American history
to launch this African American movement and crusade to elect this
man president of the United States,'' Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell
told the hundreds of supporters who jammed an auditorium in the
Atlanta Life offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crusade of biblical proportions because we will
change the way this country thinks about politics in the election
in November,'' Campbell added.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Mayor Maynard Jackson said black voter turnout,
if high enough, could produce ``a clean sweep'' for the Democratic
Party next year - winning the White House, the Senate and the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said African Americans, long denied the right to vote in
the South, ``have an obligation to our children to use the power
for which we have struggled.'' He said African Americans ``don't
need to beg anybody for anything'' when they can use the ballot to
``smack somebody in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   The summit coincided with the Gore campaign's announcement that
more than 2,000 African American leaders have endorsed the vice
president over rival Bill Bradley in the contest for the Democratic
presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   The list of endorsements released at the summit included nearly
every black member of Congress, some of whom were on hand to help
energize African American interest in the upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis of Atlanta, one of the most famous civil rights
pioneers, invoked the names of voting rights martyrs in order to
spur greater African American participation in next year's
election. And he called Gore ``our brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis brought his listeners to their feet when he noted that
black voter turnout could also result in the Democratic Party
reclaiming the majority in Congress that it lost in 1994, the
result of which could be to ``bring Bob Barr back to Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr, who represents an Atlanta area congressional district, was
one of President Clinton's most active critics and the first member
of Congress to call for Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Texas not only promoted Gore's
candidacy but took a verbal swipe at Gov. George W. Bush, her
fellow Texan, and his campaign rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a state that understands that 'compassionate
conservatism' speaks but it does not act,'' she said, noting the
declining enrollment of minorities at Texas universities as a
result of legal challenges to affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Roy Barnes and U.S. Sen. Max Cleland, two of Georgia's
most prominent white politicians, also were on hand to rally black
voters for Gore. Both won their last elections with the help of
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got elected because each of you rose up at a particular time
... and said, 'We are not going backward anymore','' Barnes
reminded them.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a longtime champion of improved race relations, was
largely ignored at the campaign event. Only Gore mentioned him by
name in expressing ``gratitude'' over the news of Bradley's
improved health.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man, a great competitor - I look forward to
continuing our discussion,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the focus of the event was more on the general
election, in which the turnout of minority voters is likely to be
crucial to Democratic Party successes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged as much in noting that the Republican Party is
``blowing the roof off'' election finances, a reference to the
record-setting fund raising of Bush, the frontrunner for the GOP
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that here, in the South, we have the capacity
to blow the roof off voter registration and turnout,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   African American voters constitute about 40 percent of the
Democratic primary vote in the 11 states of the Old Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
