<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-YACHT-AMERICAS-CUP-NY     12-11 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPERATE YOUNG AMERICA CAN CONTROL ITS DESTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the preliminary trials for the America's Cup began nearly
two months ago off Auckland, New Zealand, the New York Yacht Club's
Young America team was on the short list of favorites to win the
Louis Vuitton challenger series and face the defending Kiwis in
February's cup finals. But for the New Yorkers, that simple plan
has gone terribly awry.
</P>
<P>
   Six teams will advance to next month's semifinal round of
challenger racing, and Young America is now in a desperate battle
to secure the sixth and final spot. Four syndicates have qualified
for the semifinals: Italy's Prada Challenge, Paul Cayard's America
One, Dawn Riley's America True and Japan's Nippon Challenge.
Barring a total collapse in the closing days of the trials, Dennis
Conner's Stars and Stripes will retain the fifth spot.
</P>
<P>
   With a handful of squads already eliminated, that leaves Young
America and Le Defi Francais _ two teams seemingly headed in
opposite directions _ to jostle for the remaining berth. On
Saturday, the French continued their stunning third-round roll by
beating America One to register their fifth straight victory. Young
America also recorded a much-needed victory _ its 2 minute,
13-second margin over Bravo Espana dashed Spain's hopes of
advancing _ but it was only its third triumph in the last seven
races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a slump,'' Young America's president, John Marshall,
said in a phone interview from Auckland Saturday. ``For us, the
question is whether we can overcome a string of bad luck and bad
sailing and still go out and sail great races. I have a very strong
conviction that the answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   With three races remaining, including a vital match Sunday with
America True, Young America still controls its own destiny. If
Young America wins them all, it will advance. But the French also
have three races to go, and they hold a slight edge over the New
Yorkers on points. Should both teams sweep their next two races, it
will set up a winner-take-all contest between Young America and Le
Defi on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This regatta is in the human phase right now,'' Marshall said.
``It's not technologically dominated, it's now a sailors' regatta.
For our team, the coming days will be a test of inner strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Young America's early-round momentum came to a crashing halt on
Nov. 9, when the first of its two new boats, USA 53, cracked and
nearly sank.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorkers hurriedly substituted their second boat, USA 58,
but Marshall said it might not have been ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's conceivable that 58 may be underperforming,'' he said.
``The conditions have been very shifty, so it's difficult to be
dead sure on boat speed. But it may be that we're not going as fast
as we were on 53.''
</P>
<P>
   But Young America has also been plagued by tactical mistakes,
particularly in recent losses to Italy and Japan. For that reason,
Marshall also conceded that he had considered making changes in the
afterguard led by the skipper, Ed Baird.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we decided that anything we could do on short notice, that
hasn't been planned and drilled, would have a negative effect,''
Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think history bears it out. Desperation changes are almost
always negative ones.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one interested observer, America One's Cayard, believes
that Young America's near sinking had a devastating effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty major incident, and it seems like it
destabilized them,'' he said in a phone interview. ``It looks like
they haven't been able to get the program back on track where
they're solid, confident and calm. They're just not sailing their
best.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cayard, whose team scored an important victory over Young
America last Thursday, also says the light, shifty breezes of the
last week have played havoc with the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything's wrong with Young America's boat,'' he
said. ``I think they're pretty fast. But in the conditions we've
had recently, everybody's dangerous. If you sail smart, anyone can
win. It's not such a speed contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the big picture, Cayard believes that in the third
round, Italy's Prada Challenge, a team that once appeared
invincible, finally exhibited at least a veneer of vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may still come out on top of the round, but they've lost
a few races now,'' he said. ``As far as improvement goes, their
curve is much flatter than the rest of us. I didn't expect that to
happen until the semifinals.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard, for one, knows that a semifinal encounter with Prada is
assured.
</P>
<P>
   Young America must run the table to seal a similar fate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
