<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS STAY COOL AGAINST STIFF ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the the New York Giants are going to have any chance to
qualify for the playoffs, they will almost certainly have to win at
least one of their next two games: a matchup at Buffalo on Sunday
afternoon or one at St. Louis next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Some choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams have scored more points than any team in the National
Football League, and the Bills have not lost at home to any team
from the Giants' division, the National Conference East, since
1987.
</P>
<P>
   As the Giants head to Ralph Wilson Stadium on Sunday, they have
no experience playing against Bills quarterback Doug Flutie. Also,
the Giants' top four cornerbacks are injured, as are the starting
center and two of the team's three tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills, meanwhile, are coming off a bye week, and such pauses
in the schedule have been good to other Buffalo teams, which have
won nine of their 10 games after a bye week. And the Bills have won
11 of their last 13 home games.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Giants, it is not supposed to snow Sunday. Of course, the
Giants were rooting for snow, thinking it might make it harder for
Flutie and the Bills to prey on the Giants' banged-up secondary. It
is very likely that the Giants will be forced to start Jeremy
Lincoln and Emmanuel McDaniel at cornerback because Jason Sehorn
has a broken leg and Phillippi Sparks has a groin muscle pull and a
case of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, the Giants had a curious confidence about them
this past week, the sly grin of someone playing possum, as if they
_ if no one else _ truly believed they had a chance Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As the injuries mounted this week, even coach Jim Fassel was
making jokes. When tight end Dan Campbell was the last to go down
Friday with a severe hamstring pull, Fassel said, ``It's tough, but
we'll take 46 guys up there _ I think we'll find 46 _ and get ready
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   This road game is an obscure trip for the Giants, who have
played the Bills at their home in Orchard Park, N.Y., only four
times since 1970. Only two Giants who will be active Sunday played
in the last meeting, a 1993 game won by the Bills, 17-14, after a
late touchdown pass by Jim Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that game and the stadium,'' defensive tackle Keith
Hamilton said. ``The people are right on top of you, screaming at
you like Giants fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Jessie Armstead, who also played in the 1993 game,
said: ``It was loud. They love their football up there. Just really
loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel expects as much Sunday. He had the team practice inside
Giants Stadium on Friday so he could use the public address system
to blare crowd noise at his offense whenever it lined up to run a
play.
</P>
<P>
   A loud crowd will test the exchange between quarterback Kerry
Collins and center Derek Engler, who will be making his first start
in front of Collins because Brian Williams sustained a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd will also test the sideline communication system used
between Collins and the quarterbacks coach Sean Payton, who is now
in charge of calling the plays. Hand signals may be necessary,
something that can lead to confusion even among coaches and
quarterbacks who have worked together for years.
</P>
<P>
   It does not add up to the easiest assignment for these Giants,
but again, they seemed strangely at ease as they went about their
preparations for Sunday's game, one of two that will decide if the
Giants have anything to look forward to besides Christmas.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1721EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ARYAN-FAMILY-1STLD-WR     12-11 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARYAN-FAMILY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW AN HONOR STUDENT BECAME A WHITE WARRIOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Wash., Ark., Ohio, Utah, Okla., Idaho, Mont.)  (SUBS to add ``prepared in conjunction'' note)  
 This article was reported in conjunction with a documentary on the
subject produced by New York Times Television for the Showtime
network, scheduled to appear Sunday night at 9:30. 
 (lh) 
 By JO THOMAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a 10th-grader, Chevie Kehoe was an honor student who dreamed
of joining the Air Force and becoming a pilot. His parents, white
supremacists who despised the federal government, took him out of
school and urged him to become a white warrior instead. He
objected, but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   By the age of 24, Kehoe was one of the most notorious white
supremacists in the United States, having engaged in a kidnapping,
three robberies, three murders and two police shootouts, all in a
quest to establish an Aryan republic for white people.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his violent journey from talented and well-liked
teen-ager to merciless terrorist, Kehoe, now 26 and serving life in
prison, blames his family for his troubles. In a lengthy interview
in jail shortly after his sentencing, the only interview he has
given since his arrest in 1997, he said, ``In my entire life, my
dad always hated this or hated that and never gave me something to
love or something to work toward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely confusing, because you get left with this bag
of anger, and you have no place to focus, you have nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   As self-serving as Kehoe's comments are _ he also maintains his
innocence and accuses his mother of framing him _ they help
illuminate the power of family pressure to twist and distort a
young life, especially in the isolated environment of the country's
anti-government movements, and to turn promise into poison.
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe was born in 1973 and named after his father's
favorite car, the Chevrolet. The father, Kirby Kehoe, was a skilled
auto mechanic who had served with the Navy in Vietnam and had
returned with a skin rash that ultimately was diagnosed as a rare
form of cancer. He blamed exposure to Agent Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Chevie was born, Kehoe moved his family from
Florida to the mountains of western North Carolina to get away from
the crowds, settling in Sam's Gap, N.C. It was the beginning of
years of isolation and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Their home was destroyed by fire, and unable to rebuild, the
Kehoes lived in a garage with no plumbing, no insulation and no
heat. A neighbor, Dixie Lee Tipton, remembers buying Chevie and his
brothers beds; they had been sleeping on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tipton recalls Chevie as ``the most beautiful little child
I had ever seen, and very, very polite.'' In elementary school in
nearby Mars Hill, he was an ``A'' student in a class for the gifted
and talented.
</P>
<P>
   In jail many years later, he recalled having many friends, but
no close ones. And when Mrs. Tipton offered to take the boys to
church, Mrs. Kehoe refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad didn't like other people,'' Chevie Kehoe said. ``He was
concerned about bad habits rubbing off on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The pattern continued in 1985 when Kirby Kehoe moved his family
to Washington state, where he eventually bought a cabin on 20 acres
near Deep Lake, a mountain community near the Idaho border.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kirby Kehoe worked a series of jobs as a mechanic. His father,
Doyle Kehoe, said in an interview that he ``cver hold a
job,'' adding: ``Everyone he worked for cheated him. He always
didn't get along.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe put it this way: ``Dad didn't do well. He was too
independent. He didn't like to have a boss.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Chevie entered Colville Junior High School, 25 miles from Deep
Lake, as a ninth-grader in 1987. Kent Roberts, a science teacher,
remembered him as an honor student, well-liked, happy to help out
after school or on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to run track, but his parents refused to allow it. His
friends, he said, were not welcome at home; his parents grew
marijuana, and they did not want people coming around who might
talk about it. He did manage to go to a school dance after Mrs.
Roberts tailored one of her husband's suits to fit him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the parents pulled Chevie and his younger brother
Cheyne out of public school, and from then on home-schooled their
sons _ eventually they had eight. ``My father saw school as a
threat,'' Chevie Kehoe said, adding that, in his case, home
schooling did not work well. ``My mom is not a teacher. She didn't
have patience. She didn't have her education. I ended up being
self-taught. At 15, I told myself, `I'm not going anywhere.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Kehoes were anti-government white separatists, followers of
the Christian Identity religion, which teaches that whites are the
chosen people and that Jews are the descendants of Satan.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was extremely racist, extremely anti-Semitic in the
sense he would like to exterminate anything that's not white,''
Chevie Kehoe said. ``If they're not white, then they don't have the
right to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on the Kehoe boys to come around to their parents'
way of thinking was intense. Chevie won small battles, getting a
driver's license and a Social Security number despite their
disapproval. And at 17, he said, ``I was eight hours away from
signing up with the Navy. I had a person who was going to drive me
to the recruiting office in Spokane.''
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, he said, his hero had been the actor Tom Cruise in
``Top Gun'': ``Not because it was violent. Not because he had
power. It had to do with freedom. I wanted to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did not go to Spokane. ``My dad talked me out of it,'' he
said. Instead, he married a neighbor, Karena Gumm, and a year later
they had a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   They had met in junior high school, he remembered. ``Both of us
were virgins. That was a long time and a lot of innocence ago.''
</P>
<P>
   By then Chevie had entered his parents' separatist world. He
occasionally attended potluck suppers at the Ark, a Christian
Identity church not far from Deep Lake. Once, he listened to a
lecture there by the widow of Gordon Kahl, an anti-tax activist who
had become a martyr to the white right.
</P>
<P>
   He and his parents also began to study the ideas of Robert
Mathews, who had formed an underground terrorist group, the Order,
in the Pacific Northwest years before. Mathews died in 1984 in a
fiery shootout with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with his concept of separatism,'' Chevie Kehoe said of
Mathews. ``I agree with his concept that the government is not
truly for the people. I respected his dedication. I respected him
as a man, as an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   He also met Mathews' widow at the Aryan Nations compound near
Hayden Lake, Idaho. And his thinking hardened in 1992, he said,
when agents from the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms raided the home of a family friend, Del Knudson.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to see the government come up there with all these
police cars and helicopters and all that,'' he said, ``and tear his
house apart, tear books off shelves, confiscate computer disks,
confiscate every firearm he had, go through his garage, handcuff
his wife, terrorize his children _ to see that the government has
that type of power, you know something's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As time passed, Chevie Kehoe came to imagine that he might
someday achieve Robert Mathews' goal: a whites-only nation. He
wanted to call it the Aryan People's Republic.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when Chevie was 21, Kirby and Gloria Kehoe moved their
family to Kingston, Ark., in the Ozarks, they became friends
with a gun dealer, William Mueller, and his wife, Nancy. They
traveled the same gun show circuit, shared anti-government views,
and identified with the Christian Identity religion.
</P>
<P>
   But friendship did not stand in the way of profit. In January
1995, Kirby and Chevie Kehoe burglarized the Muellers' home in
Tilly, Ark., and took thousands of dollars' worth of guns and gold
and silver coins.
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe then returned to Washington, on the way stopping at
Elohim City, a Christian Identity community in Oklahoma, where he
asked an escaped convict, Faron Lovelace, to accompany him for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   On June 12, 1995, Kirby and Chevie Kehoe mounted another
fund-raising operation in Colville, Wash., sending Lovelace into
the home of two well-to-do grocery store owners, Malcolm and
Jillian Friedman. Lovelace later said he targeted the Friedmans
because he thought they were Jewish and would be easy to kill if
something went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Lovelace held Friedman hostage and ordered Mrs. Friedman to go
out and collect cash. Then he forced the Friedmans to go to
Spokane, where he set them free.
</P>
<P>
   The money from the Arkansas and Washington crimes went to buy
land near Priest River, Idaho, where Chevie Kehoe planned to set up
a training camp for revolutionaries, prosecutors in his trial said.
</P>
<P>
   By winter, the money was gone, and knowing that William Mueller
had come into a $50,000 inheritance, Chevie Kehoe decided to rob
him again. This time, his accomplice was Danny Lee, a skinhead from
Oklahoma with lightning bolts tattooed on his neck. Lee was known
as ``Cyclops'' because he had lost an eye in a bar fight.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 11, 1996, Kehoe and Lee, disguised as federal agents,
broke into the Muellers' home and waited for the family to return.
It was almost summer by the time the remains of the family _ the
father, mother and 8-year-old daughter, Sarah _ were found in the
Illinois Bayou near Russellville. A woman who was fishing hooked a
shoe and a bone.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kehoe later told investigators that her son told her about
his role in the Mueller murders shortly after the crime, but that
she kept quiet. That July 1996, the Kehoe family had moved to
another remote home, in Yaak, Mont. Cheyne and his wife and son
lived nearby until that winter, when Chevie came to get them. The
two brothers and their families drove south together to look for
work in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyne knew nothing about the murders until they were traveling
together and Chevie began selling guns because they could not find
work. At that point his brother told him, Cheyne later told
investigators, because some of the guns had been stolen from the
Muellers.
</P>
<P>
   By then, investigators were tracing other Mueller guns to the
Kehoes. Shortly after the family disappeared, the pistol from an
empty gun box found in the house was recovered at a Seattle pawn
shop and traced to Kirby Kehoe. Months later, another Mueller gun,
an AR-15 rifle, was recovered from Sean Haines, a former Aryan
Nations youth leader. It had been sold by Chevie Kehoe.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers' luck ran out as they traveled through Ohio, where
a state trooper stopped them for driving with expired plates.
Chevie broke away from being searched because he was carrying a
gun, and Cheyne opened fire. The ensuing gun battle, caught on
videotape by a camera on the trooper's dashboard, was broadcast
nationwide. But both brothers escaped.
</P>
<P>
   With help from their parents, the brothers and their families
escaped to Utah, where the men found work under assumed names. But
according to Cheyne Kehoe and his wife, Tanna, Chevie's behavior
became more violent and erratic. When Chevie said he was thinking
of killing his parents so he could raise his younger brothers
himself, Cheyne decided he had to be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyne surrendered on June 16, 1997. The next day, using his
information, the FBI arrested Chevie Kehoe.
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe was charged with federal racketeering counts that
included the three murders. At his trial in Little Rock this year,
the principal witnesses for the prosecution were his brother Cheyne
and his mother, Gloria.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Gloria Kehoe had called the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms and said her husband had struck her and pointed an
AR-15 rifle at her. ``My husband was going to kill me,'' she said.
``I knew too much. I wanted my nightmare to be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria and Cheyne Kehoe told the jury that Chevie Kehoe
confessed to them that he and Danny Lee had surprised the Muellers,
handcuffed the parents, stunned them with an electric stun gun and
taped plastic bags over their heads to suffocate. Then they had
forced 8-year-old Sarah to tell them where her parents' valuables
were hidden. Then, when Danny Lee said he could not kill a child,
Chevie Kehoe killed her.
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe was sentenced to three life terms. Lee was
sentenced to death. Cheyne had been sentenced to 24 years for the
Ohio shootout, and Kirby Kehoe had been sentenced to 44 months in
prison after pleading guilty to racketeering charges and admitting
he belonged to his son's white supremacist organization.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe said afterward that his mother's testimony
shattered him. ``What more powerful witness can you put on the
stand than a person's mother?'' he asked. He said he told himself:
``It's not Mom up there. It's somebody I don't know. Mom wouldn't
do this to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He contended that his mother, with six sons still at home,
agreed to testify because she was afraid the government would
prosecute her for tax evasion in the sale of the family's property
in Arkansas, where she had used a false Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her husband was in prison,'' Chevie Kehoe said. ``My brother
was in prison. I'm in prison. If she's in prison, where do her six
children go? I was the sacrifice to save my other brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In August, when Kirby Kehoe was sentenced, Judge G. Thomas
Eisele of U.S. District Court said he was sorry that sentencing
guidelines would not let him impose a longer sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're dealing with here is the man who is the father of
Chevie Kehoe, the man who raised Chevie Kehoe,'' he said. Although
Kirby Kehoe was not responsible for all his son's deeds, Eisele
said, ``he was a major factor in his son's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevie Kehoe put it this way: ``I'm the one left at the end of
the chain of these people's beliefs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
