<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MD-NEO-TRADITIONALISM     12-11 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MD-NEO-TRADITIONALISM-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: OUTSIDE BALTIMORE, A REACH BACK TO THE 19TH CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHARLES BELFOURE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLICOTT CITY, Md. _ A small residential subdivision nearing
completion in this Howard County community is the first in the
Baltimore metropolitan area to use a new land planning method that
is actually a throwback to late 19th- and early 20th-century
suburban neighborhood designs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Terra Maria, a 55-acre, 102-house development 14 miles west of
downtown Baltimore, is a neo-traditional neighborhood based on
century-old planning principles.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the late 1980s, urban planners and architects
sought to create residential communities different from the usual
cul-de-sac subdivisions used since World War II. These developments
are characterized by porch-fronted houses on small lots lining
narrow streets and within walking distance of parks, stores and
schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Terra Maria site was once part of a 253-acre landholding
owned by Charles Carroll of Carrollton, a signer of the Declaration
of Independence. Before his death in 1832, Carroll, a Roman
Catholic, was persuaded to give the land to the archdiocese of
Baltimore for the construction of a high school for young men
considering entering the priesthood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Named St. Charles College in honor of its benefactor, the school
grew into a large campus, but in 1911 it burned down, leaving only
the shell of a recreation hall. Over the years, the land passed
through several owners and, among other things, was used for an
evangelical camp. In 1978, the remaining acreage was purchased by
Robert and Donna Lancelotta, who named it Terra Maria, the Latin
translation of Maryland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Their son, Robert Lancelotta Jr., came up with the idea of
creating a neo-traditional development.
</P>
<P>
   In the early `90s, he had read about the pioneering traditional
neighborhood design work of Andres Duany and Elizabeth
Plater-Zyberk, Miami-based architects who created such nationally
known projects as Seaside, in the Florida panhandle near Panama
City, and Kentlands in Gaithersburg, Md., just outside Washington.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another inspiration came from a group of estate buildings in
front of Carroll's manor house, all of which survive directly
across the road. ``I wanted to create the same village-like feel
for the development,'' said the younger Lancelotta. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Duany visited the site and did some conceptual work, but
eventually the project was turned over to Uri Avin, a principal of
LDR International, a land planning firm based in Columbia, Md. The
goal of Avin, who created a new site plan in 1993, was to create an
intimate streetscape with sidewalks, a community center and open
spaces and to include a mix of uses such as a day-care center,
professional offices, and retail space.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In neo-traditional work, one of the main trade-offs is using
small lots in place of the usual one- or half-acre parcels to
preserve more of the natural features of the site and have public
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a background of tall, mature trees and each sub-area
of homes has its own greenspace as well as a main one for the
community,'' explained Avin. One of the open areas incorporates the
ruins of the recreation hall, which was preserved by the Lancelotta
family.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another important tenet of neo-traditional work that was
included in Terra Maria was the de-emphasis of the automobile. Some
garages are either off alleys behind the houses or accessed by
driveways and pushed to the rear of the lot in order to avoid a
subdivision look. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Street widths in Terra Maria were reduced from a standard 26
feet to 18 feet to reduce traffic speed and also cut paving costs.
Because of smaller lot sizes, the cost of laying utility lines was
significantly less.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Terra Maria turned out to be more of a hybrid than a true
neo-traditional project because of its lack of mixed uses. A parcel
fronting on Frederick Road was originally scheduled to be a small
retail center with apartments above. But that proved economically
unfeasible, so the lot was rezoned for a day-care center with
professional offices on the second floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lancelottas teamed with Synergy Development Venture II, a
land development company based in Baltimore that became the
managing member of Terra Maria LLC. The development company sold
the lots to individual builders who in turn sold the land and
houses beginning in January 1997. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because Terra Maria is the first development to be based on a
neo-traditional model in suburban Baltimore, many builders and
developers are looking at its sales results to gauge the market's
acceptance of the concept. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although all 102 lots are sold, according to David DeMauro of
Synergy, ``it was a hard sell.'' The main problem, he explained,
was that a buyer could purchase a house on a 6,000 to 12,000 square
foot lot in Terra Maria or go within a five-mile radius and get a
home for the same price on about a half-acre lot, the equivalent of
21,780 square feet. Given the choice, many would opt for more land
over a sense of community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prices for a 3,000- to 3,500-square-foot home in Terra Maria,
including the lot, originally ranged from $300,000 to $450,000. But
the four builders in the first phase sold a total of just 16 houses
in the first year and prices were later reduced. For the second and
last phase, however, Ryland Homes, Baltimore's second biggest
residential builder, decided to reduce the price range to $250,000
to $300,000 for homes on its 40 lots and sales were considerably
brisker, said Earl Robinson, sales and marketing manager. ``We
loved the concept and would definitely do something like this
again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Besides the issue of price, the concept of the higher density of
a neo-traditional community was initially a stumbling block. Many
potential buyers thought it would be overcrowded. ``But once the
development was 50 percent built,'' said DeMauro of Synergy,
``people could see what we were doing and were sold on the idea.
Sales have been very good since then.'' He said, however, that
sales in a normal subdivision would have been faster.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ben Sander, who became one of the first homeowners in 1997, was
immediately attracted to Terra Maria because it reminded him of the
charm and character of a historic community in which he had lived
in Northville, Mich. ``A normal subdivision is very sterile
compared to this,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One problem, said DeMauro, was that some builders did not have
the right product for this different type of development and also
were not used to the strict architectural guidelines they had to
follow, such as using certain types of brick and wood instead of
vinyl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gary Clarke of the GYC Group in Westminster, Md., who built five
homes in Terra Maria, had to create a design different from what he
normally used. ``The houses had to be narrower and deeper to fit on
the lots,'' said Clarke.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Rutter, director of planning and zoning for Howard
County, said that his flexible policy on such things as setbacks,
lot coverage and density promoted projects like Terra Maria.
</P>
<P>
   A much larger neo-traditional community of 500 acres called
Maple Lawn Farms, which was designed by Avin and will be developed
by Greenebaum &AMP; Rose, based in Baltimore, is currently under review
in Howard County, and Rutter is confident it will go forward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The younger Lancelotta believes that neo-traditional
developments will become more common in the future, but it will
happen slowly. ``People say, `I have to have my land,' but land is
becoming precious and we have to forgo large lots,'' he explained.
``Aesthetically and socially, neo-traditional is a better plan.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
