<HEADER>
A6176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SKATE-PROCHAMPIONSHIP     12-11 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-PROCHAMPIONSHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILIAR ROUTINE FOR LIPINSKI THE PRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At age 15, soon after she won the Olympic gold
medal in figure skating, Tara Lipinski turned professional. Now at
17, she had a clear path to the Metabolife world professional
championship, but she sent mixed signals over how important this
title was.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day invitational competition at the MCI Center began
Friday night with technical programs, and Lipinski took a solid
lead over Denise Biellmann of Switzerland, 98.6 points to 97.7. The
scores for the technical programs, added to Saturday night's scores
for the artistic programs, determined the winner.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, Lipinski approached this competition most
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new event for me,'' she said, ``a new atmosphere. At
other pro events, it's more of a show. Here, it's a little more
intense. For me, that's the best way I skate _ under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, her technical program was hardly testing for
a skater who, as an amateur, reeled off jump after jump in every
program. She did land three triple jumps: a toe loop, a lutz (with
a shaky landing) and a loop, but there was no combination jump
involving a triple, making her program easier.
</P>
<P>
   Two competitors did successful combinations _ Biellmann a triple
salchow-double toe loop, and Surya Bonaly of France a triple
toe-triple toe. Lipinski said she did no combination because her
choreography did not leave room for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Her technical and artistic programs were the ones she performed
in Stars on Ice, the touring show that pays her a seven-figure
salary for four months. So while titles are nice, tour income is
nicer. And while the $50,000 first prize here will pay many bills,
the tour money will pay more.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much or how little Lipinski did with her technical
program, it was difficult to argue with success. Of her 14 scores,
eight were for 9.9 and the other six for 9.8. She did not need a
tougher program.
</P>
<P>
   Biellmann, like Lipinski, landed three triples in the technical
program. Unlike Lipinski, she found a way to ad lib. When she did a
single axel instead of an intended double, she quickly interrupted
her choreography, threw in a double axel and resumed without
missing a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe maturity helped. Biellmann, who turned 37 today, is the
oldest skater here. She won the world amateur championship in 1981,
15 months before Lipinski was born.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the men's competition became a battle between the
Russians who took the last two Olympic titles. Aleksei Urmanov won
the technical program with 98.4 points to 98.0 for Ilia Kulik.
</P>
<P>
   Urmanov, 26, completed four clean triples, including a
combination of a triple salchow and a double toe loop. Kulik, 22,
had three good triples plus one that was not so good, needing an
extra step to land a toe loop. It was the first competition in more
than a year for Kulik.
</P>
<P>
   Urmanov was not celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it looks perfect,'' he said, ``there's something that
may be off. The program was pretty good, but it was hard because
everybody knows this is world professional competition. I don't
know who is more nervous, me or my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   There was disappointment for 36-year-old Brian Boitano, who had
won six world pro championships. He placed third in the technical
program with 97.4 points, but seconds after he started he lost his
chance to be more competitive when he could not complete a triple
loop and did a double instead.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else went well for him, but because a back condition
prevented him from doing a triple or a double axel or both, as all
his rivals did, he could not afford any slip. As his longtime
coach, Linda Leaver, said: ``What he does between jumps is more
difficult than what they're doing. They do crossovers and he does
intricate footwork. If they miss a triple axel, his program has
more technical difficulty than theirs. But he can't make any
mistakes on jumps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
