<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BEEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BAD BEEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Dec. 12:
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Texas has threatened the government's ability
to use modern methods to ensure the safety of the nation's food
supply. The threat is contained in a preliminary injunction issued
on Friday that prevents the Agriculture Department from regulating
salmonella _ bacteria that can be detected only by the department's
new scientific methods, as opposed to the old ``poke and sniff''
tests.
</P>
<P>
   The department had shut down the Supreme Beef Processors' plant
in Dallas, which until recently supplied a large percentage of the
ground beef used in the country's school lunch program. The plant
had failed not just one but three tests for salmonella
contamination over a period of 12 months. But that did not stop the
company from bringing a lawsuit asserting that the government lacks
the authority to enforce its new regulations, which call for
sophisticated microbial testing to determine whether a plant meets
certain health standards.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Judge A. Joe Fish extended an earlier injunction
allowing the plant to remain open. His decision showed more concern
for the immediate economic harm to the company than for the
potentially greater harm to the public posed by contaminated meat.
The department should be able to win a reversal. The language of
the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act clearly gives it broad
authority to require sanitary conditions and safe products.
</P>
</TEXT>
