<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A HOT WEEK ON THE HUSTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out there on the presidential campaign trail, it was one of
those weeks when everything was churning, both in regard to big
ideas and the poll numbers. The biggest idea and the smartest
tactical move came in the proposed joint pledge by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., and Bill Bradley, the former Democratic senator,
to forgo unregulated soft-money expenditures, should they face one
another in the general election. Their plan would bring a voluntary
end to a bipartisan abuse that Congress has refused to outlaw _ the
use of corporate and union donations by the Republican and
Democratic National Committees in circumvention of the limits on
candidate spending.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, the deal shores up his image as an insurgent
reformer who is not afraid to think outside the Republican boxes.
Moreover, it came as McCain was having his best week of the
campaign while the GOP establishment's presumptive nominee, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, was having his worst. Various New
Hampshire polls put McCain up by 3 to 15 points, while the Texan
was hit with a blizzard of questions about his intelligence from
the press and Republican political professionals. The
disenchantment process, during which front-runners get asked rude
questions, is as much a part of the run-up to Iowa and New
Hampshire as the discovery process that produced winners like Jimmy
Carter and flashes in the pan like Gary Hart, Pat Buchanan and Paul
Tsongas.
</P>
<P>
   These processes alone do not determine eventual outcomes, but
they do expose weak spots in candidacies. For Bush, the immediate
problem was the embarrassment of having to assure interviewers that
``I've been underestimated'' as a thinker. The more lingering
problem may be the performance gap that opened up between him and
the other Republican candidates in two recent debates. A comparison
with Ronald Reagan is useful here. When Reagan was asked certain
questions, one could almost see the cassette drop into place. But
the answers unspooled smoothly and with rich, if rehearsed, detail,
whereas Bush's programming shows in his stiff delivery and in the
sound-bite brevity of his responses.
</P>
<P>
   The other partner in the campaign-reform deal, Bill Bradley,
faces a different tactical situation on the Democratic side. He has
erased Vice President Al Gore's advantage as the guaranteed
nominee, but the effective Gore counterattack on the cost of
Bradley's health care proposal is based on a proven approach for
derailing Democratic insurgents. In 1984, Walter Mondale stopped
Gary Hart's red-hot challenge when Mondale cast himself as the
guardian of the party's social-welfare tradition. Bill Clinton used
a similar tactic aimed at Social Security pensioners to defeat Paul
Tsongas in the critical Florida primary in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to dismiss both the substantive and tactical
moves of the early campaign as politics as usual. But there is a
serious civics lesson in these events. On the GOP side, the debates
are filling their function as a place where candidates reveal, and
sometimes repair, themselves. The two Democrats' parrying over
health care may be cynical, but it also helps define policies for
the future. As for campaign finance, McCain and Bradley have set a
standard on the rejection of soft money that deserves to be
emulated by every candidate in both parties. Their decision to
dramatize campaign reform as a centerpiece issue could create the
best chance in years to chop down the dominant role of
special-interest money in presidential elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
