<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FIREFIGHTERS-HEROES-A     12-11 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREFIGHTERS-HEROES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS REFLECT ON A JOB OF GREAT RISKS AND REWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKFORD, Ill. _ When firefighters talk about the toughest
moments of their lives, it is not always the leaping flames or the
smoke-filled stairways that haunt them.
</P>
<P>
   For Tom Baylor, it was the face of a dying baby girl. Inside a
fire truck racing to a hospital, Baylor had tried to breathe life
into her lungs. When nothing more could be done, he went into a
bathroom at the hospital, buried his face in his hands and broke
down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firefighters are supposed to be tough, just dummy up,''
Baylor, 42, said. ``But you don't forget. You have dreams about it.
Once after a baby died, another firefighter looked over at me and
said, `Man, this really hurts.' And we just sat there with tears in
our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional tribute on Thursday in Worcester, Mass., for the
six firefighters who died in a warehouse blaze showed the depth of
respect and reverence that Americans maintain for the people who
answer their calls for help. It was a response that even tragedy
seldom evokes.
</P>
<P>
   In an age that seems rich in everything but sacrifice, the
firefighter stands, in the ways that count most, as perhaps
America's most heroic figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little kids look at you and trust you,'' said Capt. Mark
Asprooth, 42, of Fire Station No. 5 in Rockford, an industrial city
of 160,000 about 70 miles west of Chicago. ``In a way, that's part
of the reason some of us go into this line of work.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that police officers sometimes grumble, with a
mixture of humor and envy, about how warmly people treat
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police officers have to do things that make them unpopular,''
said Chris Kowalski, 27, a firefighter. ``With us, people call and
say, `Come and help me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Few civilian jobs, for that matter, get the respect accorded to
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Stassi, 45, a former plumber who became a firefighter, noted
that injuries are far more common on construction sites than on
fire and rescue scenes.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say firefighters do not encounter danger. Not
long ago, Baylor, for example, found himself in a burning house
that became so hot the picture window was blown out.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us in this station,'' Baylor said, ``have been on calls
where somebody's been carried out of a burning building on a
firefighter's back.''
</P>
<P>
   Adrenaline surges with every alarm, he said. It is impossible to
know if the call is routine or mortally dangerous. After some
calls, the Rockford Fire Department has brought in counselors and
chaplains to talk with firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Asprooth said he believed that firefighters tend to be
compassionate and spirited, people who revere life so much because
they know it cannot be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see death a lot, you greatly appreciate life,'' he
said. ``We know what it is to see sorrow and pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Working 24-hour shifts, the firefighters in Rockford spend a day
and night at the fire station and then get the next 48 hours off.
The night work can mean missing the ballgames or piano recitals of
their children. And holidays usually mean work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this line of business, you don't stop work for Christmas,''
Stassi said.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighter Lindsay Pooley, 39, told of an accident victim he
had helped, an elderly woman who hugged him and told him, ``I
needed somebody to help get me through this.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was the man who stood outside his house, most of it
burned, and still thanked the firefighter, Kowalski, for saving
what could be saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a house, it's somebody's life,'' Kowalski said.
``And if you can just save a family photo album, you've saved a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Kowalski said that firefighters do not like to be singled out
for credit. When people go into burning buildings together, he
said, they must trust one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not me or you or him, but a team,'' Kowalski said. ``If
anything ever happened to me, my crewmates would be there to help
me and get me out of there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if I didn't make it out, I know they'd be there to take
care of my family. This is quite a brotherhood.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Worcestor, firefighters on Saturday discovered the remains of
the fourth and fifth firefighters in the rubble of last week's
fire, The Associated Press reported. They were continuing to search
around the clock for the remaining victim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
