<HEADER>
A6181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-Y2K-PREPARED-REAL-NYT     12-11 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-PREPARED-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: PREPARING A BUILDING FOR Y2K 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Managing agents must walk a fine line in determining
what steps to take to address concerns presented by Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Those who fail to take proper precautions could have some
serious explaining to do if their client buildings end up with any
bites from the millennium bug. Those who overprepare _ and, in the
process, overspend clients' money _ could also have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some last-minute tips for property managers and
boards who want to be as prepared as possible for Y2K without being
too prepared for their own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not stocking up on food, but we are buying extra garbage
bags,'' said Robert Grant, director of Diversified Property
Management, based in Brooklyn. ``Nobody's going to complain if you
have an extra month's worth of garbage bags, but I wouldn't want to
be the one to tell a client that because one of our suppliers'
delivery systems fouled up, we don't have any bags to put the
garbage in.''
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, he said, his company is making sure that
any building that uses oil heat will have its fuel-storage tanks
topped off at the end of the year. ``That's a no-brainer,'' he
said. ``But it's a critical issue that shouldn't be overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant said he also intended to stock up on other basics like
light bulbs, cleaning supplies, flashlights and batteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things that are going to be outside a
board's or a management company's control,'' Grant said, referring
to problems that could result in the event of power failures or
problems with the city's water supply. ``But a prudent manager will
do his best to address all the things he can think of that are
within his control.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Kornfeld, executive vice president of Heron Ltd., a
Manhattan management company, said that notwithstanding assurances
from the various elevator contractors who service elevators in
client buildings, Heron isn't taking any chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the off chance there's something the elevator company
missed, we're bringing all our elevators down to the lobby at 11:45
p.m. and keeping them there for the next half-hour,'' Kornfeld
said. ``The last thing we want is to have a resident stuck inside
an elevator at midnight.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter G. Goodman, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that he had
advised client buildings to conduct an ``11th-hour checklist'' of
their Y2K readiness. For example, Goodman said, any equipment that
is either controlled by a computer or contains an embedded computer
chip should be checked to make sure that it will function after
midnight Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Such equipment could include building and parking access gates
and doors, fire alarms and smoke detectors, building lighting,
including emergency lighting, telecommunications equipment,
heating, ventilating and air-conditioning systems and, of course,
elevators.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you haven't addressed these things by now, it may be tough
to do so now,'' Goodman said. He added, however, that most
manufacturers of such equipment had information on their Web sites
regarding Y2K compliance or the lack thereof. Those that don't have
a Web site, he said, will certainly have telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are uncertain about a piece of critical equipment, you
can always call the manufacturer directly,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, management should make sure that all fire
extinguishers have been recharged and that there are adequate
battery-powered lighting sources for hallways and common areas. It
is also imperative for management to make a backup copy of any
computer-stored data, such as rent records, accounts payable and
accounts receivable for each of their buildings, and to contact
each building's accountant to make sure that backup disks or hard
copies of tax and financial records have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Goodman said, buildings with backup generators should
make sure that they are operational and that there is sufficient
fuel on hand to run them.
</P>
<P>
   That latter point, however, could itself present a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine to have a backup generator, but the real question
is: How much fuel do you have on hand to run it?'' said Karen
Anderson, author of the book ``Y2K for Women, How to Protect Your
Home and Family in the Coming Crisis'' (Thomas Nelson, Nashville,
1999).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson, who lives in Nashville, recently visited a
relative who lives in Midtown Manhattan. She said she had been
struck by how valuable storage space was in the city. Because of
this, she said, buildings that have backup generators should think
long and hard about where and how they will be able to store as
much fuel as is safely possible for the generator they hope to
never have to use. Ms. Anderson said she was also struck by how
vulnerable people who live in densely populated cities can be to
problems associated with failures in the water system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in a single-family house, and the water gets shut
off, you can improvise when it comes to dealing with waste-water,''
Ms. Anderson said. ``But what do you do when you're in a high-rise
building and you can't flush the toilet? Your only alternative,
really, is to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   While officials say that it is unlikely that New York City will
have a problem with its water system there is always the
possibility that glitches in sophisticated booster pumps in some
high-rise buildings could interrupt the building's water supply. In
anticipation of such an eventuality, there is a fairly simple step
that might be taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pack a bag so you can be ready to leave your apartment,'' Ms.
Anderson said. ``And once you have a bag packed it also makes sense
to have an alternative place to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
