<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: TAKE A LOOK AT WHAT EWING STILL HAS LEFT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He could not find his rhythm on offense, and he was
often fooled by the simplest of fakes on defense. But he was back
at Madison Square Garden, glowering before the ball was tipped,
taking those purposeful strides toward midcourt at 37 years old.
Somewhere in Boston, another NBA icon, Charles Barkley, was saying
goodbye to the game. In New York, Patrick Ewing was saying hello
again.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your perspective, his timing on Friday night was
either off _ or perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little rusty with my moves, but I thought I was trying
to do other things,'' Ewing said after the Knicks had held off
Philadelphia. He had played for the first time in six months after
tearing his Achilles' tendon in a playoff game. He missed all eight
shots he took in 30 minutes. But he grabbed 10 rebounds, made seven
of eight free throws and contributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can walk on a treadmill, ride the bike, but nothing takes
the place of running up and down the court _ banging, bumping,
shooting, just playing ball,'' he said afterward. ``I'm just going
to take one day at a time. It's my first day, my first game. I'm
just trying to fit in and help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   He is stubborn and proud, and rarely says what people want him
to say. But until he is gone, the Knicks need him almost as much as
the league still needs him. Only one NBA team has advanced past the
first round of the playoffs every time in the last eight years, and
there has been one constant on that team: Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the precincts in Cleveland and Dallas are
reporting, empty seats can be seen all over this season. There are
not enough entertainers in the game anymore. Four of the players
considered must-see TV _ Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant, Chris
Webber and Jason Williams _ are on two Western Conference teams.
After that lot, there are Vince Carter, Kevin Garnett, the Spurs,
the Blazers and a healthy Allen Iverson. There is but one
time-tested rivalry going, the Knicks versus the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Square Garden sold out for the 306th straight Knicks
game Friday night. That streak began long after Bernard King
stopped shooting. It did not begin because Pat Riley looked good in
Italian wool or because the brawn of Anthony Mason and Charles
Oakley was good theater. It began because a team anchored by Ewing
began winning and winning. Since 1985, he is the largest reason
people began caring about the Knicks again.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was roundly criticized this past week for his inability to
communicate his status to his teammates and coaches, for his
failure to speak to the news media while he was injured. He was
fined twice for that infraction, the first player in the history of
the game fined for such a transgression while on the injury list.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, we can't separate Patrick the person from Patrick the
player. They are completely different. The person is often an aloof
loner, who goes about his own ways. His best friends on the team,
Herb Williams and John Starks, are gone. His warrior mentality does
not mesh with the carefree demeanor of his younger, more athletic
teammates. Will this dynamic ruin the Knicks' chemistry?
</P>
<P>
   They play basketball for a living. They have to get along on the
court, not in a group home.
</P>
<P>
   Is Ewing uncomfortable trying to find his place among the
nouveau Knicks? Is he genuinely worried if he can ever be the
player he was, one of the top 50 ever and perhaps the most
proficient jump-shooting center in the history of the game?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of denigrating him for what he is not, maybe Ewing
should be appreciated for what he is, what he still has left. The
people responsible for the NBA's renaissance the past two decades _
Magic, Larry, Michael, Charles, David Robinson, Karl Malone, John
Stockton, Scottie Pippen and, yes, Ewing _ are dropping out, one by
one, leaving the game to others.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling scene came on Thursday afternoon in a
Philadelphia doctor's office. At the same time Iverson was leaving,
having had a cast cut off his broken thumb, Barkley was going in,
to check the status of a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his
left knee, a tear that ended his career.
</P>
<P>
   The sage took the youngster aside, hugged him and said it was
his turn now to make what he and the others will of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got so many guys who are not going to fill Michael
Jordan's shoes and Charles Barkley and those guys,'' Iverson said
Friday night at the Garden. ``A lot of us collectively could stick
our foot in that shoe. It probably still won't fit. But if we get a
group effort, it would be all right for this league to go on and be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   There are still a few holdovers left. One of them jumped center
for the Knicks on Friday night. He is not going to be around much
longer. His breed is fading into the landscape, making way for
quickness and youth. Here's hoping he finds his rhythm and gets his
championship ring before he's gone. Here's hoping people can admire
Patrick Ewing, the player, and stop judging him by Patrick Ewing,
the person.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1739EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
