<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONN-BROKERS-FEE-REAL     12-11 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-BROKERS-FEE-REAL-1090(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: CITING PAPERWORK, TWO BROKERAGE CONCERNS ADD FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELEANOR CHARLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It will cost a bit more to buy or sell a house or condominium in
Connecticut if your broker is Prudential Connecticut Realty or
William Raveis Real Estate, two of the largest firms in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively modest amounts _ $150 and $195, respectively _
were imposed by Prudential in September and by Raveis last month
independently of each other. The charges, established by the
companies after what they described as many months of research,
were added, the brokerage concerns said, to defray the cost of
processing numerous government-required documents for all sales
transactions. So far, no other brokerage has followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   The charges are called ``regulatory compliance'' or
``paperwork'' fees. They are billed to the buyer, the seller, or
both, depending on whether the company represents the buyer, the
seller or both. The fee goes to the firm, not to the sales agent;
it is non-negotiable and totally separate from the brokerage
commission on the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the required documentation that a real estate company
must collect, Peter Helie, owner of Prudential Connecticut Realty,
reeled off ``dual agency forms'' (relating to representation of
buyer and seller), ``lead-paint forms, well-water testing, property
disclosure forms, termite and destroying-insect testing, credit
reporting, radon testing, formaldehyde disclosure, a new law
requiring all contractors to register every job and supply 15
references or the past two years' worth of references to the state
_ and a few more that I can't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some records need to be stored for a minimum of three years,
some forever,'' he said, ``because if there's a consumer complaint
years down the road, you have to back up your position.''
</P>
<P>
   Helie contends that the explosion of legal, administrative and
storage costs and training expenses for the sales staff and
managers for instruction on compliance must be reckoned with. ``We
do 12,000 sales transactions a year,'' he said. At $150 per
transaction the new fees add up to $720,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   His concerns focus not only on the increase in state and federal
regulations requiring documentation, but on compliance with the
laws as well, he said. ``Noncompliance can result in state fines
starting at $2,000 and federal fine minimums of $10,000, plus
suspension of our license,'' Helie said. ``If we don't hand out the
federal lead-paint pamphlet and there's a problem, we have a
$10,000 fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Additional pressure, he said, is exerted by the public's growing
fascination with online real estate. ``It's cutting into our
business,'' Helie said. ``We will do what we have to, recertifying
the staff to communicate and do business online and draw contracts
online.'' He expects to see new laws governing the legality of an
online signature until the original can be obtained.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Real Estate Commission, a state agency, met on
Dec. 3 to begin considering recommendations for legislation on the
charges. But legally, Raveis and Prudential appear to be on safe
ground. ``There are currently no statutes in place in Connecticut
which would prohibit the charging of such a fee,'' said Rosamond
Koether, corporate attorney for the Raveis company.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Ficeto, managing attorney for the Department of Consumer
Protection, said the legislature probably would not be able to
eliminate the fees, but could require them to be negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the issue of a company's legal right to charge the
fee, said Ms. Ficeto, whose agency is the administrative arm of the
state's Real Estate Commission, is the term itself _ regulatory
compliance fee. ``It suggests that this is a state or federally
mandated fee,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Breunich, managing partner of William Pitt Real Estate in
Stamford, Conn., reacted angrily to the issue. ``We don't charge
fees that don't have value associated with them,'' he said. ``We
feel it's insulting to the customer and to our agents who would
have to ask for them. Yesterday there was no fee. Today you are
charging $150 or more to handle documents for asbestos and
lead-paint removal. What happened overnight?''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he was ``passionate about it because I feel it's
not good for the industry to have its leaders act this way.'' He
added that the charges were ``so opposed to the trust we've
established with the consumer over 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   An outside consultant advised Century 21 to consider charging
the fees, but Bud Farris, owner of Century 21 A&AMP;B Realty in
Stamford, said: ``Why? I've been storing paperwork for years. I
might as well charge the students in my real estate class for
collecting and storing their exam papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Schappert, owner of Buyers' Trust Real Estate in
Brookfield, is reminded of the $1,000 retainers that some buyer
brokers (those who represent only the buyer) charged when such
agencies first came into being. ``If you bought a house it was
applied to the commission,'' he said. ``If you didn't, you lost the
$1,000. It was not popular and it lasted barely a year. I wouldn't
think of charging compliance fees either.''
</P>
<P>
   In letters to various newspapers, John Lamb, an independent
Norwalk broker, wrote: ``Charging $195 for copying three pages of
required disclosures and handing out a 10-cent pamphlet on lead
paint is price gouging at its worst!''
</P>
<P>
   With the issue mired in controversy, Ms. Ficeto said, ``I've
been telling real estate people and the public who have been
calling us about this that the fee does not have to be paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers have the option to go elsewhere, but agents who
complete a transaction without collecting the fee will have it
deducted from their commissions, according to a Compliance Fee
Instruction Package sent by Raveis to all of its agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``An expensive home may make it worthwhile for the agent to pay
the fee,'' said Ms. Ficeto. But, she added, she believes that most
agents, rather than annoy a client in a normal sale, would be
inclined to pay the fee themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Blumenthal, the state's attorney general, is reviewing
the legality of the fees under current statutes. ``The fact that
only a couple of companies have begun charging them belies any
claim that they are needed,'' he said. ``If fees can be attributed
to a specific cost or service there might be some justification for
them. But the explanations I've seen, that they somehow relate to
asbestos or underground oil storage tanks, is extraordinarily lame.
They are simply fees that the companies are tacking onto their
commissions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Reactions to the fees from individual agents and managers in the
various Prudential offices around the state have been guarded.
Terry Mercede, manager of Prudential's Danbury office, said: ``I
haven't had a problem up to now. Nobody has objected or walked out.
I'm not trying to avoid the issue, but I'm reluctant to talk about
it. This is where we are now, we don't know what the future will
bring.'' Attempts to get the names of customers to discover their
reactions were rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   At a Prudential office in Stamford, Elayne Jassey, a longtime
sales associate, said: ``Customers ask questions, but nobody has
walked out or objected. We're all feeling our way _ it's so new.''
</P>
<P>
   No Raveis agents or managers responded to requests for
information, but the company's instructional package includes
details similar to those described by Helie, and it states that the
compliance fee ``is disclosed on the listing agreement and the
buyer-broker contract.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once an offer becomes a contract and the closing attorney(s)
are selected,'' it says, ``they will be sent a bill for payment of
the fee.'' In certain cases where government-subsidized loans for
buyers, bank-owned homes and foreclosures are involved, Raveis will
absorb the fee.
</P>
<P>
   The instructional package compares the fee to those charged by
lawyers for long distance calls, travel, copying and postage, and
to mortgage and title company courier fees and document preparation
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate compliance fees are not without precedent. In parts
of Florida, California and Pennsylvania, among other areas of the
country, Helie said, similar fees are charged, ranging from $110 to
$295. ``Corporate executives I've talked to at brainstorming
sessions in Stamford are surprised we didn't do this sooner,'' he
said. ``They've been doing it for years.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that other real estate companies would go along
with Prudential and Raveis because of the value to the consumer in
retaining crucial documentation on properties for future use by
home buyers and sellers, brokers, and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Another new type of charge is being imposed by one agency to its
rental clients. Weichert Realty, with offices in Greenwich,
Stamford and Norwalk, appears to be the only company now charging a
$25 non-negotiable, nonreturnable ``registration fee'' for showing
houses and apartments to rental clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are watching our competitors with interest,'' said Peggy
Doepper, Connecticut manager for Coldwell Banker Residential Real
Estate, ``taking a wait-and-see attitude in evaluating the whole
situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
