<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-BARKLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARKLEY REMAINS A GOOD INFLUENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (With BKN-NOTEBOOK) 
(rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Barkley has railed against young players the past few
years, as if he were Jack Lemmon or Walter Matthau and the rest of
the NB A was composed of uppity youngsters about to knock over his
mailbox with a bat. But there he was last Thursday, the day after
his career ended, walking into a Philadelphia physician's office at
the same time Allen Iverson was walking out.
</P>
<P>
   The broken-down vet with a career-ending knee injury. The young
buck having a cast removed from his thumb, almost all better again.
You could not stage this sort of symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing I got out of seeing Charles that way,'' Iverson
began, ``was that I always said once I started playing basketball
that I would play every game like it was my last, because I owed
that to myself and I owed it to God just for giving me the talent.
And to see Charles like that, it put my whole career in
perspective. Because it can be last your last game; any night can
be your last game.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who had often taken Iverson to task for not treating
the game more like a privilege than a birthright, did not lecture
Iverson the day after his knee injury ended his career. He merely
told Iverson that it was indeed his league now, to not let the news
media bother him, to play hard and to cherish the game as much as
he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that went on with me and Charles, I feel even worse
now because of how he left the game _ and it being in the city that
I'm playing for and the city that loves him more than anybody,''
Iverson said Friday night at Madison Square Garden, where his 76ers
played the Knicks. ``It's tough to watch that, but it was important
for me to show him my love and my respect. I cared about him as a
person and I wish him well, and I meant that. And every word that
he said to me are words that I'll cherish for the rest of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows where Iverson goes from here, whether he is saying
what everyone wants him to say or genuinely feels different about
his career since his encounter with Barkley. And who knows if we'll
ever see Barkley on the floor again. Like Magic Johnson before him,
he needs an audience. He's 99 percent retired, but you never know.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, he was one of the best entertainers the game has
ever seen. And after all his transgressions and ill-timed remarks,
what Barkley's career was truly about had nothing to do with him
not winning a title.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between his rookie night with the 76ers at the
Spectrum and last Wednesday night with the Houston Rockets in
Philadelphia, Charles Barkley transformed himself from a young,
unthinking knucklehead into a folk hero who understood how lucky he
was to have had a chance to play in the NBA. Neither Iverson nor
anyone else will ever have his charisma, but they can find his
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether I play good or bad, I'm just fortunate and happy
enough to be out on the court regardless,'' Iverson said. ``Whether
I get this award or that award, it doesn't mean anything to me.
Just the fact that I'm in the NBA is enough for me. I'll play every
game like it's my last and cherish every game. Because just like it
happened to Charles 16 years later, it could happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
