<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YO, ADRIAN  
 GLARE IS ON AN OWNER
</HEADLINE>
   (With BKN-NOTEBOOK-BARKLEY) 
(rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Herald has used the headline ``Yo, Adrian'' while
trumpeting the quick start of Celtics rookie Adrian Griffin. Given
the Rockyesque nature of his story, including that he was actually
playing in Europe a year ago, the headline is as appropriate as it
is cornball.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has a 25-year-old won the NBA rookie of the year
award, but perhaps the one player who may give the Clippers' Lamar
Odom a decent run this season is Griffin, who makes his Madison
Square Garden debut Sunday against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too old,'' his teammate Paul Pierce joked.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, a 6-foot-5-inch swingman, has started all 17 Celtics
games. He is shooting 53 percent from the field and averaging 33.1
minutes, 10.1 points, 7.4 rebounds, 3.7 assists and 2.1 steals.
Modest numbers for a top rookie. Unreal numbers for a training-camp
invitee who was hardly expected to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   Undrafted out of Seton Hall, Griffin spent three seasons with
the Connecticut Pride of the Continental Basketball Association. At
one time or another since college, he had been passed over by
Miami, Golden State, Philadelphia, Milwaukee and Dallas. At 25, he
was beginning to think the NBA would never beckon again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at all those guys who made it from the CBA, guys like
Chris Childs and especially Mario Elie,'' Griffin said via cell
phone from Boston on Friday before scoring nine points in the
Celtics' 100-96 victory over Houston. ``Whenever things weren't
going well, I always tried to look at it like, `Those guys made
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the statistics, coach Rick Pitino noticed the intangibles
about Griffin: the way the ball moves when he is on the floor, the
way he uses his body on defensive assignments and the way the
Celtics have become better with him on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very few people in this league in this day that really
know how to play the game,'' Larry Bird said recently. ``That kid's
got the talent to just go out there and play because he knows what
he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   If he has taken his game to another level, Griffin's salary and
comforts took flight, too. He went from Motel 6 and $1,300 a month
in the CBA to the Four Seasons and $385,000 a year in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite different,'' Griffin said. ``The pay is definitely
much better. Really, it's unbelievable how much money we make. You
could live off that and your family could live off that for
generations. It's just a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the league's genuine feel-good tales this season,
Griffin has gone from the status of anonymous rookie to near
celebrity in Boston. He knows his NBA existence could change
quickly, but he has not forgotten to enjoy the start of what may be
a long career in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, it was kind of weird,'' he said. ``I'd see
guys on television, like Kenny Anderson and Antoine Walker. To
actually be playing with them and against other NBA players, I
still haven't gotten over that I'm actually here. I've settled in a
little bit. But it's still a great feeling, especially where I came
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Glare Is on an Owner &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From corporate offices in Charlotte to the Olympic Tower in
Manhattan, people were watching television at work on Friday
afternoon. The programming did not come from nba.com but from Court
TV, where George Shinn, the principal owner of the Hornets, was
being tried on charges of sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   With each sexually explicit piece of testimony on the stand, one
wondered how much more embarrassment the Hornets franchise and the
league could take.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond making money, one of the precepts of the collective
bargaining agreement is the league's and the players' need to put
out a wholesome product. During the labor negotiations, players
were asked to agree to various measures in the name of promoting
the league and enhancing their image.
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, a more comprehensive drug agreement was put
into place and a provision against a player's attacking his coach
was agreed to by both sides. That rule, an outgrowth of Latrell
Sprewell's choking P.J. Carlesimo two years ago, states that a
player will have his contract terminated if he attacks his coach.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what happens when an owner is accused of sexually assaulting
several women? When does Shinn's appearance on Court TV in
midafternoon become detrimental enough to the league's image that
the NBA decides to take action? Commissioner David Stern may
actually be subpoenaed to testify at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Stern must do something. The language from the
NBA constitution that the league has repeatedly cited in regard to
the the recent sexual allegations surrounding the Knicks in 1997 in
Charleston, S.C., refers to behavior that is ``materially
detrimental or materially prejudicial to the team or league.''
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't that passage apply to everyone affiliated with the
NBA?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
