survey by government researchers in China, more than 100 unlicensed
schools, most of them much smaller than Xingzhi and some run by
people with no more than a junior high school education, have
sprung up in Beijing. (Erik Eckholm/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) XINGZHI, China -- Dec. 11, 1999 -- CHINA-MIGRANTS-2 -- An
old paint factory has become the home of Xingzhi primary school, an
unlicensed school for rural migrants in western Beijing. The cost
of attending is about $86 per year, hundreds of dollars less than
migrants must pay at the public schools. The educational plight of
the migrant children in China is so acute that some official
newspapers have carried exposes, and students and faculty members
from teacher colleges have given volunteer help. (Erik Eckholm/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) XINGZHI, China -- Dec. 11, 1999 -- CHINA-MIGRANTS-1 --
The exercise yard at the Xingzhi primary school for rural migrants
in western Beijing. The cost of attending the school is about $86
per year, hundreds of dollars less than migrants must pay at the
public schools. But the school is unlicensed and illegal, and its
booming growth attests to one of China's most enduring social
tensions: the degrading treatment of the tens of millions of rural
Chinese who seek better lives in the cities but are consigned by
law and habit to second-class citizenship. (Erik Eckholm/The New
York Times)
</P>
