<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH GETS IOC TO APPROVE REFORM PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Members of the International Olympic
Committee compliantly fell into line Saturday with the insistence
of Juan Antonio Samaranch that they begin instituting legitimate,
if incremental, reform in an attempt to restore credibility to the
badly damaged Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   The 93 voting delegates unanimously voted to end their unlimited
memberships and to restrict future presidents to a maximum of 12
years in office, as well as to select 15 active athletes to the
IOC. The session will continue Sunday with a vote on the
contentious issue of whether to allow delegates to visit cities
bidding on the Winter and Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old Samaranch has called for an end to the visits,
but the IOC is said to be split on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's reforms will not immediately change the makeup of
the IOC in any substantive manner, nor will they represent an
overhaul in the way it operates. Rather, they represent another
step in a continuing attempt to convince the public, corporate
sponsors and lawmakers that the IOC has begun to transform itself
into a more open, accountable and less corrupt organization a year
after the Salt Lake City bidding scandal was disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the IOC has been transformed from being a small,
personal organization through its history into something as
transparent as we could make it and responsive to the tasks now
before it,'' said former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger,
who was the most visible outside member of an 82-person reform
commission that has been working since June.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant reforms enacted Saturday reduced the age
limit for new IOC members from 80 to 70 and subjected all delegates
to re-election every eight years. Previously, they did not have to
face re-election. Current members can still serve until age 80.
Supporters of the age and term limits said the changes will allow
for more frequent turnover in delegates. Of the 102 current
delegates, 66 are 60 or older.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must obligate the IOC to renew itself more quickly than in
the past,'' said Franco Carraro, a delegate from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said that renewable terms are not term limits at
all, and that the IOC will continue to perpetuate itself in an
essentially closed operation. In any case, the IOC will undergo an
extended transition period.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will increase to as many as 130 members until 2003
with an eventual limit of 115 _ 70 selected at large, 15 athletes,
15 presidents of international sports federations and 15 presidents
of national Olympic committees. Complete turnover of the current
IOC membership may not occur until 2047, when the youngest
delegate, 32-year-old Prince William of Orange turns 80.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates also voted unanimously Saturday to restrict future
IOC presidents to an eight-year term, plus a second term of four
years. This is intended to prevent leaders in the future from
gaining the same autocratic hold on office that Samaranch has held
since being elected in 1980. Before the vote on presidential term
limits, a surreal moment occurred when the governing styles of the
Rotary Club and the former Ugandan dictator Idi Amin were invoked.
</P>
<P>
   Philipp von Schoeller of Austria suggested that the IOC follow
the procedures of the Rotary Club in electing ingoing and outgoing
presidents. Maj. Gen. Francis Nyangweso, a former military leader
in Amin's government who noted that he had ``lived in a country
with an unstable presidency,'' cautioned the delegates to limit
future IOC presidents to four-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we will have chance for change,'' Nyangweso said.
``Otherwise, we will have coups around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The ease with which Saturday's measures were passed reflected,
in large part, the shrewdness of Samaranch, who received a vote of
confidence by 86-2 from the delegates last March. He has since
convinced the members that serious reform was necessary, and he
helped solidify the necessary votes by naming 41 IOC members to the
reform commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the members who don't like the medicine take it, because
he's a leader with a proven track record,'' said Kevan Gosper, a
member of the IOC executive board from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   While saying that change was necessary and unavoidable,
Samaranch also persisted Saturday in blaming ``pressure'' from bid
cities for much of the culture of corruption in the IOC. That
culture was fully exposed in the past year with the disclosure that
Salt Lake City officials who successfully bid on the 2002 Winter
Games had given millions of dollars in cash payments, scholarships,
free medical treatments and gifts to the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been facing harsh criticism, very often unfair,''
Samaranch told the IOC delegates. ``You have gone through
undeserved sufferings and pains. I have suffered, too. We all
suffered. Believe me, there was no alternative but to work hard to
solve the crisis. We did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The athletes who are candidates for IOC membership include Bob
Ctvrtlik, a volleyball player from the United States; Hassiba
Boulmerka, a 1,500-meter runner from Algeria; Sergei Bubka, the
pole-vaulter from Ukraine; Johann Olav Koss, the Norwegian
speedskater, and Alexander Popov, the Russian swimmer. All are gold
medalists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
