<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6197 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     12-11 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV13-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMING THE GREAT OUTDOORS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, Dec. 13)  
(lb) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As someone whose main objection to the ``outdoor experience'' is
that it is outdoors, I sympathize with those rugged individuals who
filled out the following comment cards at the Bridger-Teton
National Forest in Wyoming:
</P>
<P>
   _ Trails need to be wider so people can walk while holding
hands.
</P>
<P>
   While holding hands is fine in most circumstances, I'm not sure
it's such a hot idea while navigating a twisting, turning
wilderness trail. For one thing, the person whose hand you are
holding may slip and fall down a steep precipice, dragging you with
her unless you are alert enough to quickly let go. Also, holding
another person's hand can slow you down while running away from a
bloodthirsty bear, land-shark, squirrel or other dangerous woodland
beast.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I agree that nature trails should be made as wide as
possible so I don't scratch the sides of my car.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trails need to be reconstructed. Please avoid building trails
that go uphill.
</P>
<P>
   In mountainous regions, it is unavoidable that some trails go
uphill. Still, this is America, and there's no reason why
escalators can't be installed in these areas or burly rangers made
available to carry tired hikers to their destination.
</P>
<P>
   _ Too many bugs and leeches and spiders and spider webs. Please
spray the wilderness to rid the area of these pests.
</P>
<P>
   Amen to that. It would also be nice if park management built a
coal-fired power-plant nearby to enhance the color of the sunsets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Please pave the trails so they can be plowed of snow during
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Right on. To me, nothing says ``wilderness'' like the sound of a
20-ton, 180-horsepower John Deere crawler-dozer firing up its
diesel engine on a frosty winter morning. Equipped with altitude
compensation, turbocharger and a 207-inch blade, this baby can not
only scrape the snow off any trail you care to name, it can also be
counted on to scare off any annoying wildlife that would otherwise
detract from your outdoor experience.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chairlifts need to be in some places so that we can get to
wonderful views without having to hike to them.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know. Chairlifts tend to give me vertigo. Plus, unless
the chairlift is enclosed and equipped with heating and
air-conditioning, you are still at the mercy of the dreaded
elements, including sun, wind and, worst of all, rain. It is
probably a better bet to just stay in the visitors center and load
up on postcards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Need more signs to keep area pristine.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking along the lines of the flashing-neon variety, the
kind you need sunglasses to look at or risk going blind. Messages
could include: Danger! Uphill trail ahead! or Warning! Spraying for
leeches! Do not breathe air!
</P>
<P>
   _ A McDonalds would be nice at the trailhead.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me about it. What wouldn't taste better before a hard day's
ride on the escalator than a nice, lukewarm Big Mac and a side of
greasy fries? It certainly couldn't be any worse than the vile
``trail mixes'' that serious hikers pretend so hard to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Too many rocks in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   My sentiments exactly. The way I look at it, if rocks are so
cool, then why are the ones at Disney World artificial? My
suggestion is that while they're paving the trails, installing the
escalators and spraying for leeches, they remove all the
unnecessary rocks and replace them with softer, more lifelike,
fiberglass imitations. When the glow of the McDonalds sign reflects
off them at just the right angle, the view is unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
