<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS-GRIFFEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS GIVE UP ON GRIFFEY, SAYING PRICE IS TOO HIGH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ever since the Seattle Mariners began trying
to trade Ken Griffey Jr. last month, the prevailing view in
baseball circles was that they would trade baseball's ranking No. 1
player to the Cincinnati Reds. Jim Bowden, the Reds' general
manager, shot the prevailing view out of the sky Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After five weeks of attempting to negotiate a trade for Ken
Griffey Jr.,'' Bowden said, ``the Reds today have pulled out and no
longer will pursue a trade for Ken Griffey Jr. Neither side has
moved in five weeks. It's a waste of time to continue to have
discussions and meetings when we get absolutely nowhere. We haven't
moved a centimeter, let alone an inch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden made his announcement at an unusual news conference at
the winter meetings at the Anaheim Marriott Hotel. General managers
usually do not call news conferences to announce what they are not
doing.
</P>
<P>
   But the Griffey matter has captivated the attention of everyone
in baseball because it is not every year that a player of his
caliber is traded. Now the question is whether the Mariners will be
able to meet the center fielder's request and find a team for him
closer to his home in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Gillick, the Mariners' general manager, said he would
continue to talk with other teams. ``We have a difference of
opinion in personnel,'' he said of the Reds. ``Jim has the right to
think as he wishes for the Reds, and we have a right to maintain a
position with the Seattle club.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillick declined to say which other teams he was talking with,
but acknowledged he would most likely talk to the New York Mets
during the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Some people keep trying to paint the Mets as serious contenders
for Griffey, but they have not made an offer for him and the
Mariners have not told them what they would want in return.
</P>
<P>
   Gillick's talks with the Reds, Bowden said, broke down over one
player. Bowden declined to identify him, but he was believed to be
Pokey Reese, the Reds' second baseman, whom his manager, Jack
McKeon, calls the best in the National League defensively at his
position. Reese, 26 years old, made seven errors in 146 games,
batted .285 and had 38 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a certain player that that was key for them and we
were not going to trade that player,'' Bowden said. ``We told them
that at one of the first meetings. We never wavered off that. We
just can't get past that particular player.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said he made an extended series of offers, one a
five-player package, several with four players involved, the last
two with three players, ``different variants of quality and
quantity,'' he said. ``We put in proven players, top prospects, we
put in impact type, top-of-the-line quality players both at the
major league level and the minor league level. They just weren't
the names they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden hasn't identified any of those players, but he is
believed to have included at one time or another starting pitchers
Denny Neagle and Brett Tomko, reliever Scott Williamson (National
League rookie of the year) and outfielders Mike Cameron, Dmitri
Young and Michael Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made significant offers to them,'' Bowden said, ``offers
that if I were on that side and I had a player who was going to be
a free agent at the end of 2000, I would make a deal in their
shoes. We made that type of offers and it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden and Gillick had one last meeting Saturday. It lasted
about 35 minutes and ended as did all of their other meetings or
telephone conversations in the past five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``After five weeks of no progress,'' Bowden related, ``Pat
Gillick and I shook hands and agreed not to continue any more
discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there a possibility that they, nevertheless, would start
talks again at some point? ``No chance at all, zero,'' Bowden said.
``It's behind us. The next time we'll pursue him is if he becomes a
free agent at the end of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said the Reds wanted to acquire Griffey, whom he
described as his personal favorite, for one season, then see the
kind of economic impact he made in Cincinnati before they
considered negotiating a long-term contract that would be the
richest in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to see if he would have the effect that Mark McGwire
had in St. Louis,'' the general manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's father, Ken Sr., is the Reds' hitting coach and the
presumed manager-in-waiting. The Reds figured that if they could
trade for Griffey now they would have an edge in having him stay
because of his father. But now they'll have to see if they can get
him as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said he was somewhat optimistic in his chances of getting
Griffey only once, when Chuck Armstrong, the Mariners' president,
called him last Friday. ``I felt possibly from a negotiating
perspective maybe they were considering blinking at that point,''
he said, ``but it never happened.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
