u a BC-CLINTON-GAYS-665&AMP;ADD-     12-11 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GAYS-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMITS `DON'T ASK' STANCE HAS BEEN FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (Eds: This story is now on page 1 of The New York Times.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ President Clinton said Saturday that he
agreed with his wife that the military's ``don't ask, don't tell''
policy in dealing with homosexuals had been a failure, and he
accused military leaders of not enforcing it properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of whack, and I don't think any serious person could
say it's not,'' the president said in a radio interview with CBS
News. He noted that he adopted the policy in 1993 after Congress
rejected his proposal to end separate treatment of gay men and
lesbians in the military.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Hillary Rodham Clinton told a group of gay
contributors that she would work to overturn the policy if she
became a senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   In his interview Saturday, Clinton said, ``For me, what's
important is that the policy as implemented does not work as I
announced and as the leaders of our military at the time in 1993
pledged to implement it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was here for a convention of the Florida state
Democratic Party. He gave a speech defending affirmative action and
urged Floridians to reject efforts to curtail its use to overcome
the effects of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In his first campaign for president in 1992, Clinton promised to
lift the military's longstanding ban on service by homosexuals in
the military. The issue surfaced only occasionally during the
campaign, but it dominated Clinton's first weeks in office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Most senior military officials were vehemently against any
change in the policy of excluding gays from the military.
</P>
<P>
   They were supported by most Republicans in Congress and many
important Democrats, including Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia, then
chairman of the Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the president retreated from his campaign promise, the
lawmakers said, they would write into law the regulation barring
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   As a compromise, the president settled for the ``don't ask,
don't tell'' policy. Under it, homosexual activity is prohibited.
But gay men and lesbians may serve in the armed forces if they do
not disclose their sexuality, and the military is not supposed to
initiate unfounded inquiries about homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the policy satisfied no one _ neither those
who wanted to retain the ban nor gay rights advocates who wanted it
lifted entirely.
</P>
<P>
   In his radio interview Saturday, Clinton said, ``The reason I
went for `don't ask, don't tell' is that it's all I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped the beating death of a gay soldier at Fort
Campbell, Ky., last July would ``give some sobering impetus to a
re-examination about how this policy is implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me remind you that the original intent was that people
would not be rooted out, that they would not be questioned,'' the
president said, and that homosexuality ``would not be sufficient to
keep them out of the military or subject them to harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the Florida Democrats, Clinton said,
``Affirmative action actually began under a Republican
administration, back when both parties were really committed to
civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said no one could ``make a serious case that we'd be
better off if we were growing more divided by walking away from one
of the tools that helped to bring us together as a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward Connerly, a conservative black businessman and opponent of
affirmative action who successfully advocated a ballot initiative
on the issue in California, has been pressing a similar campaign in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But the state Supreme Court, which must review such ballot
initiatives before they can be put before the voters, appears
likely to take so long that the question will not be put on the
Florida ballot in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asserted that ``Mr. Connerly is wrong in wanting to end
affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Toiv, a spokesman for Clinton, said the president believed
that Connerly's efforts in Florida were ``extremely divisive,'' and
that ``it's important for leaders to speak out against them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, before leaving his hotel in Disney World here,
Clinton met for about 45 minutes with Nelson Mandela, the elder
statesman of South Africa, who has been visiting the United States.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed prospects for peace in the Middle East, among
other issues, Toiv said. On Wednesday, Clinton announced that Syria
and Israel had agreed to hold peace talks in Washington this week
to try to resolve their long-running dispute over control of the
Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Toiv said, ``Mr. Mandela believes that Mr. Clinton can play a
unique role in the Middle East,'' and the former president of South
Africa urged Clinton to make every effort to achieve that
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela also told Clinton about his plans for negotiations in
Burundi. Mandela was recently asked to lead new peace efforts in
Burundi, where at least 150,000 people have been killed in six
years of civil war and ethnic fighting.
</P>
<P>
   In his regular Saturday radio address, Clinton announced plans
Saturday to improve the safety of imported food and to reduce the
number of illnesses caused by eggs infected with salmonella
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, foreign-grown food products that are
rejected because of a serious public-health or safety violation
will be destroyed, so they cannot be brought into the United States
at another port. Often, federal officials said, importers whose
cargo is denied entry at one port try to introduce it at another
port.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
