<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN EXPOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) 
(lb) 
 By CARL HULSE AND SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMLAND LOSS IS PAVING THE WAY FOR SOUTHERN GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Southern Sun Belt states are paying for their
population and economic growth with drastic reductions in farmland
and open space, according to a new survey of agricultural lands.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture's National Resources
Inventory ranked five Southeastern states in the top 10 for acreage
converted to urban and other uses and put seven in the top 15. The
survey, covering the years 1992-97, reflects what many Southerners
already know _ asphalt is rapidly replacing rolling fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate at which we're paving over good, productive working
land is accelerating at a horrifying speed,'' said Ralph Grossi,
president of the American Farmland Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Texas was again the top state, with 243,000 acres lost annually,
followed by Pennsylvania, which saw a huge jump in conversions.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was third, with a significant increase in farmland
losses to 210,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Growth slowed slightly in Florida and North Carolina from the
previous survey, but they still ranked fourth and fifth
respectively with 189,000 acres converted in Florida per year and
156,000 in North Carolina. Tennessee ranked seventh with 122,000
acres plowed under each year followed by South Carolina in ninth
place with 107,000 acres, Virginia 12th with 93,000 and Alabama
13th with 89,000.
</P>
<P>
   Groups like the farmland trust are trying to maintain farm
acreage inventories through approaches such as preservation
easements _ paying landowners to hold onto their property. But the
financial pressure to sell to developers can be irresistible,
especially in cases where younger family members have no interest
in farming.
</P>
<P>
   The report is likely to boost the visibility of urban sprawl as
a political issue in the 2000 campaign season. ``We can help
preserve our communities, and our environment, by keeping farmers
on the land,'' said Vice President Al Gore, who has seized on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTIONABLE TRANSACTION
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of a House banking subcommittee, Alabama Rep.
Spencer Bachus is a natural to talk about service fees,
international monetary policy _ and the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Bachus, a Republican, recently presided over a hearing looking
at the pending transfer of the canal from the United States to
Panama. He is one of several conservatives sounding the alarm about
that move.
</P>
<P>
   Bachus said his banking subcommittee has jurisdiction over the
matter because of concerns that ``alleged corruption'' in the
Panamanian government threatens U.S. commercial interests.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives also see a threat from China because a Hong
Kong-based company operates ports at both ends of the canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is legitimate concern that Panama cannot provide the
necessary security to protect the canal, which is vitally important
to our commerce and national security,'' Bachus said.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer will take place Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN'S WORK
</P>
<P>
   Some Southern states are lagging in appointing women to top
government posts, with a few states in Dixie moving backward even
as women make gains elsewhere in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In a new review done for the Center for Women in Government,
based in Albany, N.Y., Mississippi ranked 49th in terms of the
number of women in state leadership posts when compared with the
state population overall. Louisiana ranked 47th, Alabama 39th and
South Carolina 38th, down substantially from the year before.
Though North Carolina ranked 11th, that state too had fewer women
in top roles than in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Florida was the leader among Southern states, ranking fourth,
with women holding 42 percent of the state's top policy jobs while
comprising almost 52 percent of the state's population. Vermont was
the national leader.
</P>
<P>
   TROLLING FOR TROUBLE
</P>
<P>
   Federal fishery managers are demonstrating that they are serious
about protecting dwindling red snapper and other species of fish in
the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration charged the
owners and operators of 25 commercial fishing vessels with multiple
counts of catching red snapper when the commercial season was
closed, assessing more than $1.2 million in penalties and seeking
fishing permit suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said over 35,000 pounds of snapper was sold after the
1996-97 season was closed. Snapper fishing in the Gulf has been
under tightening restrictions in an attempt to restore the depleted
stocks of one of the region's signature fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illegal activities like these, if unchecked, make a mockery of
the sacrifices honest fishermen make to rebuild the red snapper
fishery,'' said Bill Hogarth, Southeast administrator for NOAA.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
