<HEADLINE>
DEVILS NAP AND OILERS SKATE PAST THEM, 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Brimming with confidence after their
victories over Pittsburgh and Chicago, the Devils came into
Saturday's game against the worst road team in hockey and did
exactly what center Bobby Holik had feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played right into their hands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Edmonton Oilers scored three goals in less than eight
minutes in the first period and went on to win their first road
game in nearly a month and second of the season, defeating the
Devils, 3-1, before 14,224 at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out ready to play and we didn't,'' said defenseman
Lyle Odelein, who was on the ice for all three Oilers goals and had
an assist on Krzysztof Oliwa's slow-rolling goal at 17 minutes 3
seconds of the second period. ``After the first period, we said a
few things, the guys did, and played hard. But when you only play
40 minutes, you're not going to win too many hockey games.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter, Holik said, for the Devils to play ``a good 40
minutes if the game was decided in the first 20.'' With the loss,
the Devils fell to 15-10-3 but still possessed one of the best home
records at 11-3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-skating Oilers, infrequent visitors to the New York
area, jumped all over a somnolent Devils defense, peppering
goaltender Martin Brodeur and breaking through at 6:45 when Boyd
Devereaux took a nice pass from Georges Laraque and put it in off
the rebound for his second goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Just over three minutes later, Ethan Moreau made the score 2-0
when he beat Sergei Nemchinov to Devereaux's pass and put it past
Brodeur on his glove side at 10:05, and Josef Beranek made it 3-0
when he came across the blue line with the puck and sent a hard
shot past Brodeur at 14:24.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third one came in at an angle, bouncing a little bit, but
I should have had it,'' said Brodeur, who stopped 20 shots and
whose record is now 15-7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Devils' offense mustered only five shots on goal
in the first period, getting off the first shot of the period and
then not again until 9:45 had elapsed. It was a different game in
the second and third periods, with the Devils outshooting the
Oilers by 25-10, but Bill Ranford made several spectacular saves to
keep the Devils at bay and register his first victory in seven
outings this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels real good,'' said coach Kevin Lowe, whose Oilers
(9-14-7) have lost 9 of 11 games by two goals or fewer, seven of
those by one. ``We have played some good hockey on the road this
year; it just hasn't been rewarded. It is kind of ironic that it is
rewarded against one of the best teams in the league.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
