<HEADER>
A6204 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-49ERS-CAP12-COX     12-11 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-CAP12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debt comes due for 49ers dynasty
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Bill Walsh retired as coach of the 49ers
after the 1988 season, he left behind one of the NFL's greatest
dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco had won three Super Bowls in eight years and still
featured superstars Joe Montana, Roger Craig, Ronnie Lott and Jerry
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator George Seifert took over only four days
after San Francisco won Super Bowl XXIII in January '89, and
uttered the words that would become a mantra around the 49ers'
empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ship will not sink on my watch,'' he vowed.
</P>
<P>
   The dynasty didn't crumble under Seifert. San Francisco won two
more Super Bowls and reached the NFC Championship Game three other
times during his eight-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a standard,'' 49ers defensive tackle Junior Bryant
said. ``We didn't have to talk about it too much. It was the way we
approached each season. Some teams might say, `We want to get a
winning season.' For us, that was taken for granted. The ultimate
goal was always the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Seifert was pushed out in a power struggle with former president
Carmen Policy. Replaced by Steve Mariucci, who had coached at
California for just one season, Seifert is in his first year as
coach of the Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   When Mariucci was hired in 1997, Policy told him, ``You're in
for the ride of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mariucci knows what Policy meant. The dynasty is over.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers (3-9) have lost eight games in a row going into
today's contest against the Falcons (3-9) at 3Com Park. San
Francisco, which won at least 10 games in 16 consecutive seasons
before this year, hasn't lost nine in a row since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain the emotions that you go through,''
Mariucci said. ``I guess shock is the best word. We know where we
are. We know why we are in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the 49ers lived on borrowed time, or credit,
mortgaging the future on a yearly basis in hopes of putting that
season's team in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Eddie DeBartolo, serving an NFL suspension because of his
involvement in a gambling fraud case, demanded the drive. And it
worked.
</P>
<P>
   This year will be the first season the 49ers will miss the
playoffs since '91, when they finished 10-6 and won their final six
games.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo was willing to pay whatever it cost _ generally huge
signing bonuses and restructured contracts _ to attract and keep
top talent.
</P>
<P>
   Last offseason, the bill collector came calling.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, 68, returned to the franchise in January and was named
the team's vice president and general manager. His first task was
trimming the 49ers' payroll _ the team was $28 million over the $57
million cap in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came on board I knew to a certain extent what was going
to be ahead of us,'' Mariucci said. ``Really, there's no need for
any finger pointing or trying to find a reason why this is all
coming down right now. There was a conscious decision made five or
six years ago by Mr. DeBartolo and Carmen Policy to try to continue
to win games and try to be a contender every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And while they decided to do that, it required spending money,
bringing in free agents, pro-rating signing bonuses and
restructuring contracts, pushing the debt into the future. That was
the decision that was made.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh was forced to purge the team's roster. He traded defensive
end Roy Barker, tight end Irv Smith, quarterback Ty Detmer and
fullback Marc Edwards to Cleveland, where Policy and Clark had fled
to run the expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Bowl guard Kevin Gogan was dealt to Miami, and longtime free
safety Merton Hanks was cut in a cost-cutting move. Mariucci said
30 players are missing from the team that lost to the Falcons in
last year's NFC divisional playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh managed to bring the 49ers under the cap this year. But
Mariucci said the team will have to cut an additional $24 million
to $26 million after this season as the projected cap is $62
million for 2000. By contrast, projections put the Falcons roughly
$15 million under next year's salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly not out of the woods,'' Mariucci said. ``I
think everybody in the 49ers empire really did enjoy the long
stretch of success. But it was expensive to do that and sooner or
later you must pay the bill. It's come due.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers don't figure to get much better any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions must be made about the futures of quarterback Steve
Young and receiver Jerry Rice. Young hasn't played since Sept. 27
because of post-concussion syndrome. Rice isn't nearly as
productive at 37.
</P>
<P>
   Young's cap charge is $8.1 million next season. It will be $6.9
million if he retires or is waived. Rice's cap charge is $5.95
million next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my druthers, I would like to see a final game being
played with Steve Young throwing a touchdown pass to Jerry Rice,''
Walsh said, ``everything stopping and both of them coming off the
field together. That would be the appropriate finale for two great
careers.''
</P>
<P>
   And the appropriate end of a dynasty, although the 49ers would
still be paying for them for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
