<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECO-CHALLENGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALANDERS WIN 197-MILE ADVENTURE RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALICIA AULT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARILOCHE, Argentina _ As the 1999 Eco-Challenge adventure race
came to a close Friday, a full two days ahead of schedule, the
winners had already enjoyed several days of catching up on sleep
and stuffing themselves with Argentine beef.
</P>
<P>
   The race was decided at 9:20 a.m. Monday when Team Greenpeace of
New Zealand paddled across the finish line on Lake Nahuel Huapi,
about 20 miles from Bariloche. The team completed the 197-mile
course in a blistering five days, finishing on a placid Patagonian
summer day that belied the fierce storm two days into the race that
divided the leaders from the followers.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Eco-Challenge course, which teams of four
competitors traveled by kayak, horse and foot, was almost 100 miles
shorter than previous races, to give racers a greater margin of
safety in Patagonia's rugged terrain and unpredictable climate.
</P>
<P>
   The race director, Mark Burnett, allotted 12 days for the teams
to pass the race's 28 checkpoints, and had estimated it would take
the speediest teams eight. Many had strong kayaking and
mountaineering experience and, aside from the storm, the weather
was mostly on their side. This led to one of the closest finishes
ever in an expedition race.
</P>
<P>
   Two other teams paddled close in on Greenpeace's wake: Team
Sierra Nevada from Spain came across just 50 minutes later and Team
Condor an hour later. Condor, from Bariloche, was met by thousands
of local fans lining the beach and chanting ``Bariloche,
Bariloche'' while firemen let loose their shrill sirens in tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Four other teams finished that afternoon and evening: the
largely female American team Atlas Snowshoes/Rubicon; Finland's
Team Halti; the 1998 titleholder, Team Vail from the United States;
and Foster's Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 50 teams that started the morning of Dec. 1, 34 finished.
Seven others lost members with injuries and completed the race
unranked. There were only a few medical problems, including a
broken ankle, an ovarian cyst that needed emergency surgery and
several severely infected blisters.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenpeace team, which is named after the environmental
group but has no connection to it, did five days of deep-water
kayaking, bushwhacking through thick bamboo and multiple ascents
and descents of 10,000-foot-plus mountains and was ready to go
around again, said its captain, John Howard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't pushing ourselves _ we could have gone faster,''
said the 44-year-old Howard, one of the world's premier adventure
racers and a well-known character. Howard, who cleans windows at
mansions around Christchurch, New Zealand, lives in a bus
overlooking the city. He has won every major race, including three
Raid Gauloises titles and two previous Eco-Challenge titles.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the team were Andrea Murray, 35, a garden designer
from Christchurch; her husband, Keith Murray, 38, a doctor; and
Neil Jones, 38, a kiwi grower.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenpeace team will take home $50,000 for its victory. Many
teams are sponsored, allowing them to be outfitted with the latest
gear and clothing, but not Greenpeace. It's a situation Howard
prefers. He provided teammates with drugstore shower caps _ lighter
than any technical gear _ to keep their heads warm and dry during
the three kayaking segments. And it would be hard to forget the
sight of team members jumping into a churning river clutching black
plastic garbage bags full of their gear as they frantically swam
across to pick up their horses for the riding segment.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of the race was the storm that began on the afternoon
of the race's second day. Temperatures quickly dropped and winds
exceeding 90 mph were recorded at a checkpoint halfway up the
Agostini Wall, a sheer rock face that a majority of the teams had
yet to ascend when the storm arose.
</P>
<P>
   Those who had begun their climb returned to a base camp, where
temperatures fell into the 20s overnight. Snow began in earnest at
daybreak, and the upper mountain checkpoint was later closed as the
fixed ropes were buried by up to a foot of snow. Racers were later
sent on a longer, roundabout path to the next checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace and Rubicon were already far ahead, as were Sierra
Nevada, Halti and Condor. Rubicon spent eight hours mostly on the
move to stay warm, while Sierra Nevada found shelter in a
campground and slept. Greenpeace waited out the storm under a
tarpaulin, catching catnaps.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing when and at what point to sleep was important.
Greenpeace slept a total of 9 1/2 hours over five days. But by
sleeping mostly on course, not at checkpoints, it fooled
competitors into thinking it was barely resting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're pushing on, they think we're not sleeping,'' Howard
said.
</P>
<P>
   At checkpoint 23 on 12,000-foot Mount Tronador, a climbers'
refuge perched on a glacier 5,000 feet below the summit, racers
could stop for a hot bowl of pasta and sleep. Rubicon arrived giddy
from sleeplessness and decided to rest before attempting the next
glacier crossing. The members zipped themselves into reporters'
sleeping bags and shut down for two hours. While they slept, Team
Sierra Nevada whizzed in and out, as did Team Condor, and Rubicon
fell from second to fourth. But its captain, Rebecca Rusch, said it
had given up its lead much earlier in the race by forgoing sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubicon's members were not disappointed, having expected
only to be somewhere in the top 10, she said. ``We were really,
really psyched,'' Rusch, 31, said of their finish. ``It was a
near-perfect race for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
