<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-CHEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS CHANCELLOR FIRES NINE IN CHEATING SCANDAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew has fired nine educators
and taken steps to dismiss 11 others in the latest fallout from a
cheating scandal in New York City's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Crew fired three teachers' aides and six teachers who did not
have tenure on Thursday evening after concluding that they helped
students cheat on standardized tests, said Pam McDonnell, a
spokeswoman for the Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor has also brought misconduct charges against 11
other teachers and principals, Ms. McDonnell said. Under state law,
tenured employees are entitled to hearings before state-appointed
administrative law judges as part of a review process that can last
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDonnell would not release the names Saturday of those
educators who had been fired or disciplined, because of privacy
concerns. But she stressed the chancellor's intention to deal
thoroughly with the matter: ``The chancellor has made it clear that
one cheater is one too many, and it is immoral and he will not
tolerate it.''
</P>
<P>
   A total of 47 principals, teachers and staff members from 32
elementary and middle schools were implicated in a cheating scandal
in a report released this week by Edward F. Stancik, the special
investigator for the city's public schools. The report said those
educators had encouraged and directly helped students to cheat on
highly competitive city and state standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Federation of Teachers, the teachers' union, has
questioned the accuracy of the report and has hired a private
company to verify the report's conclusions. ``The union will make
sure that all its members get a fair hearing, including those tried
by press conference,'' said Dick Riley, a spokesman for the union.
</P>
<P>
   The educators named in the report were immediately removed from
their school jobs and transferred to district offices while school
administrators conduct their own investigation, Ms. McDonnell said.
They will continue to receive their full salaries, which range from
$40,000 to $60,000 per year, Ms. McDonnell said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, seven teachers mentioned in the report had left the
school system before the report was released, and their names have
been placed on a list that will prevent them from being hired for
any public school in New York City, Ms. McDonnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDonnell said that the rest of the educators named in the
report were still being investigated by the chancellor's school
administrators, but that she did not know how long that would take.
``The ones that were the most egregious, we already knew about and
acted on,'' she said. ``The ones we're not acting on are still
under investigation because it's not as clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Stancik's report criticized the way school
administrators had handled the allegations of cheating, Ms.
McDonnell said they had helped Stancik's investigation by passing
along complaints and other information about individual educators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
