<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-WARN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US ISSUES GLOBAL CAUTION FOR HOLIDAY TRAVEL ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an extraordinary worldwide advisory, the State
Department Saturday cautioned all Americans living or traveling
abroad to avoid large crowds over the holiday season, citing
``credible information that terrorists are planning attacks''
against them.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory did not include travel inside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no specific information at this time that the threat
is directed to American citizens here at home,'' said James B.
Foley, the department's deputy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   While the State Department previously has issued travel warnings
about threats in specific geographic areas, it was highly unusual
to issue a global note of caution.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said there was discussion about eeing the worldwide
caution to the United States ``because there are lot of people
trying to take advantage of vulnerabilities during Christmas and
New Year's.''
</P>
<P>
   But the credible threats of attacks involved only overseas
sites, the official said. In its statement, the State Department
said it had information indicating attacks ``could be planned for
locations throughout the world where large gatherings and
celebrations will be taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   It urged Americans traveling or living abroad ``to review their
security practices, to remain alert to the changing situation and
to exercise caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley provided no details about the threat, but added: ``We
believe the information we have is credible and specific. The
specifics include terrorist activities. . . . American citizens are
among the targets of these attacks. The planned attacks are timed
to coincide with the beginning of the New Year and the month of
Ramadan, when religious and other celebrations are taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   While the State Department avoided any specifics on the threat,
officials have previously cited Osama bin Laden, a Saudi-born
terrorism suspect, as one of the most dangerous threats to
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, believed to be based in Afghanistan, is accused of
masterminding the 1998 bombings of two US embassies in East Africa
that killed more than 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   The administration official said that one of the biggest
concerns remains in Israel, where a large number of Americans are
celebrating the holidays and the millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
