<HEADLINE>
BANNED ELSEWHERE, FALUN GONG MEETS IN HONG KONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Several hundred members of the Falun Gong spiritual
group, banned in China, tested Hong Kong's autonomy from Chinese
rule Saturday by demonstrating peacefully to urge Beijing to stop
repressing their organization.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong, the former British colony that returned to Chinese
rule in 1997 with the promise of autonomy, is the only place in
China where Falun Gong is not illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration Saturday, and the conference Sunday of 1,000
Falun Gong members from around the world at Hong Kong's convention
center, follow a five-month crackdown and thousands of arrests of
Falun Gong members in China. The events are a test of China's
effort to stamp out any challenge to its authority, as well as of
its promise to maintain Hong Kong's autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong is the center now for Falun Gong for the whole
world. . . . In China, you can't even practice in your own home,''
said Janet Xiong, 45, a Wuhan native who now works for the New York
City government.
</P>
<P>
   Xiong said she flew from New York for the conference and to
demand that China end its ban on the group. ``We don't have a
political motive. . . . It was the Chinese government who made it
political.''
</P>
<P>
   About 600 adherents who said they were from Hong Kong and 13
other countries, including Taiwan, Japan, Sweden, France, and the
United States, gathered at dawn in a park near the government news
agency office and meditated all day before leading a procession
across town. They left a petition, since no official would meet
them.
</P>
<P>
   With raised arms and closed eyes, they stretched in unison to
the sound of gongs and string instruments from boom boxes. Most
members, many of them elderly, wore yellow T-shirts and nametags,
and some carried banners with the motto ``Peace, Compassion,
Patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong combines the ancient religions of Buddhism and Taoism
with breathing exercises and meditation, and is a branch of qi
gong, an ancient teaching to channel inner energy for healing and
power. Unlike some other Chinese physical disciplines such as Tai
Chi, Falun Gong has an intricate belief system and a single leader.
</P>
<P>
   The group claims 100 million followers worldwide, although the
Chinese government says only 2 million followers are in China.
Adherents preach clean, ascetic living and follow the teachings of
a New York-based spiritual leader, whom Beijing wants to extradite
for trial as the head of an ``evil cult.''
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong was the first mainstream mass movement to emerge that
is not under Communist Party control since the 1949 Revolution.
Some analysts say it reflects frustration among dispossessed
workers who have not benefited from economic reforms. China also
has a history of cracking down on religions seen as a threat to the
leadership, including foreign missionaries 100 years ago, and the
followers of a messianic Chinese peasant in the mid-19th century.
</P>
<P>
   China says that Falun Gong has political ambitions, and that its
practices _ such as discouraging medical treatment _ have caused
the deaths of 1,400 ill members. Beijing banned the group in July,
three months after 10,000 followers surrounded the leadership
offices to demand official recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Since, Beijing has arrested and jailed more than 150 key
leaders, and last week a spokesman for the Chinese State Council,
or Cabinet, said police had detained followers 35,792 times in
Beijing in the past four months. Some Falun Gong members are
reported to have died in recent months in police custody.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong authorities, in contrast, granted permission for the
weekend demonstration and conference without difficulty, although
the police presence at the convention center has been stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   When Falun Gong was banned on the mainland and hundreds of
thousands of its practice manuals were destroyed, a Hong Kong
subsidiary of a Chinese publishing company stopped printing the
books, even though their sale had never been banned. Falun Gong
books are now shipped here from the United States. Several months
ago, a Hong Kong pager company refused to take messages related to
Falun Gong, in a violation of local rules for which the company was
reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practicing kung fu, doing exercise, and keeping fit are all
worthwhile activities,'' said Tung Chee-hwa, Beijing's choice as
chief executive of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   But, he cautioned, ``We have taken note of the Falun Gong in
Hong Kong. . . . These activities must comply strictly with Hong
Kong laws, and the organizers and participants must not act in any
manner'' against the interest of China Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Kan Hung-cheung, a businessman and group spokesman, said that
despite Hong Kong authorities' leniency, ``some people here are
still worried, with Hong Kong so close to China. Will there be
repercussions like phone taps and people followed? I'm sure it
happens, we just don't know to whom.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiona Ching, 41, a Shanghai native who lives in Hong Kong, said
she has paid for her beliefs. Ching said her boss had spotted her
on the local news handing out Falun Gong pamphlets, and had fired
her for being a ``troublemaker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
