<SLUG> BC-GORE-BLACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BEGINS NATIONAL EFFORT TO GET BLACK VOTES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Invoking the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and his
own Southern roots, Vice President Al Gore came to a historic black
section of Atlanta Saturday to launch a national effort to
encourage African-Americans to turn out for him at the polls, both
in the primaries and next November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side is counting on blowing the roof off all of the
election finance and breaking all the records and lining up all of
the special interests,'' Gore declared in a speech rife with
biblical cadences after entering to the throbbing beat of ``Love
Train,'' which is fast becoming his campaign theme song.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I can tell you that here in the South,'' he said, ``we
have the capacity to blow the roof off voter registration and
turnout and grass-roots enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to his failed 1988 presidential bid, when he
campaigned as a candidate of the South, Gore rarely mentions the
South this time around, presenting himself as a national candidate.
But he talked Saturday of the special bond that Southern whites
have with blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, especially those of us here in the South, are intensely
proud of what we have done together,'' he said, lauding ``those who
took the blows, shed blood that was redemptive for our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign considers the black vote crucial to the vice
president's ability to stave off former Sen. Bill Bradley,
especially with several Southern states holding primaries in March.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Brazile, the Gore campaign manager, said blacks
traditionally make up more than a fourth of the turnout in
Democratic primaries in the South. Most surveys show Gore with a
substantial lead among African-Americans over Bradley. The goal,
Gore advisers said, will be to get them to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been courting black voters for years, but Saturday his
campaign began a nationwide push.
</P>
<P>
   With simultaneous events in New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and
Des Moines, the campaign announced the support of nearly 3,000
prominent African-Americans, most of whom have already endorsed
him. They included hundreds of elected officials and members of the
clergy as well as the singer Aretha Franklin and the comedian Bill
Cosby and athletes like the basketball player Shaquille O'Neal and
the track star Carl Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Gore chose to kick off his campaign for the black vote in
Atlanta, where the black community's roots run deep and because
Georgia is the first Southern state to vote in a primary, on March
7.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of today's events reflected the quickly advancing
primary schedule and the fact that the candidates are in the
process of fielding delegates in several Northern states with
significant black populations, including New York, Pennsylvania,
Ohio and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke Saturday morning in the small auditorium of the
Atlanta Life Insurance building on Auburn Avenue, just up the
street from the Ebenezer Baptist Church, where King preached and is
buried. The life insurance company was started by a former slave,
Alonzo Herndon, in 1905 and became a cornerstone of black
businesses in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was praised by a succession of black politicians, who cited
his support for affirmative action, his father's record of support
for civil rights and, mostly, the Clinton administration's record
in reducing crime, reducing black unemployment, helping more blacks
attend college and appointing a record number of blacks to
positions in the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's supporters Saturday included Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga. Lewis
reminded the audience that the Georgia primary fell on the 35th
anniversary of the civil rights march in Alabama from Selma to
Montgomery, a coincidence that the Gore campaign intends to
exploit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our sisters and brothers died for the right to vote,''
Lewis told the audience. ``On March 7, we will go to the polls and
we will vote like we never, ever voted before, and then in November
2000 we will come back to the polls and vote again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the crowd: ``I make you this pledge. Together, with
your enthusiasm, your ideas and your commitment, we're going to win
this nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The next president is going to appoint three to four justices
of the Supreme Court,'' Gore said. ``What would Thurgood Marshall
have thought if he took his historic cases to a Supreme Court that
was stacked with ideological right wingers predisposed to say no?''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Anyone who says affirmative action is no longer
needed because we've reached the promised land has confused the
wilderness with Canaan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
