<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6224 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-NEWYEAR-TRAVEL-KAN &LR;      12-11 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR-TRAVEL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLATED PRICES, Y2K UPROAR DASH TRAVEL INDUSTRY'S HOLIDAY HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDWARD M. EVELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ What a New Year's Eve this was going to be.
</P>
<P>
   In search of scrapbook memories, travelers would head to exotic
hither and romantic yon in great numbers. Demand for New Year's
trips would be huge.
</P>
<P>
   At least that was the thinking a year ago. Let's just say your
travel agent is still waiting for your call. He or she is not as
lonely as the Maytag repairman _ these are the holidays, after all
_ but the year 2000 bombardment has yet to bombard.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I tell you everything is available?'' said travel
executive Kathy Sudeikis, only half-jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   The travel industry geared up for what it thought would be a
titanic travel opportunity. Certainly everyone would want to be
someplace memorable on the night of Dec. 31, 1999, right?
</P>
<P>
   Sure. And many will be. But for lots of Americans, factors
economical and psychological altered the New Year's Eve equation.
</P>
<P>
   The economic reasons are easiest to explain: Prices were too
high. Way too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just weren't going to be gouged,'' Sudeikis said.
</P>
<P>
   The irony now is that many prices are beginning to fall, from
airline fares to cruise prices, but it might be too late.
</P>
<P>
   About 14 months ago Sudeikis heard from a group of friends, 10
couples who wanted to spend New Year's together on a cruise ship.
But when it came time to book the package, they found the prices
absurd and backed out. She tried to call them when prices started
to drop, but she never heard back. Apparently they were out of the
mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the travel industry shot itself in the foot,'' said Ed
Perkins, who writes a syndicated consumer column on travel.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said plenty of people got sticker shock as they tried to
book hotel packages. Many hotels required minimum stays of five or
seven nights. It turned people off, and they started to make
cheaper, close-to-home plans.
</P>
<P>
   The American Automobile Association says 44.6 million Americans
are expected to travel 100 miles or more from their homes during
the Christmas-New Year's period. That is a lot of people, but it is
a 1 percent drop from last year and the first decline since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Youngman, marketing director for the Caribbean Tourism
Organization, reported that except at a few exclusive resorts that
often sold out at the holidays, space was available in the
Caribbean island nations.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons go beyond price, he said, to psychology. Youngman
makes the ``too much fuss'' argument: that all the talk about Y2K
and the worries about delays, breakdowns and crowds soured people
on anything potentially complicated, such as travel. It was easier
to avoid the whole idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a global thing,'' Youngman said. ``People feel they don't
want to go too far from home. It's not the fear of falling out of
the sky so much; it's just the ballyhoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently there is some fear about falling out of the sky,
reducing the demand for flights on Dec. 31. But the Air Transport
Association, an airline industry trade group, said such concerns
had lessened. Only about 10 percent of passengers questioned in a
recent poll said they would be worried about flying as 1999 turned
to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Still, airlines have cut flights 20 percent to 30 percent in
response to a lack of demand Dec. 31 and Jan. 1. Southwest Airlines
will stop flying for 10 hours starting at 10 p.m. on New Year's Eve
to give employees a chance to spend time with family.
</P>
<P>
   Staying close to home could mean booking a hotel and restaurant
package right in town. You might think the Hyatt Regency Crown
Center hotel, known locally for its New Year's Eve bashes, would be
booked solid by now. But there is room at the inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we'd be farther ahead in the game based on the
trends in New York, Las Vegas and Chicago,'' said Mark Champa,
director of sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite slower-than-expected bookings, the hotel's New Year's
reservations are still ahead of last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyatt offers several hotel and restaurant packages with two
nights' lodging. Prices range from $595 to $800 a couple and
include food, entertainment and tickets to Science City. Packages
that include Skies restaurant are sold out, Champa said.
</P>
<P>
   One brake on New Year's planning has been work schedules. Many
companies want workers on hand, or at least on call, in case Y2K
problems crop up. Some employees have waited until work schedules
firm up.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks have called to say as soon as they get the
green light, they'd be more willing to commit,'' Champa said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lodge of Four Seasons, in Lake Ozark, is using billboards to
draw area residents to its New Year's offering, a two-day package
of meals and parties for $600 a couple.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Knoke, marketing manager, said the lodge was 60 percent
booked, a figure she considered reasonable considering the Y2K
hullabaloo in the media. Reservations accelerated after
Thanksgiving, she said, and she expects them to continue. The lodge
has not dropped its prices for the package, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people want to share the moment with family and friends
when the calendar flips to 2000. Trying to arrange trips or even
local hotel stays for large numbers of family members and friends
has stymied some people.
</P>
<P>
   Sudeikis faced that challenge herself. A large group of her
relatives and friends wanted to do something unforgettable together
to commemorate the year 2000. It also happens that Jan. 1 is the
21st birthday of her daughter, Kristin.
</P>
<P>
   They decided to find the highest spot in Overland Park, Kan.,
and gather there to watch the sunrise together. If they can arrange
it, and depending on the weather, they may also ask a priest to
celebrate Mass for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could just share the moment, that's what this is all
about,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But for revelers who still harbor thoughts of sharing that
moment in a more exotic locale, there's still time to make
reservations, said Robert Vohs of TravelSmart.
</P>
<P>
   While steep prices and lack of availability probably will keep
you out of places such as London, New York and Las Vegas, most
other spots are at least worth a try, Vohs said. In some cases
cruise prices are coming down, he said, and cruises are good
choices because they are all-inclusive and feature warm-weather
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Parsons, editor of the online Bestfares.com, reported last
week that airfare to some European cities was a third of what it
was a month ago, that cruise lines were offering steep discounts
and that those long minimum stays at hotels, even in New York and
Hawaii, were being abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   One hitch so late in the season, Vohs said, will be finding
flights, which fill up as the holidays approach. Travelers with
flexible schedules will have more options.
</P>
<P>
   Or wait till New Year's Eve 2000, which will actually usher in
the first year of the new millennium. By then, maybe the travel
industry gurus will have learned their lesson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
