<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-KANASSTATE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS STATE RADIO STATION CELEBRATES 75 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN, Kan. _ It's a voice heard across Kansas _ even parts
of Missouri, Iowa, Nebraska and Oklahoma _ ethereal words emerging
from 580 kilocycles on the radio dial.
</P>
<P>
   It's KKSU public radio. Serious talk and news. Sober.
Intelligent. No bells and whistles. No psychoanalysis or political
parodies.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Chechnya? Probably there'll be a guest on live.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of Massachusetts on the settlement of Kansas?
Variable application of nitrogen? The weather and farm prices? Iron
deficiency in fields? Health trends? Legislation in Topeka?
Personal computer use? Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 1, KKSU celebrated its 75th anniversary with a reception
at the studio at McCain Auditorium here. The affair marked the date
in 1924 that a 500-watt station with the call letters KSAC, for
Kansas State Agricultural College, signed on just up the dial at
880 kilocycles.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, then as now, was ``to take the university to the
people.'' In doing so, KSAC (KKSU since 1984) became one the first
public radio stations in Kansas, one of the first in the nation,
and is among a thimbleful still directly funded by a state.
</P>
<P>
   Today KKSU has another distinction: It is one of the few
time-sharing radio stations left. From 12:30 p.m. to 5:30 p.m. on
weekdays, tuning to 580 means KKSU coming from a transmitter on the
campus of Kansas State University; the rest of the time and on
weekends the signal radiates from the WIBW antenna 60 miles to the
east in Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary reception was mainly friends talking over old
times. Still, it was more than just a group of men and women who
love radio.
</P>
<P>
   There were ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those phantasms are still visible, such as the two
long-retired transmitting towers outside Nichols and Calvin halls.
The towers, which are on the National Register of Historic Places,
were made, not surprisingly, by a windmill manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Other specters were more ephemeral: Doc Brinkley, the goat gland
doctor who put radio on the map in Kansas; the legion of speakers
who abandoned the lectern for a microphone to discuss subjects as
diverse as hog farrowing and drip irrigation; and the scratchy
voices of Dev Nelson and Paul DeWeese, who broadcast K-State
football and basketball during the lean and seemingly hopeless
years.
</P>
<P>
   The school that would become K-State got into the radio business
early, in 1903, buying a Marconi receiver _ the first in the state.
</P>
<P>
   By 1912, the school had a radio station of sorts _ called 9YV
and transmitting with 1 kilowatt of power. It sent out weather
information, the first such regularly scheduled broadcasts in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1920s came J.R. Brinkley. His station, KFKB (Kansas
First, Kansas Best) in nearby Milford, promoted his prescription
drug business and clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley claimed to cure male impotence by surgically implanting
goat glands, a procedure that, by all accounts, was excruciating.
</P>
<P>
   KFKB was a 100,000-watt blowtorch that blanketed the United
States. Looking for an outreach program, the Kansas Cooperative
Extension Service at the university connected a telephone line to
Milford and broadcast courses in agriculture, home economics,
science and engineering. Almost 1,000 students in 39 states _ and
38 from Canada _ enrolled. There was no charge for Kansans;
out-of-staters paid 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The response, especially in an era when receivers were the
exception rather than the rule, validated radio's value to the
university. It asked the Kansas Legislature for an appropriation.
On Dec. 1, 1924, KSAC went on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Titus, who retired as general manager of the station in
1994, recalled that the University of Kansas also got an
appropriation for its own station, KSKU, which signed on about a
week after KSAC went on the air. KU entered into a time-sharing
arrangement with station WREN, but ultimately dropped out after
several years. It returned to the air in 1952 with KANU-FM.
</P>
<P>
   KSAC moved down the dial to 580 in 1929, the same year that it
embarked on its time-sharing deal with WIBW.
</P>
<P>
   Old-timers said the change was precipitated, in part, by KFKB's
potent signal, which, depending on atmospheric conditions, often
overwhelmed stations up and down the dial. That problem disappeared
in the early 1930s after The Kansas City Star ran articles
unmasking Brinkley as a quack, resulting in the demise of the
Milford clinic and the removal of his radio operation to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   KSAC went about its business. It ignored swing music and soap
operas, Jack Benny and Walter Winchell _ then staples of radio _
and concentrated on getting information out to its listeners, those
Kansans whose taxes paid the freight.
</P>
<P>
   An example: KSAC pioneered what were called filmstrip
broadcasts, equivalent then to instructing today by using
videotapes. Students would gather in a school or meeting hall, KSAC
would be tuned in, a projector would be turned on, and lectures
coming out of the radio would be illustrated with images on a strip
of film. The projectionist knew it was time to advance a frame when
he heard ``ding,'' which, truth be known, was a spoon hitting a
glass in the KSAC studio.
</P>
<P>
   It was no-nonsense stuff, said Titus, aimed, as always, at
helping Kansas farmers and ranchers understand a world that was
changing around them.
</P>
<P>
   Over the following years, KSAC modernized, produced programs for
other stations and pushed for a nationwide public radio service.
Titus was on the committee that helped create the ``All Things
Considered'' news show on National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   One oddity, said Titus, was that for years K-State sportscasts
were provided free. Stations had only to pay the telephone line
charges _ maybe $20 a game. That meant, he said, that more than a
few small, struggling stations were able to survive by selling
commercials at almost pure profit.
</P>
<P>
   While sports were important, the bedrock audience remained the
farmers, ranchers and homemakers//wives who held it all together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always leaned toward the production farmer,'' said
Richard Baker, KKSU news director, ``meaning, getting information,
and lots of it, out to our listeners in rural areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, he said, is essentially the mission of the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's been an effort by some university public radio
stations to distance themselves from their schools,'' Baker said.
``Tune in and, except for the call letters, there's hardly any
indication that they are part of a university. But I understand.
It's a matter of money. They have to raise funds. They have to
reach a big audience.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade the station here, because of the loss of
federal funds, dropped the National Public Radio network and went
to almost all locally produced news and information _ a return to
its roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it intelligent news,'' said Baker. ``I don't care if we
have it first. But I do care that we have it all. There are people
all over this campus who can help that guy who is farming or
ranching. That's what we're about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
