<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6228 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-WHITEHOUSE-TREE-KAN &LR;      12-11 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-TREE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC POTTER CREATES WHITE HOUSE ORNAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The letter arrived in Kansas City in July, and the
return address said simply, ``The White House.''
</P>
<P>
   But all Irma Starr thought was, ``What did I do wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was a matter of what she had done right.
</P>
<P>
   The envelope contained an invitation: The Clintons wanted Starr
to create an ornament for the annual White House Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   Although Starr was astonished by the invitation, her inclusion
should be no surprise, given the tree's ``holiday treasures'' theme
that seeks to honor the nation's artistic heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, the potter at the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, is a
historic potter. A specialist in lost techniques, she is one of a
handful across the country who reproduce a 17th-century style of
ceramics known as slipware.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled because to think I was good enough to do an
ornament for the White House, it was one of the biggest thrills of
my pottery career,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the area's role as a jumping-off point for the West,
Starr molded her ornament in the shape of a covered wagon, taking a
month and five attempts to get it right. One hurdle was to keep the
ornament to just 1 pound of clay.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the weight limit? The glittering, 18-foot fir
that graces the Blue Room is festooned with crafts, tin icicles and
historical dolls by artisans from throughout the country. It also
is laden with state decorative balls, colored glass balls and
thousands of lights.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 11,191 ornaments cover the tree.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's whimsical covered-wagon ornament is inscribed with the
names of American Indian tribes, slogans like ``Westward Ho!,'' and
an old stagecoach company ad that reads: ``Wanted: wiry, skinny,
wiry young fellow willing to risk death daily. Orphan preferred.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr is petite, with blue eyes and rarely without a ``glitzy''
dragonfly barrette holding her blond hair in place. She favors
jeans and black turtlenecks. She's also a grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Her one-room studio is cluttered with her collection of Old
World Santa Claus figurines that she makes every season. Filled
with the telltale aroma of the potter's kiln, it is more home to
Starr than her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like walking into a kitchen with the smell of an apple
pie baking,'' she said, ``that warm feeling that says, `Oh, you're
home. This is where you belong.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been the resident potter at the Nelson Gallery for
more than 25 years. Her primary role is to reproduce objects from
the museum's Burnap collection for the gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   The Burnap pieces, which came from England, are the type of
housewares brought to the colonies, Starr said. The collection is
one of the largest displays of 17th-century slipware in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   Slip, a coating used to decorate pottery, has the consistency of
heavy cream. For the White House ornament, Starr said, she
fashioned a covered wagon out of a type of red clay used by potters
200 years ago. She then coated it with slip _ ``slyppe,'' in the
Old English spelling _ with the kind of device she might use to
frost a cake.
</P>
<P>
   To decorate the ornament, she retreated to the past again, using
tools employed by 17th-century potters, such as a comb and a white
goose feather.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love the most about being an historical potter, what I
love most about when I walk through the museum doors, is knowing
that I'm part of eternity,'' Starr said. ``It just gives me the
greatest feeling. I'm part of those who have died, those who will
be coming. I'm part of a group of artists. When I walk into the
museum, it's like an old, very special smell that puts me in touch
with the past. It's like a perfume.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr grew up in Boston and attended art school there, in New
York and at the Kansas City Art Institute. While studying ceramics
at the Art Institute, she discovered slipware after her instructor
told her to find something in the nearby Nelson Gallery that she
wanted to reproduce. In the Burnap collection, she saw a plate with
a slip rendition of a mermaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with that mermaid,'' Starr said. ``I knew I had
found something in my life I knew as my destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually she found a home at the museum as well. From there
she has made her reputation as one of the country's foremost
practitioners of an Old World craft. Two of her pieces are in the
museum's permanent collection, and the Nelson Gallery and the
Smithsonian Institution's Renwick Gallery in Washington, which
specializes in American crafts, have asked her to create
commemorative plates.
</P>
<P>
   She also travels and gives workshops. She shares her skills as
far away as Japan and as close as the schoolhouse next door when
she invites her grandchildren's elementary classes at Pembroke Hill
School into her studio to make Christmas gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Starr will be at the White House with other artists to see their
work on display.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after receiving the letter, she still is in awe of
her unexpected good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the biggest year of my life,'' she said. ``I'm
just so grateful. But I don't take it to my head, because I realize
they are gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   And more lasting gifts than any she might find beneath a tree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
