<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-FIREFIGHTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAINS OF ALL BUT ONE FIREFIGHTER ARE RECOVERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON AND THOMAS GRILLO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER _ Exhausted but determined searchers retrieved two
more bodies Saturday from the rubble of a cold storage warehouse
where sixfeighters died in a raging fire on Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, the search continued for the body of the sole
remaining firefighter, Paul Brotherton, 41.
</P>
<P>
   Working around the clock and battling biting winds and frigid
temperatures, firefighters recovered the remains of 42-year-old
Lieutenant Thomas Spencer about 4 a.m. near a wall that borders
Interstate 290 and Grafton Street, officials said. Six hours later,
rescuers found the fifth victim, later identified as Jeremiah M.
Lucey, 38, in the same area.
</P>
<P>
   The search was halted temporarily just before noon when high
winds threatened the remaining walls of the brick building, said
distrit fire chief Walter Giard. Engineers were concerned that the
highwinds would cause the weakened walls to collapse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers continued clearing the site using heavy equipment as
searchers, dressed in black and yellow jackets, emerged from
sifting through piles of scorched beams and distorted metal with
their faces covered in sadness and soot. The search resumed later
in the afternoon when winds died down.
</P>
<P>
   ``My muscles ache and fatigue take its toll, but as soon as one
of us gets tired, there's another waiting to take our place,'' said
one firefighter, who declined to give his name. ``No matter how
long it takes, we'll be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, about 1,000 mourners packed Our Lady of Rosary
Church to attend the funeral for Timothy Jackson, 51, the first of
the six firefighters to be recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters wore black, yellow and red ribbons, symbolizing
courage and bravery, while members of Jackson's two motorcycle
clubs donned leather jackets and boots.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet sobs could be heard as Joh lligher, pastor of the church,
eulogized Jackson. A yellow firefighter's helmet was laid on the
casket, which was carried to and from the church on a firetruck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Friday at 6:13 p.m., time stopped in Worcester,'' said
Kelligher.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was described as a vivacious man who turned a life of
``hell into everyday heaven on Earth,'' said Diane Flynn
Pellegrino, Jackson's stepdaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was a Vietnam veteran who drove his 1997 Harley-Davidson
motorcycle to rallies in Washington, said friends.
</P>
<P>
   He liked nothing more than to sit on the deck of his Hopedale
home, watching the birds and drinking a cup of coffee with his wife
Mary, said Pellegrino.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife and stepdaughter, Jackson leaves sons Timothy,
Scott, and Knoel.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral for 34-year-old James F. Lyons III is scheduled for
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Also killed when teams of firefighters entered the burning
Worcester Cold Storage and Warehouse Co. building looking to see if
anyone was inside was Joseph McGuirk, 38, whose body was recovered
on Friday. Jackson's remains were pulled from the rubble last
Sunday. Lyons's body was recovered Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A homeless couple, Thomas S. Levesque, 37, and Julie Ann Barnes,
19, are accused of accidentally starting the blaze. The two pleaded
not guilty to charges of involuntary manslaughter and are being
held on $1 million cash bail. Prosecutors say the fire started in
the building after the couple knocked over a candle during a fight.
</P>
<P>
   During Saturday's funeral Mass, Kelligher said the site of the
blaze will symbolize the city's week of tragedy, but he said one
day it will serve as a symbol of pride for Worcester residents.
</P>
<P>
   Even as mourners began to gatherat the church for Jackson's
funeral, there were signs across the city of how the tragedy had
galvanized residents.
</P>
<P>
   Fire stations held car washes to help raise money for the
victim's families, signs along the Massachusetts Turnpike spelled
out condolences, and a billboard bearing the images of the six
firefighters towered above the fire scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
