<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
45,000 CIVILIANS STILL IN GROZNY AS EVACUATION DEADLINE PASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND DMITRY SHALGANOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALKHAN-YURT, Russia _ As Russia's deadline for civilians to
leave Grozny or face annihilation expired Saturday, a column of
trucks and buses pulled up to a makeshift checkpoint on the
battle-scarred road leading south from the besieged Chechen
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The column was there to transport to safety anyone taking
advantage of a new ``safe corridor'' opened by Russian forces
surrounding Grozny. The vehicles were also intended to underscore
Moscow's desire to clear Grozny of civilians before it unleashes an
assault on several thousand militants holed up in the war-ruined
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin sent its top civilian official for emergency
situations, Sergei Shoigu, to open the new escape route. A little
publicity never hurts _ Shoigu is also the leader of the main
pro-Kremlin party contesting next Sunday's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem _ there were no refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Shoigu waited for over an hour, but no one approached the two
armored cars perched on the road where he stood just outside
Grozny, even though the pro-Moscow Chechen administration estimates
that 45,000 civilians are still in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Their fate was unknown Saturday as Moscow gave mixed signals on
whether its forces planned to back up the leave-Grozny-or-die
ultimatum issued in thousands of leaflets dropped on the city last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Facing increasing concern at home and growing criticism abroad,
Moscow has tried to shift attention from the sinister tone of its
ultimatum to concern for civilians trapped in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no undue concern for the civilian population.
We will look after them ourselves,'' Russian news agencies quoted
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin as saying during a visit to the
central Asian republic of Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the people left in Grozny to accept Russian guarantees
will be difficult, as Russia's three-month campaign against
separatists in Chechnya has been marked by the military's seeming
lack of concern for civilians who get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   The latest testimony to that is what remains of the village of
Alkhan-Yurt, which was not so much captured as leveled by Russian
forces 10 days ago. Hardly a building remains standing. Market
stalls, gardens, and the local mosque are shattered ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the town told the New York-based Human Rights Watch
that the army had gone on a rampage after capturing the town on
Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The residents described looting and summary executions. People
inside Alkhan-Yurt, they said, are not allowed out of their houses
for most of the day. Anyone who protests is shot; residents
interviewed by Human Rights Watch in the neighboring Russian region
of Ingushetia said that 17 villagers had been killed since Russian
troops entered the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian troops in Alkhan-Yurt are killing civilians and
looting their property with what appears to be complete impunity,''
said Holly Cartner, executive director of the Europe and Central
Asia Division of Human Rights Watch. ``It's a shocking case of
Russian force's intentional violation of international law.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports of Russian attacks on civilians in Chechnya have been
common during the campaign to subdue the separatist republic. Not
all the reports have been confirmed, and there have been reports of
rebel attacks on civilians. But the main obstacle for refugees
seems to be the Russian habit of targeting everything that moves in
areas of fighting _ a tactic aimed at avoiding the heavy Russian
casualties that sapped popular support for Moscow's failed
1994-1996 campaign to subdue the separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Shoigu and other officials continued to insist that the warning
did not mean that Russia would not wait for all civilians to get
out even though the deadline passed. But the semi-official Interfax
news agency quoted Russian military officers in Chechnya as saying
that a ban on airstrikes apparently in effect for several days was
to expire Saturday and that Russian troops would resume air and
artillery strikes against the positions of ``bandits and
terrorists,'' Moscow's terms for the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The military issued a statement blaming separatist fighters in
Grozny for preventing civilians from leaving the capital, implying
that the rebels were trying to use noncombatants as human shields.
Shoigu himself said he thought civilians, many of whom have been
hiding in their cellars for days, might not have heard about the
new route.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees trickling out of Grozny via a northern route Friday
offered another version _ that they feared being fired on by
Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   As Shoigu waited, guarded by wary troops and a helicopter
gunship circling overhead, a battery of howitzers nearby unleashed
a salvo in the direction of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military commanders, meanwhile, said that they would
soon capture Grozny. Colonel General Valery Manilov, speaking in
Moscow, spoke of ``unconventional measures'' that would be used,
although he did not elaborate. Another Russian general, Vladimir
Shamanov, told reporters in Chechnya that he had orders to ``pound,
pound, pound'' the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insurgents will not meet the New Year in Grozny,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
