<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHER BACK ON BENCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ The look of disappointment on Derek Fisher's
face is clear, even if his words are diplomatic. For the second
time since February, he's earned a starting job, only to be
shuffled back to the Los Angeles Lakers bench.
</P>
<P>
   This time, at least, he could see it coming. Coach Phil Jackson
has a clear preference for big-guard tandems and he wants Kobe
Bryant _ who returned to the starting lineup Wednesday _ paired
with the experienced Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   That left the smaller, less-experienced Fisher as the odd man
out.
</P>
<P>
   He's getting used to the routine, though. Last season Fisher
opened as the starting point guard only to be replaced by Derek
Harper, but he reclaimed the job in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   He's taking the recent role change in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different'' playing in relief, Fisher said.
``I'm a guy, I like to set the tone more so than adjust to it. But
when you're part of a team, you have to be willing to make
adjustments and sacrifice, and this is part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The adjustment proved tough in his first game back on the bench.
Fisher shot 4 for 14 against the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But against the Vancouver Grizzlies on Saturday, Fisher settled
down to hit 3 of 7 shots and appeared more at ease as he teamed
with Rick Fox and Robert Horry in one of the Lakers' better bench
efforts of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert and Rick and I play well together. . . . The three of
us kind of play the game the same way _ good defenders, smart
players, have an understanding of the game, and I think that kind
of starts to blend together, it makes a nice combination,'' Fisher
said. ``As long as I know that's the way it's a going to be, I'm
cool. The thing is, we get compensated for playing basketball,
whether you start or come off the bench. Whatever the case may be,
it's your responsibility to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Jackson said the idea to place Travis Knight on
the injured list Friday came from Knight. The little-used forward
is trying to recover from a sprained right ankle that's dogged him
since Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to Gary (Vitti, the Lakers' trainer) and asked Gary to
recommend he go on the IR, because his ankle at this point hasn't
been able to get any strength and lift off of it,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves the Lakers with just one backup center, John Salley,
and one backup power forward, Robert Horry. Knight will travel with
the Lakers on their four-game trip to the East next week and will
be eligible to play by the third game, at Toronto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
