<HEADER>
A6243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CLINTON-FLA12-COX     12-11 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FLA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prosperous nation a result of Gore's input, Clinton says
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ In a raspy, hoarse voice, President Clinton
asked Florida Democrats on Saturday to back Vice President Al Gore,
who supported ``every tough decision that I ever had to make as
president.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nostalgic look back at the seven years of his presidency,
Clinton told the more than 2,300 delegates attending the state
Democratic convention here that he and Gore have helped America
reach a level of prosperity ``that I have never seen in my
lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they took office, Clinton said, society and the economy
were in disastrous shape. ``Don't let anybody forget it,'' he said.
``What a difference in seven years. We are ending the century on a
high note.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are hoping that a strong economy combined with
portraying Republicans as a party dominated by extremists and
special interests will be enough to help them overcome the enormous
setbacks they have had throughout Florida and the nation in recent
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans can have all the rhetoric they want,'' Clinton
said. ``Let people choose between their rhetoric and our record.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a shot at attempts in Florida to ban affirmative action,
an issue Democrats hope to use against the GOP, Clinton told the
cheering crowd, ``Don't give up on affirmative action. Go out there
and defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat wistfully, Clinton said, ``I can't run for anything
this year.'' Then he reminded delegates that in 1991 as a little
known candidate from Arkansas, ``you put my campaign on the map.''
Clinton won a straw ballot at the convention that year.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the supporters of former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley
came to the convention worried about reports that Bradley had
suffered Friday from a minor heart problem, known as atrial
fibrillation. Bradley will speak to the convention today.
</P>
<P>
   During an afternoon news conference in California on Saturday,
Bradley said his doctors told him that his occasional problems with
an irregular heart beat are not serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling great,'' Bradley said. ``No problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a nuisance, quite frankly,'' said Bradley, who
takes medication twice a day for the condition.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot at stake for Florida Democrats in the 2000
election. If the party fails to win control of either the House or
Senate, they will be at the mercy of Republican lawmakers who will
be creating new legislative districts after the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could mean that Democrats will be out of power for years if
that happens,'' said state Sen. Tom Rossin (D-West Palm Beach), who
will become Senate president in November if the party wins the six
seats it needs for control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The families in this state can't afford to let the Republicans
stay in power,'' said state Rep. Lois Frankel. ``We are disgusted
with the `For Sale' sign that has gone on the state House since
Republicans took over. If they control reapportionment, the state
will be up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Before going to the convention, Clinton met privately for about
45 minutes with Nelson Mandela, who is visiting Florida. Their
conversation was about world peace, said Clinton spokesman Barry
Toiv.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically filled each other in on what they've been doing
to promote peace in various parts of the world,'' Toiv said, adding
that Clinton spoke about the Middle East and Mandela talked about
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech at the convention, Clinton played a round of
golf and then traveled to Fort Lauderdale where he attended a
dinner to raise money for U.S. Rep. Alcee Hastings (D-Miramar).
Hastings, who flew on Air Force One with Clinton from Orlando to
Fort Lauderdale, is seeking a fifth term next year.
</P>
<P>
   In a rousing speech to the convention delegates, Hastings
scoffed at the notion that Democrats are in trouble because of
``Clinton fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you tired of low interest rates? Are you tired of
Democrats working like hell for a woman's right to choose?''
Hastings shouted. ``I'm sick and tired that Americans are still
being bombarded with distortions about the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ended his trip to Florida raising money in Miami for the
Democratic congressional and senate campaign committees. The money
will be used for candidates nationwide in the effort to wrest
control of Congress from the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
