<SLUG> BC-GORE-FLA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore blasts Bush record on protecting Florida Everglades
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Since Gov. Jeb Bush took office, decisions are
being made by the South Florida Water Management District that may
not help with restoring the Everglades, Vice President Al Gore said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about saving the Everglades,'' said Gore, who
then went on to question, without offering any specifics, whether
the water management district is acting independently or at the
behest of the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a couple of decisions by the majority of the
board that would have been different under the Lawton Chiles
team,'' Gore said during an interview after his speech to state
Democratic convention delegates. ``I don't fully understand why
they are getting off track a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 40 minute speech, he slammed Republicans, bragged about
being a grandfather and did a little stand-up comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Notably absent from his speech was any reference to his
political rival Bill Bradley, who is threatening to derail Gore's
campaign in New Hampshire and Iowa. Gore's only remark about the
former New Jersey senator was to wish him well on his return to the
campaign after a minor problem with his heart on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in his interview with reporters, Gore was more critical
of Bradley, saying he does not have the experience to keep the
economy moving forward. Gore also said that Bradley doesn't have a
good answer for how he would protect Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Gore, who began the campaign earlier this year
believing Bradley would not be a serious threat, has taken Bradley
to task on a host of issues. On Saturday, however, Gore decided to
spend his time going after Republicans instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is going to determine a great deal about who we
are as a people,'' said Gore, who warned that Republicans are
controlled by extreme elements in the party who want to get rid of
affirmative action and a woman's right to have an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think is going on in those closed door meetings
when they meet with Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson?'' asked Gore.
He said that when leaders of the religious right leave the room and
say they heard everything they wanted to hear, that is code that
Republicans have agreed to ``give the ultra right wing
fundamentalists control of the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd cheered as Gore said, ``I fought against the
Newt Gingrich Republican Congress when they came in.'' He said he
intends to continue that fight against extremists.
</P>
<P>
   He said it's up to Democrats to make sure that progress is
continued in winning more rights for women and minorities,
including making sure ``there is equal pay for equal work.''
</P>
<P>
   In a strong appeal to labor, Gore said, ``You need to know this.
I am pro-labor, pro-collective bargaining, pro-union.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he stepped into the middle of Florida's debate about
affirmative action and Californian Ward Connerly's attempt to amend
Florida's constitution so that affirmative action would be banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida doesn't need Ward Connerly,'' he said. ``And they
don't need any new ballot propositions or phony quota systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing Florida as ``a battleground next year,'' Gore said
the next president must be someone who cares about the state's
environmental needs. He promised to ``fight big polluters,'' and
said he would ban new offshore oil drilling and do whatever it
takes to protect the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that Texas Gov. George W. Bush has allowed his state to
become No. 1 in water, air and land pollution, Gore warned, ``We
don't want that kind of environmental policy nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said his first act as president would be to send back to
the Senate the nuclear test ban treaty that was rejected by
Republicans and ``demand that they ratify it.''
</P>
<P>
   After his speech Gore met privately with the black and Hispanic
caucuses. He also had private meetings with Florida Democratic
leaders. Some of them warned Gore not to take Florida for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a competitive state,'' said Steve Pajcic, a
Jacksonville attorney and former candidate for governor who is
supporting Bradley. ``I think you're going to see a very positive
reaction to Bradley when he speaks to the delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
