<HEADER>
A6245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NUTSNBOLTS15-COX     12-11 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTSNBOLTS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Necessary precautions to take with gas logs and fireplaces
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The use of gas fireplaces and gas logs has
increased so dramatically in recent years that sales of gas
fireplaces now easily outstrip sales of wood-burning fireplaces,
stoves, fireplace inserts and pellet stoves.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Hearth Product Association, sales of gas logs
and fireplaces grew from 149,000 units in in 1992 to nearly 800,000
in 1998. Sales of wood-burning appliances were at 541,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising, then, that problems associated with
gas-burning fireplaces are increasing, too.
</P>
<P>
   Properly manufactured gas-burning fireplaces are safe when used
as directed, but Jeff Cooper, an air pollution control specialist
with Montgomery County's environmental health division, said many
consumers don't use them as intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have detected elevated levels of carbon monoxide and carbon
dioxide in homes that are beyond what would be considered safe in
an industrial environment,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a gas fireplace or intend to get one to burn natural
gas, propane or liquefied gas, you should be aware of safety issues
associated with their use.
</P>
<P>
   THE THREE TYPES OF GAS FIREPLACES
</P>
<P>
   Modern gas-burning fireplace products imitate the look of a
natural wood fire much better than gas logs of a few years ago, but
not all gas-burning fireplaces are the same. The products come in
three types: vented, ventless and direct-vented.
</P>
<P>
   Vented gas fireplaces and gas logs produce the most
authentic-looking flames, but they are the least energy efficient.
These units must be used with a chimney or flue to carry combustion
products out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Vented gas logs can be used in the same fireplaces that once
were used to burn wood, said Tom Stegman, vice president of the
Patio and Hearth Shoppe in Centerville. He said the damper on the
fireplace must be left open when vented logs or fireplace inserts
are used.
</P>
<P>
   Air from the room in front of the fireplace is drawn in to feed
the flames as the gas burns in these units, and most of the heat
escapes through the chimney. But because the flames have a vigorous
air supply, they burn brightly and have the look of a natural wood
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Direct-vented fireplaces are self-enclosed boxes that draw their
air from outside the house through a small plastic pipe. They are
normally placed against outside walls in any room of the house, and
the vent pipe usually goes through the wall directly behind the
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The exhaust gases escape through the same vent pipe used to
supply air to the fire. Because the firebox is a closed system,
most of the energy released by burning the gas remains in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said direct-vented fireplaces are the best choice for
most consumers because of their safety and energy efficiency. But
they are not quite as energy efficient as ventless fireplaces, and
their flames are not as dramatic as vented fireplaces.
</P>
<P>
   The last type of fireplace is ventless. These units can be used
in any room because they are designed to burn gas without producing
large amounts of carbon monoxide or carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   Since no waste gases are vented outside, practically all the
heat a ventless fireplace produces stays in the room. The flames
may not be as impressive as vented models, however, and ventless
fireplaces raise some safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   TAKE PRECAUTIONS TO AVOID INJURY
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said the health department has been called to homes
frequently in recent years on complaints of headaches, dizziness,
respiratory irritations and difficulty concentrating in homes using
gas fireplaces.
</P>
<P>
   He said burning fuel always produces byproducts, but ventless
fireplaces are designed to burn their fuels as completely as
possible so potentially harmful byproducts are minimized.
</P>
<P>
   Stegman said ventless fireplaces are very safe, but when they
are used in airtight houses _ and most houses built in the past 10
years are fairly airtight _ they can cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   The small amount of carbon monoxide they produce may be able to
build up in a closed room. ``If you're concerned, then by all means
you should have a carbon-monoxide detector in the room with your
ventless fireplace,'' Stegman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is oxygen depletion. No fire burns without
consuming oxygen, and a ventless fireplace in a tightly closed room
could reduce the available oxygen in the air to dangerously low
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Stegman said ventless fireplaces are equipped with oxygen
depletion sensors that cut off the flames when the oxygen in a room
drops below a certain level.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said the manufacturers of ventless fireplaces suggest
that people using them crack a window in the room to bring in
oxygen and allow combustion byproduct gases to escape. ``But hardly
anybody does that,'' he said. ``It seems like you're defeating the
purpose of the fireplace if you've got a window open.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading the owner's manual and following its directions are
vital for anyone using a gas fireplace product of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have an owner's manual for your fireplace or gas
logs, do not use them until you can contact the manufacturer for
detailed operating instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Also take care when purchasing a gas-burning fireplace product.
Any product you buy should include a seal from the American Gas
Association indicating the product meets safety standards. Also
check with the retailer and your local government zoning department
to be sure the type of fireplace you're considering is allowed
where you live.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is sizing. The fireplace product you use
should not be too large or small for your home, and the retailer
should be able to help you decide what you need.
</P>
<P>
   A professional installer knows how to avoid some of the problems
associated with installing a fireplace incorrectly. Many gas
fireplaces and gas logs can be installed by a competent
do-it-yourselfer, but the extra cost of hiring someone with
experience may be a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
