<SLUG> BC-TENNIS-REGIS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Philbin helps tennis charity win a million
 &HT;    By Stephen Kiehl
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Ree-gis! Ree-gis! We want to be
millionaires, too!
</P>
<P>
   The autograph hounds hit on tart-tongued talk show host Regis
Philbin like a Rhodes scholar on an easy-money question Saturday at
the Chris Evert Pro-Celebrity Tennis Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin, host of ABC's hit ``Who Wants to Be A Millionaire'' has
played this charity tournament at the Delray Beach Tennis Center
before, but this year there's no pro or celebrity who can match his
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   He's huge. Bigger than Evert. Bigger than Jimmy Connors. Bigger
than Chevy Chase. Bigger _ maybe _ than former President George
Bush, who will play today.
</P>
<P>
   And the 3,500 fans who showed up got their fill of Philbin
during a doubles match he played with Chris Evert against his wife,
Joy, and Connors.
</P>
<P>
   In a matching blue shirt and shorts, Philbin stalked the clay
court, stoking the crowd, flinging his racket to the ground after
bad shots and pumping his fists after good ones. A few times, he
even got shots past five-time U.S. Open winner Connors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too much!'' he bragged. ``Honest to God, I'm too much!''
</P>
<P>
   After the match, which he and Evert won 6-5, Philbin recounted
the victory as he signed the glossy photos and magazine covers his
fans brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see me out there?'' he asked. ``I kicked Connors' ass.
I wasn't intimidated at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10th annual two-day tournament benefits Chris Evert
Charities Inc., which gives money to drug abuse programs and
children's programs in South Florida. In its first nine years, the
event has raised about $7.5 million. And organizers expect the take
this year to be the biggest ever _ about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Evert, who won 18 Grand Slam events during the peak of her
tennis career, lives in Boca Raton with her three children and
husband, Andy Mill. She plays an active role in organizing the
tournament every year and bringing in some of the top names in
tennis and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year Connors and John McEnroe have
participated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When friends call, you're happy to help them,'' Connors said,
praising Evert's philanthropy work. ``It's amazing what can be done
when you have the right name and you put your mind to it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his matchup with Philbin, Connors said he was ``shaken
but not stirred.'' And on Philbin's caliber of play: ``He's come a
long way, but he still has a way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the weekend's most anticipated matches will take place
today, when Bush and McEnroe square off against Evert and Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Staff researcher Holly Diaz contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
