<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ARE SORE WINNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Ron Harper's left quadriceps was imprinted
with Bryant Reeves' large kneecap. Shaquille O'Neal's knees ached
through 40 minutes of near-nonstop movement. And Glen Rice's
shooting only looked painful.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, then, that coach Phil Jackson didn't fret over
the Los Angeles Lakers' failure to put away the Vancouver Grizzlies
early on Saturday at G.M. Place. A win, any kind of win, was
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   And this one, a 106-94 victory, was even encouraging, achieved
through the relief work of Robert Horry, Rick Fox and Derek Fisher
as much as O'Neal, Rice or Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The bench trio combined for 20 of the Lakers' 36 fourth-quarter
points as the Lakers broke a late tie and pulled away for a
hard-earned road win. It was easily the Lakers' best second-unit
performance in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting on it,'' Harper said, ``like Christmas.
They finally showed up tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   With impeccable timing, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzlies, 4-16 but playing surprisingly well of late, were
positioned for the upset. They had the game tied at 75 with 9:33
remaining. But Fisher and Fox propelled an 8-0 run to pull away,
and Fox later hit a 3-pointer to make it a 10-point game by the
4:40 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bibby, who led the Grizzlies with 23 points, powered a
brief Grizzlies rally to cut the deficit to 91-88 with 2:25 to go,
but Rice, Horry and Bryant all made their free throws down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we played decent,'' said Horry, who had seven rebounds
and a season-high 11 points. ``We went to the boards, we played
good defense, we made a little run.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox also finished with 11 points, on 5-of-6 shooting. And Fisher
played steady defense and kept the second unit humming while
scoring six.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big relief for us,'' Jackson said of the bench play,
``because obviously road games are games that you play your
starters 35 minutes, maybe 40. For us to be able to sit Harp and
A.C. (Green) and Glen on the bench for that period of time helped
us a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly with back-to-back games _ the Lakers have a date
with the Detroit Pistons tonight at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone rested, of course. O'Neal played a routine 44
minutes to get his 30 points and 10 rebounds. Bryant, in his second
start of the season, played 39 minutes and did a little of
everything: 14 points, six rebounds, seven assists and a
career-high five blocked shots, with just two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Rice scored 22 points but labored to get there. He was 5 of 15
from the field, making up for it with a 12-for-13 performance at
the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, O'Neal complained of stiff knees and Harper limped on
a sore leg caused by a first-half collision with Reeves. He had to
ask out of the game early in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got tight,'' Harper said. ``Long year _ I didn't need to go
out there an try to kill myself.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal blocked three shots in the game but admitted his defense,
and the team's, has slipped a notch this week. Vancouver shot 46.9
percent and was able to capitalize on second efforts thanks Shareef
Abdur-Rahim's seven offensive rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that can be fixed,'' O'Neal said. ``A lot of
guys have colds. And my knees are kind of stiff today. . . . I was
a couple steps slow, but my homeboys helped me out today.''
</P>
<P>
   The cavalry was a little late in arriving. The Lakers trailed
50-49 at halftime and by as many as six points in the third
quarter. It wasn't until they scored 36 in the fourth that the
offense got untracked. Until then, they endured an assault from
Abdur-Rahim (19 points) and the Grizzlies backcourt of Bibby and
Michael Dickerson, who outscored Harper and Bryant 34-19.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a feisty young team and they played a rather good
game,'' Jackson said of the Grizzlies. ``I expected a game like
this. Vancouver's been playing real good basketball, they've been
sticking real close to teams. They're losing, but they're giving
them a run, they're competitive, they don't make a whole lot of
turnovers . . . and they have enough offensive weapons that they
could hold us at bay for awhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
