u a BC-NY-SCHOOLS-ATTEND-NYT     12-11 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-ATTEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY SCHOOLS SAID TO HAVE INFLATED ATTENDANCE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A commission that Gov. George Pataki appointed to
investigate possible corruption in the New York City school system
has found evidence of inflated student attendance figures at dozens
of high schools, state officials who have read the panel's
preliminary report said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance figures help determine how much state aid a school
receives, and state officials have long suspected that some New
York City schools inflate the numbers to get more money.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have read the report, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the investigation had found that some high schools
kept students on the attendance rolls even after they transferred
to private or parochial schools or moved out of state. One student
who died unexpectedly in the summer of 1998 was kept on his high
school's attendance rolls for the entire 1998-99 school year, the
officials said, even though the student's mother had informed the
school of his death.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they expected Pataki to disclose more details
about the investigation in a news conference this week. Pataki
convened the commission in January to check the reliability of the
attendance figures, which help determine how much state aid each
school receives. He also directed the commission to investigate
possible corruption and mismanagement at the city's School
Construction Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Neither investigation is finished, the officials said, but
Pataki is disclosing some preliminary findings this week because he
gave the commission an initial deadline of Dec. 1 to report back to
him. Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver and other Democrats have
criticized the commission as a waste of money _ Pataki has budgeted
$2.8 million for the commission in the current fiscal year _ and
questioned whether the investigations were necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Pam McDonnell, a spokeswoman for Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew,
said Saturday that she could not comment on the preliminary
findings because nobody at the Board of Education had seen them.
</P>
<P>
   The state officials refused Saturday to discuss whether Crew or
any Board of Education officials would be implicated in the
commission's findings. The preliminary findings come after a
scathing report last week by Edward F. Stancik, the special
investigator for New York City schools, which charged that 43
teachers, 2 principals and 2 paraprofessionals at 32 city schools
had been involved in cheating on standardized math and reading
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Crew fired three school aides and six teachers who did not have
tenure on Thursday after concluding that they had directed students
to cheat on standardized tests. Both Stancik's report and the state
commission's report come at a sensitive time for Crew, since the
Board of Education is considering whether to extend his contract
and he is weighing whether he even wants to remain on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki created the commission under the terms of the Moreland
Act of 1907, which grants the governor the authority to establish
panels with the power to subpoena witnesses and documents. He
appointed Roslynn R. Mauskopf, the state inspector general, to lead
the panel, which has a staff of about 30 lawyers, auditors and
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The state commission was originally seen as a swipe at Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani when Pataki convened it last winter. The two men
had a chilly relationship at the time, and Giuliani at first
criticized the commission as a waste of time and money. But since
then, Giuliani's relationship with Pataki has improved and his
relationship with Crew has deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   The state officials who had read the preliminary findings were
already pointing figures at the Board of Education Saturday, saying
that city education officials had dragged their heels in turning
over documents and insisted that board lawyers be present at state
investigators' interviews with school officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
