<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBACOLM-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WON'T BE SAME WITHOUT SIR CHARLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; The NBA lost one of its 50 greatest players this week but just
as sadly also lost its human reality-check.
</P>
<P>
   When Charles Barkley crumpled to the floor in Philadelphia after
the left quadriceps tendon tore away from his kneecap and ``rolled
up like a Venetian blind,'' according to Sixers president Pat
Croce, the NBA lost much more than a legend.
</P>
<P>
   It lost a real, thinking person. Not someone hidden behind
shades, cell phones or bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, like Magic Johnson, was part of that dying breed of
approachable superstars.
</P>
<P>
   He was refreshing, even if the public didn't always see this
side of him, because of the blaring headlines surrounding his
problems with fans.
</P>
<P>
   No one could light up a locker room like Barkley. He didn't
brood before games, like Penny Hardaway. Or try to declare himself
off-limits, like Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley held court. His presence was so commanding that when the
Rockets played the Lakers in the first round of the playoffs, the
crowd around his cubicle dwarfed then-teammate Scottie Pippen's,
just a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   He would talk to anyone. Ball boys. Reporters. Ushers. And if
you wanted an honest answer, he was your go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I weren't earning more than $3 million a year to dunk a
basketball,'' Barkley once said, ``most people on the street would
run in the other direction if they saw me coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was perhaps his most famous quote, regarding role
models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professional athletes should not be role models,'' he said.
``Hell, I know drug dealers who can dunk. Can drug dealers be role
models, too?''
</P>
<P>
   The irony was that Barkley was often a role model, going out of
his way to give little kids his shoes or other mementos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball doesn't owe me a thing. I owe basketball,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Try finding that type of response the next time the Knicks come
to town.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a reason Barkley became embroiled in feuds with
temperamental stars like Pippen and Philadelphia's Allen Iverson.
He didn't mind puncturing a bloated ego if someone wasn't pulling
their weight. He usually won these battles too, because few could
match him in verbal jousts.
</P>
<P>
   During his post-injury press conference, Barkley found time for
humor, noting he would be limited from certain activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf and sex are the only two things you can be bad at and
still have a blast doing them,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Always the king of the one-liners, even 'til the end.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's list of accomplishments is considerable: NBA player of
the year in 1993, an All-Star 11 times, a member of the All-NBA
first team five times, two Olympic gold medals and MVP of the 1991
All-Star game. He played 1,072 games, scored 23,755 points and
grabbed 12,545 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But he'll be missed nearly as much for his honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be 37 in a couple of months and I've never had a real
job,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hughes blues: The 76ers would love to unload point guard
Larry Hughes, who has been in coach Larry Brown's doghouse, but
Toronto pulled out of a deal that would have sent forward Tracy
McGrady.
</P>
<P>
   Raptors coach Butch Carter described Hughes as being ``one of
the top 10 young players in the league,'' but said that in the
6-foot-8 McGrady, ``we have the top 20-year-old in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Philly then called New Jersey and asked for guard Kerry Kittles,
but the Nets nixed the deal because of salary-cap complications.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, after both trades fell through, Brown said, ``We're
absolutely not shopping Larry Hughes.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Company man: Bulls star Toni Kukoc was asked if he trusted
team vice president Jerry Krause and replied, ``That's a question
I'm not going to answer to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc was then asked if Krause had ever made a promise and then
broken it? ``Uh, I'm not going to tell you that one, either,''
Kukoc said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Krause heard about this and brought out his brass
knuckles. Kukoc later called a reporter and asked for a chance to
respond to the questions again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. I trust Jerry Krause,'' Kukoc said. ``Why not? He's never
done anything wrong to me.'' As for the second question, Kukoc
said, ``No, Jerry Krause has not made any promises to me that he
didn't keep. Everything that he promised me, he has done what he
said he would do.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Latest critic: Magic Johnson was in Cleveland this week and
made the mistake of watching the Cavaliers play the hapless Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Bulls management) had a master plan and the master
plan was destroyed,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Pack your bags: Washington Wizards forward Tracy Murray is
prepared for his departure as he becomes more and more irrelevant
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worn out my welcome here,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   __ First fired? Golden State coach P.J. Carlesimo is the
likeliest candidate to be the first coach relieved of his duties.
Warriors owners have reportedly told general manager Garry St. Jean
they are prepared to fire Carlesimo and make him the coach for the
remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   They are also prepared to fire St. Jean if he can't turn things
around. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOP 10 AND NO. 29 &QL; 
1. Lakers (15-5) &QL; 
Maybe Charlotte will take back Rice for Jones, Campbell? &QL; 
2. Miami (15-4) &QL; 
Pat Riley abandons plan to acquire a point guard _ this week. &QL; 
3. San Antonio (15-6) &QL; 
NBA champs had 6,000 empty seats for game with Grizzlies. &QL; 
4. Portland (16-5) &QL; 
Hitting a rut, time for Pippen to disappear. &QL; 
5. Sacramento (12-5) &QL; 
If they only played home games, NBA finals would be a lock. &QL; 
