u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-JEFFERSO     12-11 1919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-JEFFERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFFERSON LOSS WOULD CREATE CHARACTER VOID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shawn Jefferson was walking down the steps toward the locker
room when Patriots vice president of personnel Bobby Grier
intercepted him, put his arm around him, and said, ``I want you
back here next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are no different from other teams that want to
retain their ``character'' players, hoping to appeal to their sense
of being wanted and needed. These players are rare in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Teams try to look for a hometown discount with these players but
seldom get it. The Patriots didn't get it with Willie McGinest or
Ted Johnson or Ty Law. They probably got a bit of a break with
Bruce Armstrong, who stayed in New England rather than take more
money to go to New York with Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are already $5.6 million over the salary cap for
next year and that doesn't include free agents such as Jefferson,
Troy Brown, Tedy Bruschi, Steve Israel, and Chris Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, like Brown, is a hard receiver to fit into a money
slot. Neither is considered a No. 1 receiver and therefore ill not
command the $5 million-$6 million per year that Antonio Freeman and
Herman Moore make. Brown would like to be considered at least in
the No. 2 slot. Jefferson, who makes $1.8 million this year and
leads the league in receiving average (18.4 yards) f e second
straight year, is a No. 2 receiver, but given his many
contributions to the team on the field and off, he is more like a
1A. He's one of those players who is more valuable to the team he's
with than he would be to another team.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Jefferson is not expecting to be a Patriot when the
2000 season rolls around. It's not that he doesn't want to be; in
fact, he said he will make New England his home either way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here four years, we've got younger guys,'' said
Jefferson. ``I can't speak for anybody else, but I don't think I'll
be here. There are a lot of guys they have to re-sign. I'm a
realist. That's all. I'd like to be back, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   There are teams, including the Cleveland Browns, New York Jets,
and New York Giants, that would love to sign Jefferson. Cleveland
can give Jefferson what he deserves, which is probably twice as
much as he currently makes. Only the Baltimore Ravens have a better
overall cap situation than the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   While the Patriots feel they can replace Jefferson on the field
with Tony Simmons (with Vincent Brisby in the wings), Jefferson's
presence in the locker room is huge.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Jefferson will be like losing Sam Gash or Dave Meggett.
Jefferson does the housecleaning for Pete Carroll, just as Gash and
Meggett did for Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   How much is that worth?
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson is about to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly handshakes by Grier and appreciation offered by
Carroll and owner Bob Kraft have made Jefferson feel, at the very
least, that the team appreciates what he does on a day-to-day basis
in terms of setting a positive example.
</P>
<P>
   However, no contract has er been discussed with Jefferson. The
Patriots may be waiting until the season ends, but they might be
wise to do what they've done with Lawyer Milloy: lay the
groundwork. At least begin some form of negotiations, especially
with the stadium zoning now approved.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson may fall between the Darnay Scott/Johnnie Morton
level, which is about $3 million a year, and Yancey Thigpen's $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   If he does leave New England, he will leave on good terms, with
fond memories and a feeling that he helped the younger receivers.
He will leave knowing he did everything he could to bring the
Patriots together, to get Terry Glenn on the right track, to offer
common sense when none seemed to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Last week before the Dallas game, Jefferson rounded up the
receivers after having a one-on-one with Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (Bledsoe) to tell me what's up so I can be the
mouthpiece and relate it to the other guys,'' said Jefferson. ``We
had a good talk. I went back to the guys and I told them: `We're
going through tough times and nobody can determine the outcome of a
game except for us and the quarterback. We need to make plays. He's
having a little trouble right now so we have to make plays for him.
We have to make tough catches. We have to make them when the ball
is behind us or wherever it's thrown.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson would leave here with a growing appreciation for
Carroll and the feeling that the coach got a bad shake in this
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak for every one of my teammates when I say we're not
quitting on Pete,'' said Jefferson. ``We all respect Pete. Pete is
a damned good coach. Pete don't go out there and make the wrong
reads, mental mistake or fumble the ball. The responsibility lies
with the guys on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me when I hear people blaming Pete. Start blaming
players. Hold the players accountable. Hold me accountable if I'm
not getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The older Jefferson gets _ he's 30 and in his ninth year _ the
more he feels he needs to add more leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to do more,'' he said. ``Each year I'll try to do
more. Whether I'm here or not next year, they need me here now. If
I'm not here next year, hopefully Tony and Sean Morey will have
seen something in me they can learn from. I know I've given those
young guys and this team everything I have.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've learned is, it's not about what you've done. The
league has become where you have to fit under the cap. If you can
find a younger guy to do what I can do, you do it. If that's the
decision, then I'm a big boy. I can still run. I'm in great shape.
I can play another five years at this level. I pride myself in
woring hard. I'll always do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I see guys out there with stats. They also get more
opportunities. If I was getting the opportunities those guys are,
my stats would be higher. That's not what motivates me. What I care
about is what can I do to help this team win.''
</P>
<P>
   What is that worth?
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, it cannot be figured on a computer or calculator.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes this decision so tough.
</P>
<P>
   The over/under line
</P>
<P>
   Which AFC East team is in the best shape to make moves in the
offseason? Indianapolis, of course. According to the latest
management figures obtaine by the Globe, the Colts are $9 million
under the salary cap for 2000. But the figures are sed on this
year's cap, which should increase by almost $5 million next season,
giving the Colts about $14 million to work with. The second-best
situation is Miami, which is $3.15 million under. Teams over the
cap are the Patriots ($5.6 million), the Jets ($9.3 million), and
the Bills (a whopping $17.5 million). The Patriots' situation isn't
dire, but they will have to let a player or two go if they're going
to attempt to sign a free agent . . . If the Patriots drop some
payroll, they might go all-out for Jon Runyan, the Tennessee
Titans' talented right tackle, who will be an unrestricted free
agent. On the defensive side the Patriots would have to look at
free agent tackle Sam Adams of the Seahawks. Adams's father, Sam,
was a guard for the Patriots from 1972-80 . . . The Patriots have
sold about half of their 80 luxury boxes for the new stadium; the
6,000 stadium club seats will likely be snapped up quickly.
Therefore, that won't be a big issue in whether they retain Carroll
. . . From the ``Where are They Now'' file: Former Patriots wide
receiver Hart Lee Dykes is running a trucking company in Houston .
. . It's odd that, with so many former players living in the area,
the Patriots don't use them as coaches. Even if they're not hired
full time, what's wrong with utilizing Steve Grogan, Steve Nelson,
Fred Smerlas, Ronnie Lippett, Steve DeOssie, John Hannah, Pete
Brock, Tim Fox, etc., in training camp or for special instruction?
It's a different sport with a different set of rules, but the Red
Sox have always used Ted Williams, Carl Yastrzemski, Bobby Doerr,
Dwight Evans, and now Carlton Fisk as instructors . . . Desmond
Howard, whom we know in the parts as the man who ruined th
Patriots' Super Bowl hopes, was cut by the Packers for the second
time in his career because he didn't practice enough. He signed
with Detroit, and in his first game he ran a punt back 68 yards for
a touchdown . . . Thurman Thomas is set to return to the Bills as a
third-down back, which means Antowain Smith and Jonathan Linton
will share duties on first and second downs . . . Agent Ray
Anderson thi one of his clients, Minnesota offensive coordinator
Ray Sherman, has taken heat for the ``system'' he had in Pittsburgh
now that the Steelers have gone through bad times. ``Ray could be
saying a lot about that situation but he won't,'' said Anderson.
``He's too classy a guy. It's just one of those things where you
blame the coordinator when something goes wrong. It's done all over
the league.'' Certainly he doesn't mean in New England? . . . The
same kind of mean-spiritedness that's often directed at Carroll
lives in the hearts of Steeler fans for Bill Cowher. Cowher told
the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, ``People say things that sometimes you
kind of bite your tongue and you wonder why they say them and where
they come from. I guess you have to sit down and appreciate the
fact that when you're in the public eye, people can say whatever
they want with no repercussions, with no feelings that you have a
wife and children and that you're trying to live a life of
normalcy, too.'' Those same Carroll bashers speak of wanting Cowher
to coach in New England. My advice to Cowher: Don't even think
about it. It's worse here. Much worse . . . Faced with a cap
overload of $24 million for next season, the 49ers are making plans
to restructure rry Rice's contract. Rice, 37, was scheduled to earn
$2.25 million next season, but his cap number was $5.49 million . .
. Denver offensive coordinator Gary Kubiak is rumored to be going
to either Houston or New England. Kubiak has been in three Super
Bowls and has 10 playoff wins and one loss on his resume. Despite
``inside'' information by national types, the Patriots think the
reports are ludicrous. Unless Kraft is being disingenuous
concerning his public support for Carroll _ which would be
uncharacteristic of the Ptriots' owner _ then the reports are trash
. . . Dan Reeves has been a successful coach but he may go down in
history as the only one who twice went from a Super Bowl appearance
to a five-win (or worse) season. In 1990, the Broncos went 5-11
after a Super Bowl appearance. This season, Reeves's Falcons are
3-9 . . . Bo Jackson has purchased a Birmingham, Ala., franchise in
the Spring Football League, an eight-team league that begins in
March with a 12-game season. The league has franchises in Canton,
Ohio; Houston; Jackson, Miss.; Los Angeles; Miami; San Antonio; and
Washington, D.C. It will be used as a ``developmental league'' for
the NFL, though the NFL has no formal affiliation with it. Also in
the spring league's ownership loop are former NFL stars Eric
Dickerson and Tony Dorsett . . . We write about players' fights and
transgressions, so we'll write about what they do that's good and
honorable, too. Max Lane and Bledsoe collecting money from
teammates for the Worcester firefighters' families was a wonderful
thing, as was Ben Coates donating thousands of dollars for the Ben
Coates Room at Hasbro Children's Hospital in Providn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
