<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6346 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-CHARGERS-LEAF-BOS     12-11 2595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHARGERS-LEAF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF-FIELD PROBLEMS DON'T REFLECT WELL ON LEAF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by wor Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The mere mention of the name understandably might
cause him to cringe even more than the torn right shoulder labrum
almost five months ago that turned his would-be season of
redemption into a second straight eternity in purgatory. ut Ryan
Leaf was nobly diplomatic _ or at least as noble and diplomatic as
Ryan Leaf can be.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside the San Diego Chargers' training complex
Thursday, the second-year non-quarterback was asked whether he felt
an extra burden because of the breathtaking success of the
Indianapolis Colts' Peyton Manning, with whom Leaf formed a
celestial 1-2 punch at the head of the 1998 National Football
League college draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Leaf replied without hesitation. ``I wish him
the best.'' Pause. Impish grin. ``Unless we're playing them. Then I
hope he dies like a dog on the field.'' Pause. Impish grin. ``Other
than that, I wish him the best.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an ironic season's greeting, for being a canine corpse
would constitute a professional resurrection for Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Considered virtually inseparable in talent and promise on draft
day some 20 months ago, Tennessee's Manning and Washington State's
Leaf have followed slightly divergent paths since then. In a
scenario a fabulist couldn't concoct, Manning has been the ultimate
can't-miss prospect. In a nightmare beyond the devil's imagination,
Leaf has been a complete can't.
</P>
<P>
   So Manning will continue to pad his resume in Indianapolis when
he faces the Patriots as the Colts close in on what had been the
unthinkable: theAC ast championship. Meanwhile, fresh from a
four-game suspension for cursing out general manager Bobby
Beathard, Leaf will try to forget his dossier as he stands on the
sideline in Seattle, the aptly designated ``disaster quarterback''
for the second week in a row, as the Chargers close in on the
unbearable: a 5-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   And to think there was grave doubt that the Colts had chosen
correctly in April 1998, while Beathard was hailed for pulling off
a personnel coup when he sent wide receiver/kick returner Eric
Metcalf, linebacker Patrick Sapp, plus two firsts and a
second-round draft choice to Arizona to obtain the No. 2 pick _
whichever quarterback Indianapolis didn't take. At least that's the
way San Diego's ebullient first-year coach, Mike Riley, chooses to
interpret it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know (Colts president) Bill Polian,'' said Riley, ``and I
believe him when he says it was a tossup who they'd take right to
the very end.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, the early returns would cause Leaf supportes to throw up.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf had an ignominious rookie season, as he lost his starting
job after nine games, having compiled a 3-6 record, while one head
coach, Kevin Gilbride, got fired and another, interim successor
June Jones, decided he'd prefer a more tranquil setting at the
University of Hawaii. Manning actually compiled a worse record _
3-13 _ and was outpassed in his lone encounter with Leaf, 160 yards
to 137, though the Colts won the battle of the prodigies, 17-12,
Oct. 4. But Manning took every snap in 1998 while establishing
rookie standards for touchdown passes and yardage. And this year he
has merely burnished his image as the All-American success story.
Leaf hasn't played since last Dec. 13, when he established rocky
standards for ineptitude by firing two interceptions in relief of
his illustrious successor, Craig Whelihan, putting the finishing
touches on a two-TD, 15-pickoff NFL introduction. This year he has
merely tarnished his image as a one-man police blotter.
</P>
<P>
   True, he shouldn't be condemned for having suffered an
unfortunate injury. And it's equally true, as Riley maintained last
week, that ``the comparison (to Manning) is unique, but it's out
there because it was such a focal point. Manning would have been
extraordinary any year. The other point is that guys develop in
different stages. Look how long it took Brett Favre.''
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps Leaf, who Wednesday bemoaned the fact that ``I'm so
used to being superhuman, it's tough not to have full arm
strength,'' will blossom into the caliber of rifleman that was
envisioned after he led Washington State from the depths of the
Pacific-10 to the Rose Bowl in his junior season. His college
coach, Mike Price, who previously tutored a quarterback named Drew
Bledsoe, certainly is a believer: ``I'm a big Ryan Leaf fan. I
think he's going to do just fine. I don't think it's all over yet.
He's going to get through the tough times.''
</P>
<P>
   Litany of controversy
</P>
<P>
   It's those tough times off the field that keep haunting Leaf,
that he keeps bringing on himself, that magnify his on-field
failures _ and that nobody in Chargers management is willing to
discuss. But maturity must be factored into the development to
which Riley refers, and in that regard, Leaf has been a poster boy
for arrested aolescence.
</P>
<P>
   So even as he and his ologists look to a fingers-crossed rather
than star-crossed future _ now that medical clearance has been
given, in fact, Riley hopes to use him before the year is out,
though probably only for a cameo _ let us count the errors of
Leaf's ways.
</P>
<P>
   With the draft looming last year and the 1-2 sweepstakes still
too close to call, Leaf followed up his Rose Bowl glory by putting
20 pounds on his 6-foot-5-inch frame, tilting the scales at 261.
</P>
<P>
   During the NFL scouting combine in February, he skipped a
meeting with the two men who would make the top pick, Polian and
Colts coach Jim Mora.
</P>
<P>
   After his first pro loss, a 23-7 decision at Kansas City, he
screamed at a cameraman he believed was infringing on his locker
space.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, when a San Diego reporter detailed the incident in
print, Leaf went profanely ballistic on him. This time the cameras
were whirring instead of merely blocking his way, and the tirade
was featured on television screens nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Benched in the fourth quarter the following week after throwing
four interceptions in a 34-16 loss to the Giants, he was booed by
the home fans at Qualcomm Stadium when a Make-A-Wish Foundation
public service announcement featuring him appeared on the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   During the Chargers' bye week at the end of October, he returned
to Washington State to make a $200,000 donation, half of it in the
name of former Cougars and NFL quarterback Mark Rypien's recently
deceased son. This good deed was overshadowed by reports of boorish
and belligerent behavior in watering spots on and around the
Pullman campus _ reports that both Leaf and Price, who says he
questioned several witnesses, roundlyeny, claiming the rowdies were
members of Leaf's entourage. Still, that served as the enduring
image of his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   That season ended for all intents and purposes when he was
benched a week later in the wake of a 27-10 thrashing at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   All of which was a mere warmup for this year's travails, which
began when Leaf took an unappreciated hiatus from a June minicamp
to play in a charity golf tournament, then jammed his shoulder the
day he returned when he fell on a fumble resulting from a botched
handoff.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a half-hour into his first offcial training camp
workout in July, he suffered the torn labrum while throwing a deep
pass. Pegged as the third-string QB behind retreads Jim Harbaugh
and Erik Kramer, Leaf hoped it was just a sprain. But surgery was
deemed necessary, reducing him almost to tears when he met the
media two hours after receiving the diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop him from having to be restrained when he
confronted a heckler later in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Before an exhibition game against Miami, he informed Riley that
he would request a trade if the Chargers tried to place him on the
injured reserve list, which would have rendered him ineligible for
the season. He wound up being fined $10,000 after that game for
refusing to wear the team-issued Adidas jersey _ heresy to Nike
client Leaf _ on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   There were as many alibis as there were transgressions, promises
from Leaf and his supporters that the sideshows, or perceived
sideshows, were isolated mistakes and wouldn't be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   But there could be no bailing out, no pointing fingers
elsewhere, when a disagreement over a rehabilitation leg exercise
turnedhdeously ugly Nov. 1. To that point, Leaf had been a model
citizen since training camp. But when he claimed a doctor had told
him doing the exercise might damage his shoulder and the doctor
denied it, strength coach John Hastings, who had been overseeing
his rehab, confronted Leaf. The patient responded with an
ear-splitting harangue, and when Beathard was called in to
intervene, Leaf began dropping expletives on him, too. The toxic
exchange spilled out into the hallway, where Riley and several
players witnessed the fallout before defensive backs Michael Dumas
and Scott Turner interceded, Turner going so far as to walk Leaf
away from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, Leaf was suspended for four weeks and fined
an additional week's pay _ a total of $73,530 in lost salary. Leaf
spent one Saturday morning of his enforced hiatus playing flag
football in a local park _ technically a breach of contract because
such activity is prohibited without club permission. Later the San
Diego Union-Tribune reported that Leaf told two people in a Kansas
City bar he hated Beathard and would fire Leigh Steinberg (who did
not return calls from the Globe) unless the agent arranged a quick
trade.
</P>
<P>
   And in the most bizarre truce in the history of conflict, armed
or otherwise, Leaf celebrated his return to the team by filing a
grievance with the players' union, claiming the fine had been
excessive. The Chargers responded by filing a grievance with the
NFL Management Council seeking to withhold the final $2.95 million
installment, due next March, of the $11.25 million signing bonus
Leaf received when he agreed to a five-year, $31.25 million
contract. The antagonists finally reace an equally illogical
settlement: The grievances were withdrawn and a year was added to
Leaf's contract, which he now can't escape until after the 2001
season if he chooses to void the final two years.
</P>
<P>
   As we peer through the looking glass, it only makes sense that
Leaf would put this spin on the mishmash: ``The bottom line is it
puts me here two more years. That's what I'm ecstatic about.''
</P>
<P>
   Quest for respect
</P>
<P>
   He has been back in good graces _ as good as they can get,
anyway _ since the ban expired Nov. 29, when Leaf got up at a team
meeting and apologized, made amends privately with Beathard, and
told reporters his behavior toward the boss had been inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   That's all Leaf and the other principals will say about the
past. Leaf will talk only about the future, as vague as that may
be; while Riley vows he'll see action, the quarterback isn't so
sure, though he maintained last week, ``Just being back is the
great part. Football is the big issue for me. It's been almost a
year away. This year's basically been a washout. I think that's why
they wanted the extra year.''
</P>
<P>
   The washout certainly hasn't lacked for notoriety, which Leaf
believes is harder on his family than on him: ``They don't have the
shell I do.''
</P>
<P>
   He may need it to regain _ or in some cases gain _ the respect
of his teammates, who, after all, have heard this tune before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's trying really hard, working hard, to make sure he
does the right thing,'' said offensive tackle John Jackson. ``But
he still has a long way to go. He has to prove it's not just one
day but every day. He still has to prove himself. It's easy to tell
people what they want to herYou have to let them see it.''
</P>
<P>
   And linebacker Junior Seau, the heart and soul of the Chargers,
hardly offers an endorsement while trying to stay noncommittal: ``I
really haven't paid attention to the guy. We have two quarterbacks,
quarterbacks who are going to participate in games. The fact is, he
hasn't been part of the package the whole year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, others openly root for Leaf, even while expressing
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody welcomed the man back,'' said wide receiver Mikhael
Ricks, one of Leaf's friends and confidants on the team. ``I think
he realized the role he has to play on this team.Hopefully, he can
turn it around. He's been through tough times that led to some
teammates being against him. Now everybody is supporting him,
helping him be a better team player.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, the peacemaker Nov. 1, made an extraordinary goodwill
gesture in that regard. A devout Christian, he hosted a Bible study
group three weeks ago at his apartment complex. It included the
ministers of his parish, Shoreline Christian Church; 10-12
teammates who are group regulars; their wives _ and Leaf, who had
accepted Turner's invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chance to minister to Ryan,'' said Turner. ``It was
good not only for us to see Ryan but for him to see that God has a
real direction for him. It was a time for him to come and be
nurtured in faith. I don't think anything radical has happened so
far. I think there will be a transformation, and like any
transformation, it takes time. He knows it's time for him to move
forward, not only to forget what happened but to make sure it
doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who began last season as Leaf's quarterback coach, has't
altered his initial opinion that his former pupil can be ``a
big-time player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he showed in the first part of his rookie year that he
can play in the NFL,'' said the Hawaii coach. ``He's just got to
get in the right surroundings, do some soul-searching, put his
problems behind him. Ultimately, the only thing that matters is
on-field performance. If a player performs on the field, he's going
to rally his teammates. If he doesn't, he's just not going to get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Placekicker John Carney has noticed positive signs since Leaf's
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a guy eager to work, get back in the mix,'' said Carney.
``He seems hungry for competition. Certainly, all are positive
aspects of his comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   Carney also believes that deep down, Leaf doesn't _ and
shouldn't _ shy away from the implicit competition with Manning:
``It's natural for an athlete to rate himself or judge himself
according to his peers' performance. I know I do. I think it's
natural for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Price, who minimizes Leaf's behavior with the exception of the
Beathard incident, draws a different frame of reference _ with
Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bledsoe was always steady _ mmmmmm,'' said the Washington
State coach. ``He was like, `If we win, we win; if we don't, we
don't. If I get sacked, I'm going to keep going.' It wasn't that he
didn't want to win or wasn't fiery. He just kept it to himself
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan is different. He has a burning desire to be the best.
It's like that plant in `Little Shop of Horrors': `Feed me,
Seymour, feed me.' I'd be like, `Goddamn it, can't we go home?'
`No, I want to watch another (game) film.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan's much more volatile than Drew. He wears hiheart on his
sleeve. He'll tell you what's on his mind, and it's ot always what
you want to hear. By the same token, you can do the same with him.
I always thought that was a good thing. The people close to him
really like Ryan. He's more like a roller coaster _ he's up, he's
down; he's up, he's down. I'd try to smooth out the valleys.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have worked in college, but so far in the NFL, the Ryan
Leaf roller coaster is stuck in an abyss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 2209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
