<HEADER>
A6347 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SPT-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     12-11 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR YEAR-END ACCOUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You are at home one spring and your phone rings. You answer and
an executive from a professional sports team is on the line. He
offers you a five-year, $30 million deal to be the coach and/or
general manager of his team. You can be the next Pitino or Wallace,
Duquette or Williams, Carroll or Grier, Sinden or Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Can you handle the job?
</P>
<P>
   Predictable answer: Of course. Realistic answer: No chance. And
even if you did accept, I say you'd be submitting your resignation
soon.
</P>
<P>
   December is the year-in-review month in pro spt That means you
can be a terrific football coach who relaxes by sewing intricate
defensive formations into your socks, but in December a reporter
who thinks a two-deep zone is a personal pan pizza can say you had
a terrible year and call for your job. Next thing you know, the
guys at the cleaners are doing the same thing and your favorite
doctor now thinks you're an idiot for calling that sweep on fourth
and goal from the 2.
</P>
<P>
   There is criticism of your dumb draft choices, inane statements,
and sorry game plans. One newspaper editorializes that you should
be given an immediate police escort to the airport. Another says
your assistants should be fired. A national television commentator
says you've got a swagger _ a Fred Rogers/Al Gore swagger.
Basically, according to the December evaluators, you're a joke.
</P>
<P>
   The Year in Review has become a standard in pro sports. Imagine
if we were all given similar reviews based on our work the previous
12 months. Artists, truck drivers, financial analysts, and cooks
throughout New England would be able to offer their opinions on
whether you should be dismissed or not.
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you, that idea makes the Holley Lama very nervous. I
might be unemployed if Pete Carroll, Rick Pitino, Dan Duquette, and
Harry Sinden criticized me with the same vigor that I have
criticized them. If Carroll thinks he has it bad now, I'd be
routing him in the criticism-absorbed department if my 1999 report
card were ever released. Well, now that I think of it, here are
some excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   --January (writing about Michael Jordan reviving the NBA):
``Jordan's nature is to revive all things askew. But the task is
too big for even he.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. The are some brave people who edit my stories, but I was
clever enough to slip that grammatical error by them. Him. It was
my mistake. Why did I write it? That would be like the Patriots
having a choice etween Chris Canty and Sam Madison and happily
choosing Canty.
</P>
<P>
   --February/March: Some individual tutoring might be in order.
What a brutal stretch. I say the Houston Rockets will win the NBA
title. Right state, wrong city (San Antonio won it). Still feeling
good about myself, I remind Duquette that his team will be
fortunate to win 80 games (the Red Sox won 94). Obviously
encouraged by my success, I write that George Steinbrenner is crazy
for destroying the chemistry of the Yankees with his trade for
Roger Clemens (the Yankees win the World Series).
</P>
<P>
   My predictions were wildly off, but Pitino seemed to have a
clue: ``We will make the playoffs next season. Come July 1, I'm
going to make the changes _ the right changes _ it takes for us to
be a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   --April/May: This may register as the remark that triggers my
demotion to special teams coach. Before he NFL draft, I criticized
the silly Indianapolis Colts for trading their Pro Bowl running
back, Marshall Faulk. In fact, I think I said the trade to the Rams
was ``stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts traded Faulk to make room for a running back named
Edgerrin James. You may have heard of him. He is the leading
candidate for AFC Offensive Rookie of the Year. He is a member of
the AFC East-leading, 10-2 Colts. Now, I'm not saying I predicted
James would be a bust. In fact, I raved about him and said I could
envision him in the Patriots backfield (e team drafted center
Damien Woody).
</P>
<P>
   --June/July: At least I passed my take-home, open-book test. ``I
think all the (trade discussions) of Ron Mercer will eventually
result in Mercer playing somewhere else next season.'' Not being
able to contain myself, I wrote that Sinden should throw in an
extra million to end the Byron Dafoe holdout. I told him he would
have to do that if he wanted to have a good team. A few months
later, Dafoe and his agent parted ways and Sinden got the deal he
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   --August: Given Major League Baseball's awful pitching and
inconsistent strike zone, I wrote that we should not hold the
single-season home run record as something sacred. I stand by that
comment, but the problem is I was convinced Sammy Sosa would break
Mark McGwire's record of 70 in 1998. He didn't. (I also said that
``Blonde on Blonde'' is Bob Dylan's best CD;I stand by that, too.)
</P>
<P>
   --September: A month in need of a split screen. On one side of
it, I am endorsing the Michael Bishop campaign. I suggest using him
as some newfangled, lightweight H-back. I do not endorse taking
Drew Bledsoe out of the game. Ever. I say Bishop should be used for
8-10 plays per game. The Patriots are not going to use Bishop (am I
allowed to say that's a mistake?).
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the split screen, I am doing the Bruiser
Flint thing. I am taking myself out of the game. I am suspending
myself from making predictions.
</P>
<P>
   --October/November: You have to give me my props: No one is
better at riding shotgun on the bandwagon. In fact, I equipped the
wagon with some woofers and Bose speakers for my listening
enjoyment. I predicted the Red Sox would go seven games wih the
Yankees and head to the World Series. The Red Sox did not win the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   --December: Doing all right so far. But there are still 19 days
left in the month. Who said Carroll should be fired? Not me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
