<HEADLINE>
REDS BACK OFF JUNIOR CIRCUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ News item: Cincinnati Reds general manager Jim
Bowden, after a meeting Saturday with Seattle Mariners GM Pat
Gillick, calls a press conference to announce that the Reds are
abandoning their attempts to trade for Ken Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no chance at all. Zero,'' Bowden said. ``We have a
better chnc of bringing Goofy back than Griffey.''
</P>
<P>
   What it all means: Maybe less than it seems. Yes, the Griffey
deal is dead this weekend, with the Mariners' insistence that the
Reds include Pokey Reese as part of any package the deal-breaker.
Reds shortstop Barry Larkin will be 36 next spring, and the
nine-time All-Star is nearing the end of his marvelous career. The
Reds are adamant about keeping the 26-year-old Reese, who came up
as a shortstop and may return there when Larkin goes.
</P>
<P>
   But as one major league executive said minutes after Bowden
called the Griffey talks DOA: ``I'm betting that Griffey winds up
in Cincinnati, if not now, then in a spring training deal. If not
then, then in July before the trading deadline. And if not then, as
a free agent. We're not in it because we believe Cincinnati is
where Griffey wants to go.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bowden has made no secret of his passion for landing
Griffey. He said that, in the last three months, he offered Gillick
numerous packages: five-player deals, four-player deals, and
Saturday a three-player deal, with impact players on both the major
and minor league level. All-Star reliever Scott Williamson has been
discussed, as well as outfielders Mike Cameron and Dmitri Young,
shortstop prospect Travis Dawkins, and pitcher Brett Tomko.
</P>
<P>
   But Bowden, who already has picked up outfielder Dante Bichette
as a hedge against losing free agent slugger Greg Vaughn, made it
clear that he didn't want to break up the nucleus of a team that
won 96 games last season. That makes Williamson, first baseman Sean
Casey, and Reese off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   The other teams expected to be in the Griffey hunt have not
materialized. The Yankees can never be entirely ruled out, but
Griffey has made it known he doesn't want to play for them. The
Indians were said to have some interest, especially with Kenny
Lofton out until at least midseason because of shoulder surgery,
but they haven't leaped in. Neither have the Braves, who seemed to
be a natural fit because of Griffey's desire to play for a team
near his Orlando home. But the Braves will be looking to lock up
Chipper Jones, who will be a free agent next year. The Astros have
been reported in the mix, but that isn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   Could Griffey remain inSeattle for another year? Sure,
especially if he believes the Mariners can win next season, a
scenario that looks a lot more feasible with their signing of free
agent first baseman John Olerud and their pursuit of lefthander
Chuck Finley. But Gillick still can't afford the chance that
Griffey will walk after the season without getting something in
return.
</P>
<P>
   So the Reds, Griffey's hometown team, have been the one serious
candidate, and Bowden's pronouncements notwithstanding, they remain
so. It may all just be a matter of timing.
</P>
<P>
   A step back for Phillies
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that Phillies ace Curt Schilling will require
shoulder surgery is a major blow to GM Ed Wade's attempts to put
together a contender next season. The Phillies had taken
significant steps by acquiring righthanded starter Andy Ashby from
the Padres and signing free agent closer Mike Jackson, but
Schilling will be out until at least May and maybe longer after he
undergoes surgery Monday to tighten the front of his shoulder.
Schilling's shoulder woes flared after the All-Star Game in July.
He went on the disabled listfom Aug. 8 to Sept. 3, made one start,
then shut it down. He discovered the shoulder was still hurting
when he resumed throwing last week. Schilling underwent surgery to
repair a torn labrum four years ago and recovered to become one of
the National League's premier righthanded strikeout pitchers. But
he turned 33 last month, and his shoulder is showing the wear from
leading the majors in pitches in both the 1997 and '98 seasons . .
. The signing of slugger Carlos Delgado to a three-year contract
Friday stopped the bleeding in Toronto, where the Blue Jays have
been under siege after trading former Cy Young award winner Pat
Hentgen and star outfielder Shawn Green. But Delgado still could be
a short-timer, despite agreeing to a deal that will pay him $36
million in the next three years. There's a clause in his contract
that will allow him to demand a trade after next season. If the
Jays fail to trade him by a Feb. 15 deadline _ insisted upon by
Delagdo's agent, David Sloane _ Delgado can become a free agent.
Delgado had been asking for as much as $38.25 million, but
acknowledged that the three-year, $20 million deal accepted by
fellow first baseman Olerud from Seattle affected his negotiations.
Delgado insists he'd like to stay put in Toronto, for whom he has
hit 137 home runs the last four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He shall return
</P>
<P>
   He openly fought with George Steinbrenner while filling in as
Yankees manager during Joe Torre's absence, and he defended Jimy
Williams when the Boss accused the Sox manager of inciting a Fenway
Park crowd during the playoffs. He hobbled around on knees so
painful it wasn't a question of whether he could continue
year-to-year, but day-to-day. But Don Zimr will be back for his 52d
season, Torre told reporters last week, remaining with the Yankees
for another go-round as bench coach. That should be good news for
anyone who recognizes Zim for what he is, one of the game's grand
treasures. Torre, meanwhile, just finished another round of
radiation therapy, a follow-up to his prostate cancer surgery last
spring. Torre reported no untoward side effects, other than some
fatigue, and said he's working out four or five times a week . . .
The Reds may not land Griffey, but they made a significant addition
to their staff when they hired Gary Hughes as director of
professional scouting. Hughes, 58, is the man who nearly made a big
league ballplayer out of John Elway, signing him for the Yankees.
But that was merely a novelty act in a distinguished career in
which Hughes helped cultivate top young talent first in Montreal,
then with the Florida Marlins, signing such players as outfielder
Marquis Grissom and catcher Charles Johnson. Hughes went on to
Colorado, but after being passed over for the GM job that went to
Dan O'Dowd, he landed with the Reds. Recently, Hughes was named one
of the top 10 scouts of the century by Baseball America. Hughes's
responsibilities with the Reds will include evaluating free agents,
scouting talent for trades, and evaluating minor leaguers. He also
will oversee all professional scouting coverage . . . Police
blotter: A former minor league player from the Chicago Cubs system
was charged with first-degree murder last Wednesday after the
bludgeoning death of his next-door neighbor in Chandler, Ariz.
Fabio Evelio Gomez, 31, was charged by Maricopa County prosecutors
after poce discovered the body of Joan Rachelle Morane in a
dumpster at he apartments where both lived. Gomez also was charged
with kidnapping and burglary. Meanwhile, Roger Blanco, a minor
league pitcher in Atlanta's system since 1996, was shot and killed
last week in his hometown of Caracas, Venezuela. Blanco, 23, was
murdered by robbers who broke into his sister's home. He was 1-3
with a 9.71 ERA in Single A Macon last summer.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman fields offers
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins made an offer last week to first baseman/outfielder
Jeff Conine, a Marlins original who ranks as the most popular
player in team history, though his days in Florida became numbered
when then-manager Jim Leyland oddly became disenchanted with him.
But Conine, who finished last season with the Orioles, received a
better offer to stay put in Baltimore, where he would share first
base with the oft-injured Will Clark, DH, and play some outfield .
. . Terry Francona, the Phillies' 40-year-old manager, is just five
years older than his new closer, Mike Jackson, the free agent
signed away from Cleveland. The two played together for Maracaibo
(Venezuela) in 1986. ``Someone on the (Caracas) team said something
to me one day and Mike wasn't very happy about it,'' Francona
recalled. ``The next inning, he hit the guy right in the ribs with
a pitch. That kind of loyalty goes a long way when you're away from
home in a foreign country.'' . . . Mariners manager Lou Piniella
was otherwise occupied when the team signed Olerud. Piniella was at
a hospital, where his daughter-in-law was giving birth to
Piniella's granddaughter, Sophie. ``We've had a delivery here,
too,'' Gillick told Piniella whnhe finally reached him. ``Who?''
Piniella asked. ``We just signed John Olerud,'' Gillick said.
Piniella, needless to say, felt doubly blessed . . . The Mariners
are hardly done with the signing of Olerud, who elected to return
home rather than re-up with the Mets. They're pursuing Finley for
their starting rotation and Arthur Rhodes for their bullpen, and
also have offers out to free agents Graeme Lloyd, Aaron Sele, Stan
Javier, and Mark McLemore . . . As if the Yankees haven't bedeviled
Texas enough, the Rangers must go to New York for the world
champions' home opener April 11. They'll have the privilege of
watching the Yankees, who have swept them in each of the last two
playoffs, hoist another World Series flag. Including postseason
play, the Rangers have lost 28 of their last 36 games at Yankee
Stadium . . . Williams and his Jimywocky may have some competition
from new Cleveland manager Charlie Manuel, who tends to play up his
country roots. A recent sample from Manuel: ``The hardest thing for
me about this job will be when I have to talk to players who are
smart and educated _ and I've got to get on their level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
