<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-NORTONCOURSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTON COURSE A TOUR ATTRACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though it's no more than a sand wedge away, you can't
distinguish the green. Unless, that is, you are one of the
surveyors armed with maps and an uncanny sense of direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The red-and-white striped flg,'' says the man, pointing you
through a group of leafless trees. ``That's where the green will
be. The white poles are center lines (for fairways).''
</P>
<P>
   Even the architect from the Arnold Palmer Course Design Co.,
Greg Stang, laughs and shakes his head. Standing amid trees, thick
brush, and wetlands, he is very much at home, for his business is
turning unusable land like this into lavish, green playgrounds for
golfers. But it takes a lot of experience, said Stang, to get your
bearings straight and figure out just what you are looking at.
</P>
<P>
   Stang, designer of more than 20 courses worldwide, was part of a
team that recently conducted a walk-through at the site in Norton
that will become the newest addition to the Tournament Playes Club
network. TPC of Boston at Great Woods _ an $18 million partnership
between FleetBoston, PGA Tour Golf Properties, and Boston
businessman William F. Connell _ will begin to take shape in a
femths when they begin to clear the land and shape fairways. If all
goes well, it will open in spring 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That's a trip to Mars for some, particularly since it will be a
private club geared toward a corporate clientele, but the project
is noteworthy for local golf fans given this reality: Where there
is a TPC course, there usually is a pro tour stop. Since the
golf-crazed Boston area has lost PGA Tour and LPGA Tour stops in
recent years, that's good news.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the PGA Tour and its TPC Network have not
guaranteed anything for the Norton site. There is a membership
drive ongoing (if you join TPC at Boston, you join the TPC
network), likely capping off at 350.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 100 would be identified as founding members,'' said
Scott Ferrell, regional director of marketing for the TPC, ``and we
are quickly approaching that number.''
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, because Tour officials have said that in all their
marketing endeavors, they have rarely seen an area so thirsty for
golf as Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The TPC of Boston figures to draw many membership inquiries
(Woolf Associates in Boston is involved in the marketing), but it
is also an intriguing project for those starving to be part of a
gallery at a PGA Tour event. Especially when Christopher Gray, a
vice president with PGA Tour Design Services Inc., concedes that
these TPC venues are built with tournaments in mind. The numbers
prove this point: Of the 17 TPC Clubs already built, eight host PGA
Tour stops, seven host Senior PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching TPC of Boston at Great Woods with this same
philosophy, both Stang and Gray talked about all the routing plans
they worked on befo settling on the Norton site. It will feature a
starting hole that is well away from the clubhouse and a front side
that takes you to the most remote points of the course. Somewhat
odd, until you look at holes 12 through 18, which will run
virtually parallel, a short walk from the clubhouse, and offer
splendid spectator viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Having holes 12-18 routed tis way is a concession to the needs
of a tournament. So are the areas that will be devoted to corporate
tents, and a practice range that will measure 75,000 to 80,000
square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Located close to Route 495, the land involves some 400 acres,
said Stang, though more than 100 will remain open space. Plans have
been roughed out (it will play 7,115 yards from the tips, but there
will be five sets of tees on most holes) and some intriguing
features include a par-5 18th with a split fairway; a drivable
par-4 17th; and a 12th green situated so that a cropping rock comes
into play.
</P>
<P>
   The latter figured into the plans once Stang and his crew really
got onto the land and stumbled upon the rock. Too costly and too
big to move, said Stang, they decided to work it into the
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The land has been surveyed, and colored flags are everywhere;
though they indicate greens and fairways, they meant little to the
hunters who were on the prowl during the FleetBoston walk-through.
It was the opening day of deer season and Stang, Gray, and others
in the party laughed (nervously, perhaps, as gunshots rang out) as
they put on their bright orange vests.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, deer hunters and golf course designers shr the same
property. In less than two years, however, golfers chasing after
birdies hopefully will have the place to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty Quinn
</P>
<P>
   It didn't come with a green jacket or million-dollar check, but
Fran Quinn's victory at the Thailand Open last week provided an
awful lot of gratification. ``It was a lot of fun out there,'' said
the two-time Massachusetts Open champion after closing with a
1-under 71 to claim the top spot in Bangkok. ``This is some
consolation for missing out on my US Tour card.'' Quinn, who had
come up two shots shy at the final stage of the PGA Tour Qualifying
Tournament two weeks earlier in Miami, was tied for the lead as he
made the turn, but vaulted in front with birdies at the 13th and
14th, and preserved his first win on the Asian PGA Tour with a
par-par finish. Quinn is in China this weekend, playing in the
Omega PGA Championship. Peter Teravainen of Duxbury is also in the
field . . . What are they feeding these amateurs Down Under? First,
18-year-old Aaron Baddeley wins the Australian Open, then Brett
Rumord, 22, takes the ANZ Players Championship. Indeed, Rumford
drew inspiration from his fellow amateur in the days between
events. ``We went out to dinner,'' said Rumford, ``and Aaron was
waiting for me in the bar, surrounded by five women. I thought that
was really good.'' Baddeley finished 17th in the ANZ Players
Championship, but declined an invitation to this week's Australian
PGA Championship. There is an event, however, that he certainly
would not pass up _ the Masters. Bruce Devlin reportedly talked to
Baddeley's father and said he would lobby on behalf of the
youngster for an invite to Augusta . . . eaking of the Masters,
W.W. ``Hootie'' Johnson, chairman of Augusta National, recently
told a reporter that the club batted .500 with its two most
significant changes to the famed layout. The 1-inch cut of
``rough'' was a good decision, he said, but lengthening the par-4
17th wasn't. ``We really missed it on 17,'' Johnson is quoted as
saying, ``but we've made adjustments.'' . . . Nancy Scranton, a
16-year member of the LPGA Tour, was named by her colleagues to
receive the 1999 Heather Farr Player Award for exemplary attitude
on and off the course . . . The PGA of America will move its PGA
Seniors Championship _ the over-50 crowd's oldest major _ to
Ridgewood CC in Paramus, N.J., in 2001. This year's event again
will be staged at PGA National at Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., with
Norwood's Allen Doyle the defending champion . . . So how do you
put an exclamation point on a season that included seven wins and
more than $2 million in prize money? By going back to work in the
pro shop, of course. At least if you are longtime club pro Bruce
Fleisher, it seems. The Senior PGA Tour Player of the Year was
tracked down by Golfweek's Richard Mudry working at Donald Trump's
new course next to Palm Beach International Airport. Fleisher told
Mudry he was doing it as a favor to a friend but doesn't mind the
work because he still enjoys meeting people . . . Cheers to
longtime New England pro Bob Lendzion, who was one of the eight
players to earn his 2000 Senior PGA Tour card at qualifying school
last week . . . The eighth annual EMC Skills Challenge (taped Nov.
15, but televised this weekend) turned into a battle between those
Rhode Island buddies, Brad Faxon and Billy Anade. No surprise that
Faxon drained a 25-footer to win the putting portion, but Andrade
refused to be outdone. After winning the bunker competition by
holing out, Andrade flexed his muscles and drove it 344 yards to
take that event, too . . . Strange end Wednesday to the 49th season
of the Cape Cod Pro-Am League. Because an amateur entrant played
the wrong set of tees, his 3-under 51 at par 3 Blue Rock in South
Yarmouth was disallowed, giving the low round (a 54) to another
amateur, the always-present Joe Keller of Oyster Harbors. Needing a
win to overtake Jeff Bailey for the Sullivan Award, Bob Miller
stumbled with bogeys on two of the final four holes at his home
course and finished at 56, in a tie for second for low pro honors.
Bailey, head pro at the Country Club of Norwood, tied for 12th with
a 58, good enough to secure the award for overall performance . . .
Barbara McIntire, 64, a lifelong amateur who lost in a playoff for
the US Women's Open in 1956, was named recipient of the USGA's Bob
Jones Award. The honor pays tribute to someone who emulates Jones's
spirit toward the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
