<SLUG> BC-BBO-WINTERMEETINGS-FINLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX HAVE STAKE IN FINLEY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ After confirming that the Red Sox had acquired
backup infielder Manny Alexander from the Chicago Cubs for
outfielder Damon Buford, general manager Dan Duquette Saturday
acknowledged his interest in free agent Chuck Finley, saying that
acquiring a lefthanded starter would be the best move the Sox could
make at Major League Baseball's annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few lefthanders on the market,'' Duquette said.
``Ideally, we'd like to have a lefthander.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette claimed he had no meeting scheduled with Finley's
agent, Tim Shannon, but added that he expected it would take a
three-year deal to sign the 37-year-old pitcher. The Sox are
competing against Seattle and Cleveland, among others, for Finley's
services. Both the Mariners and Indians already have three-year
offers on the table, reportedly for less than $25 million; Duquette
said he has yet to make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said the Sox are also looking into trading for a
pitcher. He said he had meetings set up Saturday with five or six
clubs, including the San Diego Padres, who might be willing to part
with lefthander Sterling Hitchcock, who turns 29 next spring and
was 12-14 with a 4.11 earned-run average for a lousy team last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had looked into dealing for Finley before last July's
trading deadline, but, according to Duquette, Finley told the
Angels he was willing to be dealt to only the Indians or Yankees,
both of whom appeared at the time to be certain of going to the
playoffs. But Duquette said he has been assured that Finley, who
has 165 career wins, all with the Angels, now has no qualms about
pitching for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette acknowledged that Finley's success against the Yankees
over the years makes him especially attractive. ``Absolutely,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, Finley is 15-9 with a 3.3 ERA against the Yankees.
He has beaten only the Mariners and Twins more often in his career.
He is 6-6 with a 3.74 ERA in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Duquettelso acknowledged mild interest in free agent lefty Kenny
Rogers, who was 10-4 with a 4.19 ERA in a 1999 season split between
the A's and Mets, though he added wryly: ``Does anybody have
interest in Kenny Rogers?''
</P>
<P>
   If the Sox are unable to acquire the starter they'd like,
Duquette envisions another scenario in which they would try to
obtain a closer and convert Derek Lowe into a starter. If the
season started today, Duquette said, Lowe would be the closer, with
Rod Beck his setup man.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's acquisition, Alexander, comes with a modest price
tag. He signed a one-year deal with the Cubs last week for
$612,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our reports on him are good,'' said manager Jimy Williams. ``I
think he'll be able to help us on both sides of the line. I pretty
much remember him as a shortstop, but will we expose him to the
other side of the diamond? We're not afraid to move people
around.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Duquette confirmed that reliever Tom Gordon will have surgery on
his right elbow Monday at Centinela Hospital in Inglewood, Calif.
Lewis Yocum, the Angels' team orthopedist, will perform the
procedure, which will be attended by Sox doctor Bill Morgan.
Duquette said he still hopes Gordon will not require Tommy John
tendon-transplant surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
