<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-JOHNSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSCURE FIGHETER DIED PURSUING DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most boxers, Stephan Johnson lost his final fight. The
tragedy is that he lost his life along with it.
</P>
<P>
   Until that moment three weeks ago, when he was carried from an
Atlantic City ring on a stretcher with an oxygen mask over his face
and no future in his blank eyes, few people had ever heard of
Stephan Johnson and even fewer cared about him.
</P>
<P>
   He was just a fighter to most people, a faceless man in a savage
sport. That's the fate of most of those who sacrifice their bodies
and youth without notice, gambling their lives in the most savage
arena in sports with slim hope anyone will ever remember they were
there.
</P>
<P>
   If they are lucky, you might remember them for a night, when the
savagery and the bravery are so compelling that you cannot ignore
them. If they are very lucky, you might notice them for a year or
two for the same reasons. If they are lucky beyond good fortune,
they g even make a few dollars selling out their bodies for your
viewing pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Few fighters ever really make it in the sport, but from where
they come, few make it in life, either, and the odds are better in
the ring than on the streets. It is almost a requirement that
fighters come from the most desperate circumstances, otherwise why
would they choose to do what they do? There is the occasional rare
exception, like Gene Tunney, but the address of most fighters is
Hell's Kitchen, either the real one in New York or the one society
has made for them elsewhere, in whatever corner of poverty they
spring from.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters are far too undervalued in today's sporting society,
far too often mocked by peoplewho don't know any better. They are
seldom the ones behind the machinations that lead to federal
indictments or shoddy decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters come to fight every night, most often for chump change.
There is no harder way to try to feed yourself in sports than to be
punched in the mouth for your pay.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, they come as Stephan Johnson did, with hope, making a
fool's bet on a sport that is cruel far more often than it is kind.
There is an endless supply of fighters like Stephan Johnson, who
died at 31 last Sunday, hoping to get a title shot or write a
novel. He was working on both Nov. 20, the night he stepped into
the ring for the last time, believing if he could just upset former
world champion Paul Vaden he would get his chance, and if he
didn't, he'd have more material for that book.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that he had collapsed in the ring last April in Canada
and was on a medical suspension across the boder. Forget that he
had fought twice after that in US towns willing to ignore that
suspension if they could find a doctor who would judge Johnson fit
to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody protects the boxer who doesn't protect himself, and few
are capable of that. After all, what they do is fight, the most
unreasonable decision in sports, so why would they stop unless
someone makes them?
</P>
<P>
   In Stephan Johnson's case, he stopped for the worst reason. He
stopped fighting because he stopped breathing.
</P>
<P>
   So now the hue and cry probably will begin again. The
abolitionists will call for the end of the sport. They will say
boxing is barbaric, a form of sporting slavery.
</P>
<P>
   But fighters like Johnson understand the bet they are making
when they become prizefighters. They know the odds are long that
they will become a champion and even longer that they will make any
real money even if they do win a champion's belt.
</P>
<P>
   For many fighters, that gamble is worth taking because
everything in their life is a gamble. If there were more Beverly
Hillses and fewer Hell's Kitchens, boxing would die on its own from
a lack of practitioners. But as long as there is poverty, there
will be struggle, and as long as there is struggle, there will be
someone willing to fight to overcome it, and as long as there is
someone willing to fight, there will be someone else willing to
fight back and someone with a cigar in his mouth willing to promote
them for a piece of the action.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, as long as we are fascinated by this brutal art and pay
to watch it, there will be men like Stephan Johnson, who fight in
obscurity until they die under the bright lights.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was, from all reports, a wonderful young m who taught
boxing fitness to rich guys on Wall Street, went to school, hoped
to write a book, and could fight like hell. But too many guys could
fight better than Johnson, so he fought in obscurity until he
ignored the warning in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks or a few months, Stephan Johnson will be
forgotten. But people will still fight because they have no other
choice and young boys will watch them and dream of a better day.
They will dream not of Stephan Johnson, who died fighting for his
dream.
</P>
<P>
   They will dream instead of Oscar De La Hoya with his millions of
dollars and the starlets on his arm. They will dream of Roy Jones
Jr., the best in the world at the moment. They will dream of
Evander Holyfield or Mike Tyson because his life looks good if you
haven't had to live it.
</P>
<P>
   They will dream the boxer's dream and fight the good fight. If
they are lucky, you will notice them one night and marvel at their
courage or their skill.
</P>
<P>
   If they are very lucky, you won't notice them the way you
noticed Stephan Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, De La Hoya will announce from New York that he will
fight Derrel Coley Feb. 26, but it is unclear why De La Hoya wants
this fight. Coley was the World Boxing Council's No. 1-rated
welterweight for nearly two years and De La Hoya had no interest in
fighting him. Once De La Hoya lost his WBC welterweight title to
Felix Trinidad, his promoter, Bob Arum, convinced Coley's people to
accept $1 million to fight De La Hoya for the IBA welterweight
title. Coley had been offered $375,000 to fight Trinidad for the
more widely recognized WBC portion of the belt but went for the
larger purse withoutonsulting his promoters, America Presents.
However, Coley was in a pickle with Trinidad because of a rule Arum
rammed through at the WBC convention in South Africa two years ago.
Under that rule, any fighter weighing above 135 pounds who had not
made a major purse but became a No. 1 contender did not get to go
to a purse bid and receive 25 percent of the take. Instead, he
could not receive more than 15 times his highest previous purse,
which in Coley's case was $35,000. Coley's promoters fought that
rule but lost. Arum pushed it, not coincidentally, because he knew
De La Hoya was facing a Coley mandatory defense and he didn't want
to pay him in excess of his value. Until De La Hoya was without a
title. But Coley's promoters, insiders say, had already arranged
for him to receive mony to step aside and allow Trinidad to fight
World Boxing Association 154-pound champion David Reid while
keeping his rights intact with the WBC as the next challenger for
the 147-pound title. He would have received a tuneup fight as well.
In addition, he would have gotten more money if Trinidad or his
replacement didn't honor the commitment with Coley. But Arum
convinced Coley's manager that he would pay more and get Coley a
shot at the WBC title because if Reid and Trinidad fought, he would
demand that Trinidad be stripped by the WBC and that De La
Hoya-Coley serve as a fight for the vacant title. Well, guess what?
Arum got what he wanted _ which is an opponent for De La Hoya _ and
Coley did get $1 million. But he would have gotten as much or more
if he had let the Trinidad-Reid fight go forward and still would
have had his No. 1 WBC ranking, which he will now lose in a fight
for nothing b cash on Feb. 26. ``We don't know what the fight
isfor,'' said HBO executive Lou DiBella Friday. ``It could be an
eliminator, with the winner to get a title shot. It could be for a
vacant title. It could be for an interim title. Or it could be just
a good 12-round fight.'' Whatever it is, it may be the first time
in boxing history that a $1 million deal wasn't a good one for the
kid getting the money . . . America Presents has signed
International Boxing Federation top-rated heavyweight David Tua
away from Main Events, marking another defection from the newly
revamped company started by Dan Duva. Word is Tua received a $1
million signing bonus, although Dan Goossen of America Presents
denied it . . . Former cruiserweight champion Marcelo Dominguez has
been added to the list of fighters promoted by Germany's Universum
Box-Promotion, which also handles world champion Juan Carlos Gomez,
who twice beat Dominguez. The Argentine is 3-0 with three knockouts
since he lost the rematch to Gomez in March to push his record to
29-3-1. His management team said it is looking for a shot at
Vassily Jirov but has no interest in a third fight with Gomez . . .
Peter Hanraths, manager of European champion Wladimir Klitschko,
says he would like to match him early next year with either Andrew
Golota or Zeljko Mavrovic . . . Tyson has officially set the date
for his next fight, Jan. 29 in Manchester, England, vs. Julius
Francis. He might as well be fighting Julius Caesar for all the
fight Francis will put up . . . Tyson's decision leaves Jones with
a wide-open TV date for Jan. 15 on HBO when he fights hard-hitting
David Telasco in the first fight ever at Rado City Music Hall in
New York . . . As promised here before, undefeated WC super
bantamweight champion Erik Morales will defend his title against
World Boxing Organization champion Marco Antonio Barrera Feb. 19 at
Mandalay Bay in Las Vegas. Morales is 35-0 with 28 KOs. Barrera is
49-2 with 36 knockouts . . . Word is Arturo Gatti will appear on
the undercard of the De La Hoya fight against either Joey Gamache,
Shea Neary of Ireland, or Billy Irwin . . . In a bit of a surprise,
Ring magazine named Paulie Ayala its fighter of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
