<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-LARRYMILLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER PAID PRICE; LOYALTY IS REWARDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LrMiller had some tough decisions this summer. The owner of the
Utah Jazz for the last 15 years had some key free agents to sign
and it speaks volumes about the man's love of his team, and the
players who made it one of the very best, that he did what he did.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Miller put his bottom line on the line. He signed
36-year-old Karl Malone to a four-year deal for $66.5 million. He
signed 37-year-old John Stockton to a two-year deal for $22
million.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a successful businessman who bought the Jazz for $22
million, did what successful businessmen rarely do: He basically
guaranteed that he will lose money in the next couple years.
</P>
<P>
   Because Malone's big hit ($14 million) and Stockton's ($11
million) will have been on the books for only two months in 1999,
``I think this year, we'll be all right,'' said Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year, it's a big concern. I'm not sure if we can make
money even if we win the championship. I know it doesn't make
sense, but to do it any other way would not be fair to those two
guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that was going to be the case when I did it. We've had
a lot of years of prosperity and those two guys are responsible for
a lot of it. If I have to take a hit, so be it. I feel I have to
hold up my end.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is going through what the Celtics' owners went through in
the early 1990s with Larry Bird and Kevin McHale. Namely, how do
you reward the players who made you all that money even though
their best days are behind them? Money, of course, is one
expression of loyalty, certainly the most understood one.
</P>
<P>
   You could argue that Bird, McHale, Malone, and Stockton were all
compensated richly in their careers and u'd be right. But the NBA
has its own currency.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that Bird and McHale broke down, physically.
Bird got a $7 million balloon payment _ enormous at the time _ and
could have made scads more but decided he didn't want it if he
couldn't be Larry Bird. McHale's feet gave way and the best he did
was a $3.5 million hit at the end. At one point late in his career,
he was making less than Brad Lohaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had opportunities to trade players,'' former Celtics
general manager Jan Volk said. ``Were they good deals? Well, two
years after the fact, if you still had something to show, you could
probably make an argument for it. But Red (Auerbach) always felt
there was tremendous value in developing a sense of loyalty. It was
there then. I'm not so sure it still is.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Malone will be 40 when this current deal expires. He has shown
no signs of slowing down and has not missed a game because of
injury since the 1988-89 season. (There have been three
DNP-suspensions along the way.) In that final year, he'll make
$19.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I look at the whole thing,'' Miller said, ``I do feel that
there's some risk to paying him the most when he may be the least
productive. But we've also been hearing that those two are slowing
down for the last six or seven years. And, actually, I think Karl's
last two or three years have been among the best of his career. You
just never know where that cliff is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz under Miller's stewardship have been a profitable
enterprise. He's the first to admit it. The team lost $17 million
in its first 11 years of operation. Since Miller arrvd, it has
shown a profit every year, including a modest one of around
$120,000 in his first year. (He credited ex-president Dave
Checketts for that.)
</P>
<P>
   That's what made it easier for him to agree to these deals. He's
done well. His mainstays have done well. He has a new building that
sells out more often than not. He, Malone, and Stockton are Salt
Lake fixtures; all three realize that the players might have made
more elsewhere, but they chose to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never looked back,'' Miller said. ``I've always told John
and Karl I wanted two things from them: that they'll finish their
careers in a Jazz uniform and that, when it's all over, they can
turn around and say, `It's been good and fair for me.' I think now,
with these deals, it's got the making of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall tales
</P>
<P>
   What's left to say about Charles Barkley? How about this: Let's
get out the tape measure and see how tall he really is. If he's
taller than 6 feet 4 inches, I'd be stunned. Barkley's height made
his achievements even more remarkable. As writers, of course, we
loved his candor and his outlandish stuff. This was, after all, the
fellow who said he was misquoted in his autobiography. ``I guess
you could say he pioneered the genre of the unauthorized
autobiography,'' cracked Jeff Neuman, the editor at Simon &AMP;
Schuster who oversaw Barkley's book. ``I had the opportunity to
know how David Stern felt every time he picked up the newspaper and
wondered, `What has he done to us today?' But I'll say this.
Charles was the only athlete I ever did a book with who looked you
in the eye and asked you about you. Most of them are interested
only in themselves. And in this era where wesw Michael Jordan so
carefully packaged, Charles always said what was on his mind and
interacted with people. How many athletes these days do that?'' . .
. Suns boss Jerry Colangelo, who, like a lot of owners, is ringless
thanks to Jordan, had this to say about Barkley: ``Charles was one
of the great entertainers that's ever played in the league, a
terrific player.'' However, Barkley basically made himself a
pain-in-the-you-know-what after his superb first year in Phoenix
(1992-93). The Suns lost in the Finals to the Bulls and Barkley was
the league MVP. Phoenix was a logical successor to the Bulls after
MJ retired, but the Suns instead regressed to the point they were
out in the first round in Barkley's last season there, 1995-96.
``In his first season, he brought us to a level we hadn't been at
for a number of years,'' Colangelo said. ``He had a fabulous
season. I would say for that year, I am grateful for the
contributions he made.'' . . . Patrick Ewing is back, but it
remains to be seen how it all unfolds for the 37-year-old center.
The story of his return was covered in mystery and, some might say,
duplicity. None of Ewing's teammates knew he had made up his mind
to return on Friday and, according to an article by Selena Roberts
in the New York Times, the only player on the team who treats Ewing
with what Ewing feels is the obligatory, unconditional reverence,
is Mirsad Turckan. Also out of the loop was a rather important
fellow, coach Jeff Van Gundy. He heard, like millions of others,
that Ewing would play Friday after it came out of the mouth of
ex-Georgetown coach John Thompson on TNT. Meanwhile, Ewing was
fined, twice, for not being press-accessibland the Knicks were
similarly docked. Ewing has never cared about his public persona
and it looks as though he cares even less now. But someone whom he
listens to, someone like Thompson, should tell him to stop scowling
and smell the coffee. He has no beefs. None. He's got his money.
Now, as Bill Russell would say, ``What else do you have?'' . . .
Looking for a feel-good comeback story for the holiday season? You
could do worse than the Scott Williams saga. This is the same
fellow who bagged three rings as a Jordanaire in the early 1990s
and then, basically, went into (well-heeled) hibernation the last
five years. He went to Philadelphia as high-priced free agent and
either was hurt or ineffective. He played a total of 46 minutes
last season and was sent to the Bucks in the Tim Thomas-Tyrone Hill
deal, mainly as a salary cap balancer. Now, he's starting for
Milwaukee and putting up very serviceable numbers. ``This summer, I
made a decision that I wasn't going to be one of those players who
looked back and didn't give themselves every opportunity,''
Williams said. ``I participated in the summer camps in Salt Lake
City and that kind of jump-started me into training camp. And I had
the best camp since I've been in the NBA. But for whatever reason,
coach (George) Karl didn't have me in the rotation.'' Williams said
his teammates went to Karl and suggested that the coach play the
North Carolina vet (among the teammates: Tar Heel teammate J.R.
Reid). ``That meant a lot to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Back with more stuffs
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for the return of the Slam Dunk Contest during
All-Star Weekend. Commissioner Stern said last week that the event,
held on Gimmick Saturd, will be back after a three-year absence.
(The last winner was Kobe Bryant in 1997.) ``We've had a lot of
interest expressed by the best people _ the players _ who've said,
`I have a few moves that are reminiscent of Dominique or Michael,''
Stern said. ``So we'll see what our players have.'' . . . After
watching Ron Mercer struggle in his return to Boston Wednesday,
Paul Pierce vowed he will not let the same thing happen when the
Celtics play Kansas . . . The train wreck known as the Washington
Wizards had its starting lineup outscored (by 9 points) by Cliff
Robinson and Tom Gugliotta in a Thursday bludgeoning by the Suns.
Washington is off to its worst start in 32 years, but owner Abe
Pollin is saying he'll stick around until the team improves, an
actuarial challenge . . . The Timberwolves got spanked in the
Pacific Northwest by surprising Seattle and a bored Portland team.
Wolves coach Flip Saunders did not appreciate Brent Barry hoisting
a trey at the end of the loss to Seattle. The fans wanted it; free
goodies at Taco Bell were at stake. ``It's a Barry trait. It's
genetic,'' Saunders said, referring to Barry's dad, the
self-assured Rick. ``Every dog has his day. That's how you have to
look at it. I chew guys out for taking shots like that.'' The
Sonics will be in Minnesota in 11 days . . . Glenn Robinson signed
on for another year with the Bucks. But he already was under
contract through 2004. Why only one year? It's all the Bucks could
offer, given that he has five years remaining and if a player signs
an extension, it can't be longer than six years. ``He came in and
we talked. He wants to finish his career here,'' GM Ernie Grunfeld
said. The one-yr extension will pay the Big Dog a shade more than
$12 million. Also, he'll have 11 years in the league, he'll be only
32, and he'll be eligible for a Malone-type hit assuming he
continues to improve . . . If you watched Court TV last week, you
might have seen Charlotte owner George Shinn on the stand, and he
wasn't getting grilled about trading Alonzo Mourning or Larry
Johnson. He's getting sued for sexual assault. There already has
been evidence introduced that Shinn carried on a two-year affair
with a Hornets cheerleader. The assault charge comes from another
woman. Shinn has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
