<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6436 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ADVANCE-     12-11 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENT PATRIOTS CHANGE ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Serice clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the steel-cage match. The heavyweight championship. The
seventh game of the World Series. The Super Bowl. The last lap at
Indy.
</P>
<P>
   Alast it is for the Patriots Sunday when they meet the
Indianapolis Colts at the RCA Dome. Even so, the atmosphere in the
Patriots' locker room was very confident, bordering on
``dangerous,'' following their final practice of the week Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The offense, which tried a few new wrinkles last week, will add
a few more things to the mix this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something changed in here,'' said wide receiver Vincent
Brisby. ``Maybe it's because we've reached this stage where we have
to win, but the guys in here are so intense and there seems to be a
real purpose every time we go out to practice now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how good we are. We know we have talent. I think
everyone in here is mad that we've lost five games. We shouldn't
have lost that many with what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Jefferson called it ``the best week of practice of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been heard before. The Patriots, and Pete Carroll in
particular, have commented on the success of practices in the past,
and the Patriots have not always come out victorious thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the guys are really together,'' said defensive end
Ferric Collons. ``This team is as close as I've ever seen it. We
want to go out there and prove a point. This is a tough team we're
playing against. They're the best in our division. We need to beat
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Indianapolis, some fans truly believe the Colts are destined
to lose this game. They speak of the Patriots being a team the
Colts just can't beat. The Patriots have won seven straight against
the Colts, including the memorable game in September when they came
back from a 28-7 deficit to win, 31-28, on Adam Vinatieri's 26-yard
fid goal with 1:57 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look back, that was quite a game for us,'' said
Vinatieri. ``To battle back and not give up and then to win it in
the last couple of minutes is a tribute to the heart of our team. I
think we'd all like to be in position for me to kick another
game-winner, but hopefully we can put some points up early.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri could be a huge weapon for the Patriots down the
stretch. He will be kicking in a dome Sunday for the first and only
time this season, and he relishes the thought of not having any
wind to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ted Johnson also remains a key figure. If he's able
to dominate the Colt guards and contain Edgerrin James, the
Patriots will challenge the Colts' passing game to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid is an outstanding runner,'' Johnson said of James.
``He's so strong and so hard to bring down. We have to pay
attention to him with the run and also as a pass catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is Ty Law's ability to play effectively against
Colts receiver Marvin Harrison with a broken hand. Law is sporting
a very large padded cast, and that weight on his thumb should
restrict him, especially on any physical play at the line of
scrimmage. He may have to play back, more of a Deion Sanders style.
</P>
<P>
   And if he feels he can't play effectively, this could be the
time for Tebucky Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever plays out there, we have to be at the top of our
games,'' said safety Lawyer Milloy. ``Nobody can make excuses. If
you can play, you'd better play your best. We don't have time for
excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the Thanksgiving week fightbetween Brisby and Milloy bring
this team closer together? Like the old New York Yankees? Like the
old Oakland A's?
</P>
<P>
   Neither combatant would touch that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us as receivers are excited by the offense
we're seeing right now,'' said Brisby. ``We're trying different
things, spreading it out. I think with our weapons, we can create
some things with the way we're approaching offense right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing the Patriots want to do is leave their enthusiasm
on the practice field. They've done that before and had to face the
music. But if they do it this time, there will not be a chance for
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we have to win out,'' said Brisby. ``I think that's one of
the things that motivates everyone in here. We don't want to let
the fans and the organization down. We don't want to let ourselves
down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6437 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-INDIANA-MANNING-B     12-11 2194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-INDIANA-MANNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNING ALREADY PROJECTS WINNING IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The fact of the matter is that Peyton Manning
went after Ty Law, as no other quarterback has done. Three times,
three touchdown passes in one half to Marvin Harrison, three times
the Patriots cornerback scorched and burned back in September.
</P>
<P>
   The reason?
</P>
<P>
   Simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ty Law is their left cornerback and Marvin is our right
receiver,'' said Manning. ``That was something different from last
year because last year I probably wouldn't have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinges of a Southern drawl color the many words of the
Indianapolis Colts quarterback, a gentlemanly drawl, for Manning is
the truest of gentlemen. The drawl is pleasant to the ear, just as
Manning is pleasant to chat with, but even more pleasant is the
fact that the most promising quarterback to step into the National
Football League in years seems blissfully unaware that other star
QBs have their media time arranged for them, a few moments here, a
few questions there, but always controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Not Manning.
</P>
<P>
   He'll talk and talk. Then talk some more.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a question.
</P>
<P>
   A gentleman replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I probably wouldn't have had the confidence (to go
after Law) because I didn't have the confidence just where we were
in our timing,'' said Manning. ``But due to the experience from
last year, the offseason work I had thiyr (with receivers), I feel
really confident in my timing. We have the utmost respect for Ty
Law and his abilities and the respect he gets, but when you have a
guy like Marvin Harrison, you can't take him out of the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Same way with Deion Sanders of the Cowboys, the best of the
best. Other quarterbacks avoid Sanders. Not Manning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like when you play against Deion,'' said Manning, who also
burned Sanders with a TD pass to Harrison. ``You've still got to
get the ball to Marvin but how do you do it? You run really good
routes, and you be accurate with the football. If you're off a
little bit, Law or Deion are going to make you pay for it, but
Marvin ran some good routes and we were able to make some good
throws and we were able to execute.''
</P>
<P>
   The confidence oozes. Youthful confidence. Manning struggled
mightily early in his rookie year of 1998, particularly in the
second game of the season against the Patriots, when the New
England secondary suckered him into interception after
interception. And the marvel, said Colts coach Jim Mora, is that
Manning was not scarred by his rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of that,'' said Mora, ``is probably due to his father.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, said Manning, because his father gave him the best
advice any father could give any quarterback breaking into the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad told me this isn't going to be easy,'' said Manning.
``He said it was going to be tough. And you know what? My dad was
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Manning's father is ArchManning, another Southern
gentleman, and Archie Manning was a superb college quarterback at
Mississippi and then an outstanding quarterback for the New Oeans
Saints, even though the Saints never were better than .500 with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Bradshaw, Fran Tarkenton, Kenny Stabler, Dan Fouts, Roger
Staubach, Jim Plunkett, and other quarterbacks of the 1970s won
fame and adulation, but Archie Manning was as good as or better
than any of them. Archie Manning, unlike the others, never had a
team.
</P>
<P>
   And Archie Manning is still Peyton Manning's favorite
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Career wasn't destined
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Manning really doesn't have many clear memories of
watching his father play for New Orleans (``He retired in '84 and I
was like 8 then''). What he does remember, though, is going into
the locker room in the Louisiana Superdome and just hanging with
the team before or after games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can emember being in the locker room after the game and
going to Hawaii for the Pro Bowl and meeting people,'' said
Manning. ``And it was always a lot of fun on Saturdays going out to
the facility and lifting weights and doing those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning and his brother would go to the locker room after games,
too, not knowing or caring whether the Saints had won or lost.
There are more vivid memories than wins and losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tape and candy bars,'' said Manning. ``There's always a lot of
tape and candy bars in a locker room. We'd eat those candy bars and
then we'd make a football out of tape and we'd go out and play
football games _ one-on-one, 100-yard football games. Two guys here
couldn't do that now _ they'd be worn out _ but kids, you could run
all day. And my dad would be finishing interviews and finishing
autographs and he'd come out and get us and say, `Let's go home.'
''
</P>
<P>
   So tas a natural course of events, right? Peyton Manning always
wanted to be a quarterback. Just like Archie Manning. Right?
</P>
<P>
   No, said Manning, ``I was a fat little kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the sports TV guys from time to time would ask little
Peyton what he wanted to be and the boy would say, ``I want to be a
quarterback like my dad,'' it really wasn't so.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids are asked when they're 3, 4, 5 years old what
they want to be when they grow up,'' said Manning, ``and they
always say, `I want to be a football player' or `I want to be a
baseball player.' But I was only a young kid then. That's what I
said, but I was never on a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning's parents were far from stage parents. Archie Manning
may still be a legend at Ole Miss and still a revered figure in New
Orleans, but Peyton Manning was not pushed into football. It sort
of all happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always see some players say it: `This has always been a
dream of mine,' '' said Manning. ``But that's certainly not the
case with me. I guess I always had natural dreams like any kid but
I remember when I got to the seventh grade, I was kind of slow and
I was kind of stiff and I was playing quarterback and I remember
thinking, `You know what? It's going to be hard to get a
scholarship to play in college.' You have to be a good high school
player.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth grade, said Manning, ``That's when I started
working at the position a little bit. I'd ask questions of my dad
and my teammates _ you know, in high school your teammates are your
best friends _ and they'd tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, with incredulity still in his voice, he said, ``In my
junior year, I got a personal letter from (FloridaSte coach) Bobby
Bowden and that was the first tip that told me maybe I was good
enough to play college football.''
</P>
<P>
   He chose Tennessee, in part because of his mother's influence
and in part because Ole Miss had some NCAA problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again,'' said Manning, ``when I got to college, I was
thinking in my sophomore year, `Can I do it?' You know, `Can I
throw against these corners?' and `Can I beat the blitz?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the Colts made him the No. 1 pick, the self-doubts
lingered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to have things happen last year,'' he said. ``I had to
do it. We won only three games but I threw some touchdowns and we
made some plays and it sort of gave me confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   And through it all, he recalled the words from Archie Manning.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Peyton,' he told me, `This thing is going to be tough.
You're the No. 1 pick and the reason it's going to be tough is
you're going to a bad team. That's the way it works.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In college, everything went pretty good for me; I had good
players around me at Tennessee. But I had that attitude from my dad
that I might have to struggle in the pros and when you have that
attitude, it helps.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do throw three interceptions against New England and
you get killed, it helps to get up and say, `I've got to keep
going, I've got to learn.' I've seen a lot of guys who've been
thrown to the wolves and never overcome it. And I knew I was going
to be thrown to the wolves _ that was Mora's and (president Bill)
Polian's plan. They said, `You've got to learn. You've got to
play.' And I think that's the only way you can learn. You can't
learn from the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Images from the past
</P>
<P>
   The Colt_ and all of professional football _ debated 18 months
ago whether Peyton anning or Ryan Leaf should be chosen first in
the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We studied Ryan hard and we studied Peyton hard and it was
very thorough,'' said Mora. ``But we all knew what kind of a
background Peyton came from and we all knw that's why he is what he
is. We knew about his intangibles. We knew there'd be some tough
situations and we felt Peyton was a bit better equipped to handle
them. We were sure Peyton had those qualities of leadership; we
weren't sure Ryan didn't, but we were sure Peyton did.''
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom was that Manning was the more
accomplished quarterback at the moment but that Leaf had more
potential because of his size and throwing arm. Mora, Polian, and
the Colts staff would list the pros and cons of each for hours on
end.
</P>
<P>
   A factor in the final choice was where Mora had coached for the
previous decade: New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had watched Peyton and I knew Archie from my time with the
Saints,'' said Mora, whose opinion of the Mannings coincided with
most others': They are very, very solid people.
</P>
<P>
   Still in all, said Mora, ``I'm very surprised with what happened
to Ryan.'' The Colts' exhaustive study of Leaf gave no indication
of the personality and maturity problems that have plagued Leaf in
San Diego. The Colts, of course, are more than happy they chose
Manning.
</P>
<P>
   And now Manning stands in the Colts' locker room, having told
rookie running back Edgerrin James 20 minutes earlier that he'd be
leaving with James ``in just a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   James is forced to wait as Manning tells tale after tale, ancote
after anecdote.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a boy, for instance, Peyton had heard so much about
his father's greatness at Ole Miss that he would go to the tapes of
Mississippi games _ audio tapes, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to do that, just sit there and listen to the
broadcast,'' said Manning, ``and it'd be so much fun trying to
imagine what was happening on the field from the broadcast. I've
always loved imagining things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning calls it ``pictures in my mind'' and those long-ago
broadcasts still resonate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm watching film or studying defenses before a game,''
he said, ``I do the same thing I used to do with those tapes _ form
pictures in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   All week long he has prepared for this Sunday's game against New
England by drawing those pictures in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picture the New England defense, in their white jerseys, and
what it's going to look like,'' he said. ``It's always helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   He is as shocked as anyone that the Colts are 10-2. His goal
before the season was that ``we might go 10-6. I wanted to go to
the playoffs _ but in this division? The only thing I knew was that
we'd have a chance in every game this year _ last year we didn't
have a chance in a lot of games _ but I knew how tough this AFC
East was.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the ever-candid Manning went on, his No. 1 goal this
season was only to mature as a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to have better discipline and better
decision-making,'' he said. ``I wanted to learn how to throw the
ball away. That's so tough. When they've got you by your ankles and
you're going down, you go down. You don't try to be a hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned one lesson: A punt's n a bad play. Coming out of
college that's hard to lern. Coming out of college, you feel you
can make every third down. I mean, they're paying Ty Law all that
mony for a reason. Sometimes he's got your guy covered. So you
throw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning moves into his next tale, of how the fun in the family
is when son calls father after a Colts game, not to hear father
tell son what went right and what went wrong, because that doesn't
happen unless Peyton Manning asks Archie Manning.
</P>
<P>
   No, the son asks his parents how many different places the
father sat while watching the game on television: couch, sofa,
recliner, or wherever. Archie Manning's superstition is to move
from seat to seat until the Colts score, after which he remains in
the lucky seat. ``That's the first thing I ask,'' said Peyton.
``How many places Dad sat.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgerrin James was still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   And Peyton Manning, the Southern gentleman, was still talking
until that rarest of events in the NFL occurred: The media had to
curtail an interview with a star quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   But not before Manning talks one last time of his father, of how
his father was ``battered and bruised playing on a bad team'' but
week after week, year after year, even though the Saints did little
to help Archie Manning ``my dad came back and played.'' Game after
game, year after year.
</P>
<P>
   It means nothing, said Peyton Manning, that he's had success in
his second year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say what (Dan) Marino did his second year and try to
compae me to him,'' said Manning. ``But I'm more impressed with how
long Dan has played and how well he's played for so long. That's
what's important to me: to be able to plaquarterback well for a
long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
