<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Dec. 12. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
RESERVES-GAY _ The Army is moving forward with plans to discharge
openly gay state Rep. Steve May, an Army reservist, under the
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, despite glowing performance
evaluations. Officials had rated the east Phoenix Republican
legislator as ``one of the finest young officers'' in the Army and
had urged quick promotions, according to a report obtained by The
Arizona Republic. By CHRIS MOESER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTISM (First of two part series) _ Evan O'Neal, 4, who ambles into
an examination room at the Southwest Autism Research Center
cradling a worn Big Bird, is one of the lucky ones. Out of hundreds
of candidates, he was one of 30 Phoenix area children selected for
a double-blind test. Two-thirds of the kids got secretin, the drug
that many hope will cure the enigma that is autism. By JODIE
SNYDER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN _ (Undated) During the hot, humid summer of 1977,
knew the names of all four men killed that July 22 by a forest fire
in southern New Jersey. I could have told you they were members of
the Eagleswood Fire Co. out of Ocean County, N.J., and were among
crews responding to a 2,000-acre arson fire in the Pine Barrens.
What I couldn't have told you _ because I wouldn't have believed it
_ is that all these years later I wouldn't even remember how many
men died that day. Or their names. Or even the name of their fire
department. By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
