<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6455 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     12-11 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT THE TIME TO RUSH TO CONCLUSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At the first whiff of scandal, your gut reaction
is to crinkle your nose in disgust. You hear that UCLA forward
JaRon Rush has been suspended for at least two games and that an
agent and a summer-league coach might be involved and your visceral
reaction is: But of course. Another athlete milking the cash cow
that is college athletics.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, that would seem a Rush to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   There are athletes who arrive on college campuses with their
hands out and their hearts cold as currency. By all accounts, the
20-year-old Rush is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   You suspect this isn't your football team's dirty linen when
UCLA administrators, who have seen their share of self-indulgent
behavior lately, express heartfelt sympathy for Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the nearly two dozen football players who thought they
were owed preferred parking, Rush was not asking what the system
could do for him.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the hallowed halls of Pauley Pavilion you can find
plenty of people who have given serious thought to what Rush could
do for them. And therein lies the problem.
</P>
<P>
   To be a standout basketball player at an outstanding basketball
school is to learn quickly what it's like to be double- and
triple-teamed on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``At UCLA, you have a lot of people steadily in your ear,''
junior guard Rico Hines said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Oh that it were only well-meaning boosters talking to the
players. The reality is prospective agents also sidle up to them
and whisper sweet endearments in their ears. The words can be as
intoxicating as perfume.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough on a 20-year-old,'' Hines said, speaking in
generalities since he knows none of the specifics of Rush's
situation. ``You don't know who to turn to. You need some help,
some guidance, but it's sometimes hard to know who to trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines was addressing reporters shortly after the No. 11 Bruins
had suffered a 59-43 upset loss to No. 24 Gonzaga in the first game
of Rush's suspension. Rush sat on the UCLA bench in street clothes
for the game's entirety, his usual smiling self.
</P>
<P>
   He was there but he was sorely missed.
</P>
<P>
   Rush, who was slowed by a strained elbow before he was stopped
by the suspension, wasn't simply the leading scorer off the bench
and the second-leading rebounder in the previously unbeaten Bruins'
first three games. He was the human surge of adrenaline that kept
everybody's collective pulse racing.
</P>
<P>
   Without him, the Bruins were flatter than a shredded tire. The
nine-day layoff between their victory over Morgan State and their
meeting with Gonzaga wasn't the only nail that deflated them. They
felt sharply Rush's absence on the boards, especially at the
Bruins' end where Gonzaga outrebounded UCLA 31-14.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who made only seven field goals in the second half,
had no answer for the Bulldogs' tenacity. Nor were they equipped to
answer even the most rudimentary questions about Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Earl Watson, Rush's best friend on the team, wrote
Rush's initials and jersey number on his sneakers as a show of
support. Watson said he didn't know any of the specifics that led
to Rush's suspension, only the sketchy details that appeared
Saturday in published reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm letting JaRon have his space,'' said Watson, who got no
such consideration from Gonzaga. The Bulldogs gave him so little
room to create he finished with seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's ready to talk,'' Watson said, ``he knows I'm there
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush could have stayed away. He had to know he was going to be
front and center Saturday no matter where he sat. That he came,
anyway, to face the television cameras and the UCLA student body,
was a simple act that provided a window into his character, his
teammates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how strong he is,'' Watson said of Rush, who declined
interview requests. ``He's not hiding from anything. It had to be
tougher on him than on us, sitting (through that game).''
</P>
<P>
   That's saying something, considering how hard it was on Rush's
teammates, sitting alongside their friend, pretending not to smell
the smoke from the nearby fire.
</P>
<P>
   Hines spoke of feeling ``strange vibes'' in the gym. A couple of
the Bruins admitted the situation was mildly distracting.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is. They're just kids, after all, not
professionals. No matter how quickly some of them are forced to
grow up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
