<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAMIIT RALLIES INTO FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Defending champion Cecil Mamiit of Eagle Rock
battled his way back into the singles final of the drkoop.com
Tennis Championships of Burbank on Saturday, outlasting Jimy
Szymanski in a stirring 6-3, 2-6 7-6 (7-3) semifinal at Burbank
Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Mamiit, who needed to win three of the final four games to force
the tiebreaker, launched the comeback by following a Szymanski
service break in game eight with a break of his own in game nine.
Then, Mamiit rallied from 0-30 with seventh-seeded Szymanski
holding a 5-4 set lead in a dramatic 10th game.
</P>
<P>
   Before prevailing, Mamiit would need to fight off two match
points _ the second with a running volley pass that brought a roar
of applause from a tennis-appreciative crowd treated to big shots
by both players throughout the final set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was that a great match, or what?'' gushed Steve Starleaf,
tournament director for the $37,500 USTA Challenger Series event.
</P>
<P>
   But Mamiit, who won a NCAA singles title as a freshman at USC,
had little time to savor his semifinal victory. He was back on
court for his doubles semifinal barely an hour and a half later,
thanks to Alex O'Brien's quick 6-2, 6-4 win over Bob Bryan of
Camarillo in Saturday's other singles semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Mamiit, seeded third, and eighth-seeded O'Brien meet in the
singles final today at noon, to be followed by the doubles
championship, in which Mamiit will be busy again _ teaming with
Scott Humphries against the top-seeded team of Bob Bryan and Mike
Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   Team Mamiit/Humphries advanced with a 6-3, 6-4 win over Michael
Joyce/Kyle Spencer in Saturday's first doubles semifinal. The Bryan
twins followed with a 6-4, 7-6 (7-4) victory over Adam Peterson/Jim
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, who knocked off top-seeded Paul Goldstein in Friday's
singles quarterfinals, looked sharp most of the way against fellow
Stanford alumnus Bob Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien broke Bryan in the first game of the match, added
another break six games later to go up 5-2 and included a third
break while winning five straight games during a stretch that
spanned both sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of energy today,'' said O'Brien, who combined
quickness with a soft touch that produced some applause-drawing
drop-shot winners.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed headed for an even quicker victory before Bryant
rallied from a 2-5 second-set deficit with back-to-back wins in
games eight and nine. In the process of that rally, Bryan outlasted
one of the most entertaining shots of the day _ O'Brien's charge to
the back wall and overhead, high-lob backward return that caught
Bryan's backline and induced a return into the net.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien wound up bowing happily to a whooping crowd after that
remarkable point, and although Bryan won the game, O'Brien took
both the set and match two games later by winning five of the final
six points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
