</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-ROCKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS BEAT ROCKETS, 106-94  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ One night after crumbling in humiliating
fashion against perhaps one of the worst teams in National
Basketball Association history, the Nets continued their
ebb-and-surge routine with an artistic display against the Houston
Rockets Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   With sleight-of-hand passing, accurate shooting and textbook
execution, the Nets beat the Rockets, 106-94, at Continental Arena.
On Friday night, the Nets dropped a miserably played contest,
71-69, to struggling Chicago, giving the Bulls only their second
victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday night, the 9-point fourth quarter and 37.5 percent
shooting that cost the Nets against the Bulls seemed an ancient
memory. Instead of sulking, the Nets regrouped to dominate the
struggling Rockets, who were playing their second game without the
probable Hall of Famer Charles Barkley, who sustained a
career-ending knee injury last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas the Nets lacked balanced scoring against the Bulls, they
shot 50 percent from the field and had plenty of firepower Saturday
night. Six Nets scored in double figures, including the reserve
point guard Sherman Douglas, who dropped jump shots with surprising
accuracy in scoring 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Van Horn, shooting at least 50 percent for the fourth
straight game, led the Nets with 21 points. Kerry Kittles followed
with 16, and Kendall Gill, his jump shot falling regularly for one
of the few times this season, had 17.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury scored all of his 14 points in the first half,
but do not be fooled by his low point total. Marbury, who made 6 of
13 field-goal attempts and had 7 assists, played an outstanding
floor game, making numerous nifty passes, including a no-look dish
from the hip to a cutting Jamie Feick (14 points) to put the Nets
up by 27 points, 76-49, late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets outscored the Nets by 36-24 in the final period to
close the gap, but the Nets were never challenged. The victory
improved the Nets' record to 5-16, but, more important, it gave
them a 3-1 mark in a week that included victories over tough teams
from Sacramento and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   From tip-off to buzzer Saturday night, the Nets were strong in
the first half. Their offense flowed smoothly as they executed as
well as they have all season. They notched 12 assists, several of
them on nice backdoor feeds and cuts, in the first two quarters _
they average 17.5 assists a game _ and shot 53.5 percent from the
floor, both statistics being testaments to the symmetry they
displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury accepted the challenge delivered by Steve Francis, and
the result was an enticing matchup between two of the league's most
exciting point guards. Francis, one of the league's top rookies,
along with Lamar Odom of the Los Angeles Clippers, had the early
advantage, using between-the-leg dribbles and spin moves to create
space for his jumper or to drive past Marbury altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Francis' most dynamic move came on a miscommunication by the
Nets that left Marbury hanging out to dry. Marbury had Francis
covered on the wing but, anticipating help from a teammate on the
backside, allowed him to drive baseline toward the basket. By the
time Feick arrived to help, Francis was rising high for a
ferocious, one-handed, lean-in dunk. The play gave Francis 11
points, and clearly lighted a fire under Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   On the Rockets' next possession, he called off the help and
guarded Francis one-on-one, forcing the rookie to commit two
turnovers in the final three minutes of the quarter. Marbury, who
attempted to answer Francis' dunk with a 3-pointer, shut down
Francis for the rest of the half, and the Nets pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   After Francis' dunk put the Rockets ahead by 19-18, the Nets
closed the quarter with a 14-4 run to take a 32-23 lead into the
second. The Nets' bench, behind 6 points from Douglas, maintained
the advantage, and then the starters re-entered midway through the
quarter to increase the lead to 55-43 at the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
