</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-WEB-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFLTODAY WEB SITE OWNER: JUST A FAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BLEYS W. ROSE   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARLAKE PARK, Calif. _ From his modest home in northern
California, and using his love of football and newly gained
knowledge of the Internet, Ken Miller has managed to get slapped
with a penalty in the form of a hefty lawsuit from the National
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL wants Miller to give up the rights to his ``NFLtoday''
sites on the World Wide Web. The football organization says the
sites impinge upon its trademarks and copyrights. Miller, 48, says
he started the Web sites last February to satisfy his thirst for
news about the daily doings of his favorite football teams and
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a guy who was a lineman in high school and had dreams
of getting drafted someday and playing football,'' Miller said.
``Well, they didn't draft me, but I did get noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   He got noticed all right. In the form of lawsuit filed in New
York on Tuesday by NFL attorneys who allege that Miller's sites
amount to a form of cyberpiracy that recently became illegal under
new federal legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still trying to find an attorney, but I would like to get
this settled because I didn't have any intention of doing anything
wrong,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Domain names are addresses on the Internet where Web sites are
located. For a small fee, individuals or organizations can register
the names with a special Internet agency, which licenses the rights
to those addresses. In the rush to use the Internet as a public
relations and marketing tool, many companies have staked out
cyberterritory as part of their corporate identity.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has three Web sites that are identical, in that they
offer a compendium of links to other places on the Internet where
information such as statistics, game results, schedules, player
injuries and betting odds are available. The sites all begin with
``NFLtoday'' and end with either .com, .net or .org, the three most
common domain name suffixes.
</P>
<P>
   They offer little original content and act basically like a home
page for anybody looking for information about the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what a fan is? A fanatic. That's me,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who has coached Pop Warner leagues, said NFL fans turn
to his sites for advice about gambling odds as well information
about teams and players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of hits when Walter Payton died,'' said Miller,
referring to the former running back for the Chicago Bears who died
last month. ``I thought the concept of the Internet was to put
together relevant information on the highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller had a previous brush with notoriety about when he was 19
and living in Anaheim. He created and marketed the ``Ticky Dicky''
wristwatch, the face of which featured a likeness of then-President
Richard Nixon flashing his famous double-fisted V-signs.
</P>
<P>
   He said his little company sold thousands of those watches. From
there, he went on to a career in marketing and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he first got interested in the Internet and used it to
search for football news. Not finding a comprehensive site, he
designed one himself and he recalls his mother being the person who
picked the name ``NFL Today'' as the best domain name.
</P>
<P>
   Finding it owned by someone named Hank Miller, no relation, he
bought it for $200. He launched the site last February, but didn't
start working on its content until September when advertisers began
to get interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a full-time job. I am either sleeping or on the
computer,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   A letter from CBS in October demanded that Miller relinquish the
``NFL Today'' name. CBS has televised a Sunday afternoon pregame
show by that name since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Then another letter, this time from the NFL, offered Miller $270
for the domain name. Miller countered with a request for $120,000
and there the matter sat until NFL filed its lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit contends that the repeated use of NFL trademarks
causes people to mistakenly believe that the sites are sponsored or
approved by the NFL. The organization owns the rights to NFL.com,
which it promotes as the official league site.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 2258EST &QL; 
