<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6478 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      12-11 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ECHO OF A DISTANT LAST BELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a time during the hot, humid summer of 1977, I knew the
names of all four men killed that July 22 by a forest fire in
southern New Jersey, not far from the small town where I lived.
</P>
<P>
   I could have told you the men were members of the Eagleswood
Fire Company from Ocean County, and were among crews responding to
a 2,000-acre, arson-caused fire in one of the most quietly lovely
spots on Earth, the Pine Barrens.
</P>
<P>
   I could have told you the four firefighters were in an Army
surplus truck, trying to overrun the flames in what's called Bass
River State Forest.
</P>
<P>
   I could have told you that the next day, July 23, there was to
have been a party celebrating the 50th anniversary of the founding
of the Eagleswood Fire Company.
</P>
<P>
   I could have told you how news of the four deaths spread as fast
as the fire itself, and had the same effect, robbing oxygen from
those who heard it, leaving them ashen.
</P>
<P>
   What I couldn't have told you _ because I wouldn't have believed
it _ is that all these years later, I wouldn't even remember how
many men died that day.
</P>
<P>
   Or their names. Or even the name of their fire department.
</P>
<P>
   I had to look it up, which I did last week after watching TV
coverage of the memorial service for six firefighters killed in a
warehouse in Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   One of the many speakers in Worcester was President Bill
Clinton, who said, ``Too often we take them for granted, our
firefighters. In the days ahead, I hope every American will find an
occasion to thank those in their communities who stand ready every
day to put their lives on the line when the alarm bell rings.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a big memorial service back in 1977, too.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters from Mount Holly, N.J., where I worked for a weekly
paper, let me ride along with them. Their uniforms were dark and
made of wool. The guys in the truck kept their jackets off.
</P>
<P>
   The ride went along happily at first, nothing but small talk and
breezes through the windows. Then, we pulled onto the main road
leading to the service and stopped.
</P>
<P>
   For as far as we could see in front of us, there were
firetrucks. There were even more trucks behind.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters put their jackets on, and we inched along,
finally reaching a big, open area near where the service was to be
held. Trucks were squeezed into rows like red and yellow bricks,
paving the landscape like a shiny dance floor. The service was held
outside. Uniformed men and women walked toward the main podium
until the crush of firefighters in front of them, and the crush
behind, forced them to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere off in the distance, there were eulogies and speeches
and testimonials. And sad, sad music.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't see any of it, neither could the hundreds around me.
Still, throughout the ceremony, the mass of firefighters stood at
attention, not wavering unless someone nearby collapsed in the
heat, which happened more and more as the service stretched into
the miserable afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Worcester, TV cameras focused again and again on
six shiny yellow helmets on the stage of a packed concert arena.
Next to them were photographs of the men who died:
</P>
<P>
   Joseph T. McGuirk, 38; James F. Lyons III, 34; Lt. Thomas E.
Spencer, 42; Timothy P. Jackson, 51; Paul A. Brotherton, 41, and
Jeremiah M. Lucey, 38.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the dead were repeated again and again during the
service. Twenty-two years ago in New Jersey, the only thing
different was the roll call:
</P>
<P>
   Chief Harold Cranmer Jr., 32; Assistant Chief Marcus Cullen, 28;
Herb Blackwell, 23, and John Baker, 52.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial service in 1977 went on for an eternity. So did the
one last week. The speeches. The salutes. The endless procession of
vehicles. The horns and bagpipes and silent, flashing lights.
</P>
<P>
   It's always that way at a firefighters funeral. I see that now.
It's an extravagant, unrelenting event, and the only public
ceremony in America that's not nearly excessive enough. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at &QL; 
ed.montini(at)arizonarepublic.com or at (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
