<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA BATTERS BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA wasn't beaten Saturday at Pauley Pavilion. It
was banished.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after No. 3 Stanford crossed the country to win at
Georgia Tech and No. 2 Arizona hammered No. 4 Michigan State, the
Bruins failed miserably against a Gonzaga team making its third
long road trip in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, someone doesn't belong in the Pac-10's first-class
seats, at least for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a long way to go,'' Bruins guard Earl Watson said
after a 59-43 loss to No. 24 Gonzaga before 9,951 stunned fans.
``We're nowhere close to where we need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have three months to prepare for the NCAA Tournament,
which means nothing. After all, they had 10 days to prepare for
Gonzaga and responded with 16 turnovers, bad shots, clueless zone
offense, sloppy passes, a heartless second half _ ``We rolled
over,'' forward Rico Hines said _ and 26.2 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In addition:
</P>
<P>
   __ The Bruins set Pauley Pavilion records for lowest point total
and lowest shooting percentage.
</P>
<P>
   __ The point total was UCLA's lowest since the shot clock was
implemented in 1985-86.
</P>
<P>
   __ The 16-point margin equalled the worst nonconference home
defeat in school history.
</P>
<P>
   It was a memorable day, indeed, under those 11 NCAA championship
banners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had 10 days off to prepare and we played very poorly _
that one's on me as the head coach,'' said UCLA's Steve Lavin, who
also has the worst loss in school history (48 points, at Stanford)
on his record.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes for the Bruins, 3-1, who played without suspended
forwards Matt Barnes (academics) and JaRon Rush (possible NCAA
violation) and injured guard Ryan Bailey (tendinitis).
</P>
<P>
   They have six days to prepare for No. 20 DePaul, which lost at
Duke by one point. They have 18 days to ready for Purdue and they
have 25 days to prepare for the rugged Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   And those back-to-back January games against North Carolina and
Arizona? Oh, boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely aware of what Stanford and Arizona are
doing,'' Hines said. ``This game lets us know where we are. In the
second half, we didn't counter Gonzaga's spurt. We laid down and
let them run over us. Everybody was looking at each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who played Cincinnati and Temple last week, opened
the second half with a 22-6 surge, then braced for a UCLA riposte
that never came.
</P>
<P>
   Watson made 3 of 15 shots and had seven turnovers. ``Shooting''
guard Ray Young was 1 of 7. Forward Jason Kapono was 3 of 10, and
the Bruins were as inept against Gonzaga's zone as they were
against Detroit Mercy's zone in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just didn't play with a lot of fire today,'' Gonzaga
guard Matt Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't play with a lot of Jerome Moiso, either.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-10 sophomore, Moiso is UCLA's leading scorer and leading
rebounder, and he has one eye on the NBA. Perhaps he was
overzealous Saturday when Lakers Executive Vice President Jerry
West showed up. More likely, Moiso was confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got my third foul, I thought it was my second foul,''
Moiso said. ``That's why I kept going hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. Moiso committed his fourth foul with 19 minutes
left in the game, a silly reach-in 15 feet from the basket. He
spent nine minutes on the bench watching center Dan Gadzuric
struggle (2-of-7 shooting) against Gonzaga's collapsing defense.
</P>
<P>
   When Moiso returned, the Bulldogs had taken control and they
weren't about to let it go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were outcompeted in the paint,'' Lavin said, ``and it
wasn't as though we played a dominant frontcourt team like
Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   That comes Feb. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
