<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RUSH-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA LOOKING INTO TWO SEPARTE ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA is investigating unrelated issues concerning
suspended forward JaRon Rush _ one involving his former
summer-league coach, Myron Piggie, the other involving his dealings
with a sports agent, according to sources close to UCLA and Rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told an agent is involved and that sickens me,'' Pac-10
commissioner Tom Hansen said. ``Agents are the biggest problem
facing college athletics today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush was suspended indefinitely by the school Friday for a
possible NCAA-rules violation. Hansen said the potential infraction
won't violate UCLA's three-year NCAA probation, which was imposed
in 1998 for violations committed by former Bruins coach Jim
Harrick.
</P>
<P>
   Rush, a sophomore from Kansas City, Mo., missed several
practices last month to testify in a trial involving Piggie in
Kansas City, sources said, and the current investigation is related
to that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what's going on, but (Piggie) is a very touchy
situation,'' said UCLA guard Earl Watson, who also played for
Piggie and is Rush's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis and faculty athletics
representative Donald Morrison are conducting the investigation.
The Pac-10 and/or NCAA will join the process only if UCLA requires
help with interviews and fact-finding. The investigation could take
one week or several weeks, depending on the availability of the
interviewees.
</P>
<P>
   Rush won't practice until the investigation concludes, if then.
Asked Friday if Rush's future at the school is in jeopardy, Dalis
said: ``It's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalis and Morrison will submit their findings to the Pac-10's
Compliance Committee, which determines if a violation has occurred
and recommends sanctions if warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school can also self-impose penalties,'' Pac-10 assistant
commissioner Jim Muldoon said. ``That happens a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush was on the bench in street clothes Saturday watching UCLA's
59-43 loss to Gonzaga. He was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was here today, early, slapping our butts and being his
usual, energetic self,'' Bruins forward Rico Hines said. ``He told
us, `I'm with you in spirit.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
