<DOCNO> NYT19991211.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-11 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6490 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     12-11 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 19)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAST KING OF SCOTLAND &LR;  By Giles Foden. Vintage
International, $13. Nicholas Garrigan, a young Scottish doctor in
the employ of the Ugandan dictator Idi Amin, is anything but
heroic: He's weak, indecisive and easily manipulated. ``Therein
lies the admirable risk'' of this ambitious first novel, Michael
Upchurch wrote in The New York Times Book Review last year, and
despite the doctor's moral failings he emerges as an oddly
sympathetic protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AT HOME WITH THE MARQUIS DE SADE: A Life &LR;  By Francine du
Plessix Gray. Penguin, $14.95. Talk about standing by your man:
Renee-Pelagie de Montreuil de Sade, the wife of the legendary
18th-century sexual rogue, persevered through sex scandals, police
raids and prison terms (the marquis spent 15 of the 27 years they
were married in prison or on the run). In fact he might never have
written a word had it not been for her saintly servitude, according
to this biography, which effectively defangs Sade while suggesting
that perhaps a bit of the scoundrel's unfettered narcissism lurks
deep in every psyche. The result is a ``bold, imaginative'' book,
Emily Eakin wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TALE OF THE 1002ND NIGHT &LR;  By Joseph Roth. Picador USA, $14.
The Austrian writer's final work of fiction, published in 1939, is
an erotic fairy tale set in Hapsburg Vienna, featuring the shah of
Persia and a string of pearls that dooms everyone who gets near it.
Last year the reviewer Iain Bamforth praised Roth's ``wonderful
style ... for the way it plunges us into the swim of time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BIBLE AS IT WAS &LR;  By James L. Kugel. Belknap/Harvard
University, $19.95. The author draws on diverse sources to explain
how the Torah, the first five books of the Bible, was understood by
ancient peoples and how the interpretations of early scholars
altered our perceptions of biblical teachings. In 1997, Phyllis
Trible called this a ``fascinating study'' handled ``with erudition
and enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THE HIDDEN JESUS: A NEW LIFE &LR; , by Donald Spoto (St. Martin's
Griffin, $14.95), a theologian (and celebrity biographer) examines
the life of Jesus of Nazareth and argues that his true vision
remains alive and active today. The result is ``a personal
statement of faith'' that ``thoughtfully challenges some of
Christianity's traditions,'' Alexandra Hall wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JESUS THROUGH THE CENTURIES: His Place in the History of
Culture &LR; , by Jaroslav Pelikan (Yale University, $13.95), is a
celebratory study of Jesus' impact on Western art, thought and
culture over the last 2,000 years. ``Believers and skeptics alike
will find it a sweeping visual and conceptual panorama,'' John
Koenig wrote in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE SHE WENT: Stories &LR;  By Kate Walbert. Penguin, $12.95. In
these 14 linked tales, a lonely company wife moves from place to
place, a journey echoed years later by her adult daughter, who
travels the world in search of fulfillment. ``Their stories are
small, elegiac and inconclusive,'' Molly Giles wrote in 1998.
```Where She Went' contains many quick flashes of beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A HIGH WIND IN JAMAICA &LR;  By Richard Hughes. New York Review,
$12.95. This dreamlike 1929 novel explores the tangled fates of a
group of children en route from the West Indies to England and the
ragtag crew of pirates that reluctantly captures them. ``There is
an air of fantastic credibility about this odyssey,'' The New York
Times Book Review wrote, and it is a fascinating study in child
psychology.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DOCTOR STORIES &LR;  By Richard Selzer. Picador USA, $14. These
tales by a former surgeon, culled from three decades of short
fiction, explore lives on both ends of the scalpel and are
carefully imbued with the language of sickness. ``Selzer's fiction
is refreshingly old-fashioned: His prose is formal, his ironies
straightforward,'' Tobin Harshaw wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOSSIER: The Secret History of Armand Hammer &LR;  By Edward Jay
Epstein. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $15.95. The larger-than-life oil magnate
(1898-1990), who courted world leaders from Lenin to George Bush,
emerges in this well-researched biography as ``a morbidly
fascinating compound of ambition, greed, unscrupulousness and power
hunger,'' Joseph E. Persico wrote in 1996. ``It is hard to imagine
a sharper picture of how a tycoon is both born and made.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OH, JACKIE &LR;  By Maudy Benz. Berkley, $12.95. The 15-year-old
narrator of this first novel, left by her parents to spend the
summer of 1963 with her wealthy cousins in Michigan, tries to
imagine what her idol, Jackie Kennedy, would do to escape the
clutches of her lecherous uncle. Benz tells the story ``with
tenderness and impressive control,'' Sally Eckhoff wrote in The New
York Times Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAKING NEWS &LR;  By Robert MacNeil. Harvest/Harcourt, $13. This
lively novel by the former PBS news anchor centers on a 60-ish
network anchorman grappling with both a life crisis and a career
crisis. The result is ``a provocative cri de coeur aimed at what
one character calls `information/entertainment television,''' Eric
Alterman wrote in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-99 2343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
