<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINN SHOWS JITTERS, SKILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Jere Karalahti struggled in his long-awaited NHL
debut, but when the Los Angeles Kings saw him tear off a blistering
slap shot during the third period, they came away impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could he not have been nervous?'' said defensemate Mattias
Norstrom. ``He's played in world championships over in Finland, but
believe me, there is nothing like your first game here. There is
nothing you can say until you experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti was signed by the Kings last summer, but his arrival
from Finland was delayed because of a history of drug abuse. He has
been clean for two years after completing a nine-month
rehabilitation program but was tied up in red tape for three months
after his signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you could see the skill,'' coach Andy Murray said. ``And
he has a bit of an edge, which can be rare for a European player.
His quickness will pick up just by being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti was besieged by Finnish reporters after the game. He
appeared calmer than anyone, which Murray said is a big part of his
easy-going personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what was coming,'' Karalahti said. ``I've waited a long
time for this. I thought as the game went on, things got a little
better. The best part is that we won.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Blake back? Mattias Norstrom's usual defensive partner Rob
Blake missed his second consecutive game with a strained groin and
is not certain if he will play Tuesday in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better, but we'll see,'' he said. ``I won't skate on it
again until Tuesday, so that should give it some time to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   On Karalahti, who probably would be the one to be benched when
Blake returns: ``That was a tough spot for him tonight. Everyone is
telling him to relax. Matty told him to have fun in his first NHL
game, but it isn't easy. You just want to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Stepping up: Is it a coincidence that defenseman Aki Berg is
playing the best hockey of his career with Blake out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to do what I can do,'' said Berg, who Murray
claimed was the best player on the ice Saturday. ``It hasn't always
been easy this year, but I feel very comfortable. I don't know if
having (Blake) out has made a difference in me. I'd like to think I
play hard all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg, who played in his native Finland last year during a
contract dispute, was benched twice back in October for poor play.
Norstrom thinks he is finally settling in after his holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we're 30 games in, but losing a whole season takes a
lot of adjusting,'' Norstrom said. ``He looks great on the power
play now. He looks great every time he's on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Palffy flies: Injured right wing Ziggy Palffy tested his sore
lower back Saturday in Los Angeles and will rejoin the team today
in New Jersey. Palffy, the Kings' leading scorer with 27 points,
skated, but the team isn't sure if he will be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me he was flying (today), so I have to think he's
better,'' Murray said. ``The fact that he's coming is encouraging,
but we really won't know until we practice Monday. We need to make
sure he's healthy before he plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy missed his third consecutive game Saturday. Before this
year, Palffy missed a total of three games because of injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
