<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-SCWOMEN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC BOUNCES BACK BIG AFTER FRUSTRATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Perhaps still stung from its loss to Long Beach
State, the USC women's basketball team took out its frustrations on
Sacramento State on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   USC scored the first 12 points of the game and breezed to an
84-42 victory at the Lyon Center, a result that helped ease the
pain from Wednesday's loss to Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurt everybody. It was a big stab,'' forward Danielle
Golay said. ``It was kind of a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   The Women of Troy (4-2) so easily dominated Sacramento State
(2-5) that the Hornets went scoreless the first six minutes of the
second half and did not score a field goal for nearly 8{ minutes.
Sacramento State's 42 points were the ninth-fewest ever allowed by
a USC team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the Long Beach game . . . we were very,
very disappointed,'' USC coach Chris Gobrecht said. ``We're not
good enough to let anybody outhustle us.''
</P>
<P>
   Three USC players scored in double figures, with Golay getting a
game-high 12 points. Forward Tashara Carter and point guard Lauren
Smith-Hams each had 11. Forward Denise Woods, a transfer from San
Francisco, added six points and 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Smith-Hams, a true freshman, made three shots from 3-point range
in just her second start of the season, as Gobrecht searches for a
reliable point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to find the right leader for this team,'' Gobrecht
said. ``That position is really a mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   USC guard Erica Mashia scored eight points, as she makes an
impressive comeback after missing the past two seasons with a hip
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a tremendous boost in terms of intelligence,'' Gobrecht
said. ``She's not the player she was before the injuries, but Erica
at less than what she was is still a huge boost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
